— Acknowledgments —

1995年，我撰写本书初版时，得到了不少人的帮助。约翰·德尔维斯自1990年以来与我合作撰写了多篇文章，他充当我的“代理读者”，帮助我修改文本，使之更易于非游泳者或游泳新手阅读，并使其清晰易读。他是一位游泳教练所能遇到的最好的写作老师。书中所有的线条图均由我的兄弟史蒂夫·劳克林绘制。我最初的编辑贝基·卡巴扎对游泳和印刷文字充满热情。在增订版中，多丽丝·库珀顺利指导项目完成，凯蒂·迈尔斯则对我的行文进行了无缝衔接的润色。

In 1995 when I wrote the original edition of this book, I benefited from the help of quite a few people. John Delves, who had collaborated with me on numerous articles since 1990, acted as my “surrogate reader” and helped shape my text to read well and clearly for non-swimmers and new swimmers. He was the best writing teacher a swimming coach could have. My brother Steve Laughlin produced all the line drawings found within. My original editor Becky Cabaza had great enthusiasm for swimming and the printed word. For the updated edition, Doris Cooper smoothly guided the project to completion, and Katie Myers seamlessly improved my prose.

爱丽丝·麦克休·劳克林，我的妻子兼伴侣，自1974年以来一直陪伴着我。在我从事游泳教练生涯的起起伏伏中，她一直无私地给予我爱与支持，并让我保持条理，以便能够全身心投入到游泳教练、教学和写作中。我的女儿菲奥娜、卡里和贝琪无数个周末无私地与世界各地的游泳爱好者分享她们的父亲。我很高兴地说，她们现在都已接受培训，成为全浸式教学专业人士。

Alice McHugh Laughlin, my wife and partner since 1974, has been selfless and unconditional in her love and support through the ups and downs of a life in swim coaching and kept me organized so I could devote myself to coaching, teaching, and writing about swimming. My daughters Fiona, Cari, and Betsy have selflessly shared their dad with swimmers around the world on countless weekends, and—I am delighted to say—have all now become trained as Total Immersion Teaching Professionals.

- 介绍 -

— Introduction —

我问你三个问题：

Let me ask you three questions:

 

 

1.游泳是否让你感觉良好——无论是身体上还是整体上都感到满意？

1. Does swimming make you feel good—both physically and in overall satisfaction?

2.您是否觉得自己知道如何才能变得更好——不是猜测，而是有保证？

2. Do you feel you know what it takes to get better—not guesswork, but guaranteed?

3.您是否正在稳步前进——尽管进展缓慢——以提高效率和理解力？

3. Are you progressing steadily—even if slowly—toward greater efficiency and understanding?

如果你对这三个问题的答案都是“是”，如果你对游泳感到不适、沮丧或困惑，如果你在游泳教学或教练方面有过不愉快的经历，那不是因为你有什么问题。你接受的教育方式——甚至你被引导去思考游泳的方式——才是罪魁祸首。

If you can’t answer yes to all three questions, if you feel any discomfort, frustration, or confusion about swimming, if you’ve ever had an unsatisfying experience with swim instruction or coaching, it’s not because there’s anything wrong with you. The way you were taught— indeed, even the way you’ve been led to think about swimming—is to blame.

几乎每个人——除了极少数“天生”游泳者——都有过类似的经历。问题在于，鱼类和水生哺乳动物天生就适合在水中高效游动，而我们却并非如此。几乎每个人第一次尝试游泳都是一次濒死体验，如果失败，就真的有可能溺水。而且之后的情况也好不到哪里去：尽管游泳是一项必不可少的生活技能，但却从未被正确地教授过。传统的（例如红十字会的）游泳指导教你如何避免溺水，而不是而不是效仿那些对鱼类有效的方法。如果你继续阅读，这一切都将为你改变！

Virtually everyone—the tiny percentage of “natural” swimmers excepted—has had similar experiences. The problem is that while fish and aquatic mammals are ideally designed for moving through water efficiently, we’re not. Virtually everyone’s first swimming attempt is a near-death experience, with a real prospect of drowning if you’re not successful. And it doesn’t get much better after that: Despite the fact that swimming is an essential life skill, it has never been taught correctly. Traditional (i.e., Red Cross) instruction teaches you to not drown rather than to emulate what works so well for fish. If you continue reading, all that is about to change for you!

完全浸入式游泳如何彻底改变游泳

How Total Immersion Revolutionized Swimming

这本书的初版出版于1996年。几个月后，它既没有大肆宣传，也没有广告宣传，就成为了全球最畅销的游泳书籍。原因何在？因为每个读过它的人都立刻开始游得更好，也更享受游泳。他们终于明白了游泳的真正意义。他们发现自己第一次取得了稳步的进步。在过去的六年里，我收到成千上万读者的来信，他们都表达了这样的感慨：“感谢您以通俗易懂的方式撰写游泳文章，让游泳成为一项真正令人愉悦的活动。”

The first edition of this book was published in 1996. Within months, with neither fanfare nor advertising, it became the world’s best-selling book on swimming. The reason? Everyone who read it began to swim better, and to enjoy swimming more, immediately. They finally understood what really matters in swimming. And they found themselves making steady progress for the first time ever. In the past six years, I’ve heard from thousands of readers, all expressing these sentiments: “Thanks for writing about swimming in a way that makes sense and for making swimming a truly pleasurable activity.”

这些信息让我无比欣慰，因为我真心希望提供一种人人都能理解和遵循的游泳进阶方法。此外，通过实践我所教的内容，我达到了个人的涅槃境界，游的每一圈都充满幸福感。因为我从来都不是天才运动员，所以我坚信，游好泳的乐趣人人都能获得，而不是少数天才的专属。作为一名教师，我的使命就是将这份天赋带给尽可能多的人。

These messages have been enormously gratifying, as I had really hoped to provide a swimming-improvement method that anyone could understand and follow. Moreover, by practicing what I teach, I’ve reached a personal nirvana where every lap I swim feels blissful. Because I’ve never been a gifted athlete, I became convinced that the joy of swimming well is attainable by everyone, rather than a gift reserved for a talented few. My mission as a teacher has been to bring that gift to as many people as possible.

从新手到全国冠军（当然也包括教练和老师），形形色色的游泳爱好者都对TI方法充满热情，这证明了“完全沉浸式”游泳法的有效性！无论您是三岁、四十三岁还是七十三岁，无论您从未游过泳还是已经创造了无数纪录，TI都能让您……让任何人成为游泳运动员，或者让你成为比现在更好的游泳运动员。

Enthusiasm for the TI approach—from all manner of swimmers, from novices to national champions (and coaches and teachers, too)—confirms that Total Immersion works! It doesn’t matter if you’re age three or forty-three or seventy-three—or whether you’ve never swum before or have set bushels of records. Total Immersion can turn anyone into a swimmer or make you a better swimmer than you are now.

在过去的几年里，TI 已经成为一场“运动”。几乎所有接触过 TI 的人，无论是读过这本书、参加过 TI 研讨会，甚至看过 TI 游泳运动员在当地泳池里来回滑行，都意识到，正如书名所示，它具有革命性。纽约布鲁克林的丹·谢弗最近写信给我，在他第一次教授 TI 之后，学生们始终如一的热情让他相信：“五十年后，如果有人决定撰写一部权威的游泳史，你的书将被誉为游泳变革的主要影响因素。”

In the past few years, TI has become a “movement.” Virtually everyone who has been introduced to TI, after reading the book, attending a TI workshop, or even watching a TI swimmer glide back and forth in the local pool has recognized that, as the title promises, it’s revolutionary. Dan Schaffer, of Brooklyn, New York, recently wrote me that after his first experiences of teaching TI, the unvarying enthusiasm of his students convinced him that “fifty years from now, if someone decided to write a definitive history of swimming, your book would be cited as the main influence for when swimming changed.”

Total Immersion 以一种前所未有的方式教授游泳。我们称之为“鱼式游泳”（TI），这种游泳方式通常被人们称为“人类游泳”。传统的游泳老师和教练专注于划水、踢腿、用力划水和无休止的游泳圈，让你适应不断增加的游泳圈——而这些活动主要强化了“人类游泳”中所有浪费体力的行为。TI 教练会教你保持平衡、流畅和流畅——并让你在泳池中投入时间进行认真的练习，将这些高效的动作转化为坚如磐石的习惯。

Total Immersion teaches swimming in a way that no one ever has before. We call the TI method Fishlike Swimming, and the way swimming is usually taught Human Swimming. Conventional teachers and coaches focus on pulling, kicking, muscling your way through the water and endless laps to condition you for the ordeal of more and more laps—activities that mainly reinforce all that is wasteful about Human Swimming. TI instructors teach you to be balanced, slippery, and fluent—and to devote your pool time to thoughtful practice that turns these efficient movements into rock-solid habits.

TI 将如何改变你的游泳方式：

Here is how TI will change your swimming:

 

 

•你将学会像鱼一样游动。与其在水中无休止地划水、踢腿，不如像鱼一样轻松优雅地游动。从第一圈充满智慧、有目的的TI练习开始，你就能感受到其中的不同。

• You’ll learn to be Fishlike. Rather than churning out endless laps of pulling and kicking, you’ll learn to swim with the effortless grace of fish. You’ll feel the difference from your very first lap of intelligent, purposeful TI practice.

•你将学习优美游泳的特质以及技巧。虽然你最初的目标可能是游泳游得更快，你很快就会意识到，优雅、流畅、经济地游得更重要，也更令人满足。只要你先掌握了轻松，速度自然会随之而来。

• You’ll learn the qualities of beautiful swimming as well as the mechanics. While your initial goal is probably to swim faster, you’ll quickly realize that it’s far more important—and more satisfying—to swim with grace, flow, and economy. Speed will surely follow if you first master ease.

•您将在流畅的划水动作中实现蜕变。TI是所有游泳提升课程中唯一将游泳作为一种练习来教授的课程——其理念与瑜伽或太极拳一样，充满正念。通过 TI 的游泳方式，您将增强身心联系，从而提升自我意识和自我掌控能力，并拥有更佳的身心健康。

• You’ll achieve transformation along with fluid strokes. TI, alone among all swimming-improvement programs, teaches swimming as a practice—in the same mindful spirit as yoga or tai chi. By swimming the TI way you’ll sharpen the mind-body connection leading to heightened self-awareness and self-mastery, and greater physical and mental well-being.

•你将精通游泳，如同掌握一门艺术。TI强调与武术大师一样，注重精准和精益求精的训练。你将从简单的技能和动作开始，循序渐进，轻松掌握，并在对细节的关注和循序渐进的技能中不断成长。

• You’ll master swimming as an art. TI emphasizes the same studied precision and refinement taught by martial-arts masters. You’ll start with simple skills and movements, will progress by small, easily mastered steps, and will thrive on the attention to detail and the logical sequence of progressive skills.

一夜之间，你的游泳将从“沿着黑线划”转变为一种“动态冥想”，它总是感觉良好，既能带来精神上的投入，也能带来身体上的愉悦。这一点很重要，因为如果你纯粹是为了乐趣而游泳——而不是出于义务感——你就会终生游泳。而且正如我们所发现的，即使你游泳的主要原因是为了赢得比赛，那些感觉最好的动作也能帮助你游出最好的水平。

Overnight your swimming will be transformed from “following the black line” into a “moving meditation” that always feels good and is as mentally engaging as it is physically pleasurable. That’s important because if you swim for the sheer pleasure of it—rather than from a sense of obligation—you’ll swim for life. And as we’ve found, even if your primary reason for swimming is to win races, the movements that feel the best are also those that help you swim your best.

此版本有哪些新内容？

What’s New in This Edition?

《完全沉浸》一书最初出版时，已经为成千上万的游泳者带来了巨大的成功。然而，我们用来教授“鱼式”游泳的方法正如第八章所述，自1996年以来，经过数千次教学经验的积累，游泳课程得到了显著改进。到2001年，我们的教学顺序已变得更容易让每个学生学习，从基础训练到高级训练再到全程游泳的衔接也变得更加顺畅。原第八章描述的十二个步骤中，只有两个步骤保留在更新后的十四个步骤中。新的学习顺序效果显著，因此我认为有必要更新本书。

The book Total Immersion, as originally published, has worked wonderfully for thousands of swimmers. Yet the process we use to teach Fish-like Swimming, as described in chapter 8, has been dramatically refined as the result of thousands of teaching experiences since 1996. By 2001, our instructional sequence had become easier for every student to learn and the progression from basic drills to advanced drills to whole-stroke swimming had also become far more seamless. Only two of the twelve steps described in the original chapter 8 remain in the fourteen steps of the updated sequence. Our new learning sequence was working so much better that I thought it essential to update this book.

第 1 章至第 7章与以前相比没有变化，因为它们仍然简单而清楚地解释了为什么一圈又一圈地游泳对你没有什么帮助，以及为什么让你的身体滑过水中最小的“洞”对你的游泳影响比你如何用手将水推向你的脚要大得多。一旦你读完了第 1 章至第 3 章，请直接学习第 8 章中的第 1 课和第 2 课。这些身体平衡和流线型练习是接下来一切的基础。第 8 章中的技巧训练非常简单，你真的可以在没有任何准备的情况下开始做，但如果你理解它们为什么有效，做对后的感觉如何，以及如何逐渐将它们融入到你的常规游泳中，它们将更有意义- 并且可能对你起效更快，第4章至第 7章将介绍这些内容。

Chapters 1 to 7 remain unchanged from before, as they still explain simply and clearly why swimming lap after lap has done little for you and why slipping your body through the smallest possible “hole” in the water has far more of an impact on your swimming than how you use your hands to push water toward your feet. Once you’ve read chapters 1 to 3, go ahead and dive right into Lessons 1 and 2 in chapter 8. These body-balancing-and-streamlining exercises are the foundation of everything to come. The skill drills in chapter 8 are so simple you could really start doing them without any preparation, but they’ll mean more— and possibly work faster for you—if you understand why they work, how they’ll feel when you get them right, and how you’ll gradually integrate them into your regular swimming, which is covered in chapters 4 to 7.

一旦你开始以一种新的方式游泳，你就应该以不同的方式练习，第二部分将向你展示如何练习，解释“身体调节是你在练习良好技巧时发生的事情”的原因和方式。从现在开始，你会发现，“掌握节奏和消除挣扎”总是先于“肌肉力量”。

Once you begin swimming in a new way, you should practice differently, and part 2 shows you how, explaining how and why “conditioning is something that happens to you while you’re practicing good technique.” You’ll see that from now on, “mastering flow and eliminating struggle” always comes before “muscle power.”

像鱼一样游泳是人们想要长期享受的事情，第三部分关于力量训练、减肥和 5陪审团预防机制将有助于实现这一点。此外，还有一些令人兴奋的可能性，让你可以做一些你可能从未尝试过的事情——从在公开水域游泳到参加大师游泳比赛，再到通过邮寄方式提交成绩的比赛。

Fishlike Swimming is something people want to enjoy for a long time, and the advice in part 3 on strength training, weight loss, and in-5 jury prevention will help make that possible. So will the exciting possibilities for doing things you may never have tried—from swimming in open water to competing in Masters Swimming or a postal meet where you mail in your times.

道理很简单：忘掉你听过的所有游泳知识吧；旧方法难以遵循，令人沮丧，而且会因为专注于错误的事情而浪费你的精力和时间。要成为一名优秀的游泳运动员，你既不需要强壮的肌肉，也不需要年轻的体魄，既不需要卓越的运动天赋，也不需要惊人的耐力。你需要流畅的动作，以及一种明智而深思熟虑的方法来养成“心流”的习惯。有了这本书作为指导，你将两者兼得。

The message is simple: Forget everything you’ve heard about swimming; the old way is difficult to follow, frustrating, and wastes your energy and time by concentrating on the wrong things. To become a good swimmer you need neither brawn nor youth, neither great athleticism nor impressive endurance. You need fluent movement and an intelligent, thoughtful approach to making Flow a habit. With this book as your guide, you’ll have both.

1

1

游泳圈和无处可去

Swimming Laps and Going Nowhere

人们游得不够快、不够远、不够流畅，这其实并不奇怪：大多数人都是反着游的。“姿势不完美也不用担心，”教练和指导员总是这样对我们说。“只要游几圈就行。最终，你会变得足够强壮，能够练就更流畅、更有力的划水姿势。”其实反过来也行，只是教学方法不一样。

It’s no mystery why people have trouble swimming as fast or as far or as smoothly as they’d like: Most of them are doing it backward. “Don’t worry if your form’s not perfect,” coaches and instructors have always assured us. “Just get those laps in. Eventually, you’ll be fit enough to develop a smoother, stronger stroke.” It really works the other way around, but that’s not how it’s been taught.

直到现在。让我来告诉你我是如何发现真正意义上的优秀游泳的，以及这对于那些宁愿花时间更快更顺畅地成长而不是只会变得疲惫的人来说意味着什么——对于那些想要尽快完成所有事情的人来说。

Until now. Let me tell you how I came to discover what good swimming is really all about, and what this means to anyone who would rather spend his or her time growing faster and smoother instead of just growing tired—and who wants to do it all as quickly as possible.

但首先，我要坦白：我沉迷于游泳这项运动。我几乎每天早上5:30就出门，去完成我每天的游泳“约定”。只要有机会，我就会参加游泳比赛和公开水域比赛。最后，同样重要的是，我靠教其他成年人如何沉迷游泳为生。

But first, a confession. I’m addicted to the sport of swimming. I leave my house at 5:30 most mornings to keep my daily swimming “appointment,” I compete in meets and open-water events whenever I can, and last but not least, I earn my living teaching other adults how to become addicted too.

很难想象还有什么其他方式，因为在我看来，游泳比任何穿着衣服做的事都更有趣。游泳的感觉棒极了，而且无论训练多么艰苦，你都会感到神清气爽、活力四射，以至于接下来的一天里，任何挑战都显得那么重要。

Hard to imagine it any other way because, in my opinion, swimming is more fun than anything else you can do with your clothes on. It feels great and, no matter how hard the workout, you’re left so refreshed, so energized, that for the rest of the day no challenge seems too great.

再举个例子，还有什么运动能达到这样的效果？跑步后，我一整天都酸痛，而且经常持续到第二天。骑自行车很有趣，当然也是不错的运动，但前提是太阳升起，天气不冷不湿。力量训练很棒，但做完之后，我只能把健身包提回车里。

Name one other workout that can do that. After running, I ache all day long and often into the next. Cycling is fun and is certainly fine exercise, but only as long as the sun’s up and it’s not cold or wet out. Weight training is excellent, but by the time I’m done, it’s all I can do to carry my gym bag back to the car.

游泳就不一样了。每次锻炼后，我都感觉比以前好多了。正因如此，即使是在寒冷的早晨，日出之前，或是闷热的夏日黎明前，我也能轻松地离开舒适的床，准时到达泳池。

Swimming’s different. I always feel better after my workout than I did before. That’s what makes it so easy to leave a comfortable bed even before sunup on a frosty morning, or on a sultry summer predawn, to get to the pool on time.

或许称游泳为“理想运动”有点过分，但很难找到比它更合适的运动了。游泳能让你的心肺更高效地工作，增强肌肉力量和耐力，提高柔韧性，并有助于减轻压力。然而，游泳比其他任何能提高心率的运动都更能减轻关节负担。除非你把越野滑雪也算上，否则游泳比其他所有运动都更能锻炼肌肉。而且，游泳也是唯一能让你真正感受到轻松自在、自由自在的运动。

Perhaps calling swimming “the ideal exercise” is a little strong, but it would be hard to find a better contender for the title. It makes your heart and lungs work more efficiently, enhances muscle strength and endurance, improves flexibility, and helps reduce stress. Yet swimming is easier on the joints than anything else that gets your heart rate up. Unless you count cross-country skiing, swimming uses more muscles than all other exercises. And it’s the only one that can legitimately make you feel weightless and free.

厌倦了其他有氧运动带来的伤痕累累？游泳几乎是所有有氧运动中最不容易受伤的。它没有陆上运动中那种令人毛骨悚然的冲击力，也消除了困扰众多慢跑者和骑行者的关节和背部损伤。水对肌肉也更温和。它的按摩效果和稳定均匀的阻力，可以消除陆上运动中常见的运动后肌肉酸痛。

Tired of the battle scars of other aerobic sports? Swimming is about as injury-free as they come. Gone are the bone-jarring shocks of land sports, so gone too are the joint and back injuries that plague so many joggers and cyclists. The water is also kinder to your muscles. Its massaging effect and the steady, even resistance it provides eliminate much of the postworkout muscle soreness so common in land sports.

游泳时几乎不可能发生过热的情况。水的导热性能比空气好20倍，所以你可以进行高强度的训练——尤其是在夏天——而不会像在岸上那样出现脱水和潜在的中暑。

Overheating is also nearly impossible in swimming. Water conducts heat from the body twenty times better than air does, so you can train at much higher intensities—in summer particularly—without the dehydration and potential heat exhaustion common “ashore.”

游泳是一项机会均等的运动。即使你的体重，如果身体上的障碍或伤病通常会让你无法在陆地上活动，那么你或许可以游泳。事实上，许多陆地运动员在受伤后会通过游泳来恢复体力和体能，这比他们重返主要运动项目要快得多。

And swimming is an equal opportunity sport. Even if your weight, a physical handicap, or an injury would normally keep you out of action on land, you can probably swim. In fact, many land athletes use swimming to regain strength and fitness after an injury, far sooner than they could by returning to their main sport.

关节会随着时间推移而变得僵硬吗？成年人游泳最重要的原因之一就是为了提高柔韧性，因为这项运动比任何其他有氧运动都能更好地促进关节活动。虽然游泳并非心脏方面的青春之源，但 1988 年，德克萨斯大学达拉斯健康科学中心的心脏病专家和运动生理学家进行的一项研究表明，不爱运动的成年人在开始游泳训练计划后仅三个月内，心脏功能就显著改善。他们的心跳变得更慢、更有力，血液循环也更高效。研究还表明，经常游泳的人血压更低、脉搏更慢，运动耐受力也远高于同龄人。除此之外，游泳一英里带来的有氧益处相当于跑步四英里。

Joints growing stiffer with time? One of the most important reasons for an adult to swim is to increase flexibility, because this sport promotes joint mobility better than any other aerobic exercise. And while swimming’s no fountain of cardiological youth, a 1988 study by cardiologists and exercise physiologists at the University of Texas Health Science Center in Dallas showed that inactive adults improved their heart function significantly within just three months of beginning a swim-training program. Their hearts beat more slowly and powerfully and circulated blood more effectively. Regular swimmers have also been shown to have lower blood pressures, slower pulse rates, and much greater exercise tolerance than other people their age. On top of all this, the aerobic benefits of swimming one mile are equal to those of running four miles.

这些都不重要——毕竟当时我上大学游泳的时候，人们对游泳知之甚少。那时候，游泳训练很简单：上场后吃药。尽可能多地吃药，就能赢得你训练的比赛。游泳本来就应该很疼，否则你就没资格自称竞技游泳选手。而且，当你心跳加速、肌肉酸痛不止的时候，谁还会质疑呢？

None of this mattered—since little of it was known anyway—when I swam in college. Swim training was simple then: You stepped up and took your medicine. Take enough of it as often as possible and you’d win the race you were training for. It was supposed to hurt, or you had no business calling yourself a competitive swimmer. And who could ask questions when your heart was always pounding and your muscles never stopped aching?

但问题来了，它终于在大学毕业后三十多年的教练生涯中出现了。我终于能像教练一样，在泳池边观察其他游泳运动员了。真是大开眼界！我终于意识到，不知何故，出于某种原因，少数有天赋的人他们甚至不用费力呼吸就能游得非常好。事实证明这并非幻觉。在一次私人教练指导下，我惊讶地发现，他们实际上只需相对较少的力气就能游得这么好。显然，正是这种效率，而不是任何非凡的艰苦训练能力，让他们始终领先于竞争对手。

But the time for questions was coming, and it finally started during a thirty-plus-year coaching stint after college. At last, I could watch other swimmers from the pool deck as only a coach can. What an eye-opener! I finally realized that somehow, for some reason, a gifted few were able to swim extremely well without even breathing hard. It turned out to be no illusion. During some personal coaching, I was astounded to find they could, in fact, swim that well with comparatively little effort. And apparently it was that efficiency, not any unusual capacity for grueling work, that kept them consistently ahead of their competitors.

我不禁想，这究竟是天生的天赋，还是可以后天习得的。现在还无法下定论，但迹象已经显现。一次又一次，当我阻止那些水平一般的游泳运动员只顾着刻苦训练，让他们开始进行一些能更好地利用自身力量的训练和练习时，他们就会突然开始进步。

Was this an inbred gift or could it be taught, I wondered. Too soon to know for sure, but the signs were already there. Time after time, average swimmers would suddenly start improving when I stopped them from doing nothing but beating themselves up with hard training and started them on drills and exercises that let them use their existing power better.

说实话，我很享受“欺骗体制”的乐趣。通过教我的运动员比他们的对手更高效，我给了他们优势，让他们能够胜过那些训练时间更长的游泳运动员——所有这些都为我节省了大量的训练时间。说实话：即使是一位敬业的游泳教练，也不会喜欢花无数时间看着别人苦苦挣扎地游上几圈。而当我从训练监督员变成了一名“泳姿老师”时，我就不再需要这么做了。

Truth to tell, I enjoyed “cheating the system.” By teaching my athletes to be more efficient than their rivals, I gave them an edge they could use to outperform swimmers who trained for many more hours—all of which saved me a lot of time on deck. Let’s be honest: Even a dedicated swim coach doesn’t relish countless hours watching people grind out endless laps. And as I became a “stroke teacher” more than a workout monitor, I no longer had to.

1988年，一切开始步入正轨，成功游泳的真正秘诀也逐渐明朗。那一年，我结识了比尔·布默尔（Bill Boomer），之后便辞去了大学教练的工作，专攻成人游泳。布默尔——我在工作坊中频繁提及他，以至于有些营员可能以为自己见过他——是纽约州北部罗切斯特大学的游泳教练。虽然布默尔在美国游泳界名气不大，但他在该地区的其他大学教练中拥有一批狂热的追随者，这些教练的队伍经常与他交手——而且往往赢不了。他关于游泳的想法被认为是激进的，甚至是革命性的，显然值得一听。

Then, in 1988, everything began to fall into place and the real secrets of successful swimming became more obvious. That was the fateful year I met Bill Boomer and subsequently left college coaching to work exclusively with adults. Boomer, whom I refer to so often in my workshops that some campers probably think they’ve met him, was swimming coach at the University of Rochester in upstate New York. Though relatively unknown in the wider world of American swimming, Boomer had a cult following among other college coaches in the region, coaches whose teams regularly faced his—and not often successfully. His ideas about swimming were considered radical, even revolutionary, and obviously worth listening to.

一个难忘的日子，Boomer 在我碰巧参加的教练培训班上发表了演讲。演讲者们滔滔不绝地讲述着他们如何通过“打造引擎和燃料箱”来训练游泳运动员，也就是给他们施加足够的压力，让他们的身体不得不增强耐力。

One memorable day, Boomer addressed a coaches’ clinic I happened to be attending. Speaker after speaker had gone on and on about how they trained their swimmers by “building the engine and fuel tank,” so to speak—throwing enough hard work at them that their bodies had no choice but to build endurance.

然后，Boomer 登上讲台，抛出了重磅炸弹。他提出了一个显而易见的问题，但我参加这类会议二十年来从未听过：“我们怎样才能教会人们以任何速度更轻松地游泳？ ”他的答案同样令人信服，也同样激进：“通过重塑船只。”毕竟，游泳者和船只有很多共同之处，而 Boomer 就像一位造船工程师，知道有办法提高“船体设计”的效率。

Then Boomer took the podium and dropped his bomb. He posed an obvious question, but one I’d never heard in two decades of attending such meetings: “How can we teach people to swim, at any given speed, with less effort?” His answer was just as disarming, and just as radical: “By reshaping the vessel.” After all, swimmers had a lot in common with boats, and like a naval architect Boomer knew there were ways to improve the efficiency of their “hull designs.”

自20世纪70年代初燃油价格暴跌以来，底特律就一直在汽车上进行类似的尝试，但直到Boomer出现之前，没有人想到用同样的方式想象游泳。显然，他的优势在于他拥有新鲜的视角和开放的思维，因为他自己甚至都不是游泳运动员，只是在学校学习运动科学，并担任过足球和田径教练。因此，Boomer在接触游泳时，摆脱了“应该”如何做的惯常包袱，对人体的运动方式有着深刻的理解。这让他能够发现我们其他人忽略的东西。

Detroit had been doing it with cars since the price of fuel shot out of sight in the early 1970s, but no one until Boomer had thought of visualizing swimming the same way. Apparently he simply had the advantage of fresh eyes and an open mind, since he hadn’t even been a swimmer himself, studying movement science in school and coaching soccer and track. So Boomer came to swimming minus the usual baggage of how things “ought” to be done and with a deep understanding of the way the human body moves. That enabled him to see things the rest of us had missed.

Boomer 不用我多说。我立刻就知道他的想法是对的，而且专门与成年人合作给了我一个独特的机会去测试、发展和完善它。我的“全浸式”游泳训练营开始专注于一件美国其他游泳教练从未做过的事情：教授游泳技巧。 而不是提供训练计划。从某种意义上说，我变得更像一个高尔夫或网球专业人士，而不是一个训练计划制定者。

Boomer didn’t have to tell me twice. I knew right away that he was on to something, and working exclusively with adults gave me the unique opportunity to test it, develop it, and refine it. My Total Immersion workshops began concentrating on something no other swim coach in America had ever done: teaching swimming technique instead of giving workouts. In a sense, I was becoming more like a golf or tennis pro than a workout planner.

而我当时专攻的成年游泳运动员正是培养这种能力的理想对象。随着我的训练计划远比“多游几圈”复杂得多，本质上变成了一套精准的技术方案，我必须让年长的游泳运动员也能轻松练习高级技能，因为他们大多缺乏游泳经验，也不了解自己在泳池中真正行动的动力。除非我能找到一种方法，将相对复杂和高级的理念提炼成一系列简单、合乎逻辑、人人都能做到的练习，否则我们谁也做不到。由于我每周都要前往美国各地的游泳池，每次在短短几天内教授一批新学生，所以这个计划必须通俗易懂、快速吸收，并且在我离开后也易于实践。

And the adult swimmers I was already specializing in were the ideal athletes to develop this with. As my training program grew far more sophisticated than just “more laps, more laps” and essentially became a program of precise technique, I had to make advanced skills easy to practice for older swimmers, most of whom had little experience in the sport and little understanding of what really made them move in the pool. None of us would get anywhere unless I figured out a way to distill relatively complex and advanced ideas into a series of simple, logical practice exercises that anyone could do. And since I had to travel to pools all over the United States each week, teaching a new group of students every time in just a few short days, the program had to be easily understood, quickly absorbed, and simple to practice after I was gone.

那是数千名游泳运动员的旧事了。过去几年里，我的学生们也成了我长期实验室的伙伴，他们指出哪些指令太难理解或效果微乎其微，帮助我改进那些最有希望的指令，并始终参与探索更好、更简单、更直接的提高游泳水平的方法。

That was thousands of swimmers ago. Over the last few years my students have also been my partners in a long-running laboratory, making clear which instructions were too hard to understand or produced negligible results, helping me refine the ones that showed the most promise, and always being part of the search for a better, simpler, more direct route to better swimming.

一路走来，我意识到那些常见的“游几圈”建议不仅无效，实际上还可能有害。如果你的游泳姿势让你感到困难，而你又一遍又一遍地练习这种姿势，“跟着黑线走”，那它就不仅仅是坏姿势了，还会变成一个坏习惯。而且，即使你最终决定改掉，也很难改掉。

Along the way, I learned that the usual “swim-your-laps” advice was not only ineffective; it could actually be harmful. If your form is making swimming difficult for you and you practice that form over and over, “following the black line,” it’s going to become more than bad form. It will become a bad habit. A hard-to-break one too, when you finally decide to.

如今，毫无疑问，游泳不能彻底除非我们真正理解游泳的本质，否则它很难被理解，也无法有效地教授：游泳主要是一项像高尔夫、网球甚至滑雪这样的技巧性运动，而不是像跑步或自行车这样的力量型或耐力型运动。更令人难以接受的是，你的技能受躯干或核心部位的位置和移动方式的影响远大于手臂和腿部动作的影响。这真是天方夜谭吗？完全不是。正如你将在本书后面看到的，世界顶尖的游泳科学家在研究世界纪录保持者游泳方式时发现了这一点。

Today, there’s no question that swimming cannot be thoroughly understood nor effectively taught unless it’s seen for what it is: primarily a skill sport like golf, tennis, or even skiing, rather than a power or endurance sport like running or cycling. And harder yet for people to accept is the fact that your skill is far more powerfully influenced by how you position and move your torso, or core, than by what you do with your arms and legs. Fanciful theory? Not at all. As you’ll see later in this book, the world’s top swimming scientists have discovered this to be true as they studied how world record holders swim.

优美高效的划水动作以及由此带来的轻松自如的游泳体验，并非那些幸运儿的专属，他们并非天生拥有，或是倾尽青春期大部分时间去培养这些技能。这些技能是可以学习的。与你仍然听到的许多游泳建议相反，高超的游泳技巧并非一项需要付出巨额代价的资产。

A beautifully efficient stroke and the effortless swimming it makes possible are not prizes reserved for the lucky few who got them as gifts of nature or spent most of their waking adolescent hours grooming them. They can be taught. Contrary to much of the swimming advice you still hear, great technique is not an asset that carries a staggering price.

卢·菲奥莉娜是一位杰出的游泳教练，曾在全浸式游泳工作坊中与我一起执教，现在他明白了这一点。但他并不总是明白这一点。菲奥莉娜记得，几年前，当他看到美国游泳传奇人物罗迪·盖恩斯和特蕾西·考金斯在儿童游泳训练营进行示范时，他心想，他们在泳池里游得如此流畅优雅。你一定是有惊人的天赋才能游得那么好。几个月后，他去了另一家训练营。这一次，比尔·布默正在教一群普通的大学生游泳运动员，菲奥莉娜对正在发生的事情感到震惊。“当我观察时，我看到他们的划水动作开始展现出很多与盖恩斯和考金斯相同的优雅和高雅，我突然意识到这些东西是可以教的，普通游泳者可以像精英运动员一样学习游泳，而且他们可以学得相当快。”

Lou Fiorina, an exceptional teacher who has coached with me at Total Immersion workshops, knows that now. But he didn’t always. Fiorina remembers that when he watched Rowdy Gaines and Tracy Caulkins, both legends of American swimming, putting on a demonstration at a children’s clinic several years ago, he thought, They’re so fluid and graceful moving up and down the pool. You must have to be amazingly gifted to swim like that. Some months later, he went to another clinic. This time Bill Boomer was teaching a group of average college swimmers, and Fiorina was astounded by what was going on. “As I watched, I could see their strokes begin to show a lot of the same grace and elegance [as those of Gaines and Caulkins], and I suddenly realized that this stuff was teachable, that ordinary swimmers could learn to swim like elite athletes, and they could learn it fairly quickly.”

今天，他们在“全浸入式周末工作”中就做了这样的事这些商店采用的正是本书中介绍的原理，任何年龄段的游泳者都能轻松掌握。我见过七八十岁的运动员运用这些原理来提高游泳时间和体能，并获得最佳的锻炼效果——泳池时间的回报翻倍。这些技巧包含在一套简单易学的技能练习中，并被编排成一个自学系统，这套系统与你在其他任何地方都能找到的都不同。即使是精通其他运动但缺乏游泳经验的运动员，也能学会以惊人的效率和优美的姿势游泳。这个计划可以让任何游泳运动员成为自己最好的教练。

Today they are doing just that at Total Immersion Weekend Work shops, using the exact principles you’ll learn in this book, principles that are easily mastered by swimmers of any age. I’ve seen athletes in their seventies and eighties use these principles to improve their swim times and their fitness, and get the best possible workout in the bargain—doubling the payback from their pool time. The techniques are captured in a set of simple-to-learn skill drills, sequenced into a self-taught system different from anything you’ll find anyplace else. Even athletes proficient in other sports but inexperienced as swimmers have learned to swim with an amazing degree of efficiency and beauty. This program can make any swimmer his or her own best coach.

在完全沉浸式泳池中，每一分钟都用于培养正确的游泳技巧，并非刻意练习更多更难的游泳圈，而是专注于更少、更轻松、更有意义的游泳圈——停止浪费时间的“训练”，专注于高效且有效的“练习”。如今，大多数参加完全沉浸式训练营的游泳者已经游了几个月甚至几年，却没有任何进步。我希望我这样说，听起来不像个狂欢节的叫卖者：当他们学习完全沉浸式方法后，他们会感觉更好，游泳水平几乎立刻就提高了。你也可以。

Every minute of Total Immersion pool time is devoted to building proper technique, not by grinding out more and harder laps but by concentrating on fewer, easier, and more purposeful laps—stopping time-wasting “workouts” and focusing on efficient and effective “practice.” Today, most swimmers who come to a Total Immersion workshop have been swimming for months or even years without seeing any progress. I hope I don’t sound like a carnival barker when I tell you that when they learn the Total Immersion method, they begin to feel better and see improvement in their swimming almost immediately. You can too.

训练都去哪儿了？哦，你最终会进行一些速度和耐力训练，但至少在一开始，你的体能是技能提升的自然红利。如果你想提高你的网球水平，你会花40分钟在底线之间来回跑动，调整状态来追球吗？不太可能。你通过练习40到45分钟的击球来提高你的网球水平，随着你水平的提高，你也就拥有了打网球所需的体能。我们在泳池里也做同样的事情，这就是为什么我总是开设全浸式游泳工作坊，我希望这对时间紧迫的游泳者来说是个好消息：“在这里，健身就是在你练习良好的技巧时发生在你身上的事情。”

Where do the workouts go? Oh, you’ll eventually do some speed and stamina training, but in the beginning at least, your fitness is an automatic dividend of skill building. If you want to improve your tennis game, do you spend forty minutes running back and forth between the baselines, getting in shape to chase shots? Not likely. You improve your tennis game by practicing your stroke for forty or forty-five minutes and, as you improve your game, you build the fitness you need to play tennis. We do the same thing in the pool, which is why I always open Total Immersion workshops with what I hope is welcome news to time-starved swimmers: “Here, fitness is something that happens to you while you practice good technique.”

这不仅仅是个好消息，更是一门科学。我们现在知道，虽然身体状况很重要，但它并不像我们所说的那么重要。事实上，世界顶级研究人员估计，冠军游泳运动员的出色表现有 70% 归功于完美的划水技巧，只有 30% 左右归功于他们的体能——在我们制定新的全浸式教练策略时，您会在本书中一次又一次地看到这个统计数据。对于我们其他“非冠军”来说，划水效率甚至更为重要，可能控制着我们 90% 的表现。想一想。一个在 10 分钟内游完四分之一英里的游泳新手，通过让自己变得更好，可能会缩短 5 到 10 秒。但只要学习如何更有效地在水中移动，他就可以缩短 50 到 55 秒，从而获得健康的成绩。

That’s not just good news, it’s good science. We now know that while conditioning matters, it doesn’t matter nearly as much as we’ve been told. In fact, the world’s top researchers estimate that champion swimmers owe about 70 percent of their great performance to perfect stroke mechanics and only around 30 percent to their fitness—a statistic you’ll meet again and again in this book as we develop your new Total Immersion coaching strategy. For the rest of us “nonchamps,” stroke efficiency is even more crucial, controlling perhaps 90 percent of our performance. Think about it. A new swimmer who does a quarter mile in ten minutes might shave five or ten seconds by whipping himself into better shape. But he could lop off a healthy 50 to 55 seconds simply by learning how to move more efficiently through the water.

别误会：一个正确、高效的游泳姿势是生活中最复杂的技能之一，比完美的高尔夫挥杆或完美的网球发球更难掌握。如果没有专家指导，你根本无法达到这种程度。但对于成年人来说，优秀的游泳老师很难找到，他们不会把你淹没在令人眼花缭乱的细节海洋中，教你如何移动手臂的每一寸，以至于你忘记自己最初是在移动哪只手臂。

Make no mistake: A good, efficient swimming stroke is one of life’s more complicated skills, far more difficult to perfect than the ideal golf swing or the picture-perfect tennis serve. You can’t come close without some expert instruction. But good teachers for adults have been hard to find, teachers who don’t drown you in such a baffling sea of detail on how to move your arm every inch of the way that you forget which arm you’re moving in the first place.

更糟糕的是，你的划臂动作实际上对你在水中的移动速度影响非常有限。即使你用一种效率极低的划臂动作，把它练得近乎完美，你的速度也只能勉强提高5%或10%。这是因为水的密度是空气的1000倍，对任何不这样做的人都会产生巨大的阻力。了解滑行技巧。学会通过改善身体姿势来减少阻力，很可能让你在一两天内速度提升20%到30%。在“全浸式”周末工作坊里，这种情况经常发生。

Worse yet, your armstroke actually has a very limited impact on how fast you move through the water. Take a horribly inefficient one and make it nearly perfect, and you might eke out a 5 percent or 10 percent increase in speed. That’s because water is 1,000 times denser than air and throws huge drag forces against anyone who doesn’t know the tricks of becoming slippery. Learning to cut that drag by improving your body position could well give you a 20 percent to 30 percent speed boost in just a day or two. It happens all the time at Total Immersion weekend workshops.

这就是为什么我们“由内而外”地教授游泳，就像本书中教你的那样。首先，我们会教你如何保持身体的平衡、流线型和稳定性。然后，我们会开始训练你的推进系统——但只针对最重要的部分。

That’s why we teach swimming “from the inside out,” just the way you’ll learn it in this book. First, we show you how to get the body balanced, streamlined, and stabilized. Then, we get to work on your propulsion system—but only the parts that matter.

这样就能开启一个充满全新回报的世界。当你的身体恢复正常运作时，游泳本身就是一种乐趣，而不仅仅是一项锻炼或一项竞技运动。当你专注于动作姿势——这正是这个项目的关键——时，你不仅会变得健康高效，还会发现自己内心的专注力得到了提升，就像练习瑜伽或太极拳的人一样。

This way opens a world of new rewards. With your body working as it was meant to, swimming becomes a pleasure all by itself, not just an exercise or a sport to compete in. And when you concentrate on form, which is the key to this program, you will not only become fit and efficient, you’ll also find yourself developing an inner focus, like students of yoga or tai chi.

优雅、速度、技术娴熟、体魄强健，以及内心的平静。等等——这是一本游泳书，还是一项关于人体潜能的运动？你会在接下来的篇幅中找到答案，那就让我们开始吧。我们要讨论的是游泳，你没时间怀疑了。你还有更重要的事情要做。

Grace, speed, technical proficiency, fitness, and peace of mind. Wait a minute—is this a swimming book or a whole human potential movement? You’ll find the answer in the following pages, so let’s get started. It’s swimming we’re going to be talking about, and you’ve no time to be skeptical. You’ve got more important things to do.

2

2

无需增强体力就能游得更好？没错！

Swim Better Without Getting Any Stronger? Yes!

我游泳并不总是那么聪明。事实上，就像大多数大学里参加比赛的人一样，我花了四年时间，却完全做错了——尽管当时没人意识到这是错的。“一分耕耘，一分收获”，我们被警告过。于是，我们一个接一个地忍受着痛苦。有些人取得了成果；但很多人却时不时地感到沮丧。问题很简单：我们努力地去完成错误的事情。直到今天，仍然有太多人让自己陷入这种没有前途的苦差事。

I wasn’t always smart about swimming. In fact, like most everyone who competed in college, I spent four years doing it all wrong—though nobody realized it was wrong back then. No pain, no gain, we were warned. So hour after wearying hour, we put up with the pain. Some of us got results; many of us got more than a little frustrated from time to time. The problem was simple: We were working very hard to accomplish the wrong things. And to this day, too many people are still putting themselves through that dead-end kind of drudgery.

事情是这样的。大一赛季初——那时我还对日常的正式训练还很陌生——我第一次参加了1650码（游泳中所谓的公制英里）的游泳计时赛。我花了大约22分钟。我们联盟的顶尖选手比我快了整整4分钟，所以如果我想在长距离游泳方面有所进步，就必须全力以赴。而我能想到的唯一方法就是加快划水速度——即使在今天，大多数一心想进步的游泳运动员也正是这么想的。手移动得更快，身体游得更快。还有什么比这更简单的呢？再说，也没人会反对。

It happened like this. Early in my freshman season—still a stranger to serious daily training—I was timed for my first 1650-yard swim, swimming’s so-called metric mile. It took me about twenty-two minutes. The top swimmers in our conference were a good four minutes faster, so if I wanted to get anywhere in distance swimming, I had my work cut out for me. And the only way I could figure out to do that was to speed up my stroke—exactly what most improvement-minded swimmers think even today. Hands move faster, body goes faster. What could be simpler? Besides, nobody bothered to disagree.

所以每天下午，我的练习策略都非常简单：尽可能快地挥动手臂，持续尽可能长的时间。我很快就发现，这很容易让人感到疲倦，但我发现，每天这样做，我会习惯的——你知道，教会我的身体嘲笑疲劳。而且这其中也蕴含着某种中世纪的逻辑。每天下午练习赛都要承受两小时240圈的折磨，比赛日感觉轻松多了。不到20分钟，66圈就结束了。真是快如闪电！就算称之为原始的运动心理学，但我毫不怀疑自己做的是对的。

So each afternoon, my practice strategy was as simple as it gets: move the arms as fast as I could for as long as I could. Makes you tired in a hurry, I quickly found out, but I figured that by doing it every day I’d get used to it—you know, teach my body to laugh at fatigue. And there was a certain medieval logic to it anyway. After diving into this punishment for two hours and 240 laps every afternoon in practice, race day felt like a breeze. It was over in under twenty minutes and 66 laps. What a snap! Call it primitive sport psychology, but I hadn’t a doubt in the world I was doing the right thing.

果然，两年之内，我实现了目标：游18分钟，在东部大学锦标赛中取得佳绩。胜利！游完后，我挣扎着从泳池里出来，泳道上的计时员突然喊道：“我从来没见过有人手臂移动得这么快，而且持续这么久！”

And sure enough, within two years I had achieved my goal: swimming 18 minutes, to score in the Eastern Collegiate Championships. Victory! As I dragged myself out of the pool after finishing, the timer in my lane exclaimed, “I’ve never seen anyone move their arms that fast for that long!”

“谢谢，”我低声说道。

“Thanks,” I muttered.

当时我们俩都没有意识到这并不是一句赞美。

Neither of us understood at the time that it was not a compliment.

但我最终还是发现了。因为尽管那时我才认真训练了两年，但我从未游得更快。我的策略已经耗尽了所有潜力。没有别的方法可以让我更快。

But I eventually found out. Because even though at that point I’d been training seriously for only two years. I never swam any faster. I had wrung all the potential out of my strategy. There was noplace else to find more speed.

虽然当时我并没有意识到——我仍然执着地想要找到更努力的方法——但我已经触及了决定游泳速度的最基本规则的极限：V = SL × SR。速度 (V) 是你每次划水的距离（划距或 SL）乘以你每次划水的速度（划频或 SR）。当你开始接近手臂移动速度的上限时，通常只有减少划距才能进一步加快速度。所以这是一场零和游戏。增加一个，同时减少另一个相同的量，你的乘积——速度——就不会改变。更糟糕的是，你会消耗更多的能量，却一无所获。在我经过大学最后两年的努力，我完善了这个令人沮丧的公式。

Though I didn’t realize it at the time—still doggedly determined to find some way to work harder yet—I had crashed into the limits of the most basic rule that governs how you produce swimming speed: V = SL × SR. Velocity (V) is a product of how far you travel on each stroke (stroke length or SL) multiplied by how fast you take each stroke (stroke rate or SR). As you begin to approach the upper limits of how quickly you can move your arms, you can usually speed them up even more only by decreasing your stroke length. So it’s a zero-sum game. Increase one and decrease the other by the same amount and your product—velocity—doesn’t budge. Worse yet, you’re burning up much more energy to achieve nothing. During my final two years of hard work in college, I perfected that frustrating formula.

但这一切即将改变。毕业后的那个夏天，我得到了第一份教练工作。我终于可以在甲板上舒服地分析游泳了，这极大地提升了我的视角，让我能够理解是什么让人们在水中游得更快，而我以前游泳时，在泳池里浑身酸痛，浑身翻腾。从第一天起，我就清楚地意识到：游得最快的人，游泳看起来最容易。

But all that was about to change. The summer after graduation, I took my first coaching job. Finally I could analyze swimming from a comfortable position on the deck, a vastly improved perspective to determine what makes people fast in the water over what I’d had as a swimmer, frothing up and down the pool in a haze of pain. And from day one, it struck me plain as day: The fastest swimmers made it look the easiest.

那些忙碌地搅动着蛋液的家伙们都在较慢的泳道里，艰难地跟在那些似乎漫不经心地来回滑行的人们身后。我难道真的看起来像那些无能的水上“菜刀”吗？毫无疑问。于是，我确定了作为教练的首要任务：防止我的游泳运动员重蹈我的覆辙。我不会简单地强迫他们尽可能地努力，而是要弄清楚是什么让我最优秀的游泳运动员看起来如此轻松，然后把这个方法教给其他人。

The eggbeaters churning busily were all in the slower lanes, struggling in the wake of people who seemed to glide almost casually up and down. Could I have actually looked like those ineffectual water choppers? No doubt. So I staked out my first mission as a coach: to save my swimmers from repeating my mistakes. Instead of simply driving them to work as hard as possible, I would try to figure out what allowed my best swimmers to make it look so easy, then teach it to everyone else.

在接下来的十二年里，我一直凭着这种直觉行事，而且确实有效。后来，在1984年，我们开始寻找原因。在美国奥运会游泳选拔赛上进行的一项研究中，比尔·布默和罗切斯特大学的一些运动科学同事，在六天内拍摄了26个男女项目的所有游泳运动员的每一个游程，总共有700多个世界顶尖运动员的演示，展示了如何像人类一样快速游动。

I operated on that instinct for the next twelve years, and it worked. Then, in 1984, we began to find out why. In a study conducted at the U.S. Olympic Swimming Trials, Bill Boomer and some sports science colleagues from the University of Rochester filmed every length swum by every swimmer in twenty-six men’s and women’s events over six days, a total of more than seven hundred demonstrations by some of the world’s best of how to swim as fast as a human can.

他们反复研究发现，80% 的情况下，游得最快的运动员划水次数最少。这绝非侥幸。四年后，宾夕法尼亚州立大学的研究人员在 1988 年奥运会上进行了一项类似的研究，也得出了同样的结论。游得最快的运动员总是效率最高的。

Over and over, what they found was that 80 percent of the time, the fastest swimmers took the fewest strokes. And it was no fluke. Four years later, a similar study by Penn State researchers at the 1988 Olympics produced the same result. The swiftest swimmers were always the most efficient.

那么，如何才能学得更好更快呢？我们现在找到了答案：划水更长，而不是更快。如今，距离大学时代的失望已经过去了三十年，在今天的练习中，我更在意的是每次划水能游多远，而不是总共游了多少码。也正因如此，当我试图游得更快时，我从不单凭计时钟来评判自己。相反，我还会衡量为了达到那个速度，我需要额外划水多少次。换句话说，我为此付出了多少代价？

So how could anyone learn to swim better and faster? We now had the answer: Work longer, not faster, strokes. In my own practices today, three decades removed from the disappointments of my college days, that’s why I care less about how many yards I total than about how many yards I travel on each stroke. And that’s why I never judge myself just by the pace clock when I’m trying to swim faster. Instead, I also measure how many additional strokes I need to gain that speed. In other words, what’s it costing me?

因此，对于任何想要游得更好更快的人来说，首要目标就是划水更长。这可以通过两种方式实现：(1) 加大推力——用你的手和脚，让每一次划水都尽可能有力，将身体推得更远；(2) 减少阻力——调整你的身体姿势，使其更无摩擦，让你每次划水都能利用已有的力量游得更远。

So goal one for anyone who wants to swim better and faster is a longer stroke. This can happen in two ways: (1) more push—using your hands and feet to thrust your body farther through the water by making each stroke as powerful as possible; and (2) less drag—shaping your body so it’s more friction-free, allowing it to travel farther with the power each of your strokes is already producing.

当然，在水中，你的本能“知道”该怎么做。划水更用力，打腿更用力，手臂旋转得更快。当然，这些都是错的。我就是这样浪费了四年大学游泳生涯的。可惜的是，当时我并不知道二十五年的执教经历教会了我世界顶尖游泳运动员究竟是如何产生速度的。速度的提升主要源于他们如何巧妙地调整身体姿势，以消除阻力，使身体变得更“滑”，而较少源于他们如何运用手和手臂推动水流。

Of course, in the water your instincts “know” just what to do. Pull harder, kick harder, spin your arms faster. All wrong, of course. That’s how I squandered four years of college swimming. Too bad I didn’t know then what twenty-five years of coaching has taught me about how the world’s best swimmers actually produce their speed. Most of it comes from how well they shape and position their bodies to eliminate drag and become more “slippery”—relatively little from how they use their hands and arms to push the water around.

一位自由泳运动员以世界纪录的速度冲刺，需要消耗超过一千瓦的电力，才能以区区5英里/小时的速度在泳池里“飞驰”。然而，鱼类的速度却达到了68英里/小时——与猎豹奔跑的速度一样快——而且能量消耗却少得惊人。根据佐治亚理工学院物理学教授文森特·马莱特的计算，一头100吨重的蓝鲸，以20英里/小时的速度巡航，大约需要448马力，但在事实上，海豚消耗的能量还不到 70 瓦。海豚消耗的能量也只是简单物理学所说的八分之一。

A freestyler sprinting at world-record pace puts out over a thousand watts of power to “streak” down the pool at a paltry 5 mph. Yet fish have been clocked at 68 mph—as fast as a cheetah can run—with amazingly little energy expenditure. A 100-ton blue whale, cruising at 20 mph, should require some 448 horsepower, according to the calculations of Georgia Tech physics professor Vincent Mallette, but in fact gets by with fewer than 70. A dolphin also uses only about one eighth the power that simple physics says it should.

人类已经适应了陆地生活数百万年，但当试图在密度比空气大 1000 倍的物质中推动自己时，却显得笨拙。每一个动作都需要消耗大量的能量。在水中速度要提高一倍，需要输出八倍的能量。游泳速度要提高 10%，需要增加 33% 的能量。在水中，阻力就是一切。主动流线型——避免水的阻力——是海洋哺乳动物的秘诀。而通过塑造和定位流畅的身体，而不是试图用力划水，是人类变得更像鱼的最简单方法。事实上，运动机能学家估计，你的游泳成绩至少 70% 取决于你的流线型程度，只有 30% 取决于你的体能或力量。

The human being, land-adapted for millions of years, struggles awkwardly when trying to propel himself through a substance 1,000 times denser than air. Every movement is bought at an extravagant cost in energy. To double speed in the water requires eight times as much power output. To swim but 10 percent faster requires a 33 percent increase in power. In the water, drag is everything. Active streamlining— avoiding water’s drag—is the marine mammal’s secret. And that, by shaping and positioning the body sleekly, rather than trying to pull powerfully, is the easiest way for humans to become more fishlike. In fact, kinesiologists estimate at least 70 percent of your swimming performance is determined by how well you streamline your body and only 30 percent by how fit or powerful you are.

所以现在我们可以开始让游泳速度公式 V = S × SR 为我们服务，而不是阻碍我们。首先，你必须学会如何调整身体姿势，让它在每次划水时尽可能地移动（SL）；然后，你必须保持足够的体能，以便以更高的划水频率（SR）进行划水。但不要太快。

So now we can begin to make that swimming-speed formula, V = S × SR, work for us instead of against us. First, you have to learn how to position your body so it moves as far as it possibly can with each stroke (SL); then you have to get fit enough to take those strokes at a higher rate (SR). But not too high.

我见过的几乎每个游泳运动员都已经拥有了他们所需的所有 SR，他们缺少的是 SL。他们总是在放弃一些 SR 来获得大量 SL 时取得最显著的进步。所以我总是建议游泳运动员先练习 SL。此外，能量消耗会随着肌肉运动速度的立方而增加，所以划水速度加倍会消耗八倍的能量。这可不是一笔好投资。

Virtually every swimmer I see already has all the SR they’ll ever need; it’s the SL they’re lacking. They always make their most dramatic improvements when they give up a bit of their SR in order to gain a lot of SL. So I always counsel swimmers to work on their SL first. Besides, energy consumption increases as a cube of muscle movement speed, so stroking twice as fast burns eight times as much energy. Not a great return on your investment.

我在大学游泳四年里一直努力提高速度，忽略了速度。难怪我的速度会遇到瓶颈。速度会随着你动动脑子。只有锻炼肌肉才能提高游泳速度，所以它的提升是短期的，肯定不可能永远持续下去。如果你不仅想游得好，还希望一辈子都游得好，那就看看你的平衡表吧。然后告诉我，你更愿意在游泳速度方程式的哪一部分上下功夫：

I spent four years of college swimming trying to maximize SR and ignoring SL. No wonder I hit a speed ceiling. SL goes up when you use your brain. SR can only improve when you work on brawn, so its improvements are short-term and certainly can’t go on forever. If you not only want to swim well but expect to do it for a lifetime, just look at the balance sheet. Then tell me which part of the swimming-speed equation you’d rather work on:

SL 注重技巧。通过改善身体姿势或轮廓，你可以获得进步。

SL is skill-oriented. You get better by improving your body’s position or profile.

SR 以训练为导向。你必须努力锻炼肌肉和能量系统，才能让肢体快速移动。

SR is training-oriented. You have to work hard to build up your muscles and energy systems to make those limbs move fast.

SL 的提升依赖于脑力。你需要运用知识、身体意识和专注力，在水中保持流畅、高效的姿势。这是神经系统训练，而非有氧系统训练。能量消耗极小。

SL improvements depend on brain-power. You use your knowledge, body awareness, and concentration to maintain sleek, efficient positions in the water. That’s nervous system—instead of aerobic system—training. The energy cost is minimal.

SR 的改善取决于你的心脏和肺部更加卖力地工作。

SR improvements depend on working your heart and lungs harder— much harder.

SL 可以在任何年龄提高。没有“太老”之说，因为它以技能为导向，而且我们学习或提高 SL 的能力即使在 70 多岁时仍然保持敏锐，这使得聪明的游泳者即使在中年甚至更晚的时候也能很好地提高速度。

SL can be improved at any age. There’s no such thing as “too old,” because it’s skill-oriented, and our ability to learn or improve SL remains acute far into our seventies, allowing smart swimmers to gain speed well into middle age and beyond.

SR 受年龄限制。最终，你的肌肉将无法再快速移动。高 SR 所需的能量来自你的有氧能力——即肌肉产生能量时燃烧的氧气总量——通常在 40 岁左右达到峰值。这意味着你提升 SR 峰值的能力也随之下降。

SR is age-limited. Eventually, your muscles just won’t move any faster. The fuel for a high SR is provided by your aerobic capacity—the total amount of oxygen your muscles can burn to produce energy—which usually peaks at about age forty. That means your ability to increase your SR peaks too.

SL 的提升是永久性的。技能一旦学会，就会永久地铭刻在我们的“肌肉记忆”中。投入时间和精力来提升你的 SL，即使你停止训练，也不会失去它。

SL improvements are permanent. Skills, once learned, become permanently imprinted in our “muscle memory.” Invest time and effort in improving your SL and you won’t lose it when you take a break from training.

SR 的提升是暂时的。它需要体能，而体能是短暂的，任何一个不得不停止锻炼几周的人都会明白这一点。稍有不慎，你就会回到原点，被迫重新开始训练来重建体能。

SR improvements are temporary. They demand fitness and fitness is transient, as anyone who’s had to quit working out for a couple of weeks can tell you. Stay away just a little too long and you’re right back where you started, forced to do the work all over again to rebuild that capacity.

世界上最优秀、最聪明的精英游泳运动员会尝试通过分担差异，以最小的努力获得更大的速度提升。如果你的划水距离增加，但频率保持不变，你就会游得更快。如果你的划水频率增加，并且划水距离保持不变，你也会游得更快。但如果两者都略微增加，你就会游得更快。他们首先建立起SL（体长），然后尝试逐渐增加SR（速度），从而放弃尽可能少的SL（体长）。这是一种微妙的权衡，也是最成功的游泳运动员坚持不懈地实践的。

The best—and smartest—of the world’s elite swimmers try to eke out further speed increases with the least effort by splitting the difference. If your stroke gets longer but the rate stays the same, you will swim faster. If your stroke rate goes up and you manage to keep the length the same, you will also swim faster. But if you increase both by just a little bit, you will swim much faster. They establish SL first, then try to gradually increase SR, giving up the least possible SL in return. It’s a delicate trade-off and one that the most successful swimmers practice unrelentingly.

让我们回到我之前提到的那个速度统计数据：提升划水长度的70%来自于减少水对身体的阻力。这不仅是事实，更是伟大游泳运动员如何让他们惊人的速度看起来如此优雅和轻松的关键。这并非幻觉。相对而言，他们确实毫不费力。而学习在每次划水后尽可能地滑行是他们掌握的最强大的技能。因此，我们显然应该在游泳时投入大部分时间和精力，以提高“消除阻力”的能力。

Let’s go back to that little speed statistic I mentioned earlier, the one about 70 percent of your ability to improve your stroke length coming from eliminating more of the water’s drag on your body. It’s not only true, it’s the key to how great swimmers make their remarkable speeds look so graceful and effortless. That’s no illusion. Relatively speaking, they are effortless. And learning to glide as far as possible after each stroke is the single most powerful skill they know. So we clearly want to devote the majority of our time and effort to becoming better “eliminators” when we swim.

这是一个由两部分组成的策略。首先，在速度曲线的平均速度线以下进行游戏（见图）。你可能没有意识到，但你的身体并不是以恒定的游泳速度移动的。在每个划水周期中，你都会像驾驶员轻轻踩下和松开油门一样加速和减速。当你开始划水时，手臂和肩膀的位置几乎没有杠杆作用或力量。将手臂进一步拉向身体下方，靠近臀部，你的手臂就会移动到一个更有效的位置，在这个位置上，强大的躯干肌肉开始发挥作用。你的速度就会加快。然后，当你完成划水并将手划出水面时，你的速度再次开始下降。并且你会继续减速，直到你的另一只手开始下一个周期。

It’s a two-part strategy. First, play the game below the average speed line on your velocity curve (see illustration). Though you probably don’t realize it, your body doesn’t move at a constant swimming speed. During every stroke cycle, you accelerate and decelerate like a driver gently pressing and releasing the gas pedal. As you begin your stroke, the position of your arm and shoulder offers little leverage or power. Pull farther under your body toward your hips, and your arm moves into a much more effective position, one where the powerful torso muscles begin to help out. Up goes your speed. Then, as you finish the stroke and slice your hand out of the water, you begin to lose speed again. And you’ll continue losing it until your other hand starts the next cycle.

大多数人为了游得更快，会用力划水、踢腿，或者更快地转动手臂。他们试图把速度曲线的顶端推得更高一些，然后再往下掉。这很浪费。但如果他们改用曲线的另一部分，就能更快、更轻松地到达目的地。

Most people strain to swim faster by pulling or kicking harder or turning their arms over faster. They’re trying to push the top of that speed curve a little higher before it slopes back down on the other side. Very wasteful. But if they worked on another part of the curve instead, they’d get where they’re going faster and with much less exertion.

当然，真正的游泳速度并非曲线的顶点，而是曲线中峰谷之间的那条线——也就是你每个划水周期中，最快和最慢进度的平均值。水对你身体产生的阻力，部分取决于你的移动速度，而速度曲线顶点的阻力远高于底端。所以，如果你试图在曲线顶点加速，你就会撞上一堵墙。但在曲线底端，速度提升的阻力要小得多，因此这是一个更明智的加速点。

True swimming speed, of course, is not the top of the curve at all but the line that runs through the curve midway between the peaks and valleys—the average of your fastest and slowest progress during each stroke cycle. The amount of drag the water throws against your body is determined, in part, by how fast you’re moving, and drag is much higher at the top of the velocity curve than at the bottom. So if you try to gain speed at the top of the curve, you bang up against a figurative brick wall. But there’s far less resistance to speed improvement at the bottom, making it a smarter place to get faster.

这就是为什么划水间隙的动作实际上比划水动作更重要。看图。你的身体哪里移动最慢，哪里恰恰是你最容易加速的地方？没错，就是在恢复过程中。所以在恢复过程中保持身体伸展、平衡和流畅，你的表现提升速度会比你现在用手做的任何动作都要快得多。

That’s why what you do between strokes is actually more important than how you take the stroke. Look at the illustration. Where is your body moving slowest, which is just where you can most easily add speed? Right. During the recovery. So keep your body long, balanced, and sleek during the recovery, and you’ll boost performance far faster than anything you can do at the moment with your hand.

对于那些从小就被告知用力划水和快速踢腿才能提高游泳速度的人来说，这是一个令人欣喜的消息，而且非常出乎意料。当我在我的“全浸式”成人游泳训练营里向游泳者们透露这个事实时，他们意识到，我们在那里学到的东西，就像我们将在这本书中学到的那样，是对传统游泳观念的挑战。它彻底颠覆了人们对“完美游泳”的普遍理解。优秀的游泳者之所以移动速度快，划水次数少，不仅仅是因为他们划水力量强大，还因为他们的身体在每次划水后，都会持续很长时间——快速地——向前划动。

It’s welcome—and extremely unexpected—news to people who all their lives have been told that pulling and kicking harder and faster is the way to gain swimming speed. When I spring this fact on swimmers at my Total Immersion adult swim camps, they realize that what we’ll be learning there, just as we’ll learn in this book, is an assault on the conventional wisdom of swimming. It does nothing less than turn upside down and inside out the common understanding of what good swimming is all about. Great swimmers move so fast and take so few strokes not simply because they stroke powerfully but because their bodies keep slicing forward—quickly—for a long time after each one.

无论你是准备参加奥运会，还是仅仅为了参加Y级比赛，这项能力都是每个人都可以提升的。你可能划水动作完美，但仍然划水过多，因为你的身体每次划水后都会突然停下来。你别无选择，只能继续转动手臂，因为你没有保存自己创造的动量。

And it’s an ability all of you can improve, whether you’re headed for the Olympics or just for the Y. You may have a perfectly fine stroke and still take too many, because your body lurches too abruptly to a halt after each one. You have no choice but to keep those arms turning over because you don’t conserve the momentum you do create.

你需要学习一些技巧，让你更滑溜。这些技巧对钓鱼来说很自然，但我们其他人一旦了解了它们的含义，也能学会。读完下一章，你就能学会了。

You need to learn a few tricks that will make you more slippery. They come naturally to fish, but the rest of us can pick them up too, once we know what they are. By the end of the next chapter, you will.

3

3

滑溜溜的游泳者

The Slippery Swimmer

阻力——在力量训练室里，它恰好是你需要的，但在其他运动中，它却会成为你的阻碍。如果你曾经在30英里/小时的逆风中艰难骑行，你就会明白锥形头盔、空气动力车把，甚至空气动力学水壶的发明初衷：就是让你尽可能地紧凑、顺滑。空气推动的表面积越小，你就越容易移动。

Resistance—it’s just what you want in the weight room, but it gets in your way in other sports. If you’ve ever struggled to bicycle straight into a 30-mph headwind, you know why tapered helmets, Aerobars, even aerodynamic water bottles, were invented: to make you as compact and slippery as possible. The less surface area the air has to push on, the easier you move.

游泳时，你穿过的介质密度是空气的1000倍！因此，虽然在游泳时，由于速度较慢，尽可能保持流线型的必要性可能不那么明显，但这实际上更为重要。所有高效的游泳者——也就是几乎所有游得快的游泳者——似乎都更本能地知道如何保持身体处于最佳位置，以便在水中轻松滑行，用尽可能小的力气滑行尽可能远。

And in swimming you move through a medium that’s 1,000 times denser than air! So while the need to become as streamlined as possible in swimming may be less evident because of the slower speeds you attain, it’s actually more important. All efficient swimmers—which means nearly all the fast ones—seem to have a more instinctive sense of how to keep their bodies in the best position for slipping easily through the water, gliding as far as possible with the least possible effort.

我采访了科罗拉多斯普林斯国际水生研究中心主任里克·夏普博士。他告诉我，他实验室的研究得出了一个令人惊讶的结果，甚至让一些世界顶尖的游泳研究人员大开眼界。“我们发现，最快的游泳运动员产生的推进力通常比亚精英游泳运动员要小，”夏普解释说。“显然，他们能够产生更大的推进力，但他们不需要它来提高速度。”换句话说，他们游得更快，并非因为他们划水的力量并非源于身体的滑溜，而是源于他们身体的光滑程度。对于这些顶尖游泳运动员来说，学习如何达到这种效率水平是一个不断尝试的过程，但任何人都能做到这一点的“秘诀”却早已流传……好吧，是永远。

I talked with Rick Sharp, Ph.D., the director of the International Center for Aquatic Research in Colorado Springs. He told me that his lab’s research had turned up a surprising result, one that proved eye-opening to even some of the world’s top swimming researchers. “We’ve discovered that the fastest swimmers generally produce less propulsive force than sub-elite swimmers,” Sharp explained. “Obviously they’re capable of producing more propulsive force, but they don’t need it to go fast.” In other words, they’re faster not because of how powerfully they stroke but because of how slippery they make their bodies. For these elite swimmers, learning how to achieve this level of efficiency was a trial-and-error process, but the “secrets” of how anyone can do it have been around for …well, forever.

这让很多人感到惊讶，他们告诉我，他们终于来参加我的工作坊是因为“我需要学习新技术。我从五十年代开始游泳，从那时起，游泳的姿势都变了。” 所以，当我告诉他们，良好的游泳姿势不像裙摆长度或领带宽度那样——每次出现新的“发现”时，都会受到今天时尚和明天过时的影响时，他们感到很惊喜。高效游泳的原则永远不会过时，因为它们基于永恒的物理定律，基于你的身体如何与水互动。

That surprises a lot of people who tell me they’ve finally come to one of my workshops because “I need to learn the new techniques. I started swimming back in the fifties and the strokes have all changed since then.” So it comes as a nice surprise when I tell them that good swimming form is not like hemline lengths or tie widths—subject to today’s fashion and tomorrow’s obsolescence every time a new “discovery” comes along. There are principles of efficient swimming that can’t go out of fashion because they’re based on the permanent laws of physics, on how your body will always interact with the water.

对某些人来说，可能觉得新鲜的是，这些原则直到现在才真正被明确教授过，尽管很久以前，船舶工程师们就发现了它们，当时他们必须找到设计史上速度最快、最易驾驶的船舶的方法。这些航海科学家做了所有的工作。今天，我们所要做的就是潜入水中，运用他们的发现。当这些发现应用于人类而非海军舰艇时，可以归结为三个加速航行的基本规则：

What probably seems new to some people is that, remarkably, these principles have never really been explicitly taught until now, even though they were discovered long ago by naval architects who had to find ways to design the fastest and most easily driven ships of all time. These nautical scientists did all the work. Today, all we have to do is get into the pool and use what they found out, which, when applied to human rather than naval vessels, comes down to three cardinal rules for going faster:

 

 

1. 在水中保持身体平衡。

1. Balance your body in the water.

2.让你的身体变得更长。

2. Make your body longer.

3. 侧身游泳。

3. Swim on your side.

这些方法听起来很费解，但效果却非常好。

They sound like contortions. But they work like a charm.

更好的平衡：最大的节能方法

Better Balance: The Biggest Energy Saver of All

每当有游泳爱好者来找我抱怨她需要练出更强的踢腿能力时，我都会想起不久前我第一次练习直排轮滑时的感受。和成千上万的人一样，我开始练习“滑轮”，是因为它看起来是一种非常有趣的户外有氧运动。结果发现一点也不好玩，至少第一次的时候不是。

Whenever a swimmer comes to me complaining that she needs to develop a stronger kick, I recall what I learned my first day on in-line skates not long ago. Like thousands of other people, I took up “blading” because it looked like a really fun way to get an outdoor aerobic workout. It turned out to be no fun at all, at least not the first time.

大概十五分钟后，我不得不转身，困惑地挣扎着回家。腰部隐隐作痛，让我很不舒服，不得不停下来。真奇怪，我心想。我的腿在做所有的工作。

After maybe fifteen minutes, I had to turn around and struggle home, confused. A dull ache in my lower back was bothering me so much I had to quit. That’s odd, I thought. My legs are doing all the work.

我决心坚持这项“艰难”的新训练，每次都增加距离，直到我把那些松弛的背部肌肉——我猜是轮滑肌肉——锻炼出来。但下次我穿上溜冰鞋时，我发现导致我疲劳的不是肌肉无力，而是姿势不正确。我注意到，有些溜冰者像糖浆一样流畅，他们的速度似乎来自毫不费力的左右摇摆。其他人则蹒跚而行，推力断断续续，吃力。从远处看，我突然意识到差异不是背部或腿部肌肉的力量，而是重心的转移。优秀的溜冰者知道何时以及如何将重心从一只脚转移到另一只脚。

I resolved to keep plugging away at this “tough” new workout, adding more distance to each session until I’d whipped those flabby back muscles—Rollerblading muscles, I presumed—into shape. But the next time I laced on my skates, I found out it wasn’t weak muscles but poor form that caused my fatigue. Some skaters, I noticed, flowed along like syrup, their speed seeming to come from effortlessly swaying side to side. Others lurched along with choppy, labored thrusts. From a distance, I suddenly realized the difference was not back or leg muscle strength but weight shift. The good ones knew just when and how to transfer their weight from one foot to the other.

一个滑得流畅的滑冰者会把全身的重量都压在左脚上，然后在恰当的时机，把重心全部转移到右脚上。像所有其他滑冰姿势摇摆不定的滑冰者一样，我当时并没有掌握这个技巧。我那200磅的体重会摇摇晃晃地超出重心，疲惫的背部肌肉必须把我拉回来，我才能摔倒了。当然，最终它们会变得足够强壮，足以胜任这项任务，但到那时，我只不过变成了一个强壮的、糟糕的滑冰运动员，而不是一个糟糕的滑冰运动员。学习平衡更明智。

A smooth skater would lean all his weight on the left skate and then, at just the right moment, shift it all over to the right. Like all other lurching skaters, I hadn’t caught on to this technique. My two-hundred-pound bulk would teeter out way too far beyond my center of gravity, and those weary back muscles would have to snatch me back before I fell. Eventually, of course, they would have grown strong enough for the job, but by then I’d merely have turned into a strong, bad skater instead of simply a bad one. Smarter to learn balance.

许多沮丧的游泳者都会犯同样的错误。他们知道自己的臀部和腿部在水面以下很深的地方被拖拽着，如果幸运的话，他们还会明白这不仅是最常见的游泳缺陷，也是最严重的缺陷：它比其他任何事情都更快地消耗他们的能量。所以他们抓起一块浮板，开始苦苦地游上几圈，希望能增强他们“有问题”的腿的力量。

Many frustrated swimmers make the same mistake. They know their hips and legs are dragging along far below the surface, and if they’re lucky they also understand it’s not only the most common stroke flaw but the most serious as well: It saps their energy faster than anything else can. So they grab a kickboard and grimly start churning out the endless laps they hope will strengthen their “problem” legs.

只是他们的腿不是问题。

Only their legs aren’t the problem.

这是因为，阻碍他们游得更好的并非糟糕的打腿，而是平衡能力差，就像我那天在桨板上发现的那样。但在泳池里，这个问题几乎可以当场纠正。一旦纠正过来，这些游泳者就会欣喜地发现，“打腿无力”不再是问题。事实上，只要保持平衡，他们几乎根本不需要打腿！

That’s because a poor kick isn’t what’s keeping them from swimming better. It’s poor balance, just as I found that day on my blades. But in the pool it can be corrected practically on the spot. And when it is, these swimmers happily discover that a “weak kick” is no longer a problem. In fact, properly balanced, they hardly have to kick at all!

但在水中保持平衡并非天生，而是我们通过练习习得的。你看，人体的设计初衷并非为了在水中有效漂浮。从进化的角度来说，我们天生就适合在陆地上活动，因为长腿和较低的重心完美地保障了我们的稳定性和灵活性。腰部以上，我们大部分都是体积大的；毕竟，肺就像个大风箱。这意味着我们的浮力在腋窝之间最大，而下半身则像石头一样。我们较长、较重的一端想要下沉，这很自然。

But proper balance in the water is not a gift of nature. It’s something we earn through practice. The human body, you see, simply wasn’t designed to float efficiently in the water. Evolutionarily speaking, we’re put together to function well on land, where our long legs and low center of gravity are perfect for stability and mobility. Above the waist, we’re mostly volume; the lungs, after all, are just big bellows. That means we’re most buoyant between the armpits, rocklike lower down. It’s only natural that our longer, heavier end wants to sink.

为了弥补自然形成的缺陷而拼命扭动双腿会让你精疲力竭。更糟糕的是，这对平衡不平衡毫无作用这会让你的速度变慢。顺便说一句，这绝对是导致铁人三项成绩不佳的最主要原因，当你从水里出来，面对接下来的自行车骑行和跑步时，你最不想遇到的就是腿部肌肉疲惫不堪。

Churning your legs hard to compensate for the way nature put you together will wear you out. Worse, it’s useless against the imbalance that’s slowing you down. And it’s the surest path to a poor triathlon, by the way, where the last thing you want coming out of the water— facing a bike ride and a run after that—is pooped leg muscles.

你真正需要的是一种更好的方法，让臀部回到它们应该在的位置。

What you really need is a better way of getting those hips up where they belong.

有一个方法。我称之为“按压浮标”。具体操作如下。

And there is one. I call it “pressing your buoy.” Here’s how it works.

如果你把一个沙滩球推入水中会发生什么？没错。水会把它推回去。你身上有一个地方有这样的浮力——腋窝之间的空间。就叫它浮标吧。

What happens if you push a beach ball into the water? Right. The water pushes it right back out. You have one place on your body that’s buoyant like that—the space between your armpits. Call it your buoy.

把浮标压入水中，水会反压你。但持续对浮标施压，反而会迫使水把你的臀部向上推。这正是你想要的。直接让水压把你的臀部推到水面，比用腿搅动来支撑臀部要省力得多。

Press your buoy into the water and the water will press back. But keep pressure on that buoy and you force the water to push your hips up instead. Just what you want. Simply letting water pressure ease them to the surface takes far less energy than trying to prop them up by churning away with your legs.

你可以利用头部的重量作为平衡物来帮助自己。记住，在水中，你的身体就像一把不平衡的跷跷板，它的支点位于腰部和胸骨之间。较长较重的一端容易下沉。但是利用另一端的重量，它就能很好地保持平衡。你可以通过表现得好像一根钢棒从腰部穿过头顶来做到这一点。保持这种“连接”完整，就能帮助你的臀部浮出水面。破坏这种连接——比如抬起头来换气，而不是随着身体转动而转动头部——重力就会把你的臀部和腿拉回水中。

And you can help yourself by using the weight of your head like a counterweight. Remember, your body in water is like an unbalanced seesaw, its fulcrum somewhere between your waist and your breast-bone. The longer, heavier end wants to sink. But use the weight at the opposite end and it levels off nicely. You do that by acting as though a steel rod ran from your waist through the top of your head. Keep that “connection” intact and you help your hips pop to the surface. Break the connection—lifting your head to breathe instead of turning it with your body roll, for example—and gravity will drag your hips and legs right back down again.

稍后，在第 8 章中，你将学习简单的按压浮标练习，让这一切自动化。你还将开始“游泳”下坡”，同时用力将身体靠在胸前。只需稍加练习，你就会发现，游泳时按压浮标，可以让水更多地支撑你下半身的重量。你突然变得轻盈的臀部和腿部将毫不费力地在水面上轻盈地游动。你会感觉自己仿佛在下坡游动。

Later on, in chapter 8, you’re going to learn the simple pressing-your-buoy drill that makes all this automatic. You’ll also start “swimming downhill,” leaning on your chest as you go. With just a little practice, you’ll discover that by pressing your buoy as you swim, you can make the water support more of your lower body’s weight. Your suddenly lighter hips and legs will be effortlessly skimming the surface just where they belong. You’ll actually feel as if you’re swimming downhill.

下图说明了当您的身体不均匀下沉、臀部和腿部拖动时，以及当您通过按压浮标均匀保持平衡时发生的情况之间的区别。

The illustration below illustrates the difference between what your body looks like when it sinks unevenly, hips and legs dragging, and what happens when you balance evenly by pressing your buoy.

我不保证每个人都能轻松做到。我们当中浮力较弱的人（通常是那些异常精瘦的铁人三项运动员和跑步运动员）会发现，把臀部完全抬起来会比较困难。如果你也是其中之一，即使你的身体离水面只有一两英寸也不用担心。你不是想像软木塞一样漂浮。你是想让你的上半身和下半身几乎与水面水平，臀部和腿部尽可能靠近水面。做到这一点，你的阻力就会大大减少。减少阻力，看看你的速度会发生什么变化。

I don’t promise it will come easily for everyone. The less buoyant among us (usually those uncommonly lean triathletes and runners) find it a little tougher to get their hips all the way up. If you’re among them, don’t worry if your body rests an inch or two below the surface. You are not trying to float like a cork. You are trying to get your upper and lower body lined up nearly horizontal to the surface, with your hips and legs as close to it as possible. Do that and you’ll cut drag enormously. Reduce drag and watch what happens to your speed.

大多数游泳者学习平衡训练后最显著的益处并非速度的惊人提升，而是在水中感觉更加放松。一旦他们意识到按压浮标可以让水支撑更多身体重量，游泳就会变得轻松许多。而一个放松的游泳者还能做出意想不到的事情。我的一位学生，来自新泽西州的52岁唐·沃尔什，在放松状态下游泳非常熟练，在9个小时完成环曼哈顿游泳后，他回忆道：“我整个过程都感觉很好，一点也不累。”

The most prominent benefit most swimmers will feel from learning balance isn’t necessarily a stunning increase in speed. They’ll be more likely to just feel more relaxed in the water. Once they realize that pressing the buoy causes the water to support more of their body weight, swimming becomes much less laborious. And a relaxed swimmer can do surprising things. One of my students, fifty-two-year-old Don Walsh from New Jersey, became so adept at swimming relaxed that after completing the Swim Around Manhattan in nine hours, he related, “I felt good the whole way and was never tired during the entire swim.”

船越长，速度越快。船体也越长。

Longer Boats Are Faster. Longer Bodies Are Too.

当我还是教练行业的新手时，我很幸运地拥有两位非常有天赋的游泳运动员，而且他们足够聪明，意识到我能从他们身上学到的东西比他们能从我身上学到的更多。我注意到的第一件事是，无论他们游得多快，看起来都毫不费力。这并不奇怪——我以前在优秀的游泳运动员身上也观察到过这种情况——但为什么他们在水里看起来也比其他人更高呢？

When I was still pretty green at the coaching business, I was lucky enough to have two very gifted swimmers on my team and smart enough to realize I could learn more from them than they could from me. The first thing I noticed was that no matter how fast they swam, they made it look relatively effortless. That didn’t come as such a surprise—I’d observed this in accomplished swimmers before— but why did they also somehow look taller in the water than everyone else?

这些年来，我注意到，最优秀的游泳运动员总是如此。这与他们的实际身高几乎没有关系。一个身高只有5英尺10英寸（约1.75米）的游泳高手在水中看起来比一个身高6英尺2英寸（约1.93米）的游泳新手更高，这并非幻觉。更优秀的游泳运动员确实“游得更高”——这是任何人都可以学会的——正因为如此，他们游得更快。这是一个多世纪以来，船舶工程师们一直用来设计快速船舶的基本原则之一。

The best swimmers, I’ve noticed over the years, always do. And it has little to do with their actual height. A skilled swimmer who is only 5'10" looks taller in the water than an unpolished swimmer who is 6'2", and it’s no illusion. Better swimmers do “swim taller”—something anyone can learn—and because they do, they go faster. It’s one of the fundamental principles naval architects have been using for over a century to design fast ships.

19世纪30年代，快速帆船的拥有者们掀起了一股热潮，想要打破最快横渡海洋的纪录。当时的船只只有帆为了获得动力，仅仅安装更大的发动机是不够的，因此更高的速度必须通过更好的船体设计来实现。英国的船舶工程师W. Froude在水箱中测试了各种船型，以找出哪种设计能产生最快的速度。他的关键发现是，在其他所有条件相同的情况下，船舶的阻力会随着其吃水线长度的增加而减小。换句话说：船越长，速度就越快，也越容易。时至今日，他的计算结果（被称为弗劳德数）仍被用来预测各种船舶设计的潜在速度。

In the 1830s, a fever broke out among clipper ship owners to shatter the record for the fastest ocean crossings. The boats had only sails for power and couldn’t simply install bigger engines, so more speed had to come from better hull design. W. Froude, a naval architect in England, tested various vessel shapes in a tank to learn which would produce the fastest design. His key discovery was that, all other things being equal, a vessel’s drag decreases as its length at the waterline increases. Translation: Longer boats go faster—and easier. To this day, his calculations, known as Froude numbers, are used to predict the potential speed of various vessel designs.

适用于快速帆船的规律也适用于你。用船舶设计术语来说，你的身体——以及赛艇、赛艇或独木舟——是一个“穿透表面的运动体”，受许多相同规律的约束。如果更长的船能跑得更快，那么更高的游泳运动员也能跑得更快。而更高的游泳运动员确实如此。在游泳的顶级短跑项目——100米自由泳中，世界上游得最快的男子平均身高约为6英尺6英寸（约1.9米）。

What applies to clipper ships applies to you. In the vernacular of naval architecture, your body—along with racing yachts, rowing shells, or canoes—is a “surface-penetrating moving body” subject to many of the same laws. If a longer vessel can go faster, a taller swimmer can too. And taller swimmers do. In the 100-meter freestyle, swimming’s premier sprint event, the fastest men in the world average about 6'6".

无论身高多少，总有办法让你游得更高。学习这些方法很重要，因为它们能让你掌握强大的数学知识。假设一个身高六英尺（约1.83米）的人，25分钟就能游完一英里。给他喂点生长激素，他就能长到九英尺（约2.73米）。他不需要再训练更长时间或更努力，他也不会变得更强壮或更健康，他也不会改变任何泳姿。他只是长高了。但根据改进后的弗劳德数预测，他很可能能在18分钟内游完一英里！

There are ways you can swim tall too, regardless of your height. And they are important to learn because they put mathematics powerfully in your favor. Take a hypothetical six-footer who swims the mile in 25 minutes. Feed him some growth hormone so he sprouts up to nine feet. He doesn’t train any longer or harder, he doesn’t get any stronger or fitter, he doesn’t change his stroke in any way. He just gets taller. But his improved Froude number predicts that he can probably do the mile in 18 minutes!

好吧。但如果你“只有”6英尺高，而且到了30多岁还很可能保持这个身高呢？嗯，就水而言，你仍然可以长高，只需将手臂举过头顶，就能从指尖到脚趾的6英尺长到将近9英尺。如果你能保持这个身高在每个划水周期中，你都处于伸展——更高的——位置，这样你就能够提高自己的弗劳德数，从而以相同的能量游得更快。

Fine. But what if you’re “only” 6'0" and at thirty-something quite likely to stay there? Well, as far as the water is concerned you can still grow, stretching your six feet to nearly nine feet from fingertips to toes by simply extending your arm overhead. And if you can stay in that extended—taller—position for more of each stroke cycle, you improve your own Froude number enough to go much faster on the same amount of energy.

这里有一个简单的实验来证明这一点。在水下，双臂放于身体两侧（六英尺深的位置），用力蹬开泳池壁，尽可能远地滑行直到浮出水面。然后再次尝试，双臂伸直，呈流线型，过顶（九英尺深的位置）。看看你能滑行多远？

Here’s a simple experiment to prove it. Under water, push off the pool wall as hard as you can with your arms at your sides (the six-foot position) and glide as far as possible until you surface. Then do it again with your arms straight and streamlined overhead (the nine-foot position). See how much farther you go?

这也是游得更高的秘诀，我的导师比尔·布默（Bill Boomer）称之为前象限游泳（FQS）。在下图中，将水线视为 x 轴，将一条穿过肩部的假想垂直线视为 y 轴。这两条线将游泳空间划分为几个象限，前象限是指肩部前方、水下的区域。

That’s also the secret for swimming taller, what my mentor, Bill Boomer, calls front-quadrant swimming, or FQS. In the illustration below, consider the waterline as the x-axis and an imaginary vertical line through the shoulder as the y-axis. The two lines divide the swimming space into quadrants, the front quadrant being the one in front of the shoulder and under the water.

FQS 游泳意味着始终将一只手或另一只手保持在前象限。（当然，每次划水开始时，双手都在那里。）这实际上只是“高抬腿游泳”的另一种说法，指的是拉长你的身体线条，让你比实际更高。左手划水时，右手放在前面，然后当左手回到前象限时开始划水，依此类推。一只手要等到另一只手几乎回到前象限时才开始划水。每只手在原地停留哪怕一瞬间，就能对你的弗劳德数产生很大的影响。

FQS swimming means always keeping one or the other of your hands in that front quadrant. (At the beginning of each stroke, of course, both hands are there.) It’s really just another way of saying “swimming tall,” of lengthening your body line and making you taller than you really are. Leave your right hand out in front while the left is stroking, then begin stroking the right just as the left returns to the front quadrant, and so on. One hand doesn’t start until the other one’s nearly back. Leaving each in place just a split second extra can make a big difference in your Froude number.

常识？嗯，其实不太常见。不然为什么我周末训练营的几乎所有学员第一天上课时都是后游的？不然为什么我大学时要那么努力地练习后游？因为很容易掉入这样的陷阱：“我通过向后拉手来移动身体，对吧？那么，为了让身体游得更快，我只需要更快地向后拉手，对吧？双手向前伸着滑行？那样只会让我慢下来！”

Common sense? Well, actually not so common. Why else would almost all the swimmers in my weekend workshops show up the first day as rear-quadrant swimmers? Why else would I have worked so hard when I was in college at being a rear-quadrant swimmer? Because it’s easy to fall into the trap: “I move my body by pulling my hands back, right? To get it going faster, then, I just move my hands back faster, right? Gliding along with hands stretched in front? All that will do is slow me down!”

所以我的大学游泳策略就像浴缸里的发条玩具：手一沾水就往里扎，然后往后拉。不幸的是，这注定了我几乎不会花任何宝贵的时间把两只手放在头前。我游得短，而且很明显。我每游24到25次划水，而我现在五十出头的时候每游14到15次。快速划水让我更难游得快。

So my college swim strategy was like a bathtub windup toy: Dig in and pull back as soon as my hands touched the water. Unfortunately, it guaranteed that I would spend precious little time with either hand out in front of my head. I swam short, and it showed. I took 24 to 25 strokes per length, compared to the 14 or 15 I now use in my early fifties. Stroking fast was making it harder to swim fast.

有些人，就像我一样，是故意用后肢游的。但有些人却没办法——他们的手一旦进入前肢，就会被向下和向后推。他们的手臂“很重”，因为他们支撑着身体的重量，如果他们的平衡能力更好，这些重量就会分散到其他地方。面对现实吧：你根本无法成为FQS游泳者。除非你也是一位平衡能力极佳的游泳者。无论你的后肢倾向是否有意识，FQS 都不是天生就能做到的。你必须明白它的重要性，然后有意识地努力养成习惯，并相信自己正在朝着成为更快、更高效的游泳者迈出重要的一步。

Some people, as I was, are rear-quadrant swimmers by intent. But others can’t help it—as soon as their hands enter the front quadrant, they’re driven down and back. Their arms are “heavy” because of the weight they’re supporting, weight that would be distributed elsewhere if their balance were better. Face it: You just can’t be an FQS swimmer unless you’re also a well-balanced swimmer. But whether or not your rear-quadrant tendencies are intentional, FQS is something no one does naturally. You have to know it matters, then consciously work on making it a habit, confident that you’re taking another important step to becoming a faster and more efficient swimmer.

如果运用得当，FQS 绝对是一种革命性的思考方式，它能让你更好地理解双手在游泳时的作用。你会突然意识到，双手作为身体线条延伸器对速度的贡献远大于用来推水。一旦你发现了这一点，你就能更有效地利用它们，通过几种方式让自己变得更高。

Done right, FQS is nothing less than a revolutionary way of thinking about what your hands do for you when you swim. Suddenly, you understand they contribute far more to your speed when used as body line extenders than when used to push water back. Once you’ve discovered that, you can use them more effectively to make you taller in a couple of ways.

首先，在用手划水之前，先用手拉长身体线条。这应该是一个真正的伸展动作，就像伸手到高高的架子上去拿刚好够不着的东西一样。这应该很容易，只需在手入水时先将手完全向前伸——而不是向下伸。但对一些人来说，这并不容易。他们的手一碰到水，多年的坏习惯就会滋生，手臂会自动向水底游去。直到我让他们假装伸手去够墙壁，就像他们在每一圈最后一次划水时那样。就肌肉而言，情况就不同了——现在手臂可以很好地伸直。身体在后面滑动得也更容易了。

First, use your hand to lengthen your body line before using it to stroke. This should be a true reaching action, like stretching up to a high shelf for something just out of your grasp. It should be as easy as extending your hand all the way forward first—not down—when it goes into the water. But for some people, it’s not that easy. As soon as their hand hits the water, years of bad habits take hold and the arm automatically heads right for the bottom. It does, that is, until I ask them to pretend they’re reaching for the wall as they would on the last stroke of each lap. As far as the muscles are concerned, that’s different—now the arm goes out nice and straight and long. And the body glides along more easily behind.

不要操之过急。先保持手伸直，再开始往后拉。不要急着开始划水。如果有帮助的话，默念：“入水、伸直、暂停、划水”。只要让你的手保持向前滑动，尽可能长时间地伸展，然后再开始划水。

Don’t rush the process. Leave your hand extended before starting to pull back. Don’t be in a hurry to start stroking. Chant silently, if it helps: “Enter, e-x-t-e-n-d, pause, and pull.” Just let your hand keep gliding forward out there, reaching as long as possible before you begin stroking.

其次，通过以下方式让你的手臂更好地延伸身体线条卸下它们——字面意思——这样它们就会感觉没有重量。如果你按照我说的按压浮标，并且头部的重量由水支撑，并且与躯干保持一条直线，那么你已经达到了平衡。但如果你做到了，那么你就是少数已经达到平衡的幸运儿。如果没有，你需要先用第8章中的具体练习来练习无重手臂，然后再尝试真正带着它游泳。

Second, make your arms better body line extenders by taking a load off them—literally—so they feel weightless. If you’re pressing your buoy as I told you to, and if you’re keeping your head’s weight supported by the water and in line with your torso, you’re already there. But if you are there, you’re in the happy minority of the already balanced. If not, you’ll want to work on a weightless arm using the specific drills in chapter 8, before trying to actually swim with one.

当你这样做时，你会发现那些沉重的手臂和手的重量通常来自两个地方之一：

When you do, you’ll find that the weight of those heavy arms and hands usually comes from one of two places:

 

 

1. 你没有把所有重量都放在浮标上，所以一部分重量落在了臀部和腿部，导致它们下沉。为了弥补这一损失，你的手和手臂会快速下沉，并脱离前象限。你的身高正在变矮。

1. You haven’t put all your weight on your buoy, so some of it has gone back to your hips and legs, and they’re sinking. To compensate, you’re driving your hand and arm quickly down and out of the front quadrant. You’re becoming shorter.

2. 呼吸时，你的头会抬起来——哪怕只是稍微抬一下。这会把更多的重量转移到你的手上，而你的手需要支撑头部。每次呼吸时，你的手都会快速地、反复地向下沉。

2. You’re lifting your head—even the littlest bit—as you breathe. That shifts more weight to your hand, which has to support it. Down it goes too fast, over and over again, every time you breathe.

我保证，你只需要花费我一小部分时间就能了解我所花的时间。游泳不仅是我的谋生手段，更是我的挚爱，多年来我一直在努力提高我的划水效率。但我追求速度的地方总是错的，我仔细检查着划水过程中手部的每个动作，每两年平均能少划一次就觉得很幸运了。后来，我又开始练习无力臂，短短几周内就少划了两次。之后又少划了一次。相信我，一位专业教练在近三十年的努力下，每25码的划水次数从16次降到了13次。他几乎想把这招的说明纹在任何站着不动的人身上。我对此深信不疑。

I promise it will take you a fraction of the time to learn that it took me. Swimming is not only my livelihood but my love, and I’ve been working on my stroke efficiency for years. But I was looking for speed in all the wrong places, minutely examining every movement of the hand through every centimeter of the stroke, and feeling lucky to shave maybe one stroke from my average every two years. Then I hit on the weightless arm and lopped off two strokes in just a matter of weeks. Then another after that. Believe me, when a professional coach’s count per 25 yards tumbles from 16 to 13 strokes after almost thirty years of trying, he practically wants to tattoo instructions for the technique onto anyone who’ll stand still. I’m that convinced.

教练杰基·赫斯蒂也是如此。赫斯蒂是35至39岁女子大师赛游泳世界纪录保持者，断断续续地跟随我执教了五年。但直到我们在波士顿一起教授“完全沉浸式”游泳工作坊时，她才听说了“无重臂”这个技巧，我终于把这个技巧完善到可以与学生们分享的程度。工作坊结束后的第二天，她亲自尝试了一下。她轻松完成了一组400码的重复游动，速度比过去几年都要快，而且她的划水次数实际上还更少了。

So is coach Jacki Hirsty. Hirsty, a Masters swimming world record holder in the women’s 35 to 39 age group, had been coaching with me on and off for five years.
