But it wasn’t until we taught a Total Immersion workshop together in Boston that she heard about the weightless arm, a technique I’d finally polished up enough to share with students. The day after the workshop she tried it herself. She cruised through a set of 400-yard repeats faster than she had in several years, and on top of that her stroke count was actually lower.

不要平泳，要侧泳

Don’t Swim Flat; Swim on Your Side

游泳者还能从船舶设计师那里学到另一课：如何让自己的身体像赛艇一样飞翔，而不是像平底船一样艰难前行。你能想到最快的帆船是什么？也许是美洲杯帆船赛的有力竞争者？它们只靠风力驱动，航行起来就像……嗯……像风一样。你能想到动力最慢的船是什么？那一定是驳船。你想让它多大马力就多大马力，它还是会爬行。好吧，我们都可以选择像驳船一样畅游，或者像美洲杯帆船赛一样。

There’s still another lesson swimmers can learn from boat designers: how to make their bodies fly like racing yachts instead of plowing along like scows. What are the fastest sailboats you can think of? Maybe the America’s Cup contenders? With only the wind for power, they go like, well … like the wind. What’s the slowest powered boat you can think of ? It has to be the cargo barge. Load it up with as much horsepower as you want and it will still crawl. Well, we all have the choice of swimming like barges or America’s Cup yachts.

关于这项运动，一个流传已久的误区是，自由泳的正确姿势是俯卧，需要换气时将头转向一侧。红十字会培训的教练已经教会了数百万人这样游泳。而红十字会漏掉的少数人也自然而然地选择了俯卧，因为他们觉得平躺更舒服、更安全。

One of the most enduring myths about our sport is that the correct position for swimming freestyle is lying on your stomach, turning your head to the side when you need a breath. Red Cross–trained instructors have taught millions to swim that way. And the few the Red Cross missed automatically swim that way too, because they just feel more comfortable and secure flat on their stomachs.

但这是错的。如果你想游得更好，就不能趴着游自由泳（顺便说一句，仰泳也不能仰着游）。世界上速度最快、最高效的游泳运动员都是侧身切水，每次划水时身体从一侧滚到另一侧，并尽可能多地在每个划水周期保持在一侧。这样做的好处很容易理解：比趴着游更容易滑过水面。

But it’s wrong. You don’t swim freestyle on your stomach if you want to be any good (and by the way, you don’t swim backstroke on your back either). The fastest, most efficient swimmers in the world cut the water on their sides, rolling from one side to the other with each stroke and staying on each side for as much of each stroke cycle as they can. The advantage is simple to understand: You slip through the water more easily that way than on your stomach.

让我们暂时回顾一下海军术语。你会记得，你的身体——以及游艇和驳船——是一个穿透水面的运动体，它们都遵循相同的物理定律，因为它们在行进过程中都会划过水面。（潜艇、鱼雷和鱼类——以及蝶泳和蛙泳运动员——都在水面以下游动，它们所受的流体动力学影响略有不同。）其中一条定律是，阻力或阻力的增大程度与水流移动距离的平方成正比。距离增加一倍，难度增加四倍。那么，你是愿意像驳船一样游，在水面前推着水流，还是像游艇一样，让水流轻松地在你周围滑动？真是个愚蠢的问题。

Let’s go back to naval jargon for a moment. You’ll recall that your body—along with yachts and barges—is a surface-penetrating moving body, and that all of those are subject to the same physical laws because they all slice the surface as they go. (Submarines, torpedoes, and fish— as well as butterfly and breaststroke swimmers—hang out below the surface and are subject to slightly different hydrodynamics.) One of those laws is that drag or resistance goes up by the square of the distance the water travels to get out of your way. Twice as far equals four times as hard. So would you rather swim like a barge, pushing water in front of you, or like a yacht with the fluid slipping easily around you? Dumb question.

其实，你从小就明白这个道理，小时候把手伸出车窗外。当你把手伸直，手掌平放在气流中，就像交警的停车信号灯一样，风会用力地推它。然后，你弯曲手肘，手掌朝下，指尖朝前。哇，几乎没有任何压力。

And you’ve actually understood this principle since you were a little kid, holding your arm out the window of the car. When you held it straight up, palm flat against the airflow like the traffic policeman’s stop signal, the wind pushed it hard. Then, you bent your elbow so the palm faced down, fingertips pointing forward. Wow. Hardly any pressure.

同样的情况也适用于你（渗透到水面的）身体在水中的情况。游泳时，水会绕过你，很少会滑到你下面。俯卧时，你就像一艘驳船，用“宽阔的肩膀”迫使水流到很远的地方，以至于它不断地推动着前方巨大的水流。而游艇，即使船宽，前部也像刀一样，所以水流很容易绕过去，如下图所示。当你像游艇一样侧身划水时，阻力可能只有像驳船一样的一半。

Same thing applies to your (surface-penetrating) body in water. As you swim, water goes mostly around you to get out of the way. Very little slips underneath. On your stomach, you’re like a barge with its “broad shoulders” forcing the water to move so far that it’s constantly pushing along a huge volume of water in front. Yachts, on the other hand, even if they’re broad in the beam, are knifelike up front, so it’s easy for the water to go around, as shown in the illustration below. When you swim like a yacht, cutting water on your side, drag may be half as much as when you swim like a barge.

我知道。你不可能永远保持侧卧姿势。但你可以边划边从一侧翻滚到另一侧。自由泳最有效的方法是有节奏地翻滚，直到肩膀和臀部略微偏离水面的垂直度，并尝试在每个划水周期中增加侧卧时间。

I know. You can’t stay on your side forever. But you can roll from one side to the other as you stroke. The most efficient way to swim freestyle is to roll rhythmically until your shoulders and hips are a bit less than perpendicular to the water and to try to spend just a bit more time on your side in each stroke cycle.

翻滚也能让你的身体显得更长一些。你可以这样证明：面壁站立，一只手臂伸直过头顶，手掌平贴水面。保持手的位置不变，将身体向侧面转，然后再向后转，如此反复几次。注意看，当你转身时，你的手是如何向上滑动的，当你转身回来时，手是如何向下滑动的。这让你每次侧身时都“更高”，而当你转身面向墙壁时，则“更矮”？当你侧身翻滚时，情况也是一样的：你游得更高了。

Rolling also helps make your body a little longer. Prove it to yourself this way: Stand facing the wall closely, one arm straight overhead, palm flat against the surface. Leave your hand where it is, and turn your body to the side, then back again several times. Notice how your hand slides up as you turn, and down as you turn back, making you “taller” each time you turn sideways and “shorter” as you turn back to face the wall? Same thing when you roll to your side: You swim taller.

考虑到所有这些优势，你显然希望每次划水时都保持翻滚姿势，每次划完后都尽可能接近侧卧姿势。这时，你能做的最明智的事情就是在将手臂放回入水位置时，保持身体原位——侧卧。这样，在你不划水的整个过程中，你都能保持快速移动的侧卧姿势滑行。而且，由于你没有推开身前的海水，你滑行得更远更快。

Given all these advantages, you obviously want to roll on every stroke, ending up as close to a side-lying position as possible at the end of each one. The smartest thing you can do then is stay right where you are—on your side—as you return your arm to where it will reenter the water. As a consequence, you glide in the fast-moving side-lying position the whole time you’re not stroking. And you glide farther and faster because you’re not pushing all that water in front of you.

这样一来，自由泳就变得优雅有力，成为一种智能身体工程学的杰作，而非在水中艰难跋涉的累人训练。它变成了一系列长距离滑行，由快速的翻滚连接，伴随着划水和换边。每一次，你的身体都有一侧在用力划水——也就是你划水的那一侧——和另一侧在滑动——也就是拉长身体，以便划水时尽可能地释放速度和距离。你在每个划水周期中保持侧身的时间越长，你的身体就能游得越远越快。游泳也会变得更加轻松自在，用力更少，甚至看起来更轻松。

Done this way, freestyle becomes graceful, powerful, a feat of intelligent body engineering instead of a tiring exercise in plowing through the water. It becomes a series of long glides linked by quick rolls as you stroke and change sides. Each time, your body has a working side—the one you’re pulling with—and a sliding side—the one that’s making your body longer so the pull delivers all the speed and distance it can. The longer you stay on your side in each stroke cycle, the farther and faster your body will travel. Swimming also becomes much more restful and a lot less work. It even looks easier.

这或许会让一些人抓狂。不久前，我去参加我的一个工作坊，参加了一个大师组的训练。练完一组之后，我泳道上的一位游泳运动员走过来，语气略带一丝不苟地说：“我真不明白你是怎么跟上我们的。你看起来什么都没做。 ” 嗯，跟其他人比起来，我的确没那么做。他们只是稳定地挥动着手臂，使劲地拍打着水花，“完成训练”。而我就像帆船一样，每次划水之间，我都会静静地滑行，靠在我身侧——而且跟他们保持同步。没有翻滚和滑行，他们别无选择，除非不停地转动手臂，否则每次划水之间都无法停下。当然，我的游泳看起来并不费力。和他们相比，确实如此。甚至可能看起来像是在作弊。

And that may drive some people crazy. While traveling to one of my workshops not long ago I was a guest at a Masters group’s workout. After a single set, one of the swimmers in my lane came over to me and, with just a bit of an edge in his voice, said, “I can’t figure out how you’re keeping up with us. You don’t look like you’re doing anything.” Well, compared to everyone else, I wasn’t. They were churning their arms steadily, splashing mightily, and “getting the work done.” I was like a sailboat, quietly gliding and resting on my side between strokes— and staying right up with them. Without roll and glide, they had no choice but nonstop arm turnover if they didn’t want to stop dead in the water between strokes. Of course, my swimming didn’t look like a lot of work. Compared to theirs, it wasn’t. It may even have looked like cheating.

那么，为什么不是每个人都这样游泳呢？他们是自讨苦吃吗？不。但即使大多数游泳教练实际上并不阻止人们进行像翻滚这样重要的动作——而他们确实会这么做——你仍然会看到更多“平躺”游泳，因为这样我们感觉更舒服。向一侧翻滚会让我们感到不稳定、摇晃、失控。所以我们几乎不会向一侧倾斜，而且我们肯定不会在那里停留超过必要的时间一纳秒。脸朝下似乎是正确的。

So why doesn’t everyone swim this way? Are they gluttons for punishment? No. But even if most swim instructors didn’t actually discourage people from something as valuable as rolling—which they do— you’d still see more “flat” swimming than anything else because that’s how we feel more comfortable. Rolling to the side makes us feel unsteady, tippy, out of control. So we barely tip to one side or the other, and we certainly don’t stay there a nanosecond longer than we have to. Facedown just seems right.

平衡能力差就是个老问题，如果学习平躺需要练习，那就等到你需要侧卧平衡的时候再说吧。侧卧平衡并非自然而然，也不是本能，而且如果不集中注意力、有意识地努力，很难学会。但在此之前，你只能避免翻滚，只能勉强维持平衡。你不需要侧卧，第八章的技巧训练会循序渐进地教你，最终让你感觉像赛艇一样灵活自如。

It’s that old bogeyman, bad balance, and if learning to do it flat on your stomach took some practice, wait until you have to balance on your side. It’s not natural, it’s not instinctive, and it’s difficult to learn without concentrated, conscious effort. But until you have it, you’re going to avoid rolling and you’ll settle for being a barge. And you don’t have to settle, not when the skill drills in chapter 8 give you a step-by-step approach to ultimately feeling as slick as a racing yacht.

当我第一次说，流线型身体可能对游泳水平的提升贡献了70%时，我预料到会有人会感到惊讶。我在游泳训练营里也经常遇到这种情况——直到我们跳进泳池，开始彻底摆脱那些造成阻力的坏习惯。“我从来没见过池底滑得这么快，”有人有人会说，或者有人会说他们刚刚在25码的常规击球数上减少了6杆。我们使用的练习和你在第八章中看到的一样。你的结果应该同样令人兴奋。

When I first said that streamlining your body probably accounts for about 70 percent of your potential swimming improvement, I expected those raised eyebrows. I always get them in my swim clinics too— until we jump into the pool and start shedding resistance-causing bad habits left and right. “I’ve never seen the bottom slide by so fast,” some one will say, or someone else will report that they’ve just cut six strokes from their normal count for 25 yards. The drills we use are the same ones you’ll find in chapter 8. Your results should be just as exciting.

但就连我也不得不承认一件事：如果没有什么东西一开始就推动你，你就无法滑行。这叫做推进力，我认为它被高估了，但这并不意味着它无法得到显著提升。不过，首先，你必须忘掉那种你可能认为需要强壮的肩膀才能把身体的其他部分拖入泳池的想法。然后我会告诉你真正起作用的是什么，以及如何让它更有力地发挥作用。

But even I have to admit one thing: You can’t glide if something didn’t push you along in the first place. That’s called propulsion, and just because I think it’s overrated doesn’t mean it can’t be dramatically improved. First, though, you must forget the idea you probably have of needing powerful shoulders to drag the rest of your body down the pool. Then I’ll tell you what really does the job, and how you can make it happen more powerfully.

4

4

调整引擎：发现并利用你的游泳力量

Tuning the Engine: Finding—and Using—Your Swimming Power

“如果你的身体是一艘摩托艇，那么你的引擎就在你的臀部。你的手实际上只不过是螺旋桨叶片的尖端。”

“If your body were a motorboat, your engine would be in your hips. Your hands are actually nothing more than the tips of the propeller blades.”

我从我的导师比尔·布默那里学到了这一点，一开始我也觉得这听起来很不靠谱。毕竟，我指导过无数游泳运动员，让他们在力量房里花上几个小时来锻炼强壮的手臂和肩膀。现在，一个教练界的怪咖却试图告诉我，我完全错了？告诉我，这些根本不是让我在水中前进的动力？告诉我，我实际上是在误导我的游泳运动员？

I learned that from my mentor Bill Boomer, and at first it sounded backward to me too. After all, I’d directed countless swimmers to spend hours in the weight room building powerful arms and shoulders. And now a coaching maverick was trying to tell me I’d had it all wrong? That they’re not what moved me through the water in the first place? That I’d essentially been misleading my swimmers?

嗯，是的，他几乎就是这个意思。我停下来思考，意识到他的话很有道理，尽管当时几乎没有人这么认为。“游泳是有节奏地运用力量”是婴儿潮一代的另一句格言，虽然无辜，但实际上颇具煽动性，因为它意味着节奏（游泳者很少练习），而不是力量（他们一直在练习），才是创造精彩游泳推进力的核心。良好的身体节奏能让你的力量由手臂和肩膀传递。而且，节奏动作必须源自身体的中心或核心，而不是四肢。（手臂和腿）——与游泳运动员一直以来尝试的方式正好相反。

Well, yes, that’s almost exactly what he was saying. When I paused to think about it, I realized that what he was saying made perfect sense even though, at the time, virtually no one else saw it that way. “Swimming is the rhythmic application of power” was another Boomer aphorism, an innocent but actually quite seditious statement, since it meant that rhythm (which swimmers seldom worked on), not power (which they worked on all the time), is what’s actually at the heart of creating propulsion in brilliant swimming. Good body rhythms give you the power that the arms and shoulders simply deliver. And rhythm movements must originate in the body’s center or core, not at the extremities (the arms and legs)—just the opposite of how swimmers have always tried to do it.

当我们其他人还在仅仅拍打水面的时候，Boomer 已经洞悉了游泳推进的核心，理解了游泳的物理原理。Boomer 告诉我们，推进力——我们如何产生力量来推动自己在水中前行——并不像我们想象的那样运作。但当时很少有人足够开明地倾听他的想法。

Boomer had seen to the heart of swimming propulsion, understanding the underlying physics of swimming while the rest of us were still just slapping the water. Propulsion—how we produce the force that actually moves us through the water—did not work the way we all thought it worked, Boomer told us. But few were open-minded enough to listen at the time.

你可能刚刚从上一章关于流线型的学习中获益，开始思考你的体型和平衡是否才是真正重要的。但请停下来思考：即使你70%的潜在速度提升确实来自于学习使用第三章中的技巧更轻松地在水中滑行，但你仍然可以利用另外30%的潜能。而这30%来自于学习一种更经济、更有效的推进方式。

You may be wondering, freshly convinced from the previous chapter on streamlining, whether your shape and balance might be all that really matters. But stop and think: Even though 70 percent of your potential speed improvements will indeed come from learning to slip through the water more easily using the techniques in chapter 3, that still leaves another 30 percent you can tap. And that 30 percent comes from learning a more economical and effective style of creating propulsion.

这是我所说的“消除/创造”过程的后半部分：首先消除阻力，然后创造更多动力。这正是你应该努力的方向。首先要了解在水中保持和谐平衡的感觉，然后调整身体姿势，使其能够很好地避开正面水压，最后学习运用有节奏的强劲动作。现在，我们即将开始在你的适航船上安装发动机。

It’s the second half of what I call the eliminate/create process: First eliminate drag, then create more power. That’s exactly how you should work on it too. Start by understanding what it feels like to be in harmonious balance in the water, then shape your body so it evades frontal water pressure well, then learn to apply rhythmically powerful movement. We’re now about to start installing the engine on your seaworthy vessel.

这不仅把重要的事情放在首位，还能把容易的事情留到最后。虽然减少阻力当然不复杂，但提升推进力却更简单。如果你曾经对掌握“S 型划桨”、手型、俯仰或涡流等看似高深的科学感到绝望，其他游泳书籍中叙述的模式，我们将使它变得更简单、更清晰。

Not only does this put first things first, it saves the easier work for last. For while reducing drag is certainly not complicated, improving propulsion is simpler yet. If you’ve ever despaired of mastering all the seeming rocket science of “S-strokes,” hand shape, and pitch or vortex patterns recounted in other swim books, we’re about to make it much simpler and more lucid.

更妙的是，整个推进过程都基于你已经学过的减阻技巧。你仍然“由内而外”地游动，首先通过左右摇晃身体来产生动力，然后用双手将动力传递到水中。一旦你掌握了“消除”的技巧，你就已经完成了“创造”的大部分步骤。所以，这不是一门新课程，只是你已经熟悉的课程的第二学期。

Better yet, the whole propulsion process follows from the techniques you’ve already learned to reduce drag. You’re still swimming “inside out,” first generating power by rolling your body from side to side and only then using your hands to deliver that power to the water. Once you master “eliminating,” you’re already doing most of what you need to do for “creating.” So it’s not a new course, just the second semester of the one you’ve already grown familiar with.

了解你的游泳实力

Get Hip to Your Swimming Power

首先，我要告诉你一些乍一看可能不太合理的事情：你的手臂其实没那么重要。嗯，可能不像你想象的那样。大多数运动——包括游泳——的力量都源自身体的下半部分。在大多数情况下，手臂只是“传递系统”。

I’ll start off by telling you something that, at first glance, may make little sense: Your arms are not that important. Well, not the way you may think. Power in most sports—swimming included—originates much lower down in your body. In most cases, the arms are just the “delivery system.”

想象一下老虎伍兹开球时流畅的弧线。或是塞雷娜·威廉姆斯爆发力十足的发球。又或是巴里·邦兹一记势大力沉的劈球！想想把球猛击出300码，或以每小时130英里的速度将球轰过网，或将球划出450英尺甚至更远的弧线飞向看台，需要多大的力量啊？

Picture the smooth arc of a Tiger Woods drive off the tee. Or the explosive serve of a Serena Williams. Or the powerful crack! as Barry Bonds drives yet another one out of the park. Then think of the power it takes to slam a ball over 300 yards, or blast one over the net at 130 mph, or send it arcing 450 feet or more into the stands. What arms, eh?

嗯……不是。手臂摆动或许是我们最容易看到的，但它并非真正的发力点。手臂摆动实际上是一系列连续动作中的最后一个，也是力量最小的一个，每个动作都从前一个动作中汲取动力。投手投球时，击球手的第一个动作是将手臂和肩膀向远离球的方向伸展（这种所谓的增强式收缩就像上紧弹簧，储存能量，稍后会在相反方向释放）。然后，一切开始放松。他首先向投手迈步，同时臀部开始旋转，进而带动躯干转动，从而推动肩膀向投球方向旋转。肩膀拉动上臂，增加速度。上臂拉动前臂，只有在前臂也达到速度后，手腕才会猛地一甩，完成一个“啪啪啪”的链条，最终击出球。强大的肌肉群（主要在臀部和躯干）共同产生巨大的力量，以完美的时机移动最大量的肌肉。

Well…no. Arm swing may be what is most visible to us, but it’s not what’s doing the work. Arm swing is actually the last—and least powerful—of a linked series of actions, each of which takes its momentum from the one before. As the pitcher releases the ball, the batter’s first action is to cock his arms and shoulders away from the ball (a so-called plyometric contraction like winding up a spring, storing energy that will later be released in the opposite direction). Then it all begins to unwind. He starts by stepping toward the pitcher as his hips take up the rotation and in turn power the torso around, which drives the shoulders toward the pitch. The shoulders pull the upper arms through, adding speed. The upper arms pull the forearms, and only after the forearms have gotten up to speed do the wrists snap, completing a crack-the-whip chain that finally drives the ball. Huge forces are generated by a combination of powerful muscles—mostly in the butt and torso—moving a maximum amount of mass with perfect timing.

那么，为什么那些站在本垒板或发球台上会利用臀部发力的人，认为游泳时应该像风车一样旋转手臂呢？像打出本垒打那样有力的划水动作，应该由身体有节奏的旋转驱动，就像击球手那样，从臀部开始。还记得我们在第 3 章中介绍的最后一种技巧——减少阻力的身体滚动吗？让水在你周围滑动的滚动也恰好产生了你几乎所有的划水力量。是的，全靠臀部，而你已经开始引导臀部进行有目的的旋转。当你这样做时，你正在使用身体最强大的肌肉——臀大肌（臀部肌肉），来左右移动你的重心。而移动大块物体的强大肌肉会产生令人印象深刻的力量。

So why do the same people who would go to their hips for their power if they were standing at home plate or on the tee think they ought to swim by spinning their arms like a windmill? A powerful stroke, like the one that results in a home run, should be driven by rhythmic rotation of the body starting, as does the batter’s, at the hips. Remember the last technique we covered in chapter 3, the drag-diminishing body roll? Well, the same roll that lets water slip around you also conveniently produces virtually all of your stroking power. Yes, it’s all in the hips, and you’ve already begun to direct them into purposeful rotation. When you do this, you’re using the body’s most powerful muscles, the gluteals (the butt muscles), to move your center of mass from side to side. And powerful muscles moving a large mass generate impressive force.

相比之下，手臂和肩膀的肌肉其实不算什么，所以为什么要费力地用它们来驱动你的引擎呢？你总不会想用雨刷器的马达来驱动你的车吧？然而，手臂和肩部的肌肉是极好的稳定器，利用这一点的方法是用它们来抓住水。

The arm and shoulder muscles don’t really amount to much by comparison, so why struggle to use them as your engine? You wouldn’t try to move your car with your windshield-wiper motor, would you? Those arm and shoulder muscles are, however, superb stabilizers, and the way to take advantage of that is to use them to hold on to the water.

即便没有其他原因，那些能坚持下来的肌肉也不会像那些像主力一样拼命工作的肌肉那样受伤。把你的手臂和肩膀想象成发动机，你总是会用力过猛。你所能期望的最好结果就是过早地耗尽体力，而你确实会这样。你的手臂很快就会因为过度用力而失去力量，而下半身真正负责工作的肌肉却在偷懒。更糟糕的是，你可能会受伤。大自然母亲真正希望的是你的肩部肌肉能够简单地保持连接并稳定关节，让你的手臂处于最大杠杆位置，以便更好地抓住水面，抵抗身体滚动产生的强大力量。她从未想过它们会像密西西比河上的明轮船一样，每小时都带着你的手臂在水中穿梭。所以，如果让这个关节承担大部分带你下潜的工作，迟早大自然会给你一个严重的错误信息。

If nothing else, muscles that hold on don’t get hurt like muscles that are trying to act like workhorses. Think of your arms and shoulders as the engine, and invariably you’ll push them too hard. The best you can hope for is wearing yourself out too soon, and you will. Your arms quickly lose their punch because they’re doing way too much, while the true workhorse muscles lower down are loafing along. Worse, you could be heading for an injury. Mother Nature really wanted your shoulder muscles to simply hold together and stabilize the joint, setting your arm in a maximum-leverage position where it can better hold the water against the powerful forces developed by your body roll. She never envisioned them driving your arms through the water by the hour, like a Mississippi River sternwheeler. So make this joint do most of the work moving you down the pool, and sooner or later Mother Nature is going to send you a big error message.

然而，挖掘你真正力量源泉的力量，看看会发生什么。所有这些强健的体魄，这种可以永远坚持下去的感觉，这种无比轻松的自由，都是从哪里突然冒出来的？就连之前那种在每次划水的后半段试图加速划水的技巧——所有游泳者都听说过，并且至少应该尝试一下——现在看起来都很容易了。

Tap the power in your real power source, however, and watch what happens. Where did all this fitness, this feeling you could go on forever, this freedom from fatigue, suddenly come from? Even the previously exhausting little trick of trying to accelerate your hand during the second half of each stroke—something all swimmers have heard of and at least have to try—seems easy now.

为什么？因为只用手臂游泳就像用手臂挥棒一样合理，而不是先把身体的其他部分卷起来，然后再释放所有动量。如果是后者，你连一个无力的内野滚球都打不出来。本垒打是靠臀部发力的。游泳奖杯也是如此。而游泳过程中所需的能量，其实就是在挥动鞭子时，协调能量链展开的简单技巧。让我来解释一下。

How come? Because swimming with just your arms makes as much sense as trying to swing a bat with just your arms instead of winding up the rest of your body first and then unleashing all that momentum. Do the latter and you’d be lucky to manage a feeble infield grounder. Home runs come from the hips. So do swim trophies. And the energy that powers the process in swimming comes from a simple trick of coordinating that whip-cracking energy chain as it unfolds. Let me explain.

你高中物理课上的一个小公式 F = M × A，期末考试后可能就忘得一干二净了。现在是时候把它找回来了。这样，你就能拥有新的游泳动力来源，而且不会消耗任何能量。

A little formula from your high school physics class, F = M × A, probably went right out the window after your final exam. Well, it’s time to get it back. When you do, you’ll have a new source of swimming power that won’t cost you any energy.

这个等式告诉我们“力等于质量乘以加速度”，当时，就连那些在房间后面打瞌睡的人都知道，如果等号右边的任何一个值增加，合力也会增加。所以在这种情况下，有两种方法可以增加力。一种是保持质量不变，增加加速度——换句话说，不要用更多的身体力量，只要更快地移动你的手臂。如果你想浪费能量，这就是这样做的，因为能量消耗会随着肌肉速度的增加而膨胀。要将手臂移动速度提高一倍，需要做八 (2 3 )倍的功。

“Force equals mass multiplied by acceleration” is what the equation tells us, and back then even those dozing in the back of the room knew that if either value on the right side of the equals sign went up, the resultant force would go up too. So in this case there are two ways to increase the force. One is by keeping mass the same and increasing acceleration—in other words, don’t put more of your body into it, just move your arms faster. If you want to waste energy that’s the very way to do it, since energy expenditure balloons as a cube of any increase in muscle speed. To move your arms twice as fast takes eight (23) times more work.

但如果你反过来想想呢？如果你的划水力量能大幅提升，而用力程度基本保持不变，会怎么样？难道你不能游得更快，而且不会感到疲倦吗？你可以，而且你一定可以。这可以通过增加公式中的M来实现。只需在划水时一次性移动更多身体重量即可。你的手臂以相同的速度划动（你甚至可以稍微放慢速度），但现在你的整个躯干都在为它们提供动力。感受那股新的力量。让你的臀部成为每次划水时身体最先移动的部位，感受你的力量增长。

But what if you turn this around? What if your stroke power could somehow go way up and the effort stay pretty much the same? Couldn’t you swim much faster without getting tired? You could and you can. It’s done by increasing the M in the formula. Simply move more of your body mass all at once when you stroke. Your arms go at the same speed (perhaps you can even slow them a bit), but now your entire torso is powering them. Feel that new force. Make your hips the first part of the body to move in each stroke, and watch your power grow.

换句话说，让你的臀部来设定你的划水节奏，因为当你做对的时候，臀部是动作的核心。试着设定它用手臂引导，它们会很快自行启动，断开链条，最终与发动机分离。如果你是一辆汽车，你的变速器就会失效。用臀部引导，你的划水动作会既有节奏又有力。你的手臂也会乐于跟随。

In other words, let your hips set your stroke rhythm, since they’re the core of the movement when you’re doing it right. Try to set it with your arms instead and they’ll quickly go off on their own, breaking the chain and essentially disconnecting themselves from their engine. If you were a car, your transmission would be gone. Lead with your hips instead, and your stroke will be both rhythmic and powerful. Your arms will be happy to follow.

它们不再是手，而是锚

They’re Not Hands Anymore: They’re Anchors

“好吧，”我听到有人嘀咕，“手不重要。它们不像我们从小学开始就学到的那样，能把我们在水中拉动。但它们必须做点什么。什么？”别担心。我并不是提倡游泳时解放双手。但考虑到它们可能只占你整体效率的 10%，我把手放在了最后。正如我反复说过的，游泳并不复杂。游泳教学很复杂。部分原因是它通常像自卸卡车一样，一下子就完成了，没有轻重缓急。比如，如果你过早地把注意力集中在手上的动作上，你就会把注意力从更重要的身体动作上转移开。然而，一旦你的流线型、平衡感和节奏感都掌握得很好，你就有权思考如何最好地利用手臂末端的这些附属物了。

“Well and good,” I hear the mutters, “the hands aren’t important. They don’t pull us along through the water the way we’ve been taught since grade school. But they must do something. What?” Don’t worry. I’m not advocating hands-free swimming. But since they account for perhaps as little as 10 percent of your overall efficiency, I’ve left the hands for last. As I’ve said over and over, swimming isn’t complicated. Swimming instruction is complicated. And that’s partly because it’s usually delivered by the dumptruck load, all at once and with no priorities. Try to concentrate too early on what your hands are doing, for example, and you’ll divert concentration from the far more important body movements. Once your streamlining and balance and rhythmic power are well under way, however, you’re entitled to wonder how to best use those appendages out on the ends of your arms.

你能做的最好的事情就是把它们留在那里——不仅在你的手臂上，还要留在水里。之前我多次质疑过用手把水拉回来的过时观念。你不会的。现在是时候回答一个显而易见的问题了：那么你用它们做什么？我的答案是，让它们静止不动。把你的手固定在水中，这正是所有伟大的自然自由泳运动员所做的。

The best thing you can do is leave them there—not only on your arms but in the water. Several times earlier, I challenged the outmoded notion that you pull water back with your hands. You don’t. Now’s the time to reply to the obvious question: Then what do you do with them? And my answer is, make them stand still. Anchor your hands in the water, which is precisely what all great natural freestylers do.

自1992年以来，亚历山大·波波夫一直是世界上最具统治力的短距离自由泳运动员，他的表现甚至比这还要出色。每次划水时，他的手都会在入水前先行。手划入水中后，他抓住水面并保持平衡，利用“抓握”将身体滑过手掌，就像抓住了水下梯子的横木一样。让手在水中静止不动是世界级游泳运动员的关键“创造”技能之一，他们中的许多人似乎天生就具备这项技能。但这对我们其他人来说并非学不会。

Alexander Popov, since 1992 the world’s most dominant sprint freestyler, does even better than that. On every stroke, he takes his hand out ahead of where it entered. After he slices his hand in, he grabs and holds the water, using his “grip” to slide his body past his hand, almost as if he had grabbed a rung on a submerged ladder. Making the hand stand still in the water is one of the key “creating” skills of world-class swimmers, many of whom appear to be born with it. But it’s nothing the rest of us can’t learn.

我相信现在你听到这也是从臀部转动开始的，应该不会感到惊讶。但现在事情变得更有趣了。力量只有在有阻力的时候才是力量，如果你的手在每次旋转开始时没有先稳定上身，臀部就不可能以那么大的力量转动。因此，在划水开始时将手臂向前伸展并保持在那里，实际上的作用不仅仅是“让你的船更长”。首先，它让你避免在微弱的划水中浪费能量，而你只能用虚弱的肩部肌肉来拉，而没有其他力量或杠杆作用。其次，它让你“加载弹簧”，储存你将在即将到来的划水中释放的能量。还记得击球手在转臀部开始挥棒之前，手臂和肩膀翘起，向外弯曲以避开投手吗？高尔夫球手和网球运动员的后挥杆是同一种能量库，将躯干中的肌肉张力储存起来，然后在挥杆时释放，就像射箭前拉紧弓弦一样。

I’m sure by now you’re not surprised to hear that this too starts with hip roll. But now things get more interesting. Power is power only when it has something to act against, and the hips couldn’t roll with nearly as much force if your hand didn’t first stabilize your upper body at the beginning of each rotation. So the combination of stretching your arm forward at the beginning of the stroke and leaving it there actually does more than “make your boat longer.” First, it keeps you from wasting energy in the puny stroke you’d be able to manage with only weak shoulder muscles to pull and no other power or leverage to speak of. Second, it lets you “load the spring,” storing up the energy that you’ll release in the stroke to come. Remember that batter cocking his arms and shoulders, coiling away from the pitcher before leading into his swing with a hip turn? The golfer’s and tennis player’s back-swing is the same kind of energy bank, storing muscle tension in the torso that will later be released in the swing, like pulling a bowstring taut before shooting the arrow.

划水时也一样。你的手入水，在水面下向前伸——我的意思是伸手，就像伸手去够高架子上指尖刚好够到的东西。接下来，你的手尽可能地伸出，身体滚动侧身时，你的手臂会固定到位。现在，随着躯干移动，手臂固定，你的上半身会逐渐绷紧，就像高尔夫球手的上杆一样。就像高尔夫球手一样，你也在为接下来的动作储存能量——开球、臀部转动。

Same thing in your stroke. Your hand enters the water and reaches forward just beneath the surface—and I mean reaches, like stretching for something barely beyond your fingertips on a high shelf. Next, with your hand as far out as it can possibly go and your body rolling onto its side, your arm anchors itself into position. Now, with the torso moving and the arm fixed, your upper body becomes increasingly taut, just like the golfer’s backswing. And just like the golfer, you’re storing up that energy for the action to come—the drive off the tee, the roll of the hips.

亚历山大·波波夫深谙这种感觉。如果你走到墙边待一会儿，你也可以。面朝墙壁，伸出右手，尽可能向上滑动。然后旋转并稍微抬起肘部，使其离开墙面。你会感觉到腋窝周围的肌肉被拉伸。将左髋和左肩向墙外旋转约45度，你会感觉到强大的背阔肌（位于背部，腋窝下方）开始紧张，而不是较弱的肩部肌肉。这就是波波夫开始划水的方式。

Alexander Popov knows just what it feels like. And if you’ll walk over to the wall for a minute, you can too. Face the wall and reach up with, say, your right hand, sliding it as far up as you can. Now rotate and lift your elbow slightly off the surface. You’ll feel a stretch in the muscles surrounding your armpit. Turn your left hip and shoulder about 45 degrees away from the wall and you’ll feel tension building in the powerful latissimus muscle (in your back, below the armpit)—not on the weak shoulder muscles. That’s Popov beginning his stroke.

这就是为什么你要抓住水并坚持住，就像你从车窗里拉出手时抵抗空气一样。通过练习，你可以在整个拉水过程中保持这种持续稳定的压力感。

And that’s why you grab the water and hold on, just as you resisted the air on your hand out the car window. With practice, you can keep that sense of pressure constant and steady throughout the whole pull.

就是这样。把手伸进去后立即猛地往后拉，你就会开始徒劳无功的练习，因为水会从冲程的一端滑到另一端。就像在冰路上磨光的轮胎一样。相反，你应该把手伸进去，稳住，为拉动做好准备，同时保持抓握，用强健的躯干肌肉而不是虚弱的肩部肌肉来上下移动手臂。欢迎来到镶钉雪地轮胎、V-8 发动机和四轮驱动的世界。

So there you have it. Jerk your hand back immediately after plunging it in and you’ve started an exercise in futility as it slips water from one end of the stroke to the other. Bald tires on an icy road. Instead, slip your hand in, anchor it to get ready for the pull, and keep your grip as you move your arm down and back using robust body-roll muscles, not weak shoulder muscles. Welcome to the world of studded snow tires, a V-8, and four-wheel drive to boot.

但仍然要注意你的牵引力。注意你拉动双手的速度。比较一下你手向后拉的速度和身体向前移动的速度。如果速度更快，你就是在滑倒，而不是在抓握。你的手永远不应该比你的身体移动得更快。不断练习，直到它们不再比身体移动得更快为止。

But still, watch your traction. Tune in to how fast your hands are moving as they pull. Compare the speed of your hands pulling back with the speed of your body moving forward. If they’re going faster, you’re slipping, not gripping. Your hands should never move faster than your body. Keep practicing until they don’t.

最后一个异端邪说。你的手只要沿着直线从这里到那里就没问题了。所以，如果有哪个穿着白大褂的游泳理论家拿着写字板和教鞭追着你，喋喋不休地谈论着“S 形划水”、“内扫”、“外扫”和“投球”，告诉他们你不会扫水，你也不是投手。告诉他们你只需要将手以直线拉回到身体下方（当然，是在身体正中央），并穿过臀部即可。如果这对 Johnny Weissmuller 来说足够好，对我们其他人来说也足够好。收杆时，甚至不用费心将手划过臀部外侧。只需笔直地用力即可。如果你的臀部运动正常，它们就会向一侧滚动，方便地避开。

One final heresy. Your hand gets from here to there just fine by following a straight line. So if any of the white-coated swimming theoreticians come after you with their clipboards and pointers, sputtering about “S-strokes” and “insweeps” and “outsweeps” and “pitches,” tell them you don’t sweep and you’re not a pitcher. Tell them you simply pull your hand in a straight line back under your body (right down the center of the body, of course) and through the hips. If it was good enough for Johnny Weissmuller, it’s good enough for the rest of us. Don’t even bother about slicing your hand back outside the hips as you finish. Just press straight through. If your hips are moving as they’re supposed to, they’ll just roll to the side, conveniently out of the way.

但请记住：首先要有一艘流畅的船，然后是一台强大的发动机，之后才是一台好的螺旋桨。不要把超过10%的训练时间花在完美运用双手上。双手只是一条线的末端的脚注，你应该从最重要的动作开始。为了方便起见，训练就是这样安排的。要事第一。

But remember: first a sleek boat, then a powerful engine, and only after that a good propeller. Don’t spend more than 10 percent or so of your available training time fussing with perfect use of the hands. They’re a footnote at the end of the line, and you want to start at the beginning where the most important action is. And conveniently, that’s how the drills are organized for you. First things first.

让我们来看看。

So let’s have a look.

5

5

鼓起勇气！——一种全新的训练方式

Some Nerve!— A Whole New Way to Train

到现在为止，你可能已经明白，如果你指望这本书能给你提供一次又一次“冠军训练”，那你来错地方了。事实上，作为一名职业游泳教练，我可以告诉你：如果说有什么东西几乎肯定会破坏你的状态，让你的进步停滞不前，那就是训练。

By now, it’s probably clear that if you expected this book to give you one “workout of champions” after another, you’ve come to the wrong place. In fact, as a professional swim coach, I can tell you this: If there’s one thing practically guaranteed to break down your form and bring improvement to a halt, it’s a workout.

想想看。按照传统定义，锻炼意味着更卖力、更长时间地训练你的心肺和肌肉，使其忽略疲劳。这意味着更多圈，或更高强度地游，或两者兼而有之——故意制造疲劳。这些传统锻炼的目的是竭尽所能让自己疲惫不堪；然后，当你成功地让自己感到疲惫时，所有你刻意练习的平衡、流畅和拉伸等关键训练都会化为泡影。一旦你的注意力分散，或者你的决心稍有减弱，你就会回到原地，继续原地奔波。

Think about it. Workouts, by conventional definition, mean working harder or longer to train your heart and lungs and muscles to ignore exhaustion. That means more laps, or harder laps, or both—fatigue by design. The point of these conventional workouts is to do all you can to tire yourself out; then, when you’ve succeeded in making yourself tired, all those crucial refinements you’ve been working on so consciously to balance, streamline, and lengthen yourself go right back out the window. The moment your concentration wavers or your resolve weakens even a little bit, you’re back to just churning along.

说到游泳，你只有拒绝再用那种姿势游泳，才能改变糟糕的泳姿。一次都不能，永远都不能。但改变并非自然而然。所以，即使“完全沉浸式”游泳项目没有给你安排任何训练，你仍然有很多工作要做。这是因为，正如我们已经说过的，你需要掌握一些技巧，才能显著地改变你的游泳水平。游泳——动态平衡、前体游泳、侧身游泳——都不是你能自然而然或本能做到的事情。你必须有意识地决定以这种方式游泳，即使你做出了选择，它们仍然是陌生的感觉，陌生的指令沿着你的神经系统传递，动作一开始会让你觉得很奇怪。你的挑战是改变它，让它们成为第二天性。这意味着，如果你想要的不仅仅是理解如何以最高效率游泳，如果你想要让这种游泳方式成为你一直以来的习惯，你必须练习特定的泳姿调整。不断练习。把它看作是一种新的训练，针对神经系统而不是有氧系统的训练。

When it comes to your swimming, you can change a poor stroke only by refusing to swim that way even once more. Not one stroke. Ever again. But the change doesn’t come naturally. So even though the Total Immersion program doesn’t throw workouts at you, you can be sure there’s still plenty of work to do. That’s because, as we’ve already said, the techniques you’ll need to make a dramatic difference in your swimming—dynamic balance, front-quadrant swimming, swimming on your side—are things you just don’t do naturally or instinctively. You have to make a conscious decision to swim that way, and even when you have, they’ll still be foreign sensations, alien commands traveling along your nervous system, movements that feel funny at first. Your challenge is to change that, to make them second nature. This means that if you want to go beyond just understanding how to swim with maximum efficiency, if you want to make it the way you swim all the time, an absolute habit, you have to practice specific stroke modifications. And practice, and practice. Think of it as a new kind of training, training that targets the nervous system instead of the aerobic system.

别担心。对于那些缺乏青春、力量、基因或没有时间进行“真正”训练的人来说，这并不是一个毫不掩饰的“安慰奖”。事实上，这才是真正了解自己运动项目的冠军们训练的方式。亚历山大·波波夫，当今世界上最快的游泳运动员，凭借非凡的效率，在前所未闻的十一年里连续赢得世界冠军，并在2003年赢得了两项世界冠军。

Don’t worry. This isn’t a thinly disguised “consolation prize” alternative for people without the youth or the power or the genetics or the hour-upon-hour of time to do “real” workouts. It is, in fact, the way the true champions who understand their sport train themselves. And Alexander Popov, the fastest swimmer in the world today, has used extraordinary efficiency to continue winning world championships for an unheard-of eleven years, as he won two world titles in 2003.

从1988年到1992年，近五年时间里，美国游泳运动员马特·比昂迪一直稳坐冠军宝座。他实至名归。比昂迪的游泳效率比任何对手都高，并且在专项比赛中保持不败。1992年奥运会期间，比昂迪已经宣布这将是他的最后一场比赛，波波夫似乎成了冠军的继承人。多年来，他的教练一直录像研究比昂迪，将这位冠军——世界上最高效的游泳姿势——作为他这位冉冉升起的新星的榜样。教练和游泳运动员孜孜不倦地练习，力求掌握比昂迪那样的动作。

For nearly five years, from 1988 to 1992, the American swimmer Matt Biondi had a hammerlock on that title. He deserved it. Biondi swam more efficiently than any of his rivals and was undefeated in his specialty events. During the 1992 Olympics, with Biondi having already announced it would be his last meet, Popov seemed the heir apparent. For several years his coach had videotaped and studied Biondi, using the champion’s stroke—the world’s most efficient—as a model for his rising star. Coach and swimmer worked tirelessly to master Biondi-like movements.

决战在巴塞罗那举行，在 50 米自由泳决赛中。该项目是终极效率实验室，是所有短跑项目中最纯粹的短跑项目——一个泳道，没有转身，大约 20 秒就完赛。波波夫和比昂迪站在八人决赛中间相邻泳道的起跑器上，枪声响起，选手们沿着泳池飞驰而去。波波夫以 21.8 秒率先触地，比昂迪以 22.0 秒紧随其后。一位新的奥运冠军就此诞生。但最让分析家们惊讶的是，波波夫不仅以较大优势击败比昂迪，而且在比昂迪最长的一项——划水效率上彻底击败了他。波波夫用了 34 划水，比昂迪用了 37 划水。时间差距可能只有 1%，但三划水的差异，世界上两位最优秀的短跑运动员之间接近 10% 的效率差距，几乎是不可想象的。

The showdown came in Barcelona, in the final of the 50-meter free. That event is the ultimate efficiency laboratory, the purest sprint event of them all—one length, no turns, over in maybe 20 seconds. Popov and Biondi stood on the blocks in adjacent lanes in the middle of the eight-man final heat, the gun went off, and the field streaked down the pool. Popov touched first in 21.8 seconds, Biondi right behind at 22.0 seconds. A new Olympic champion had been crowned. But what most amazed analysts was that Popov had not only beaten Biondi by a comfortable margin, he had beaten him thoroughly at Biondi’s longest suit—stroke efficiency. Popov had taken 34 strokes, Biondi 37. The time gap may have been just 1 percent, but the three-stroke difference, an efficiency gap of nearly 10 percent between the world’s two best sprinters, was nearly inconceivable.

这只是全新效率标准的开端。此后数年，波波夫继续称霸短距离项目，不断提升效率和速度的标准。波波夫能够以更少的体力游出惊人的速度，因此未来没有哪个游泳选手能够威胁到他在短距离项目上的统治地位。当其他人都在拼命努力时，效率超群的波波夫却仿佛在优雅地滑行。

It was just the beginning of a new efficiency standard. In the years since, Popov has continued to dominate the sprint events, raising the bar again and again for efficiency and speed. No swimmer on the horizon threatens his stranglehold on the sprint because Popov can swim at startling speeds with much less effort. While everyone else is working furiously, the supremely efficient Popov just seems to be gliding majestically along.

这位冠军能给我们其他人的教训是，这一切可能根本不会发生。如果他像其他人一样，每天花几个小时在泳池里快速游动——锻炼——他就会养成效率更低的划水习惯，最终沦为群体中的普通游泳者——尽管他已经是一群非常优秀的游泳者。然而，他接受了精准技术的训练，所以这变成了一种习惯。比赛当天，随着氧债的增加，他的心率飙升，肌肉也随之悸动，与对手们一样；其他人的状态他会崩溃——哪怕只是一点点；但他不会，而且即使这点微弱的优势也足以让他每次都赢。他出色的表现证明了练习胜过训练，证明了你的神经系统至少和你的有氧系统一样训练有素——用心工作，而不是徒劳无功。

The lesson this champion can teach the rest of us is that it might not have happened at all. Had he simply swum as others did, obsessed with moving briskly up and down the pool for several hours a day— working out—he would have developed less efficient stroke habits and turned into just another swimmer in the pack—albeit a very good pack. Instead he was trained to practice precise technique so it became utter habit. On race day, as his oxygen debt mounts, heart rate soars, and muscles throb, along with his opponents’; everyone else’s form breaks down—if only a little bit; his doesn’t, and even that modest edge is enough to win every time. His sterling performances are proof of the victory of practice over training, of having a nervous system that’s at least as well trained as your aerobic system—working smart rather than working out.

学习与训练：我们如何培养技能

Learning Versus Training: How We Build a Skill

完全沉浸式学习系统比其他所有成人游泳教学方法都更有效，因为它是唯一一种以我们学习新技能的最佳方式——小步教学——来教授新技能的方法。就你的身体而言，锻炼手臂肌肉和训练手臂肌肉以高效的泳姿运动完全不同。技能涉及感觉、习惯和动作，这些动作一开始会让人感到笨拙，必须让它们变得自然。因此，学习一项技能最好是循序渐进，将大任务分解成小部分，然后循序渐进地重新组合，使每个步骤都易于掌握。而判断你是否掌握得当的最有效方法就是感受。在本课程中，你将被要求练习的每一个动作，都旨在让即使是新手也能体验到顶尖运动员对游泳关键动作的感受。到目前为止，每位游泳专家都告诉你奥运会游泳运动员的泳姿是什么样的。但模仿外表很难，而模仿感受则容易得多。

The Total Immersion learning system has outperformed all other methods of teaching adults to swim because it’s the only one that teaches new skills the way we learn them best—in small pieces. As far as your body is concerned, the job of pumping up an arm muscle is altogether different from teaching that arm muscle to move in an efficient swimming stroke. Skills involve feelings, habits, movements that feel awkward at first and must be made to feel natural. So learning a skill is best organized into a step-by-step process that breaks the big job down into bite-size parts, then recombines them so gradually that each step is easy to master. And the most effective way to tell if you’ve got it all right is by feel. Every movement you’ll be asked to practice in this program is designed to give even the newest swimmer a taste of what the key parts of the swimming stroke feel like to an elite athlete. Up to now, every swimming expert has told you how the strokes of an Olympic swimmer look. But looks are hard to mimic. Feelings are much easier.

然而，一遍又一遍地重复同样的事情并不能让你成为任何领域的专家——包括自由泳的泳姿。我们都听说过那个倒霉的绅士漫无目的地游到纽约市第 57 街的一位女士拿着小提琴盒，最后拦住一位路人问道：“打扰一下，请问我怎样去卡内基音乐厅？”

However, just doing the same thing over and over won’t make you an expert at anything either—including the freestyle swim stroke. We’ve all heard of the hapless gentleman wandering aimlessly down New York City’s 57th Street carrying a violin case, finally stopping a passerby to ask, “Excuse me, but how do I get to Carnegie Hall?”

讽刺的回答是：“练习！练习！练习！”

The sardonic reply: “Practice! Practice! Practice!”

这句话虽然简洁，但只对了一半。假设他确实练习了，但没听。如果他每天只是用弓刮弦，不管发出什么声音，都很高兴自己的手臂肌肉得到了锻炼，这样第二天他就能花更多时间刮出难听的声音了，那会怎么样？

Snappy but only half true. Suppose he did practice, but without hearing. What if he just scraped his bow over the strings each day no matter what squawks came out, happy that he was getting his arm muscles in shape so he could spend even more time scraping out ugly sounds the next day?

荒谬？除非你完全确定你——或许还有你认识的大多数人——多年来练习游泳的方式并非如此，否则别回答。音乐家们投入大量时间排练，只为创造出美妙的声音，但练习时间的质量对他们来说远比数量重要。游泳运动员也应该如此。我们必须明白，练习只是让你正在练习的一切——无论好坏——都变得永久。

Ridiculous? Don’t answer until you’re absolutely sure that’s not how you—and probably most of the people you know—have been practicing your own swimming for years. Musicians dedicate monumental amounts of rehearsal to produce beautiful sounds, but the quality of their practice time matters to them far more than the quantity. So it should be for swimmers. Practice, we must come to understand, merely makes permanent whatever you happen to be practicing. Good or bad.

如果你和大多数游泳者一样，那么在你的有氧银行账户里存钱是你最关心的事情。当然，你知道，做到这一点的方法是让你的心脏保持在有氧范围内工作，通常持续一个小时左右。本质上，游泳训练会产生额外的心跳。如果你的有氧训练范围是每分钟120次，而你的步行心率是每分钟80次，那么一小时的训练就能产生2400次额外的心跳。对于像跑步这样非技术性运动来说，这是一个非常不错的投资回报。但在游泳方面则不然。

If you’re like most swimmers, making deposits in your aerobic bank account is your main concern. And of course you know that you do that by keeping your heart working in the aerobic range, usually for an hour or so. In essence, a swim workout creates extra heartbeats. If your aerobic training range is 120 beats per minute and your walking-around heart rate is 80, an hourlong workout will create 2,400 extra heartbeats. A perfectly good return on your investment in a nontechnical sport like running. But not in swimming.

在水中，你每2400次心跳，都会记录一个更重要的数值，那就是你划水的大约2000次。每一次划水都会在你的中枢神经系统留下微弱的印象，形成一种运动模式——一种习惯。如果你曾经游了几年泳，这些划水习惯已经相当牢固了。现在停下来想一想：既然2400次“健身”心跳只影响你游泳表现的30%，而2000次“技巧”划水影响了你游泳表现的70%左右，正如我们之前所说，哪一个更值得你关注？没错。你已经开始像全浸式游泳者一样思考了，你准备将游泳视为肌肉记忆，而不是肌肉力量。

In the water, you’re ringing up a far more important tally during the course of those 2,400 heartbeats, and that tally is the 2,000 or so strokes you take. Each one leaves a faint impression on your central nervous system, forming a pattern of movement—a habit. If you’ve been swimming for a few years, those stroke habits have become pretty strong. Now stop and think: Since the 2,400 “fitness” heartbeats impact only about 30 percent of your swimming performance while the 2,000 “skill” strokes affect about 70 percent, as we said earlier, which one deserves more of your attention? Right. You’re beginning to think like a Total Immersion swimmer already, and you’re getting ready to see swimming as a matter of muscle memory, not muscle power.

肌肉记忆就是教练所说的熟悉的、习惯性的动作模式。正是因为有了肌肉记忆，你才能骑自行车、系鞋带、在电脑上打字，而无需停下来思考。一旦你掌握了一项技能，你就可以让肌肉接管一切。不幸的是，如果你的技能学得不好，它们也会同样积极地接管。如果你认为它们想放弃这些习惯，那就再想想吧。

Muscle memory is what coaches call familiar, habitual patterns of movement. Thanks to muscle memory, you can ride a bike, tie your shoelaces, and type on a computer without stopping and thinking about it. Once you learn a skill well, you can just let your muscles take over. Unfortunately, they’ll take over just as aggressively if you’ve learned a skill badly. And if you think they’re interested in giving up those habits, think again.

肌肉记忆就像一张播放过数百次的旧黑胶唱片。唱针一遍又一遍地在唱片的凹槽中划过，逐渐磨损得更深。在运动中，你的肌肉和神经系统会越来越“习惯”以相同的方式自动执行动作。如果你的击球动作高效，那就没问题。如果效率低下，那就不好了。练习得足够久，糟糕的击球动作几乎不会改变。

Muscle memory is like an old vinyl LP that has been played hundreds of times. The stylus, tracking in the record’s grooves over and over, gradually wears them deeper. In sports, your muscles and nervous system become more and more “grooved” to automatically execute a movement the same way. Fine if your stroke is efficient. Not fine if it’s not. Practiced for long enough, a bad stroke becomes almost immune to change.

几乎免疫。但这是可以做到的。要打破低效的旧习惯，让新的高效习惯取而代之，需要的是决心，先消除，再取代。你必须确保你训练中2000次划水的每一次都尽可能地像熟练游泳者那样高效。如果只满足于更少的划水，你就会变成一个水平较低的游泳者。

Almost immune. But it can be done. What it takes to break old, inefficient habits so new, efficient ones can take their place is the determination to first erase, then replace. You have to make sure that every one of those 2,000 strokes in your workout hour is as much as possible like the economical strokes of skilled swimmers. Settle for less and you’re training to become a less accomplished swimmer.

那么，为什么大多数健身游泳运动员——甚至是渴望获得奖牌的运动员有教练的竞技运动员——大部分泳池时间都用来训练，试图通过增加游泳圈数、提高游泳难度或减少组间休息来改善生理机能？他们的水平正在走下坡路。注意力不集中、疲劳、努力跟上时间或追赶其他游泳运动员，都会逐渐降低他们的效率。最终，他们只会重复犯错。

So why do most lap-and-fitness swimmers—and even medal-hungry competitive athletes with coaches—spend most of their pool time working out, trying to improve their physiology with more laps or harder laps or less rest between repeats? They’re on a downhill road. Faltering concentration, fatigue, trying to keep pace with the clock or keep up with another swimmer, will all gradually erode their efficiency. They end up practicing their mistakes.

今天就开始改变吧。从一名纯粹的训练型游泳者转变为一名练习型游泳者。作为一名纯粹的训练型游泳者，划水动作只是让你从泳池的一端游到另一端的工具。游泳圈才是关键，成绩更是神圣不可侵犯。作为一名练习型游泳者，你会意识到每一次划水都是对你未来游泳生涯的一项投资，每一圈都是一个机会，让你要么将划水动作打造成一台运转良好的机器，让你游得更快更远，要么将其分解成一团费力的混乱。练习型游泳者不会更加努力，而是会用同样甚至更少的努力来获取更多益处。

Start your change today. Begin your transformation from a strictly workout swimmer to a practice swimmer. As a workout-only swimmer, strokes were just something that got you from one end of the pool to the other. Laps were the point. The tally was sacred. As a practice swimmer you’ll realize that each stroke is an investment in your swimming future, each lap a chance to either build your stroke into a well-oiled machine for carrying you fast and far or to break it down into a laborious mess. A practice swimmer works no harder, instead squeezing more good out of the same—or even less—effort.

与此同时，你的肌肉力量会发生奇妙的变化，就像亚历山大·波波夫的经历一样。即使力量不再是你的终极追求，它也会增长，但真正让你高效运动的肌肉会变得越来越强。波波夫正是通过不断练习才成为世界顶尖游泳运动员。而与此同时，他的肌肉也变得强健，足以打破世界纪录。为了最大限度地发挥你的生理机能，与其关心游了多少码，不如更多地关注每次划水时你的身体游了多少码。你仍然可以额外获得2400次心跳，你的肌肉仍然会得到锻炼。你又能失去什么呢？

And while all this is going on, a curious thing will happen to your muscle strength, just as it happened to Alexander Popov’s. Even though strength is no longer your holy grail, it will grow, but it will be the muscles that move you most efficiently growing stronger. Popov got to be the best in the world by practicing. And while he was doing that, his muscles grew fit enough to break world records. To get the most from your physiology, be less concerned with how many yards you swim and more concerned with how many yards your body travels each time you take a stroke. You’ll still get the extra 2,400 heartbeats and your muscles will still get a workout. What can you lose?

让这2400次心跳为你服务

Make Those 2,400 Heartbeats Work for You

在TI周末研讨会上，我们耐心地解释了几个小时，游泳的70%是机械效率，只有30%是体能，练习比锻炼更有价值，并敦促参与者将体能视为“练习良好技巧时自然而然发生的事情”。我们仍然期待着大家对游泳运动员需要达到什么样的体能水平感到好奇。总有人会问：“是啊，但是我每周需要游多少码才能为1500米铁人三项游泳项目做好准备呢？”

During TI Weekend Workshops, after patiently explaining for hours that swimming is 70 percent mechanical efficiency and only 30 percent fitness, that practice is more valuable than workout, and urging participants to regard fitness as “something that happens to you while you’re practicing good technique,” we still expect curiosity over just how fit a swimmer needs to be. Someone always asks: “Yeah, but how many yards a week do I need to be ready for a 1500-meter triathlon swim leg?”

我们告诉他们，健身很重要，非常重要，但原因可能并非你想象的那样。你想要保持最佳体型的原因并非成为一名力量型运动员，而是成为一名精准型运动员——这样你就能在更长的距离、更高的速度和更高的心率下，继续运用你的高水平技术。正因如此，我们的训练计划从最简单的方式开始：以高效的动作、短距离、低速度和低心率进行训练。你逐渐提升自己的能力，以便更长时间、更努力、更快地保持这种体型。听起来很像比赛准备，不是吗？

Fitness is important, we tell them, very important, but not for the reasons you’ve probably thought. The reason you want to be in the best possible shape is not to be a powerful athlete but a precision one—so you can keep using your high-level technique over longer distances, at higher speeds and higher heart rates. That’s the reason our program starts in the easiest possible way: with efficient movements, over short distances, at low speeds, and at low heart rates. You gradually build your capacity to hold that form longer, harder, and faster. Sounds a lot like race preparation, doesn’t it?

所以，健身的重要作用是帮助你保持体形。但并非所有健身都一样。我定期参加大师游泳比赛。参加比赛时，我通常会在夏天瞄准地区或全国公开水域锦标赛，花几个月的时间进行高强度、专注的备战。夏天过后，我会减少游泳训练，开始每周跑步几次，以改变节奏。每次我都会这样做，无论我训练多么刻苦，身体状况多么好我已经进入水中，我的肌肉粗鲁地提醒我，作为一名跑步者，我还是个新手。

So the big role of fitness is to help you hold your form. But all fitness is not alike. I compete in Masters swimming on a semiregular basis. When I do, I usually target a regional or national open-water championship in the summer, devoting several months to intense, focused preparation. After the summer I cut back on my swimming and start running several times a week for a change of pace. And every time I do, no matter how hard I’ve worked and how well-conditioned I’ve gotten myself in the water, my muscles rudely remind me that as a runner, I’m a rookie.

这和你在泳池里换泳姿时发生的情况是一样的。如果我主要进行自由泳训练，那么在蛙泳比赛的前半段能感觉良好就算幸运了。后半段就会陷入一场与肌肉纤维的殊死搏斗，这些肌肉纤维因为缺乏训练而一个接一个地退出。蛙泳肌肉和自由泳肌肉不同。如果它们是新来的，它们撑不了多久。

It’s the same thing that happens right in the pool when you switch strokes. If I’ve done mostly freestyle training, I’ll be lucky to feel good for the first half of a breaststroke race. The second half crumbles into a desperate struggle against muscle fibers that are quitting one after the other because they simply haven’t been trained. Breaststroke muscles are different from freestyle muscles. If they’re new to the job, they won’t do it for very long.

现在让我们更细致地区分一下。你甚至在以良好姿势游自由泳时使用的肌肉和以不良姿势游自由泳时使用的肌肉也是不同的。如果训练得马虎一些，你那些状态更好、但姿势不佳的肌肉反而会保持良好的状态。你可以猜到接下来会发生什么。到了比赛时间——或者甚至是比平时更长的训练时间——你那本意良好的大脑会给你的身体发出正确的激励信号（“好了，现在，让我们真正保持良好的姿势！”），但如果你没有训练它所针对的肌肉，它们的回答很快就会是“算了”。你将只能依靠“马虎游泳”的力量。

Now let’s cut the distinction finer still. You even use different muscles for swimming freestyle with good form than you do with poor form. Train sloppily and your better-conditioned poor-form muscles will be in great shape. You can guess what happens next. Come race time—or even a longer-than-usual workout—your well-intentioned brain will give your body the right pep talk (“Okay, now, let’s really hold good form here!”), but if you haven’t trained the muscles it’s talking to, their answer will quickly be “Forget it.” You’ll be stuck with “sloppy-swimming” power.

无论追求速度还是距离，没有人能侥幸逃脱。无论是最高速度还是有效耐力，都无法靠代练肌肉来实现。如果你在大师赛中用60秒游完了100码自由泳，现在想在58秒内完成，你的首要目标就是训练自己在动作更快的情况下保持效率。你会获得那两秒甚至更多的时间。或者说，你用36分钟完成了1500米铁人三项的游泳项目，现在想在30分钟内完成。现在的策略是保持更长时间的效率。如果你以前在300米左右的时候划水不稳定，现在却能一直保持状态到最后1200米，你肯定会在完成时间上取得很大进步。除非你像波波夫一样，为你的肌肉进行编程，否则这一切都不会发生。

Nobody can get away with that whether they go for speed or distance. Neither top speed nor effective endurance can be achieved with pinch-hitting stand-in muscles. If you swim the 100-yard freestyle in a Masters meet in 60 seconds and would like to do it in 58, your primary goal is to train yourself to stay efficient as you move everything faster. You’ll get those two seconds and more. Or say you do a 1500-meter triathlon swim leg in 36 minutes and would like to do it in 30. Now the strategy is to stay efficient longer. If you used to get a shaky stroke at around 300 meters, and can now hold form right through the final 1200, you’re going to make a serious dent in that finishing time. None of that happens unless, like Popov, you program your muscles to do it.

除了肌肉在完成每一次划水动作时的工作之外，你认为是什么首先激发了它们？没错，是神经系统。虽然训练过程的这一部分几乎总是被忽视，但神经系统也会储存你在泳池中大约一个小时里所做的一切。一圈又一圈，它会选择性地招募肌肉“运动单位”以特定的方式移动你的胳膊和腿，并边做边学。就像肌肉本身一样，你要么训练它变得习惯性高效，要么训练它变得习惯性低效。如果你在一个小时内经常让你的效率下降，那么你的神经系统就会准备好在下一次和下下下一次为你做些什么。它会记住的。你需要确保它记住你想要它记住的事情。

And more than your muscles are working to form every stroke. What do you think fires them in the first place? Right. The nervous system. And though this part of the training process is almost always overlooked, the nervous system also stores away everything you do during that hour or so you’re in the pool. Lap after lap it selectively recruits muscle “motor units” to move your arms and legs in certain ways, learning as it goes. Just as with the muscles themselves, you’re either training it to be habitually efficient or habitually inefficient. Routinely let your efficiency slip over the course of an hour and that’s just what your nervous system will be ready to do for you next time and the time after that. It will remember. You need to make sure it remembers what you want it to.

通过成功练习学习技能

Learning Skills with Success Drills

新的铁人三项运动员常常会惊讶于自己能够在二十年没有骑车之后重新拿起自行车，并且感觉自己一天也没有错过。没有生疏，不需要重新学习——嗖！他们出发了。那是因为这种能力已经存在很多年了；只是被储存起来了。这项技能很容易再次掌握，因为它相当简单——循环、有节奏，手脚固定就位。除了平衡和转向之外，你不需要重新打磨太多，而且这不需要很长时间，因为我们小时候骑车的经历在我们的神经系统上留下了强大而永久的印记。你的自行车骑行唱片上的神经凹槽已经很深了。唱针永远不会跳动。而且演奏起来要简单得多。

New triathletes are often amazed that they can pick up a bike after a cycling layoff of twenty years and feel like they never missed a day. No rustiness, no relearning—zoom! Off they go. That’s because the ability has been there all those years; it’s just been in storage. The skill comes out again easily because it’s fairly simple—cyclical, rhythmic, hands and feet fixed in place. You don’t have to repolish much besides your balance and steering, and that doesn’t take long because all the time we spent doing it as kids left a powerful and permanent imprint on our nervous systems. The neural groove on your bike-riding LP is already deep. The needle never jumps. And it’s a much simpler tune to play.

当然，游泳和网球不一样。虽然表面上看，这两项运动似乎没什么共同点，但它们之间的共同点远比大多数运动员——以及他们的大多数教练——意识到的要多得多。事实上，要了解身体如何最好地学习一项技能，以及全浸式训练系统为何如此有效地加速这一过程，就必须观察一名运动员在优秀教练的指导下在网球场上学习的情景。

Swimming, of course, is nothing like that. Neither is tennis. And though on the surface there seems little to unite those sports, they have far more in common than most athletes—and most of their coaches— realize. In fact, the way to understand how the body best learns a skill and why the Total Immersion training system is so effective at speeding that process along is to watch someone with a good coach learning his or her way around the tennis courts.

首先，基础。网球和游泳都是运动技能型运动，需要力量和耐力才能成功。在游泳中，技巧和耐力的结合能让你在泳池中游得更快、更远、更轻松。在网球中，技巧能让你精准地将球打到你想要的位置，而耐力则能追赶回球，并避免因划水而产生的疲劳感。

First, the basics. Tennis and swimming are both motor-skill sports that also take strength and endurance for success. In swimming, skill and stamina combine to move you up and down the pool faster, farther, and easier. In tennis, skill puts the ball right where you want it, while stamina chases down the return and holds stroke-crippling fatigue at bay.

所以，你可能会认为游泳运动员和网球运动员会互相学习有用的训练技巧，但事实并非如此。你可能会认为他们会意识到彼此的训练方式很相似——或者应该如此。但他们并没有。游泳运动员试图通过更多游泳来提高水平。但他们并没有。

So you’d think swimmers and tennis players would learn useful training techniques from each other, but they don’t. You’d think they’d realize their practices are a lot alike—or should be. But they don’t. Swimmers try to improve just by swimming more. But they don’t.

网球运动员的悟性更快。许多人一开始都是“照做”，找个能忍耐的搭档，然后来回击球。通常这样进步不大。尤其是在刚开始的时候，他们花在追跑球上的时间比打对打的时间还多。很快他们就会意识到，如果连球都控制不住，就很难进步。

Tennis players wise up faster. Many start the same way by “just doing it,” digging up a tolerant partner and smacking the ball back and forth. They usually don’t get very far that way. In the beginning especially, they spend more time chasing down wayward balls than hitting rallies. It soon dawns that they won’t improve much if they can’t even keep the ball in play.

于是他们报名参加了一位网球专业人士的课程。毕竟，“专业人士”这个词听起来清脆悦耳，非常……嗯，非常专业。“教练”，比如游泳教练，则暗示着只会告诉你如何挥汗如雨的人。很多时候，这两种含义都恰到好处，这对网球运动员来说非常有利。

So they sign up for lessons with a tennis pro. “Pro,” after all, has a nice, crisp ring that sounds so …well, so professional. “Coach,” as in swimming coach, implies someone who just tells you how to sweat. Too often, both implications are on target, to the great advantage of the tennis player.

网球专业人士深知，对学生来说，最重要的事是传授知识，而不是训练。他们需要掌握能在球场上保持竞争力的技能，而专业人士需要帮助学生学得更快，并尽可能减少困惑。这意味着要从最简单的动作开始——基本击球的几个小片段。例如，在正手课上，学生只需双脚站立，球拍向后，老师将球抛起，使球在齐腰高度轻轻弹起，几乎是自动落到拍线处。这样就能保证回球成功。

The tennis pro understands that the most important thing to do for his or her students is teach them, not train them. They need to master skills that will make them competitive on the court, and the pro needs to help those students learn faster and with the least possible confusion. That means starting off with the simplest possible movements— small segments of the basic strokes. In the forehand lesson, for example, the student simply stands with his feet planted in one spot, racquet held back, while the teacher lobs the ball so that it bounces up softly at waist height and practically into the strings of the racquet all by itself. A successful return is guaranteed.

即便如此，最初的十几二十次挥拍动作仍显得笨拙、机械、飘忽不定。渐渐地，它们变得更加流畅、精准、连贯。随着肌肉和神经记录并记住有效挥拍和无效挥拍之间的区别，学习和整理的过程开始了。如果球飞出了界外，学生就会从肌肉记忆中“抹去”这次挥拍。如果球正好落在她想要的位置，她就会一遍又一遍地重复这次挥拍。她不仅能看到自己的成功和失败，还能感受到它们。击球失误时，震动的“砰”的一声直冲她的前臂，而球拍击中“甜蜜点”的精准“砰”的一声，感觉和听起来都真实扎实。每一次，经验都被“写入”神经系统的磁盘，最终，成千上万次这样的运动技能“实验”开始构建一个庞大的神经肌肉经验数据库。当然，其中只有一两次能打出好球，所以学生的肌肉会逐渐掌握如何做到这一点。这时，职业球员就会看到特别有成就感的事情：回球几乎是自动的了。第一步完成了。基本的正手击球技巧已经融入肌肉记忆中。

Even so, the first ten or twenty are awkward, mechanical, erratic. Gradually they grow smoother, more accurate, more consistent. The learning and sorting-out have begun as muscles and nerves catalogue and memorize the difference between swings that work and swings that don’t. If a ball flies out of bounds, the student “erases” that swing from muscle memory. If it ends up just where she wants it, she replays that one over and over. Not only can she see her successes and failures, she can feel them. The jolting thwwoong of a vibrating mis-hit rockets right up her forearm, while the precise pong of the racket’s “sweet spot” feels and sounds solid and true. Each time, the experience is “written to disk” in the nervous system where, eventually, hundreds and thousands of such “experiments” in movement skill begin to build a vast neuromuscular database of experiences. Only one or two of those resulted in hitting a good ball, of course, so gradually the student’s muscles figure out how to do just those. That’s when the pro sees something especially rewarding: The returns are now virtually automatic. Step one is complete. The basic forehand has become encoded in muscle memory.

学习任何新的运动技能都是一种类似的解决问题和反复尝试的过程。但过多的错误可能会令人沮丧，热情也会随之消散，进步的机会也会随之消失。秘诀在于练习你能做到的，而不是你做不到的。一项容易掌握的基本技能可以成为更高级技能的跳板，以此类推。你每一步都能看到成果。

Learning any new motor skill is a similar problem-solving, trial-and-error exercise. But too much error can be so discouraging that enthusiasm goes right down the drain, and with it the chance to improve. The secret is to practice something you can do, not something you can’t. An easily mastered basic skill becomes the springboard for a more advanced one, and so on. You see results every step of the way.

这就是为什么职业选手要等到第二步才开始击球，让比赛看起来更像一场真正的网球比赛。学生会想，这应该很有趣，直到她漂亮、流畅、协调的基本击球再次变得支离破碎，因为她现在需要猜测球的落点，然后才能想出如何用球拍击球。想一想，仅仅是击球背后意味着什么。大脑和肌肉会观察球的轨迹和方向，计算球的落点，冲向那个位置，并在球到达之前将双脚和躯干调整到位，准备挥拍。只有这样，他们才能运用现在已熟悉的基本技能——回球。此外，他们现在需要根据球的落点和速度，为每一次击球制定独特的计划。仅仅掌握基本的网球技巧，可能需要几十节这样的课程。显然，要想在技能培养的荒野中脱颖而出，唯一的方法就是采用循序渐进的学习体系和有组织的练习，带领学生完成整个过程。

That’s why the pro waits until step two to hit the ball around, making it seem a little more like a real game of tennis. This should be fun, the student thinks, until her nice, new, smooth, and coordinated basic stroke turns to shreds again as she now tries to second-guess where the ball is going to be before she can figure out how to meet it with her racquet. Think for a minute what’s behind just getting to the ball. Mind and muscles watch the ball’s trajectory and direction, compute where it’s going to land, rush to that spot, and get the feet and torso into position to swing before the ball arrives. Only then do they get to use that now-familiar basic skill—returning the ball. Moreover, they now need a unique program for each shot depending on where the ball lands and how fast it’s going. It may take dozens of such lessons just to develop a rudimentary tennis game. Obviously, the only way to make sense out of the wilderness of skill building is by a stepwise system of learning, and practice that’s organized to take the student through it.

这正是大多数游泳教学所缺失的。游泳教练们花费大量时间进行训练，却很少花时间进行教学，以至于很少有人真正思考过如何将这项同样复杂的运动分解成一系列可以循序渐进教授的基本动作。相反，他们的划水建议往往是零散的、突如其来的，而不是一系列可以掌握的“成功经验”。快速学习，这会自动为下一个技能奠定基础。他们的游泳运动员花了太多时间练习整个划水动作，却始终无法完全流畅地掌握每个动作。而通过“全浸入式”教学，我们则像网球专业人士一样进行教学。

Which is exactly what’s been missing from most swimming instruction. Swimming coaches spend so much time training and so little time teaching that few have ever really thought about how to break down their equally complex sport into a series of fundamentals that can be taught step by step. Instead, their stroke advice comes in scattershot bursts, not in a series of “success lessons” that can be mastered quickly and that automatically lay the groundwork for the next skill. Their swimmers spend too much time swimming the whole stroke, never quite able to achieve fluency in all its parts. With Total Immersion, we teach like the tennis pro instead.

但有一个重要的区别。网球运动员比游泳运动员有一个很大的优势：他们能看到自己的结果，而且是立竿见影。球要么打对了，要么打错了。游泳运动员没有那么明显的指导。除非有人像教练一样站在池边对你大喊大叫，否则你只能依靠水囊里的感觉。所以，你的技能训练必须融入“感觉反馈”，让你的神经末梢成为你的教练。

With one important difference. Tennis players have a big advantage over swimmers: They can see their results, and they can see them right away. Ball goes right or ball goes wrong. Swimmers have nothing that obvious to guide them. Unless someone is standing poolside bellowing at you like a coach as you swim, you have to rely on how things feel inside your water capsule. So your skill-building drills must be designed with “feeling feedback,” letting your nerve endings be your coach.

让我们回到你能做的最重要的改进——保持身体的平衡和稳定。这并非与生俱来，也不是自然而然就能做到的，而能凭本能保持平衡的游泳新手就像平衡的联邦预算一样稀有。大多数人需要多年的反复练习才能自己找到平衡点，如果他们真的能做到的话。我们的技能训练完全跳过了反复练习，而是通过告诉你应该追求什么样的感觉，让你快速完成过程中的每个关键步骤。例如，你可以在三十分钟或更短的时间内学会平衡。通过一次又一次的练习，省去了数小时的无休止的实验，我们让整个学习过程进入了高速运转的状态。

Let’s go back to the most critical improvement you can make—getting your body balanced and stable. It doesn’t come naturally, it doesn’t feel natural, and new swimmers who balance by instinct are as rare as a balanced federal budget. It takes most people years of trial-and-error practice to figure out balance on their own, if they ever do. Our skill drills skip trial and error entirely and, by telling you what feeling you should aim for, put you through each critical step of the process quickly. You can learn balance, for instance, in thirty minutes or less. Drill by drill, cutting out hour after hour of dead-end experimentation, we put the whole learning process into high gear.

这就是完全沉浸式的游泳方式。现在你意识到你的技能比你的体能更能让你走得更远，你不再锻炼——你练习。你会尽可能多地对自己说：“体能就是我在练习好技巧时自然而然发生的事情。”然后不断练习，因为你现在也知道旧习惯很难改掉，尤其是肌肉上的旧习惯。如果你曾经事实上，你已经在无人指导的情况下游泳好几年了，你可能已经练习了太多次低效的游泳方式，以至于你的身体已经完全掌握了游泳技巧。要想学习更好的游泳方式，你必须摒弃你一直坚持的游泳方式，这意味着你永远都不能再这样做了。你每游一段距离，姿势都很糟糕，进步就更加困难。

So that’s swimming, the Total Immersion way. Realizing now that your skills carry you a lot farther than your fitness, you don’t work out anymore—you practice. And you repeat to yourself as often as necessary: “Fitness is something that happens to me while I’m practicing good technique.” And practicing, and practicing, because now you also know that old habits die hard, especially old muscle habits. If you’ve been swimming without instruction for several years, in fact, you’ve probably had so much practice at inefficient swimming that your body is an absolute champion at it. To learn a better way of swimming, you have to unlearn the one you’re stuck with, which means never doing it again. Every length you swim with poor form makes it harder to improve.

确保你以糟糕的姿势游完最后一程的方法是使用网球专业人士早已完善的循序渐进的策略。在帮助运动员培养良好技术方面，球拍运动没有任何理由比水上运动更好。网球运动员可能更早意识到这一点，但有了“全浸式”训练，游泳运动员现在也能做到了。

And the way we’ll make sure you’ve swum your last length with poor form is to use the same step-by-step strategy that tennis pros perfected long ago. There’s no reason for racquet sports to be any better than water sports at helping athletes build good technique. Tennis players may have gotten wise sooner, but with Total Immersion, swimmers are now there too.

网球训练计划之所以如此有效，是因为它制定了一系列易于掌握的小技巧，这些小技巧逐渐串联起来，形成一项更流畅、更有力的比赛。如今，高效的游泳也可以通过同样合乎逻辑、循序渐进的过程来教授。这一切都始于游泳者神经系统最好的朋友：技能训练。它让复杂变得简单，让令人畏惧变得轻松，让困难变得轻松。在下一章中，这项小技巧终于来到了泳池。

The tennis program works so well because it meters out a series of easily mastered mini-skills that gradually link together into a smoother, more powerful game. Efficient swimming can now be taught in the same logical, step-by-step process. It all starts with the best friend your swimmer’s nervous system ever had: the skill drill. It makes the complex simple, the intimidating comfortable, and the difficult easy. In the next chapter, the mini-skill finally arrives at the pool.

再见，“教练”。欢迎来到与“游泳专家”的第一堂课。

Good-bye, “coach.” Welcome to your first lesson with the “swimming pro.”

6

6

技巧训练：提高击球速度的最快方法

Skill Drills: The Fastest Way to a Faster Stroke

有时我想，如果我们把这件事交给专家来做，那么唯一敢于穿上泳衣的人就是那些满怀奥运梦想的优秀运动员，以及那些无忧无虑、毫无梦想的孩子。因为“专家”们都警告我们：高效的游泳姿势是一项代价高昂的奖品。有那么多动作需要协调！有那么多地方容易出错！难怪要达到不错的技巧和流畅度需要无数个小时的练习。为什么呢？奥运级别游泳运动员的培养通常在幼儿园后不久就开始了——七八岁！即使到了那时，可能也需要五年的时间，反复练习基本技能，然后才开始进行力量和耐力训练。

Sometimes I think that if we left it up to the experts, the only people who’d dare to get into a swimsuit would be elite athletes with burning Olympic aspirations and children too carefree to have any aspirations at all. Because the “experts” all warn us: An efficient swimming stroke is a prize with a staggering price. So many motions to coordinate! So many ways to go wrong! No wonder it takes countless hours of practice to reach a decent level of skill and smoothness. Why, the grooming of an Olympic-level swimmer usually begins not long after kindergarten—at the age of seven or eight! And even then, for maybe five years, the basic skills are hammered in over and over before the first hints of training for strength and endurance.

胡扯。对于一位渴望奥运的选手来说，也许这就是必需的。但我们其他人不必如此。对于成年人来说，他们通常从小就没有那么多时间，更不应该这样。所以，在没有专业人士指导、又没有多少时间投入的情况下，成年游泳希望之星通常只是缓慢地游几圈，希望随着游泳里程的增加，他们的划水动作会有所提高。然而，正如我们在上一章所说，他们不断地练习错误，只会让情况变得更糟。而且他们游得越多，这样，将来就越难摆脱这种状态。他们最终可能会陷入我的一位露营者所称的“终极平庸”状态。

Rubbish. For an Olympic aspirant, maybe that’s what it takes. But it doesn’t have to be that way for the rest of us. And for adults, who generally haven’t had that kind of time since they were kids themselves, it simply can’t be that way. So without professionals to guide them and with few hours to invest, grown-up swimming hopefuls usually just plod through the laps, hoping that as the mileage piles up their strokes will improve. Instead, as we said in the last chapter, they’re making things worse by practicing their mistakes. And the more they swim this way, the harder it will become to snap out of it someday. They may finally reach a state that one of my campers wistfully called “terminal mediocrity.”

过去，想要摆脱这些坏习惯，唯一的希望就是找到一位优秀的教练。现在不一样了。有一些方法可以让你扭转局面，开始自学提高技能，我们将在接下来的几章中教你这些方法。

It used to be that your only hope for breaking out of those bad habits was to find a good coach. Not anymore. There are ways you can turn things around and begin learning improved skills all by yourself, methods we’ll teach you in the next few chapters.

一切都始于我所说的“泳姿保护法”，也就是所谓的技能训练。你可以把技能训练想象成你强大的私人蝙蝠侠，对抗那些坏习惯的“小丑”，它能够彻底根除这些坏习惯，几乎自动地用健全的新习惯取而代之。毫不夸张地说，技能训练是通往精通游泳的最快、最有效的途径。技能训练是我二十多年来一直使用的成功方法的核心，它帮助各个年龄段的游泳者显著提高水平。原因之一是这些训练非常容易学习，即使是没有经验的游泳者也能成为自己最好的教练。

It all starts with what I call the stroke saver, otherwise known as the skill drill. Think of the skill drill as your personal and powerful Batman against the Joker of bad swimming habits, able to root them out thoroughly, replacing them with sound, new ones almost automatically. The skill drill is—no exaggeration—the quickest and most effective path to masterful swimming. Skill drills are the core of the successful method I’ve used for over two decades to help swimmers of all ages to improve dramatically. One of the reasons is that the drills are so easy to learn that even inexperienced swimmers can become their own best coaches.

我不在乎你是否已经沮丧了好几年。通过这些技巧练习，你只需几个小时就能显著提高你的游泳水平，而如果你在泳池里漫无目的地来回练习你的错误，这个过程是不可能发生的。

I don’t care if you’ve been frustrated for years. You can dramatically improve your swimming in just hours with these technique drills, a process that has no way of happening when you plod mindlessly up and down the pool practicing your mistakes.

在传统的教学中，学习过程可能会耗费数月之久，既乏味又令人沮丧。训练的作用是加快你的学习进度，这绝非易事。即使是那些看起来天生就拥有轻松优雅的优秀游泳运动员，也可能花费了数月甚至数年的时间来磨练这种流畅、近乎芭蕾舞般的动作。有时教练的指导起了作用；有时，他们非凡的直觉就足够了。但无论如何，过程是一样的：随着时间的推移，他们会找到突破性的划水时机，感觉恰到好处。这些时机会被身体立即捕捉，并——就像我们网球学生的身体一样——储存在一份类似的“如何移动”经验的目录中。最终，这份“经验目录”变得足够全面，最终形成一种极其流畅、高效的游泳方式。

With conventional instruction, the learning process can consume tedious and frustrating months. Drills work by speeding up your learning curve, and that’s no small feat. Even excellent swimmers who look like they must have been born with their effortless grace have probably invested months, or more likely years, in polishing that smooth, almost balletlike way of moving. Sometimes a coach’s guidance did the trick; in other cases their exceptional intuitions were enough. But either way, the process is the same: Over time, they’ve hit on breakthrough moments when their stroke feels just right, moments that the body immediately seizes and—just like the body of our tennis pupil—stores in a catalogue of similar how-to-move experiences. Eventually, the catalogue becomes comprehensive enough to produce an extremely smooth and highly efficient way of swimming.

这是一个永无止境的过程——这也是游泳最令人兴奋的事情之一。说到良好的技术，几乎没有进步的上限。无论你是刚刚“摸索”的初学者，还是渴望在全国比赛中夺牌的专家，总有地方需要改进。改进的过程只会变得越来越微妙。在1988年赢得七枚奥运奖牌后，马特·比昂迪承认：“我仍然把每次练习都视为一次学习经历，因为我逐渐意识到，即使是现在，我对高效游泳的理解也只占了十分之一。”

It’s a process that never really ends—which is one of the most exciting things about swimming. There’s virtually no improvement ceiling when it comes to good technique. Whether you’re a beginner just “getting your stroke wet” or an expert looking to medal at a national meet, there’s always something left to work on. The refinements just become increasingly subtle. After winning an astounding seven Olympic medals in 1988, Matt Biondi admitted, “I still see every practice as a learning experience because I’ve come to realize that even now, I only understand about ten percent of what efficient swimming is all about.”

但是，对于像游泳这样复杂的技能来说，反复尝试非常耗时——任何自学成才的网球运动员都会告诉你这一点。因此，“完全沉浸式”方法将这种杂乱无章、缓慢得令人痛苦的过程，为你精心组织起来。其结果是，一套循序渐进的训练系统，让任何游泳者都能以一种有条理、便捷可靠的方式，重现自己的“学习灵光”，并将其记录下来。突然之间，你就能随时随地捕捉到那些难以捉摸的“同步”感，而不是偶尔偶然发现。最重要的是，你可以反复练习。

But trial and error is a very time-consuming way to pick up an involved skill like swimming—as any self-taught tennis player can tell you. So the Total Immersion method takes this haphazard and painfully slow process and organizes it for you. The result is a step-by-step system of drills selected so any swimmer can re-create, in an organized, convenient, and reliable way, his or her own “flashes of learning” to put into the catalogue. Suddenly you can capture those elusive feelings of being “in sync” whenever you want instead of stumbling onto them now and again by accident. Best of all, you can practice them again and again.

然而，正如国王的所有马匹、国王的所有士兵和汉普蒂·邓普蒂都发现的那样，零件只是零件，直到你把它们放回原位重新组合起来。当你在练习中磨练了各个部分后，重新开始完整地游动时，你的身体会自然地将它们重新组合成一个进步很大的整体。你的神经末梢已经帮你完成了学习，它捕捉了顶尖游泳运动员在水中像刀子一样划水时持续感受到的感觉，并将它们组合成一本完整的相册：你的划水动作。

Still, as all the king’s horses, all the king’s men, and Humpty-Dumpty all found out, parts are just parts until you put them back to gether again. When you go back to swimming the whole stroke after polishing pieces of it in your drills, your body reassembles them naturally into a much-improved whole. Your nerve endings have done your learning for you by taking “snapshots” of sensations that elite swimmers feel consistently as they knife through the water, and assembling them into a complete photo album: your stroke.

现在，如果您怀疑我们只是在通过所有这些拆开和重新组合来延长学习过程，那么我将向您介绍四个强有力的物理事实，这些事实使技能训练成为如此强大的击球改进工具：

Now, if you suspect that we’re really just drawing out the learning process with all this pulling apart and putting back together, I’ll let you in on the four powerful physical facts that make skill drills such a potent stroke-improvement tool:

 

 

1. 事实：你的肌肉需要“健忘症”。正如我们所说，肌肉是有记忆的。习惯的力量是强大的。而你多年来一直使用的划水姿势，也已经变成了一种习惯。而且可能还不是什么好习惯。因为你一直在努力，你的肌肉已经变得非常习惯这种动作了。事实上，它们更愿意一直保持下去。

1. Fact: Your Muscles Need a Dose of Amnesia. Muscles have memories, as we said. Habits are powerful. And that’s just what the stroke you’ve been using for years has become—a habit. Probably not a good one either. And because you’ve been struggling for so long, your muscles have become very good at moving like that. They’d prefer to keep right on doing it, in fact.

划水练习之所以有效，是因为它们经过了伪装，足以打破这种循环。它们与你的正常动作截然不同，以至于你的肌肉无法识别这些动作，并坚持让你以原有的方式进行。你可以在神经肌肉的空白板上练习新技能，而无需事先清除任何信息。

Stroke drills are powerful enough to break that cycle because they’re disguised. They’re so different from your normal motion that your muscle doesn’t recognize the movement and insist you do it in the same old way. You practice new skills on a neuromuscular blank slate without having to erase anything first.

 

 

2. 事实：小块内容更容易消化。学习专家告诉我们，通过将复杂的动作序列分解成易于掌握的练习片段，我们可以更快地掌握技能。由于游泳动作由许多精细协调的部分组成，因此几乎不可能完全消化。因此，我们的“完全沉浸式”游泳训练是“一口大小”的，将整个划水动作分解成一系列小技巧，每个技巧都能快速掌握。然后，你只需将这些小技巧重新组合成一个新的、更高效的划水动作即可。每个练习都教授一项关键技能，我们会按照身体最容易理解的顺序进行讲解。这就像盖楼：第一个练习是地基，每个后续练习都会增加一层楼，掌握每个步骤都会为你提供解决下一个步骤的关键。

2. Fact: Small Pieces Are Easier to Swallow. Learning specialists tell us we pick up skills faster by breaking a complex movement series into manageable segments for practice. Because the swimming stroke is made up of so many finely coordinated parts, it’s virtually impossible to digest the whole thing. So our Total Immersion stroke drills are “bite-size,” reducing the whole stroke into a series of mini-skills, each of which can be quickly mastered. Then you simply reassemble these building blocks into a new, more efficient stroke. Each drill teaches a key skill, and we present them in the order the body best understands. It’s like putting up a building: The first drill is the foundation, each succeeding drill adds a floor, and mastery of each step gives you the key to solving the next one.

 

 

3. 事实：与其说是“尝试与错误”，不如说是“尝试与成功”。练习能让你的学习成果对你有利，你不会失败。因为小技巧可以快速轻松地掌握，所以你可以立即开始练习流畅的动作。你练习每个流畅动作的次数越多，它就越能成为你的新习惯，并取代那些马虎的旧习惯。你花在马虎旧习惯上的时间越少，你游得就越快。一连串的成功会增强你的动力和自信——研究表明，当你对自己所做的事情充满信心时，这种动力和自信会更快地增强。

3. Fact: Instead of Trial and Error, It’s Trial and Success. Drills stack the learning deck completely in your favor. You can’t lose. Because mini-skills can be mastered quickly and easily, you begin practicing smooth movements right away. The more you practice each smooth movement, the more it becomes your new habit and crowds out the sloppy old one. And the less time you spend swimming with your sloppy old one, the faster you learn to swim better. That string of successes boosts your motivation and self-confidence—and studies have shown that happens faster when you believe in what you’re doing.

 

 

4. 事实：它是身体能理解的语言。告诉肌肉该做什么有点像教你的贵宾犬法语：你会全神贯注，但很难记住。传统的划水指导也存在同样的弱点。它太理性了。它试图通过你的思维来影响你的肌肉，即使肌肉对指令的反应并不那么好。想想看。首先，你必须听到，或者可能读到，关于你将要尝试的动作的描述。接下来，你试着弄清楚这个动作会是什么感觉。然后你指示你的肌肉模仿那种感觉。最后，你问自己是否做对了。如果做错了，你就稍微换一种方式再试一次。

4. Fact: It’s Language the Body Understands. Telling a muscle what to do is a little like teaching French to your poodle: You get rapt attention but not much retention. Conventional stroke instruction suffers from the same weakness. It’s too rational. It tries to get to your muscles through your mind, even though muscles really don’t respond all that well to being lectured. Think about it. First you have to hear, or possibly read, a description of what you’re going to attempt. Next, you try to figure out what the movement will feel like. Then you instruct your muscles to imitate that feeling. Finally, you ask yourself if you got it right. If you didn’t, you try it again a little differently.

训练可以避免所有这些模糊的理解。它们简化并加速学习过程。从一开始，你就在教会你的身体如何游得好。

Drills bypass all those vague translations. They simplify—and accelerate—the learning process. From the very beginning, you teach your body how it should feel when you swim well.

最棒的是，技能训练具有自我调节功能。你越需要它们，它们就越有效。初学者练习这些技能时，他们会大量学习基本技能，粗糙之处很快就会被磨平。经验丰富的游泳者在进行同样的训练时，会自然而然地适应更细微的改进，从而将他们已有的技能提升到更高的水平。

The great part is, skill drills are self-adjusting. The more you need them, the better they’ll work for you. When beginners practice them they learn basic skills in big chunks and rough edges get smoothed off quickly. Experienced swimmers, doing the same drills, tune in naturally to far more subtle refinements, bringing a higher degree of polish to skills they already have.

你需要学的越多，就应该练习得越多——如果你真的有充足的训练量，训练量最多是平时游泳的四倍。这或许是摆脱多年来根深蒂固的坏习惯的唯一方法。你可以这样想：每一次练习，你都能很快学会，这对你的游泳能力来说都是积极的强化。每一次游泳都可能让你重蹈覆辙。我告诉我的研习班学生问问自己：“当我试图教会我的身体新技能时，我能承受多少游泳的痛苦？”

And the more you have to learn, the more you should drill—up to four times as much as your normal swimming if you really have your work cut out for you. It may be the only way to make headway against bad habits so hardened through the years that they’re all but concrete. Think of it this way: Every lap of drilling, which you can learn to do well quickly, is positive reinforcement for your swimming. Every lap of swimming may pull you back toward old habits. I tell my workshop pupils to ask themselves: “How much swimming can I suffer, as I try to teach my body new skills?”

虽然每个游泳者都不一样，但这些训练对大多数人来说都见效神速。我教过的每个人都进步神速。我想不出还有什么其他游泳教学方法能做到这一点。而且，如果你做到以下几点，效果会更快：

And though every swimmer is different, drills work for most with incredible speed. Everyone I’ve taught them to has improved. I can’t think of any other swim instruction method that can claim that. And they’ll work even faster if you:

 

 

1. 游泳前三思。每个训练都是一个解决问题的练习，当你试图解决问题时，没有什么比耐心和坚持更能体现传统美德了。每次进行新的训练，以及每次在训练后的一两个月进行复习训练时，都要保持耐心和坚持。想要练习这个计划——请遵循以下步骤：首先，重复几次，提醒你的肌肉记住这个练习要解决的问题，比如在转动身体呼吸时，头部和躯干一起移动。接下来，重复几次，找出解决方案。最后，再重复几次，记住这个解决方案，让它自然而然地出现。现在，你已经“掌握”了它。

1. Think Before You Swim. Every drill is a problem-solving exercise, and nothing beats the old-fashioned virtues of patience and persistence when you’re trying to solve a problem. With each new drill—and every time you do refresher drilling the first month or two following this program—take these steps: First, a few repetitions just to remind your muscles of the problem the drill is meant to solve, such as moving your head and torso together as you roll your body to breathe. Next, several repetitions to work out the solution. Finally, several more repetitions spent “memorizing” that solution so it comes naturally. Now you “own” it.

 

 

2. 带着感觉去做。这些训练让你的肌肉与大脑对话，而不是大脑与肌肉对话。如果你的大脑在倾听，它就能学习到你练习的动作或技巧在正确完成时的感觉。当它学会了这一点时，它就能开始自动回放。感觉对了，就是对的；大脑与肌肉的联系就会开始更加顺畅地运作。所以，最初几次练习任何新动作时，至少要坚持10到15分钟，把新的感觉牢牢地印在你的记忆里，这样大脑最终就能依靠感觉而不是思维来做事。不要死板。尝试进行细微的调整。看看你到底能控制多少，以及当你稍微改变这些新动作时会发生什么。最终，你会希望你的身体接管你的大脑，自动完成最初需要你全神贯注的事情。

2. Do It with Feeling. These drills get your muscles talking to your brain instead of the other way around. If your brain is listening, it’s going to learn what the motion or skill you’re practicing feels like when it’s done right. And when it learns that, it can start to replay it automatically.
