Feels right, is right; and the mind-muscle connection begins to work more smoothly. So the first few times you work on any new drill, stick with it for at least ten to fifteen minutes to firmly imprint the new sense into your memory so the brain can eventually go by sensation rather than by thought. Don’t be rigid. Experiment with subtle adjustments. See how much control you really have and what happens when you alter these new movements even slightly. Eventually you want your body to take over from your mind, automatically doing what at first required all your concentration.

 

 

3. 不要把自己逼入绝境。马拉松式的训练很容易弊大于利，就像过犹不及。如果你疲惫不堪、无法集中注意力，就无法很好地训练，而只有训练得当才能培养良好的技能。以25码为单位进行重复练习，每组之间休息10到15秒。每次练习都应该感觉更流畅、更放松、更精准、更高效。如果没有，请重新阅读说明，或者回到之前的练习，完善一下，然后再回到那个让你感到困难的练习。

3. Don’t Drill Yourself into a Hole. Marathon drill sets can easily do more harm than good, a case of too much of a good thing. If you’re tired and can’t concentrate, you won’t drill well, and drills build good skills only when they’re done well. Practice them in 25-yard repeats, resting ten to fifteen seconds between. Every rep should feel a little smoother and more relaxed, a little more precise and economical. If not, reread the instructions or go back to the previous drill and polish that one up before returning to the one that’s giving you trouble.

 

 

4. 带着你的练习进行游泳测试。每次练习一个新的练习，时间不要超过10到15分钟。然后交替练习和游泳距离，试着让每个游泳距离更有效率——用更少的划水次数——也更轻松一些。比较你的练习和划水。练习中哪个感觉更好？很好。试着在划水中加入更多这种感觉。比如，当你按压浮标时，你的臀部和腿部会突然感觉轻盈，因为它们掠过水面，而不是拖在身后。专注于这一点。看看你在游泳时能感受到多少。把它想象成你用波波夫划水进行虚拟现实游泳的机会。坚持下去。持久的进步不会一蹴而就。

4. Take Your Drills Out for a Test Swim. Work no more than ten to fifteen minutes at a time on a new drill. Then alternate drill lengths with swim lengths, trying to make each swim length a little more efficient— taking fewer strokes—and a little easier. Compare your drill and your stroke. What felt better in the drill? Good. Try to get more of that feeling into your stroke. When you’re pressing your buoy, for example, your hips and legs will suddenly feel light as they skim the surface instead of dragging along behind you. Focus on that. See how much of it you can feel when you’re swimming. Think of it as your chance to do a virtual-reality lap with a Popov stroke. And keep at it. Lasting improvement won’t happen instantaneously.

 

 

5. 如果脚蹼合适……这里有一个悖论。训练的目的是让你的身体保持良好的平衡，这样你就不需要用力打腿就能游得很好了。无力的打腿不会减慢你的速度。但你需要腿部提供一些推进力才能更好地进行训练。训练时，你的身体移动速度比游泳时慢，因此在水中的位置也更低。一点打腿可以弥补这一点。如果你的打腿力弱，你会浪费大量精力去调整正确的身体姿势，以至于没有多少精力可以用来训练。戴上一双脚蹼，你就能专注于真正重要的事情——每个训练中的细微之处。顺便说一句，对于技巧训练来说，刀片式脚蹼比所谓的快速脚蹼要好得多，尤其是在你的脚踝还不能轻易弯曲的情况下。

5. If the Fin Fits… Here’s a paradox. Drills are designed to get your body so well balanced that you won’t need much of a kick to swim well. A weak kick won’t slow you down anymore. But you will need a bit of propulsion from your legs to drill well. Your body’s moving slower—and lower in the water as a result—while drilling than when you swim. A bit of kick helps compensate. If yours is weak, you’ll waste so much energy struggling for the right body position that you won’t have much left to drill with. Slip on a pair of fins, and you’ll be able to pay attention to what matters—the fine points in each drill. By the way, for skill work bladed fins are far better than the cut-off, so-called speed fins, particularly if your ankles don’t flex easily yet.

钻进游泳：需要一些组装

Drill-and-Swim: Some Assembly Required

在我的训练计划中，技巧训练简直就是魔法——绝对是提升水平的最佳途径。但只有当你把它们巧妙地融入到整个游泳姿势的拼图中时，它们才能发挥作用。正如特定的拼图碎片必须以特定的方式融入整体一样，技巧训练在游泳训练中也不会随心所欲。没有计划的训练，你可能会错失关键。

In my program, skill drills are little short of magic—absolutely the best way to improve. But they can do that only if you fit them properly into the puzzle of the whole swimming stroke. And just as particular puzzle pieces have to fit into the whole in a particular way, drills don’t go just anywhere in your swimming workouts. Drill without a plan and you could miss the whole point.

你看，训练就像游泳训练里的薯片：它让人上瘾，以至于你开始对其他事情失去兴趣。比如游泳。我见过一些人成为了训练高手，却在训练过程中几乎不怎么练习游泳姿势。他们把良好的训练变成了最终目的。

Drills, you see, can be the potato chips of swim training: so addictive you begin to lose your appetite for other things. Things like swimming. I’ve seen people become absolutely terrific drillers and do little to nothing for their swimming stroke in the process. They’ve let good drilling become an end in itself.

如果你只是想保持健康，那未必是坏事。训练本身就是一种锻炼，有时甚至比游泳更有益。事实上，你完全可以只做训练，甚至不用任何常规划水动作，就能轻松保持良好体型。但这岂不是有点像把所有零件都小心翼翼地组装成一辆经典的名爵，却从不造车？没错，训练确实很有趣，而且它们确实能为在单调乏味的收费公路上——在黑线上来回游动——提供一些风景优美的小路，但我们也不要沉迷其中。

That’s not necessarily bad if all you want is to be fit. Drills can be a workout all by themselves, sometimes more of a workout than swimming would have been. In fact, you could easily stay in great shape doing nothing but drills without ever taking a single conventional stroke. But wouldn’t that be a little like carefully assembling all the parts to a classic MG and then never building the car? Yes, drills can be fun, and they do offer scenic byways to the monotony of the turnpike— swimming the black line back and forth and back and forth—but let’s not get carried away.

训练可以培养技能，但如果你能有条理地将训练与游泳结合起来交替进行，效果会更好。记住，训练是：(1) 教会肌肉新运动模式的最简单方法；(2) 提升感觉的最佳方式，让你感觉游得好。与游泳交替进行将让你的练习对你的击球产生最强大的影响。它们会给你一个感官目标，一种你正在寻找的感觉。当你拥有了你想要的感觉，你就能更好地集中注意力练习。

Drills build skills, but they build them best if you integrate and alternate them with swimming in an organized way. Remember, drills are: (1) the simplest way to teach your muscles new movement patterns; and (2) the best way to turn up the volume on feelings that tell you when you’re swimming well. Alternating with swimming will give your drills the most powerful influence over your stroke. They’ll give you a sensory target, a feeling you’re looking for. And when you have a feeling you’re looking for, you can better focus your practice.

您将在本课程中稳步前进，因为我们将这些感官练习按您的身体学习的逻辑顺序组织起来。每项感官技能都建立在前一项技能的基础上。例如，您必须先保持平衡，才能延长划水距离。

Your progress in this program will be steady and reliable because we’ve organized those sensory exercises into logical sequences, just the way your body wants to learn them. Each sense skill builds on the one before it. You can’t lengthen your stroke, for example, until you’ve first gotten yourself balanced.

要有耐心。练习游泳会起作用。事实上，它不会失败，因为它采用了自然的学习方法。你的身体是一个极具直觉的仪器，只要提供足够的信息，它就能完美地感知到自己需要什么。在练习和游泳的过程中，你会感觉到什么最有效，并逐渐掌握它，使其成为你自己的。但请记住：当这个学习工具允许它按照自己的节奏学习时，它会发挥最佳效果。你不会在一夜之间养成所有坏习惯，你也不会在一夜之间养成新的习惯。只需重复一次新的练习，就可以启动学习过程，甚至可能开始追踪微弱的神经印记，使下一次重复更容易、更自然。但真正的技能需要通过多次重复，每次都以同样的方式进行，才能深深地打下基础。

Be patient. Drill-swim will work. It can’t fail, in fact, because it employs natural learning methods. Your body is a brilliantly intuitive instrument, with a faultless sense of what it needs—given enough information. As you drill and swim, you’ll sense what works best and gradually capture that and make it your own. But remember: This learning instrument works best when allowed to learn at its own pace. You didn’t pick up all your bad habits overnight and you’re not going to pick up new ones overnight either. Just one repetition of a new drill may start the learning process, may even begin tracing a faint neurological imprint that will make the next repetition easier and more natural. But real skill requires that the groove be cut deeply through many repetitions, each done the same way.

所以不要强迫自己。耐心、坚持地重复练习，找到感觉，然后交替进行游泳练习，感受这种感觉并将其融入到你的划水动作中，这才是让练习发挥其魔力的最佳方法。使用短重复次数和短组数。新鲜的肌肉训练效果更好。疲劳——无论是精神上的还是身体上的——都会导致马虎。而马虎正是你在疲惫或无聊时练习的。只需进行25码的练习，然后游25码，再短暂休息，就能获得最高质量的练习。尽你所能大概十分钟左右。然后做一些不需要太过专注的事情，让你的大脑休息一下——比如，数几圈划水，看看你的效率提高了多少。

So don’t try to force-feed yourself. Patient, persistent repetition of the drills to get the feeling right, alternating with swim laps where you take that feeling and put it right into your stroke, is the best way to let drills work their magic. Use short repeats and short sets. Fresh muscles train well. Fatigue—mental or physical—brings sloppiness. And sloppiness is what you’ll be practicing once you’re tired or bored. Just 25 yards of a drill, followed by 25 yards of swimming, followed by a short rest, will give you the highest-quality practice. Give it all you’ve got for maybe ten minutes or so. Then give your brain a rest by doing something that requires less concentration—a few laps of stroke counting, for example, to see how much more efficient you’ve become.

正如法官们喜欢提醒律师的那样，你必须抓住重点。不要在训练中专注于一件事，然后在游泳过程中走神去想别的事情。专注，专注，专注，无论是在训练中还是在游泳中。如果你在训练中练习了按压浮标，就不要在游泳过程中开始想着臀部旋转。这样你永远都做不完任何事。

And as judges are fond of reminding lawyers, you need to keep to the point. Don’t work on one thing in your drill and drift off into thinking about something else during the swimming you do right afterward. Focus, focus, focus, in drills and in swimming. If you worked on pressing your buoy while drilling, don’t start thinking about hip roll on your swim length. You’ll never finish anything.

我还要更进一步。本书游泳课中的训练指南建议在每个训练中集中注意五六个要点。如果同时做所有要点，那就太多了。你可以只考虑一个，并且足够清晰和专注，以便做好它。但如果贪心，同时考虑两三个，它们就会变得模糊。你不会做好任何一个，因为你的注意力会四处跳跃。相反，在我允许的情况下，强迫自己做一些训练分类。确定你明显感觉到哪些点对你的划水影响最大，并花更多的训练时间来思考这些点。在下一个游泳距离中记住这一点。（请参阅附录中的练习示例。）专注，专注，专注。

And I’ll go even further. Your drill guidelines in this book’s swim lessons suggest five or six points to concentrate on in each drill. That’s about four or five too many to do all at the same time. You can think about exactly one, and one only, with enough clarity and focus to do it well. Get greedy, go for two or three at the same time, and they’ll all get fuzzy. You won’t do any of them well as your concentration leapfrogs all around. Instead, force yourself to do a little drill triage, with my permission. Decide which points you clearly feel make the greatest difference in your stroke and spend more drill lengths thinking about those. Keep the exact same point in mind on your next swim length. (See the appendix for sample practices that do this.) Focus, focus, focus.

渐渐地，当你准备好了，就慢慢地减少训练量，慢慢地减少训练量。在回到练习中提醒自己之前，把你能游得更远一些，然后再回去练习。因为事情就是这样发生的，也许前进三步（或划水），后退一步。一开始，你看，那种神经信号仍然很微弱。你可能需要完成三到四个练习长度才能清楚地意识到你在练习什么，而一旦你有了这种感觉，你所能做的可能就是保持这种感觉游完整个长度。所以，你的练习长度与……的比例游泳距离的比例很容易达到3:1或4:1。不过，随着你不断练习，你的身体会越来越快地适应。最终，一个训练长度可能会让这种感觉牢牢地扎根在肌肉记忆中，并直接过渡到游泳距离。

And gradually, when you’re ready, wean, wean, wean. Stretch farther and farther the distance you can swim with better form before heading back to the drills for a reminder. For that is how it will happen, maybe three steps (or strokes) forward, one step back. In the beginning, you see, that neurological tracery is still faint. It may take you three or four drill lengths to even get a clear sense of what it is you’re practicing, and it may be all you can do just to hold that sensation for one full swim length once you get it. So your ratio of drill lengths to swim lengths could easily be as high as 3:1 or 4:1. As you continue practicing, though, your body will get it faster and faster. Eventually, one drill length might groove that feeling back into muscle memory firmly enough to shift right over to a swim length.

慢慢地，你会进步到游两个来回，然后你的姿势开始摇摆不定，需要重新练习。然后是三个来回。然后……但要耐心地延长距离。最终，你将能够以全新、进步的自我进行更长时间的巡航。感觉很棒，不是吗？好吧，恭喜你。你的旧习惯正在消失，你的肌肉现在开始记住正确的动作，而之前阻碍你的划水动作也开始对你失去控制。现在是时候再放松一些了。集中注意力，但不要再进行训练。让我们开始全程游泳吧。

Little by little, you’ll work up to two lengths before your form begins to wobble and need a drill refresher. Then three lengths. Then. … But be patient at stretching the distance. Eventually, you’ll be able to take the new, improved you for much longer cruises. Feels good, doesn’t it? Well, congratulations. Your old habits are on the run, your muscles are now beginning to remember the right stuff, and the stroke that was holding you back is losing its grip on you. Now it’s time to pry loose a few more of its fingers. Hang on to your concentration but take off the training wheels. Let’s start some full-stroke swimming.

7

7

恢复理智，凭感觉游泳

Come to Your Senses. Swim by Feel

如果“感觉技能练习”在你听来就像是深夜有线电视上的成人录像带广告，那么在我们继续之前我需要占用你一分钟的时间。

If “sensory skill practice” sounds to you like an ad on late-night cable TV for an adult videotape, I need a minute of your time before we go any further.

因为我所说的SSP，实际上远比这重要得多——嗯，对一个渴望进步的游泳者来说，当然更重要。它无疑是整个“全浸式”学习过程的顶峰，画龙点睛之笔。每个“全浸式”练习都侧重于第2章至第4章中描述的游泳的某个方面。反过来，每个练习都会增强“正确游泳”的动觉或感官体验。在SSP中，我们练习游泳时会专注于这种感觉。

Because SSP, as I call it, is actually something a good deal more important—well, more important to an improvement-minded swimmer, certainly. It’s nothing less than the capstone, the finishing touch, on the whole Total Immersion learning process. Each Total Immersion drill focuses on some aspect of swimming described in chapters 2 through 4. Each drill, in turn, heightens the kinesthetic, or sensory, experience of how “right swimming” feels. In SSP, we practice swimming while focused on that feeling.

在感觉技能练习中，你会掌握高效划水的所有要素，包括你在技能训练中精心打造、在游泳练习中排练过的要素，并将它们永久化。自动化，属于你。良好的姿势会让你的身体本能地跟随，最终摆脱大脑中那些喋喋不休的提醒。那份令人畏惧的心理清单——我是否足够用力地按压浮标？我的身体够长吗？臀部旋转怎么样？我是否游到了远端？——被简化为一个简单流畅的身体检查：感觉对吗？

In sensory skill practice you take all the ingredients of an efficient stroke, the ones you so meticulously developed in your skill drills and rehearsed in your drill-swim sessions, and make them permanent. Automatic. Yours. Good form that your body follows instinctively, free at last of those nagging reminder lectures from your brain. That daunting mental punch list—Am I pressing my buoy enough? Is my body long? What about hip roll? Did I reach for the far end?—is edited down to a simple and smooth body check: Does it feel right?

教会你的感官什么是“正确的游泳”的感觉，你看，它们会接管一切，并比摄像机更有效地帮助你保持良好的游泳姿势。自动且准确。

Teach your senses what “right swimming” feels like, you see, and they’ll take over and do more to help you hold good swimming form than a video camera ever could. Automatically and accurately.

挑战在于如何充分利用你的新乐章。目前，它们就像一张张独立的乐谱，无论它们在乐谱架上出现的顺序如何，你都能演奏得很好。但如果它们要成为一首协奏曲，就必须遵循一定的连贯顺序。

The challenge is figuring out how to take full advantage of your new movements. At this point they’re like individual sheets of music that you can play well in whatever order they turn up on the music stand. But if they’re ever going to become a concerto, they must follow a certain coherent sequence.

因此，在感觉技能练习中，我们所做的就是将你的技能按逻辑顺序排列，并以此方式“运用”它们，因为有些技能可以让你解锁其他技能，就像打开一连串嵌套的俄罗斯套娃一样。虽然我在本书中不断宣扬成为更好游泳者的方法是减少游泳时间并练习、练习、再练习，但总有一天你必须游、游、游。但现在不同了！你已经克服了黑线热。里程表不再主宰你的生活。重要的不是游了多久或多远，而是游得有多好。你终于知道当你做对了是什么感觉了。你现在的任务是确保从现在开始总是有这种感觉。

So what we do in sensory skill practice is to arrange your skills in a logical order and “play” them that way, since some let you unlock others, like opening a series of nested Russian dolls. For though I preach consistently throughout this book that the way to become a better swimmer is to cut swim time and drill, drill, drill, there comes a point when you have to swim, swim, swim. But what a difference now! You’ve gotten over your black-line fever. The odometer no longer rules your life. It’s not how long or how far but how well. You finally know what it feels like when you’ve got it right. Your job now is to make sure it always feels that way from now on.

如果你的身体一开始难以接受这种“凭感觉游泳”的方法，也不要感到惊讶。毕竟，这和我们学校教练教的正好相反。那时候，我们练习的是忽略而不是集中注意力。面对现实吧：我们大多数人接受的教育是，如果你认真对待体育运动，就不会害怕累得倒下。在那个年代，一个好的教练可以帮助你把思绪转移到其他事情上，而不是让你去想你的痛苦，让你从训练中“抽离”，忘记自己有多累，然后设法坚持得更久一些。就像我的同龄人一样——可能也像你的一样——当我稍微注意一下我的身体正在做的事情，从开始到结束都让我怀疑自己用手划桨的水平如何。

Don’t be surprised if your body at first has trouble trusting this “swim by feel” approach. After all, it’s just the opposite of what many of us were told to do by our school coaches. Back then, we worked on ignoring instead of paying attention. Face it: The way most of us were schooled, if you took athletics seriously you didn’t shrink from getting falling-down tired. And a good coach, in those days, was someone who could help your mind wander off to something other than how miserable you were feeling, to “disassociate” from the workout so you’d forget how exhausted you were and manage to keep on going just a little longer and a little longer after that. Like my peers—and probably like yours—when I paid any attention at all to what my body was doing, it began and ended with wondering how well I was using my hands to paddle.

这就是我三十多岁恢复常规游泳训练时，对技术的专注程度。而今天，你的专注程度很可能依然如此。

So that was the extent of my technical focus when I came back to regular swim training in my late thirties. And today, it very probably is still yours.

当我逐渐意识到身体姿势对有效游泳的重要性远超耐力或力量时，我知道我必须彻底改变我的训练理念。我不再指挥身体该做什么，而是开始倾听它的声音，它从成千上万个神经末梢发出信号，并像它一直以来试图做的那样，告诉大脑哪些动作有效，哪些动作无效。但现在，我不再忽视所有这些信息，而是引导它找到尽可能流畅的技巧，并将大部分注意力集中在我的躯干——身体的力量源泉——而不是我的手臂和腿上。

When it gradually became clear that body positioning is so much more important to effective swimming than endurance or strength, I knew I would have to completely reverse my idea of training. Instead of telling my body what to do, I would start listening to it as it reported in from thousands upon thousands of nerve endings and informed the brain—as it had always tried to do—what was working well and what wasn’t. Now, though, instead of ignoring all this information, I would guide it into the smoothest possible technique and focus the lion’s share of that attention on my torso—the body’s power source— instead of my arms and legs.

我的第一个感官实验是按压浮标。作为教练，我教蝶泳运动员这个动作已经近二十年了。在这种划水姿势下，身体靠在胸前，明显更容易抬高臀部。但直到1990年左右，我才意识到，抬高臀部和腿部以减少阻力的原理在自由泳中也同样有效。为了测试，我请了几个游泳特别吃力的新手尝试一下。效果立竿见影，而且非常显著，即使不是专业教练，也能感受到它带来的震撼。我意识到，这个动作也能帮助我自己提高游泳水平，或许对其他人也一样。

My first sensory experiment was with pressing the buoy. As a coach I’d been teaching it to butterfliers for nearly twenty years. Leaning on the chest in that stroke made it conspicuously easier for them to bring their hips up. But it wasn’t until around 1990 that it occurred to me that the same principle of lifting the hips and legs to reduce drag might work in freestyle too. As a test, I asked a couple of new swimmers who were struggling especially hard to give it a try. The difference was immediate and so dramatic you didn’t need to be a professional coach to be impressed with the results. I realized that it could help my own swimming as well. And probably everyone else’s.

但教练的习惯，即使是年轻的教练，也和其他人一样难以改变。诚然，那些最初尝试改变以增强躯干意识的尝试立刻就提升了。但我已经游了25年泳，长期的习惯让我的思绪总是飘回到我的双手正在做的事情上。一分心，我就知道身体姿势也变了。后半身突然受到的阻力让我明白了这一点。显然，如果我想保持这种进步，或者任何其他进步，我必须找到一种方法，让它变得自动化、本能化——可以说是“存入银行”。然后我才能继续下一个。

But the habits of coaches, even young ones, die just as hard as anyone’s. True, those first tentative shifts into greater torso awareness sparked an immediate improvement. But I’d already been swimming for twenty-five years, and long habit kept my mind drifting back to what those hands of mine were doing. The moment I lost concentration, I knew I had also lost body position. The sudden drag on my back half told me so. Obviously, if I wanted to hold on to this improvement, or any other improvement for that matter, I had to figure out a way of making it automatic and instinctive—“in the bank,” so to speak. Then I could go on to the next.

于是我做了任何优秀运动员都会做的事：竭尽全力，力求进步。我最终意识到，长距离游泳或高强度游泳只会破坏至关重要的专注力。它们实际上会让旧习惯焕发新生。唯一有效的方法是短距离重复训练，在训练中我会忽略时间、其他游泳者、我的双手以及我晚餐可能吃什么。我脑子里只允许做一件事：用胸部压力保持臀部放松。完全的感官吸收。而且，这真的有效。

So I did what any good athlete would do: worked as hard as I could at nailing that improvement down. What I nailed down instead was the realization that long swims or hard swims simply break down the critical ability to concentrate. They actually give new life to old habits. The only thing that worked was short repeats where I ignored the clock, other swimmers, my hands, and what I might be having for dinner. Just one thing was allowed on the mental table: chest pressure for keeping the hips light. Total sensory absorption. And it worked.

最棒的是，它持续帮助我提升每一点技能。接下来的两年里，我的击球效率比过去二十五年加起来还要高。你也可以做到。

Best of all, it continued to work for every piece of the skill puzzle I wanted to add. In the next two years I packed more efficiency into my stroke than I’d managed to eke out in the previous twenty-five years. You can do the same.

如果感觉良好，就去做。并且多做几次。

If It Feels Good, Do It. And Do It Some More.

感官技能练习和“操练游泳”的区别，就像骑自行车不用辅助轮和用辅助轮的区别一样。“操练游泳”就是用辅助轮游泳：如果你开始如果踩错踏板，失去平衡或姿势，你可以依靠练习来获得支撑。感觉技能练习会尽可能长时间地让踏板脱离。它挑战你尽可能直而稳地踩踏板，直到再次摇晃。

The difference between sensory skill practice and drill-and-swim is the difference between cycling without training wheels and cycling with them. Drill-and-swim is training-wheel swimming: If you start to go wrong and lose your balance or form, you can fall back on the drills for support. Sensory skill practice takes the wheels off for as long as you can leave them off. It challenges you to pedal straight and true, as far as you can go, before starting to wobble again.

原理如下：在每次练习中，你都要专注于一种特定的感觉——臀部和腿部轻盈，身体更挺拔，手臂无力，臀部滚动——然后在游泳时保持这种感觉，就像一遍又一遍地练习一小节音乐一样。你这样游得越多，这种感觉就越深入你的神经记忆库。最终，这种感觉会深入到足以成为你自然的划水姿势。

Here’s how it works. On each drill length, you zeroed in on one specific sensation—light hips and legs, longer body, weightless arm, rolling hips—then held on to it as you swam, like practicing a bar of music over and over. The more lengths you swam that way, the deeper that feeling sank into your neurological memory bank. Eventually, the feeling sank in deeply enough to become your natural stroke.

真的吗？你练习感官技能的目标就是找到答案。拿出同一份理想的感官清单，看看你能在特定感觉下游多远或多快。有意识地练习熟练的游泳技巧——别无其他。你不必计算圈数，也不必与时间或其他游泳者赛跑，而是专注于利用每一圈、每一次划水，将特定技能越来越深刻、越来越持久地铭刻在脑海中。

Or did it? Your objective in sensory skill practice is to find out. Take the same catalogue of desirable sensations and see how far or how fast you really can swim with one or another of them. Consciously practice skillful swimming—and nothing else. Instead of counting laps or racing the clock or another swimmer, you’re focused on using each lap and every stroke to imprint specific skills more and more deeply, more and more permanently.

从某种意义上说，感觉技能练习是学习过程的点睛之笔。在第一步中，你通过练习学习了新的移动方式。在第二步中，你将这些动作融入了你的游泳划水动作中。现在，你正在测试自己能否持续游得更好——并且持续地减少思考。这是无需练习的练习。练习教会你这些感觉是什么样的；然后你把它们融入到你的划水动作中，并在游泳时练习这种感觉。

In a sense, sensory skill practice puts the finishing touches on the learning process. In step one, you learned new ways of moving using drills. In step two, you integrated those movements into your swim stroke. Now you’re testing your ability to swim consistently better—with consistently less thought. It’s the drill work without the drills. Drills teach you what these sensations feel like; then you take them into your stroke and simply practice feeling like that as you swim.

但这远不止是“收尾”工作。记住，很多这样的动作一开始对我们的神经系统来说都很陌生，所以几乎任何锻炼最终都会摧毁你刚刚建立的、仍然脆弱的形式。坦白说，要让新的形式自然而本能地融入其中，你需要付出所有的耐心和决心。但这一切都是值得的。

But this is far more than just “mop-up” work. Many of these movements, remember, are alien to our nervous systems at first, so almost any workout will eventually break down your new and still-fragile form. Frankly, it will take all your patience and determination to make the new form natural and instinctive. But it will be worth it.

好消息是，你需要练习的减少阻力的SSP动作屈指可数，正如以下五个步骤所示。“操作方法”部分听起来很像练习，事实也确实如此。但现在，你不再只是练习了。俗话说，“这可不是练习”。这需要你变得更有效率，真正地与它共舞：

The best news is that you can count on the fingers of one hand all the drag-minimizing SSP movements you need to practice, as you’ll see in the following list of five. The “how-to” part sounds a lot like the drills, and it is. But now, you’re not drilling anymore. “This ain’t no practice run,” as the saying goes. This is taking the more efficient you and really swimming with it:

 

 

1. 下坡游泳：这项训练测试你能否有效地按压浮标，从而改善平衡，将臀部浮出水面并减少阻力。学会正确的练习，进步立竿见影。保证！

1. Swimming Downhill: This tests how well you’re able to press your buoy to improve your balance, bring your butt to the surface, and reduce drag. Learn to do it right, and improvement is instantaneous. Guaranteed.

保持这种SSP感觉：就像你在按压浮标练习中所做的那样，告诉自己游泳时必须将身体靠在胸前。你可能会感觉自己像在顺坡游动。这很好。其他游泳者说，这就像有人在游泳时按压他们的肩胛骨。一位跑步者在她的运动中也体会到了这种感觉：她感觉自己好像微微前倾，以保持平衡并支撑身体抵御强劲的逆风。当你做对了，你的臀部会感觉更轻，打腿也会更轻松。事实上，完全放松你的腿，这样它们就可以自然地跟着一起游动。保持身体前倾并掠过水面。如果你有意识地、虔诚地这样做，你最终会本能地做到这一点。

HOLD ON TO THIS SSP FEELING: Just as you did on the pressing-your-buoy drill, tell yourself you’ve got to lean on your chest as you swim. You may feel as if you’re swimming downhill. That’s good. Other swimmers have said it’s like someone pressing down on their shoulder blades as they swim. And a runner recognized the feeling from her sport: She felt as though she were leaning forward slightly to balance and brace her body against a punchy headwind. When you get it right, your hips will feel lighter, your kick far easier. In fact, relax your legs completely so they can simply follow along. Keep leaning and skimming the water. If you do it consciously and religiously, you’ll eventually do it instinctively.

 

 

2. 无重手臂游泳：前躯游泳的关键，它可以让你的身体在水中更高、更快。

2. Swimming with a Weightless Arm: The key to front-quadrant swimming, which makes your body taller and faster in the water.

保持这种SSP的感觉：当你顺势游下坡时，将全身重量压在浮标上，伸展的手臂应该感觉几乎没有重量，因为它入水后几乎漂浮在你面前。你的指尖毫不费力地向泳池远端推去，直到你选择对手施加压力并开始划水。你还会感觉到被拉长了——无重量的手臂让你每次划水时都显得更高，当你翻身换气时，甚至更高。

HOLD ON TO THIS SSP FEELING: When you swim downhill, putting all your weight on your buoy, your extended arm should feel virtually weightless as it practically floats out in front of you after it enters the water. Your fingertips thrust effortlessly toward the far end of the pool until you choose to apply pressure to your hand and begin the stroke. You also feel elongated—your weightless arm makes you taller each time you stroke, and even taller as you roll to breathe.

 

 

3. 伸手去够远墙：这是对无重臂的补充。有些游泳者一接触水就忍不住想直接跳入水中划水。这很不好。这会让他们的身高变矮，速度变慢，而且失去平衡。这可以打破这个习惯。

3. Reaching for the Far Wall: This complements the weightless arm. Some swimmers can’t fight the impulse to dive right into the stroke as soon as their hand touches the water. Not good. It makes them shorter, makes them slower, and makes them unbalanced. This breaks that habit.

保持这种SSP的感觉：如果你的手一入水就顽固地向下向后抽搐，试试这个。假装每一次划水都是你游完这圈的最后一次，也就是你伸手去够泳池壁的那一次。以这样的方式游完这一圈的每一次划水。伸手去够池壁。当你伸手的时候，感觉你的肩膀贴着下颌线。（如果是呼吸划水，你应该感觉到你的耳朵贴着伸出手臂的肩膀。）然后，当你再也伸不下去的时候，就开始划水。还有一点：慢慢地伸手去够池壁；你的手伸开的速度不应该比你身体向前移动的速度快。

HOLD ON TO THIS SSP FEELING: If your hands stubbornly jerk down and back as soon as they enter the water, try this. Pretend every stroke is the last of your lap, the one where you reach out for the pool wall. Swim every stroke of the lap that way. Reach for the wall. As you’re reaching, feel your shoulder press alongside your jaw-line. (If it’s a breathing stroke, you should feel your ear pressing into the shoulder of the extending arm.) Then, when you can’t reach any farther, begin to pull. One more point: Reach slowly for the wall; your hand shouldn’t be extending any faster than your body is moving forward.

 

 

4. 手交换：你已经学会了伸展手臂和身体，但“伸展器”应该在外面停留多久才能另一只手出现了吗？换手可以告诉你，当恢复手过来时，何时开始抚摸伸出的手。

4. Hand Swapping: You’ve learned to extend your arm and lengthen your body, but how long should that “extender” stay out there before the other hand shows up? Hand swapping tells you when to begin stroking the extended hand as the recovery hand comes around.

保持这种SSP的感觉：是不是感觉你比平时等得更久才开始划水？就是这样！其实，关键在于把伸出的手的划水动作推迟到另一只手即将重新入水并位于头部前方时再开始。正如我们所说，这能让你的身体在每次划水循环中保持更长、更快的速度。但除非你伸出的手臂没有重量，否则你无法做到这一点，所以如果你还没有掌握SSP，请先回去掌握它。

HOLD ON TO THIS SSP FEELING: Does it seem like you’re waiting to start your stroke just a little longer than you’re used to? That’s it! The whole point, in fact, is to put off pulling with the extended hand until the other one is just about to reenter the water and take its place in front of your head. As we said, this keeps your body longer—and faster—for more of each stroke cycle. But you won’t be able to do it unless your extended arm is weightless, so go back and master that one first if you haven’t yet.

你可能需要做一些小练习才能掌握正确的换手动作。“哇！又要开始练习了？”你抗议道。“你为什么让我在你的游泳学校留级？”别担心。这是所有感官技能目标中最难学的，因为它涉及细微的划水时机调整，但它值得掌握，因为它可以大大增加你的划水长度。以25码为增量练习这个序列，直到感觉舒服为止。

You may have to do a little drill to get hand swapping right. “Whoa. Back to drills again?” you protest. “Why are you making me repeat a grade in this swimming school of yours?” Don’t worry. This is the hardest to learn of all the sensory skill targets because it involves subtle stroke-timing adjustments, but it’s worth mastering because it can greatly increase your stroke length. Practice this sequence—in 25-yard increments—until it begins to feel comfortable.

 

 

1. 当恢复的手位于伸出的手的肘部和手腕之间时，开始每次新的划水。

1. Begin each new stroke when your recovering hand is between elbow and wrist of the extended hand.

2. 当恢复的手位于伸出的手的肩膀和肘部之间时开始每次划水。

2. Begin each stroke when your recovering hand is between shoulder and elbow of the extended hand.

3. 当恢复的手经过护目镜时开始每次划水。

3. Begin each stroke when your recovering hand passes your goggles.

4. 安静地游泳并数着你的划水次数。

4. Swim silently and count your strokes.

一开始，换手会感觉夸张而不自然。这个四步练习将引导你的身体逐渐适应动作。反复循环这个序列，你很快就会找到划水时机的“最佳点”。

Initially, hand swapping feels exaggerated and unnatural. This four-step practice guides your body into gradually feeling at home with the movement. Cycle over and over through this sequence and you’ll soon pinpoint the “sweet spot” in your stroke timing.

 

 

5. 移动你的腹部：如果侧身游泳仍然让你感觉不舒服，而且你的臀部抵抗着大脑发出的滚动信号，那就练习这个动作。

5. Moving Your Midsection: If swimming on your side still feels awkward and your hips resist your brain’s message to roll, practice this one.

保持这种 SSP 感觉：这里要做什么都很清楚。每次划水时，只需将肚脐朝向泳池两侧的墙壁。当然不是字面意思——你需要一个装有滚珠轴承的脊柱才能滚动那么远。但有了这个目标，你会移动得更好。当增加滚动开始感觉更自然时，你可以放松，因为你会不假思索地做到这一点。只需确保你总是有节奏地左右移动你的腹部。现在你用你强有力的臀部游泳，而不是你弱小的手。当你想游得更有力时，在你的臀部节奏中增加更多的力度。当你想游得更快时，在你的臀部节奏中增加更快的速度。坚持下去，直到你对划水节奏的整体感觉是你腹部来回移动的节奏，而不是你手臂搅动的节奏。

HOLD ON TO THIS SSP FEELING: Nothing ambiguous about what to do here. On every stroke, just point your belly button toward the pool side wall on each side. Not literally, of course—you’d need a ball-bearing-mounted spine to roll that far. But with that target, you will move better. And as increased roll begins to feel more natural, you can relax because you’ll be doing it without thinking. Just make sure you’re always shifting your midsection rhythmically from side to side. Now you’re swimming with your powerful hips, not your puny hands. When you want to swim more powerfully yet, put more snap into your hip rhythm. When you want to swim faster, put more speed into your hip rhythm. Keep it up until your whole sense of stroke rhythm is the rhythm of your midsection moving back and forth, not that of your arms churning.

我能给出的最有力的证明是，感官技能练习的有效性在训练失败的地方却取得了成功。尽管我见过训练给人们带来诸多好处，但有些游泳者在练习中却遇到了困难。由于这样或那样的原因——打腿不好、协调性差，甚至对下水感到焦虑——他们在练习时很吃力，不幸的是，他们甚至开始怀疑自己是不是游泳学生的料。

The most powerful testimony I can give for the effectiveness of sensory skill practice is that I’ve actually seen it succeed where drill work stumbled. Despite all the wonderful things I’ve seen drills do for people, some swimmers just have a hard time with them. For one reason or another—poor kick, poor coordination, even anxiety about being in the water—they struggle when they drill, and unfortunately even begin to wonder if they’re swimming-student material.

感官技能练习：轻松搞定

Sensory Skill Practice: Easy Does It

1. 首先，交替练习SSP和传达相同信息的钻头长度。两者之间的相似之处将帮助你更清晰、更深入地掌握你想要的确切感觉。

1. Start by alternating SSP with drill lengths that broadcast the same message. The similarities between the two will give you a clearer and stronger grasp of the exact sensation you’re after.

2. 一开始练习的次数限制在25码（或单程）的重复练习。前半程不换气——不是为了测试你是否能做到不吸气，而是因为如果你的身体不需要调整呼吸机制，就能更快地吸收新的感觉。然后平稳地过渡到正常呼吸，但要集中注意力，专注于感觉本身。

2. Limit your practice to 25-yard (or single-length) repeats at first. Swim the first half-length without breathing—not to see if you can do without air but because your body will absorb the new sensation faster if it doesn’t also have to attend to the mechanics of breathing. Then segue smoothly into normal breathing but stay strongly and narrowly focused on the sensation.

3. 慢慢来。在水中轻柔移动时，你的身体对新感觉更敏感。之后你有足够的机会加快速度。

3. Go slowly. Your body is more sensitive to new sensations when moving gently through the water. You’ll have plenty of chance to pile on speed later.

4. 每游完一程，停下来思考一下你刚才做了什么。如果你顺坡游，你的臀部是否感觉更轻盈，打腿是否更轻松？如果你正向池壁游去，你是否感觉身体伸展开来？如果没有，那就回到之前的练习，这会强化并明确你想要营造的感觉。

4. At the end of each length, stop and think a moment about what you just did. If you were swimming downhill, did your hips feel lighter and your kick easier? If you were reaching for the wall, did you feel your body lengthen? If not, go back to the related drill, which will accentuate and clarify the feeling you’re trying to create.

5. 练习足够长的时间，直到感觉稳定下来。当感觉稳定下来时你就会知道，但当你练习新动作时，我建议你练习大约八到十次。

5. Do enough lengths for the sensation to settle in. You’ll know when that happens, but I’d look for it at around eight to ten repeats while you’re working on something new.

当你掌握了所有这些技能后，请继续保持你的动力：

And when you’ve got all that under your belt, keep your momentum going by:

 

 

1. 逐渐将你的重复游程延长到50码、100码，甚至200码。最终游到1英里或更远也不算太远大。如果这是您计划参加的比赛长度，那么您的新效率将保持不变。

1. Gradually lengthening your repeats to 50, 100, perhaps even 200 yards. It’s not too ambitious to want to eventually swim a mile or more with your new efficiency intact, if that’s the length of a race you plan to swim.

2. 在一次游动中融合两种感觉（例如，手臂无重量地顺坡游，或者手臂无重量地伸手去够墙壁，或者手臂腹部左右移动地顺坡游）。

2. Blending two sensations in one length (e.g., swim downhill with a weightless arm, or reach for the wall with a weightless arm, or swim downhill moving your midsection from side to side).

3. 在每个游程中交替感觉目标（例如，在一系列 50 米游程中：在第一个 25 米时顺坡游动，在第二个 25 米时无重量手臂游动）。

3. Alternating sensory targets on each length (e.g., on a series of 50s: swim downhill on the first 25, weightless arm on the second 25).

4. 加大油门：游一组50秒：25秒慢速/25秒快速。让“更快”的速度接近（或逐步提升）你在比赛中能达到的努力程度。你能保持多好的专注力？保持好你的游泳姿势？这决定了你在比赛中能否保持高效。

4. Pumping the throttle: swim a series of 50s: 25 slow/25 faster. Make the “faster” approximate (or build toward over the series of 50s) the effort level you’ll reach while swimming your race. How well can you keep your focus? Hold your form? That’s how well you’ll be able to stay efficient in races.

当然需要。他们只是需要更个性化的课程。所以，对于那些抗拒练习的人，我的做法是减少他们的练习。我们寻找一种刚开始为针头切入感官凹槽的最低限度，并花更多时间在更有意识地调整感官技能练习的笔触上。他们运用练习所教授的相同原则，但能更直接、更快速地将其运用到笔触中。

Of course they are. They just need a more customized curriculum. So what I do for these drill-resistant types is pull back on their drill work. We look for a minimum that just begins to cut the sensory groove for the needle, and we spend more time on the more conscious stroke modifications of sensory skill practice. They apply the same principles the drills teach, but they apply them directly and more quickly into the stroke.

通过练习，大多数人都能更好、更快、更清晰地掌握新的感觉。但如果这些练习对你不起作用，感觉技能练习或许能帮助你快速进步。

Most everyone can learn the new sensations better, faster, and more clearly with drills. But if they’re not working for you, sensory skill practice may jump-start your progress.

划水消除器和游泳高尔夫：SSP 的两项测试

Stroke Eliminators and Swimming Golf: Two Tests of Your SSP

当然，感觉技能练习的最终目的并非让你感觉更好，而是让你游得更好，练就更高效的划水技巧。你会记得，更高效的划水技巧是让你的身体在水中划得更远，这样你游任何给定距离只需要更少的划水次数。用更少的能量做更多的功。由于更少、更长的划水次数已被反复认定为专业游泳运动员的标志，这种优势不仅仅是理论上的。它能为我们其他人赢得奖牌，带来竞技和个人满足感。

The whole point of sensory skill practice, of course, is not to make you feel better but to make you swim better, to build a more efficient stroke. And a more efficient stroke, you’ll remember, is one that moves your body farther through the water so you need fewer of them to go any given distance. More work from less energy. Since fewer and longer strokes have been identified over and over as the consistent mark of the expert swimmer, the advantage is not merely theoretical. It’s what earns medals for the competitive and personal satisfaction for the rest of us.

好的。但是你如何知道自己是否取得了进步呢？很高兴你问到这个问题。我们接下来的两个练习策略就是为了衡量这一点。

Fine. But how do you find out whether you’re making any progress? Glad you asked. Our next two practice strategies measure just that.

中风消除剂

STROKE ELIMINATORS

第一个被称为“消除击球次数”，因为它就是这个意思——没有什么比简单地训练自己使用比平常更少的击球次数更花哨的了。

The first is called stroke eliminators because that’s just what it is— nothing fancier than simply disciplining yourself to use fewer strokes than you usually do.

亚历山大·波波夫正是运用这一有效策略，成为全球最高效的游泳运动员之一。即使你的成绩略有不同，它也同样有效。别忘了，波波夫在50米自由泳中赢得了无人能及的称号，这可是游泳界的全速冲刺。在一场又一场的比赛中，他从泳池的一端游到另一端，只需要划水33下。但为了达到这个惊人的低划数，他在训练中严格要求自己做得更好，经常在50米重复赛中强迫自己每次划水都极其吝啬地只用24次。通过训练，他能够勉强完成这24次划水，比赛当天他允许自己划33次（不过，这仍然比他的对手少了3次）就轻而易举了。

It’s an effective tactic Alexander Popov has used to become one of the most efficient swimmers on earth. And it can work just as well for you—even if your numbers are understandably a little different. Popov, remember, has earned the title of being untouchable in the 50-meter freestyle, swimming’s version of a flat-out sprint. Race after race, he takes exactly 33 strokes to get from one end of the pool to the other. But to achieve that remarkably low count, he disciplines himself to do even better in practice, often forcing himself during 50-meter repeats to take an extremely stingy 24 strokes on each. By training his body to get by on those 24, the 33 he allows himself on race day (still three fewer than any of his rivals can manage, mind you) are a piece of cake.

如果这九个划水动作看起来不太惊艳，那就自己试试吧。找一个真正的奥林匹克标准泳池（50米或165英尺，而不是收费公路边的汽车旅馆喜欢吹嘘的那种“奥林匹克标准”的浴缸）。首先，看看你慢游一程需要多少划水。接下来，看看你快游一程需要多少划水。差别很大，不是吗？我就是这么想的。你可以先做波波夫已经完善的一套动作的变式，来缩小差距。

If that nine-stroke spread doesn’t seem exactly stunning, try this for yourself. Find a true Olympic-size pool (50 meters or 165 feet, not the bathtubs that turnpike motels love to trumpet as “Olympic size”). First, see how many strokes it takes you to swim a slow length. Next, see how many strokes it takes you to swim a fast length. A huge difference, isn’t there? I thought so. You can start narrowing that down by doing a variation of a set Popov has perfected.

目标是：看看他能在不超过24次划水的情况下，多快地接近比赛速度。他从“慢速”50米开始（可能比他22秒的比赛成绩慢10秒或更多），之后每次重复，他都会加快一点速度。当他无法再加快速度的同时还能保持24次划水时，他就会降回“慢速”，然后再逐步提高速度曲线，在每一轮中都努力提高速度，在不超过24次划水配额的情况下，越来越接近比赛速度。

Its objective: to see how close he can get to his race speed without taking more than 24 strokes. He starts with a “slow” 50 meters (maybe 10 or more seconds slower than his 22-second race time) and on each successive repeat he goes a little faster. When he can’t go any quicker and still hold 24 strokes, he drops back to “slow” and works his way back up the speed curve again, trying on each round to eke out a bit more speed and get ever closer to his race speed without ever exceeding his 24-stroke allotment.

这就是纪律。你也可以尝试一下，用波波夫的训练方法的变式。首先，计算25码（或你常用泳池的长度）的平均划水次数。这个数字要切合实际，而不是为了完成一次完美、充分休息的划水。比如说，在游完半英里（约800米）的27分之一时，就计算划水次数。你已经训练了一段时间，感觉有些累了，你的状态可能处于“可用”的水平。

Now, that’s discipline. And it’s discipline you can try too, using a variation of Popov’s set. First, get an average stroke count for 25 yards (or whatever the length of your regular pool). Make it realistic, not what you need to do a single, perfect, well-rested length. Make it the count at the end of, say, the twenty-seventh length of a half-mile swim. You’ve been working a while, you’re getting tired, and your form is probably somewhere around “serviceable.”

从现在起，这就是我们要打败的数字，无论有多少游完你游过的距离。立下誓言。拒绝再次以任何理由，在耻辱和羞辱的痛苦下，游完这段距离。

From now on, that’s the number to beat, no matter how many lengths you swim. Take the pledge. Refuse, under pain of disgrace and dishonor, to take that many strokes for that distance again, for any reason.

它的工作原理如下。如果你通常每圈划21到22下，那么现在你的任务就是用19到20下划完成所有循环，而不是多划一次。乍一看很简单，不是吗？你游了10个50码的循环，前几次感觉很清爽，并且轻松保持19到20下划数。这个划数消除过程轻而易举！

Here’s how it works. If you normally take 21 to 22 strokes per length, your mission now is to do all repeats in 19 to 20 strokes and not one more. Seems simple at first, doesn’t it? You swim a series of ten 50-yard repeats, feeling fresh on the first few and easily holding the 19- to-20-stroke count. This stroke elimination’s a breeze!

然后，在第四次游的第二段，你漫不经心地游向泳池，游了第二十次，然后啊哦。为什么墙还在五码之外？

Then, on the second length of the fourth repeat, you head nonchalantly down the pool, take your twentieth stroke, and uh-oh. How come the wall is still five yards away?

你能怎么办呢？你发誓不接受第二十一击，所以只有一件事可做：侧身翻滚，然后踢向墙壁。嗯……看来，这消除划水的计划终究还是要费一番功夫的。

And what can you do about it? You’ve sworn not to take the twenty-first stroke, so there’s only one thing to do: roll to your side and kick to the wall. Hmmmmm. Evidently this stroke elimination business will take some work after all.

所以，当你开始下一个划水长度，以及从现在开始的每一个划水长度时，你都会变得非常注重手臂的周转，敏锐地意识到你如何运用每一次划水，确保你完成了20次划水，划出了25码。时间被遗忘了。隔壁泳道的对手也被遗忘了。唯一重要的是你如何运用你必须付出的——这就是你学会节省的方式。就像现实生活一样。

So as you begin your next length, and every one from now on, you become the miser of arm turnover, keenly aware of how you spend every stroke, making sure that you make twenty of them stretch 25 yards. The clock is forgotten. The rival in the next lane is forgotten. The only thing that matters is how you’re spending what you have to spend—which is how you learn to save. Just like real life.

跟我重复一遍：你努力的是你达到目标的程度，而不是速度。一开始，较低的划水次数会让你的速度变慢。这是预料之中的，不必担心。你还需要伸展身体，滑行更长时间。这也没关系。你之前的划水次数“正常”了很长时间，你的身体需要一些时间来适应。最终，较低、更高效的划水次数会成为你的“新常态”，不知何故，在你痴迷于击球的过程中，你的速度也会在你不经意间恢复过来。正如优秀的老师们所知道的，纪律能教会你放纵无法做到的事情。

Repeat after me: You’re working on how well you get there, not how fast. At first, a lower stroke count will slow you down. Expect that and don’t worry about it. You’ll also have to stretch and glide longer. That’s okay too. Your old count was “normal” for so long that it will take some time for your body to adjust. Eventually, the lower, more efficient count will become your “new normal,” and somehow, in all that obsession with strokes, your speed will have come back too while you weren’t looking. As good teachers have always known, discipline teaches what indulgence never could.

每25码划水20次是一个有意义的基准，它能区分出游泳的优劣。如果你的划水次数更高，不要放松减少划水次数的努力，直到达到或低于这个数字。当你能轻松地用20次或更少的划水次数游完25码时，尝试用40次或更少的划水次数游完50码，然后用60次或更少的划水次数游完75码。但如果这意味着每段划水次数超过20次，就不要盲目地增加重复次数。成为一名持续高效游泳者的唯一方法是拒绝练习低效的游泳方式。

Twenty strokes per 25-yard length is a meaningful benchmark for where the swimming wheat and chaff are separated. If your count is higher, don’t slacken your stroke-eliminating efforts until you get there or below. When you can easily swim 25 yards in 20 strokes or less, try for 50 in 40 or less, then 75 yards in 60 strokes or less. But don’t blindly add lengths to your repeats if it means taking more than 20 strokes per length. The only way to become a consistently efficient swimmer is to refuse to practice inefficient swimming.

当你能经常以80次或更少的划水次数游完100码（四个长度）时（美国1650码自由泳纪录保持者汤姆·多兰在创造一英里纪录时，每100码划水次数为56次），你就可以开始进行间歇15到30秒的100码重复训练了。一旦你能完成8到10次这样的训练，并且每次划水次数不超过80次，你就已经跨过了通往游泳成功的重要门槛。你当然可以带着这样的划水次数去参加铁人三项或大师赛，自豪地炫耀一番。

When you can routinely swim 100 yards—four lengths—in 80 strokes or less (Tom Dolan, the American record holder in the 1650-yard freestyle, took 56 strokes per 100 yards while setting his mile record), you’re ready to start building sets of 100-yard repeats on 15 to 30 seconds of rest. Once you can do eight to ten of those—and never take more than 80 strokes—you’ll have crossed an important threshold toward swimming success. You could certainly take that stroke to a triathlon or Masters meet and show it off with pride.

所以，要训练自己几乎每游一圈都数划水次数，直到效率成为习惯。然后，像波波夫一样，你可以开始精明地用划水次数换取速度。用最少的划水次数换取最大的速度提升，如果你对这个代价不满意，就再试一次。用你最低的划水次数游两到三次50码。然后再游几次，每次都稍微快一点，试着减少每一秒速度提升的“划水成本”。一遍又一遍地重复这个循环。每次都争取更好的价格。和自己好好讨价还价。当你掌握了50码的比赛，不妨试试100码的重复赛，这样你就能有更大的场地来打比赛。高尔夫比赛，也就是游泳高尔夫。

So discipline yourself to count strokes nearly every length until efficiency has become habit. Then, like Popov, you can begin to trade them shrewdly for speed. Spend the fewest strokes for the most additional speed, and if you’re not satisfied at the cost, try it again. Swim two or three 50-yard repeats at your lowest count. Then several more, each one a little faster, trying to reduce the “stroke cost” for each second of speed gain. Run through the cycle over and over. Get a better deal each time. Drive a hard bargain with yourself. As you master the 50-yard transaction, try it with your 100-yard repeats, which will give you a larger field on which to play the game. The game of golf. Swimming golf, that is.

游泳 高尔夫

SWIMMING GOLF

当你的划水次数少到令人咋舌的地步，以至于你永远也游不到终点时，你可能会沉迷于这种消除划水次数的做法。聪明的人还能想出办法来欺骗划水消除系统，让划水次数增加，但游泳效果却不好——比如滑行或在蹬水后踢半个身子。如果所有这些效率提升的真正目的是游得更快，你肯定想知道这是否真的实现了。好吧，那就准备开始玩游泳高尔夫吧，这是提高划水效率的第二个策略。

It’s possible to get too carried away with this business of eliminating strokes when you’re down to such a triumphantly tiny number of strokes that you’re taking forever to get to the other end. Clever types can also figure out a way to cheat the stroke-eliminator system so the numbers are better but the swimming is not—say by gliding or kicking half a length after pushoff. If the real point of all these efficiency gains is swimming faster, you want to know whether that’s happening. Well, just tee up for some swimming golf, the second strategy for increasing your stroke efficiency.

SSP：冠军通过慢速游泳获得了什么

SSP: What Champions Gain by Swimming Slowly

当俄罗斯国家游泳队在南卡罗来纳大学训练一个月，力争击败美国国家队时，他们几乎对比尔·欧文隐瞒不了任何秘密。欧文是我高中开始游泳时的第一位真正的教练，他住在南卡罗来纳州的哥伦比亚市，每天都在南加州大学游泳。所以他每天早上都和俄罗斯队员们一起露营，睁着眼睛，手里拿着笔记本，摄像机嗡嗡作响。

When the Russian National Swim Team spent a month at the University of South Carolina training to beat the U.S. National Team, they could hardly keep any secrets from Bill Irwin. Irwin, my first real coach when I began swimming in high school, lives in Columbia, South Carolina, and swims every day at U.S.C. So he just camped out with the Russians each morning, eyes open, notepad in hand, video camera humming.

欧文承认，他并没有看到自己预期的结果。的确，游得令人印象深刻，但并不费力，速度也不算特别快。“整个月他们几乎都没出过一滴汗，”欧文回忆道。“他们每天游四五个小时，不停地做着轻松的自由泳重复动作，并采用半追赶式的划水。”（参见91-93页的换手练习。）

He didn’t see what he expected, Irwin admitted. Impressive swimming, yes, but not grueling nor even especially fast. “The whole month they hardly ever broke a sweat,” Irwin recalled. “They swam four to five hours a day, doing endless sets of easy freestyle repeats with a half-catch-up stroke.” (See the hand-swapping drill on pages 91–93.)

也许很容易，但要求很高。

Easy, perhaps, but exacting.

欧文问俄罗斯教练，为什么他们要为这种夸张的划水动作做那么多练习？教练回答说，因为世界冠军亚历山大·波波夫的一大优势就是他习惯于始终将一只手放在头前，以拉长身体。所以教练希望他的所有自由泳运动员也养成这个习惯，他知道这并非自然而然。他们必须让它自然而然，“把它刻进神经系统”，每天反复练习这个循环数小时，直到每个游泳运动员的神经系统都接受它。不管俄罗斯人怎么称呼它，他们都用整整一个月的时间，以非凡的耐心练习一种感觉技能——换手。毫无疑问，这是在任何艰苦或快速的游泳之前进行的。

Why, Irwin asked the Russian coach, did they do all that work on this exaggerated stroke? Because, came the answer, one of world champion Alexander Popov’s big advantages was his habit of always having one hand in front of his head to lengthen his body. So the coach wanted all of his freestylers to make that a habit too, and he knew it didn’t come naturally. They would simply have to make it natural, “burn it into the nervous system” by running that loop over and over for hours a day until each swimmer’s nervous system owned it. Whatever the Russian term for it may be, they devoted that entire month to practicing one form of sensory skill practice—hand swapping—with extraordinary patience. No question that it came before any hard or fast swimming.

可惜美国最有天赋的自由泳运动员之一没能到场观看。在西海岸参加一个“全浸式”训练营时，我有幸观看了他30分钟的训练。我知道他曾与世界顶尖选手同场竞技，甚至在接力赛中打破过世界纪录，但过去几年却与这些精彩的成绩擦肩而过。他甚至说过要退役，尽管距离巅峰状态还有几年时间。

Too bad one of the most gifted freestylers in the U.S. wasn’t there to watch. On the West Coast for a Total Immersion workshop, I had a chance to watch him train for thirty minutes, knowing that he’s raced with the world’s best, even swimming on world-record-setting relays, but that those great swims have eluded him for the past few years. He’s even talked of quitting, though still years short of his prime.

于是，我好奇地看着他进行一系列冲刺跑和轻松恢复跑交替进行。你知道吗？每次冲刺，他的身体都会伸展开来，效率极高。但每次轻松跑，他的状态就变得马虎。他只想着身体的恢复，却没有意识到轻松跑也在训练他的神经系统，让他在疲惫时变得效率低下。在他看来，艰苦的努力——锻炼生理机能——才是训练中最有价值的部分。但他对神经系统的粗心训练，却完全破坏了有氧训练。

So I watched, curious, as he did a series of sprints alternating with easy recovery lengths. And what do you know? On each sprint, his body stretched out long and efficient. But on every easy length, he lapsed into sloppy form. Thinking only of physical recovery, he didn’t realize his easy laps were also training his nervous system to lapse into inefficiency whenever he got tired. In his mind, the hard effort—working the physiology—was the valuable part of the workout. But his careless training of his nervous system was completely undermining the aerobic work.

他的低迷不再令我感到惊讶。

His slump no longer surprises me.

你不需要俱乐部会员资格，规则也很简单。对于给定的距离，计算你的划水次数，并将其加到你的时间（以秒为单位）上。一个相当优秀的游泳者通常可以在40次划水和40秒内完成50码重复游的两段距离。那就是80分。（请注意，50码重复游的分数与打高尔夫球的分数非常接近。）“笨蛋”通常可以争取90分，而真正的游泳者可能在60分出头。50码的重复游是最好的，因为数字很容易计算。

You don’t need a club membership, and the rules are simple. For a given distance, count your strokes and add that to your time in seconds. A reasonably good swimmer can usually swim the two lengths of a 50-yard repeat in 40 strokes and 40 seconds. That’s a score of 80. (Notice how conveniently the scores on 50-yard repeats approximate those on a golf round.) A “duffer” can usually aim for a score of 90, serious swimmers might be in the low 60s. Repeats of 50 yards are best because the numbers are easy to work with.

降低分数的秘诀总是先减少划水次数，然后再尝试提高速度。只需几轮就能让你眼前一亮。你会惊讶地发现，多加一点努力就能快速增加划水次数。如果这些划水次数没有转化为足够的速度来降低你的总分，你马上就会明白自己是多么浪费时间。记住，速度等于划水频率 (SR) 乘以划水长度 (SL)，几乎每个人的 SR 都足够。你需要提高的是你的划水长度 (SL)。你的高尔夫分数将准确衡量你如何利用划水长度来提高速度。前进！

Always lower your score by reducing stroke count first and later by trying to swim faster. Just a few rounds should be eye-opening. You’ll be amazed how quickly a bit more effort can add a lot more strokes. If those strokes don’t translate into enough speed to lower your total score, you know right away how wasteful you’ve been. Remember, speed equals stroke rate (SR) multiplied by stroke length (SL), and just about everyone has enough SR. It’s your SL that needs work. Your golf score will be an unerring measure of how well you’re using SL to create speed. Fore!

我们终于完成了“完全沉浸式”学习曲线的绘制。现在你明白了，技术才是你即将开始的游泳进步的基础，而不是汗水或肌肉。一切始于了解你的身体是如何运动的。在水中，您可以做出最快、最显著的改变来改善这一点，进行那些改变的练习，最后如何练习更顺畅、更令人满意的游泳，这些练习可以帮助您实现这一目标，以便您的新泳姿成为第二天性。

We’ve finally finished drawing the Total Immersion learning curve. You now understand that technique, not sweat or muscle, is the foundation for the serious swimming improvement you’re about to embark on. It started with finding out how your body really moves through the water, the quickest and most dramatic changes you can make to improve that, the drills that start those changes happening, and finally how to practice the smoother and more satisfying swimming that the drills are helping you achieve so that your new stroke becomes second nature.

现在是时候去泳池，开始实施你的新计划了——通过练习正确的技巧来保持健康。在第8章中，我们将穿上泳衣，来到甲板上，浑身湿透。是时候开始你的“锻炼”了——全新的方式。

Now it’s time to get to the pool and start putting your new plan to work—getting fit by practicing proper technique. In chapter 8, we’ll get suited up, onto the deck, and wet. It’s time to start your “work-outs”—the new way.

8

鱼泳学校

The School for Fishlike Swimming

到目前为止，我们一直致力于构建知识基础知识，让你了解什么是良好的游泳水平，以及如何通过改变“船”的形状来游得更好。既然你已经对游泳有了一定的了解，现在是时候把课堂搬到游泳池，开始训练你的肌肉了。在六节完全沉浸式“游泳课”和其他关于如何成功自学的指导之后，你将学会一种全新的游泳方式，这种方式会更快、更轻松、更有趣。我准备了这个课程计划，就好像每个拿起这本书的人都对游泳一无所知一样。我们发现，我们所有的学生，无论他们已经游了多少泳，如果从最基本的技能开始，并按逻辑顺序完成整个 TI 练习，进步会更快。所以，让我们开始吧。

Up to this point, we’ve focused on building a knowledge foundation that allows you to understand what constitutes good swimming and how you can swim better just by changing the shape of your “vessel.” Now that you’re book-smart about swimming, it’s time to move our classroom to the pool and begin teaching your muscles. Over the course of six Total Immersion “swim lessons” and other guidance on how to teach yourself successfully, you will learn to swim in a completely new way that will be faster, easier, and more enjoyable. I’ve prepared this lesson plan as if every person who picks up this book knows nothing at all about swimming. We’ve found that all of our students, no matter how much swimming they may already have done, progress much faster by starting with the most elementary skill and progressing logically through the whole sequence of TI drills. So let’s get right to it.

但首先：接下来的六节课包含了TI学习序列中每个练习的详尽说明，并配有关键位置的插图。不过，正如我们的一位学生所说：“如果一张图片胜过千言万语，那么视频一定胜过万言。” 除了TI教练的面对面授课外，掌握所有基本技能最可靠的方法是使用配套DVD 《自由式轻松学》（Freestyle Made Easy）将作为您掌握要点和所需动作质量的主要指南。本视频旨在完美补充本章内容。有关视频的详细信息，请参阅背面的资源部分。

But First: The six lessons that follow contain exhaustively detailed instructions on how to do each drill in the TI learning sequence, complemented by illustrations of the key positions. Still, as one of our students said, “If a picture is worth a thousand words, video must be worth ten thousand words.” Short of being taught face-to-face by a TI Coach, the surest way to master all of the essential skills is to use the companion DVD, Freestyle Made Easy, as your primary guide to the fine points and desired movement quality. This video has been designed as the perfect complement to the information in this chapter. For info on the video, please refer to the resources section in the back.

从“初学者的心态”开始

Starting with a “Beginner’s Mind”

下次去泳池的时候，花十分钟观察其他游泳者。你会发现——即使你观察一个人一个小时——他们的每一次划水动作看起来都一模一样。就像别人看着你一样。你的划水动作是一种习惯模式，它被成千上万次之前的划水动作深深地印在你的神经系统中。“熟能生巧”这句话只说对了一部分。“熟能生巧”才是更贴切的。

Next time you visit the pool, spend ten minutes watching other swimmers. What you’ll see—even if you watch someone for an hour—is that every stroke looks exactly the same. Which is just how you’d look to someone watching you. Your stroke is a habit pattern, deeply embedded in your nervous system by thousands or millions of previous strokes. The phrase “practice makes perfect” gets it only partly right. “Practice makes permanent” is far truer.

当我们从理论转向实践时，你即将成为自己的教练和老师。你的成功取决于只练习那些你“肌肉记忆”中喜欢的动作，并严格避免任何你不想被刻印的动作。“调整”你现在的划水动作会限制你的进步，因为数百万次之前的划水动作留下的印记很难改变。幸运的是，你现在有了一个行之有效的替代方案。

As we switch from theory to practice, you’re about to become your own coach and teacher. And your success will depend on practicing only the movements you’d like in your “muscle memory” and on scrupulously avoiding whatever you don’t want imprinted there. “Tweaking” your present stroke will limit your progress, because the imprint of millions of previous strokes is so resistant to change. Fortunately you now have a proven alternative.

每年，我们在TI工作坊中教授约1500名学生。他们在工作坊开始时的平均划水次数为21到22次，游25码。一天后，这个平均值提高到了16到17次，平均效率提升了近25%。经过几个小时的指导，这种程度的进步对于那些可能已经游了五年或十年却几乎没有明显变化的人来说是惊人的。这种卓越进步的两个主要原因分别是“肌肉失忆症”和“武术游泳”。你也可以通过在自我训练中遵循这两个原则来创造转变。

Each year we teach about 1,500 students in TI workshops. Their average stroke count at the beginning of the workshop is 21 to 22 strokes for 25 yards. A day later that average has improved to 16 to 17 strokes, or an average efficiency gain of nearly 25 percent. This degree of improvement, following several hours of instruction, is stunning for people who may have swum five or ten years with little noticeable change. The two primary reasons for such transcendent improvement are “muscle amnesia” and “martial-arts swimming.” You can also create transformation by observing these two principles in your self-coaching.

避免斗争

Avoiding Struggle

周六早上，我们录下学生们自由泳的全程视频后，他们直到周日下午的最后十到十五分钟才开始进行另一段完整的自由泳——到那时，他们已经花了大约六个小时练习高效的游泳动作，没有使用任何“老套”的自由泳划水动作。到那时，大多数人已经用一种新的、改进的划水动作取代了原来的划水动作。通过教授他们的神经系统无法识别为游泳的动作，我们让他们患上了“肌肉失忆症”，让他们从零开始学习新技能，摆脱旧习惯。

After we videotape our students doing a length of freestyle on Saturday morning, they don’t swim another length of whole-stroke freestyle until the final ten to fifteen minutes on Sunday afternoon—by which time they’ve spent about six hours practicing efficient swimming movements without a single “old” freestyle stroke. By then, most have replaced their old stroke with a new, improved stroke. By teaching with movements their nervous systems don’t recognize as swimming, we’ve given them “muscle amnesia,” a blank slate for learning new skills and bypassing old habits.

成功的第二个关键是“武术游泳”部分。正规的游泳教学仅存在了五十年左右，而武术的教学和练习却已有数千年的历史，这为武术大师提供了更多机会来学习教授动作技能的最佳方法。他们的不可动摇的规则是：“避免练习你无法正确完成的动作。” 我们添加了我们自己的不可动摇的规则：“永远不要练习挣扎。” 武术学生总是从看似极其简单的姿势和动作开始，然后循序渐进地学习更具挑战性的动作。

The second key to success is the “martial-arts swimming” part. Formal swimming instruction has existed for only fifty years or so, while martial arts have been taught and practiced for thousands of years, giving martial-arts masters considerably more opportunity to learn the best way to teach movement skills. Their nonnegotiable rule is: “Avoid practicing movements you cannot perform correctly.” We’ve added our own nonnegotiable rule, which is: “Never practice struggle.” Martial-arts students always start with positions and movements that seem ridiculously simple and progress through more challenging movements by small steps.

他们很快就会发现，看似最简单的动作最终会展现出巨大的复杂性，并且可以在多个层面上掌握。他们越耐心、越用心地练习每个步骤，动作就越流畅、轻松掌握高级技能。我们将引导你完成同样的步骤，最终成为像鱼一样的鱼。

As they soon discover, movements that seem the simplest eventually reveal great complexity and can be mastered on many levels. The more patiently and mindfully they practice each step, the more flowing and effortless they become at advanced skills. We’ll guide you through the same kind of progression on the way to being Fishlike.

通过“瑜伽呼吸”休息一下

Take a Break with “Yoga Breathing”

大多数游泳运动员和教练员在做任何事（包括技能训练）时，都根深蒂固地认为速度要快，休息要少。他们从不停止担心“保持码数”。所以让我澄清一下：训练的目的是最大限度地提高能量供应。技能训练的目的是最大限度地减少能量消耗。节约能源总能更快地带来更大的进步。为了获得所有潜在的好处，你必须耐心而专心地练习。一个行之有效的方法是忽略时钟。当我最专注于动作质量时，我从来不会看时钟。我只关心我能多么轻松安静地滑过水面，以及我的动作感觉多么流畅和协调。

It’s culturally ingrained for most swimmers and coaches to do every-thing—including skill drills—faster or with less rest. They never cease worrying about “keeping up the yardage.” So let me clarify: The purpose of training is to maximize energy supply. The purpose of skill drills is to minimize energy cost. Energy conservation always produces greater improvement, faster. To reap all their potential benefits, you must practice drills patiently and mindfully. One proven way is to ignore the pace clock. When I’m most focused on movement quality, I never so much as glance at the clock. I’m solely interested in how easily and quietly I can slip through the water and how fluent and coordinated my movements feel.

虽然我忽略了计时钟，但我仍然希望我的学生得到足够的休息，以保持心率处于中等有氧状态，从而能够专注、细致地运动。我们通过放松的“瑜伽呼吸”来休息和恢复。这有两个恢复性的好处：它们使呼吸正常化，有助于降低心率。它们还能让你的精神“集中”，减少干扰，提高注意力。

But though I ignore the pace clock, I still want my students to get enough rest to keep their heart rate in a moderate aerobic state that allows attentive, meticulous movement. We do that by using relaxing “yoga breaths” for rest and recovery. They bring two restorative advantages: They normalize breathing, which helps keep your heart rate down. They also “center” you mentally, reducing distraction and improving concentration.

每圈恢复

Recover During Each Lap

技巧很简单：慢慢吸气，然后呼气。放松片刻，再吸气。你可以在下一个训练周期或一圈之前，通过增加或减少瑜伽呼吸次数来轻松调节休息时间。在教学中，我建议学生在学习练习时，在“甜蜜点”（所有TI自由泳练习中内置的恢复暂停；你将在练习2和3中学习）的循环之间暂停，并至少进行三次呼吸。之后，他们可以将“甜蜜点”的瑜伽呼吸减少到一到两次，使他们的练习节奏更像“游泳”。将“甜蜜点”的暂停增加到五到七次呼吸，可以将任何练习变成踢腿练习，这比使用浮板更有价值。如果你的呼吸次数减少，请注意不要减少到让你感到匆忙的程度。

The technique is simple: Inhale slowly, then let your breath fall out. Relax a moment before inhaling again. You can regulate your rest easily by taking more or fewer yoga breaths before your next drill cycle or lap. While teaching, I recommend that students take at least three breaths while pausing between cycles in Sweet Spot (the built-in recovery pause in all TI freestyle drills; you’ll learn this in Drills 2 and 3), as they are learning the drills. Later, they can decrease to one or two yoga breaths in Sweet Spot to make their drill rhythm more “swimming-like.” Increasing the Sweet Spot pause to as many as five or seven breaths will turn any drill into a kicking exercise, which will be far more valuable than using a kickboard. If you take fewer breaths be careful not to reduce to the point where you feel rushed.

在墙上恢复

Recover at the Wall

我们还会在两圈之间靠墙做瑜伽呼吸来休息。我还建议每次重复练习之间至少做三次瑜伽呼吸。同样，你可以通过增加呼吸次数来轻松调整休息时间。你感觉有点气喘或疲劳吗？只需增加呼吸次数即可。如果重复次数较长，比如50秒而不是25秒，你可以将休息间隔从三次呼吸增加到五次。一旦你有机会尝试瑜伽呼吸间隔，你就会发现这是调整休息时间最简单的方法，只要你想……同时还能带来额外的好处，那就是提高注意力，而这种游泳方式总是需要更敏锐的注意力。

We also use yoga breaths to rest at the wall between laps. I also recommend at least three yoga breaths between each repeat. Again, you can easily adjust your rest taken by taking more breaths. Are you feeling slightly breathless or fatigued? Just add breaths. On longer reps, say, 50s, rather than 25s, you might increase your rest interval from three breaths to perhaps five. Once you’ve had a chance to experiment with the yoga-breathing interval, you’ll find it the simplest way to adjust your rest period as finely as you want … while bringing the additional dividend of improved concentration to a style of swimming that always benefits from more acute attention.

如果你像我一样，很快就会发现自己在其他活动中也会用呼吸作为恢复手段。我最初是在上瑜伽课时学到这个技巧的，很快就意识到它在游泳中的价值。现在，我把呼吸运用到各种运动中——从控制伸展姿势的持续时间，到调整瑜伽练习的节奏，从冥想式（每个姿势呼吸更多次）到动态式（每个姿势呼吸一次），再到在划船机上进行500米或1000米的重复训练时设置休息间隔。

If you’re like me, you’ll soon find yourself using breaths as your recovery device in other activities. I first learned the technique when taking yoga classes and quickly realized its value for swimming. Now I use them in all manner of exercise—from governing how long I hold a stretching position to varying my yoga practice from more meditative (more breaths in each position) to more dynamic (one breath in each position) to setting rest intervals between 500- or 1000-meter repeats on my rowing machine.

第一课：找到平衡点和你的“最佳点”

Lesson One: Finding Balance and Your “Sweet Spot”

这是武术游泳中“简单到爆”的部分，至少对一些运动员来说是这样。你甚至可能想跳过这节课。千万别！如果你拥有人类DNA——即使你已经参加过奥运会游泳——你仍然可以提高平衡能力，而且随着平衡能力的提高，无论速度如何，你消耗的能量都会更少。

This is the “ridiculously simple” part of martial-arts swimming, at least for some athletes. You may even be tempted to skip this lesson. Don’t! If you have human DNA—even if you’ve already swum in the Olympics—you can still improve your balance, and as it improves you’ll use less energy at any speed.

另一方面，如果你每次划水都令人沮丧，如果你游两圈就累得筋疲力尽，如果你总是感觉脚趾甲随时都有可能刮到池底，那么第一课能给你一种前所未有的感觉，让你仿佛躺在那里，轻轻地踢腿，紧张和不适感瞬间消失。一旦你掌握了这种感觉，你就会立刻游得轻松许多，剩下的课程也会更加顺利。

If, on the other hand, every stroke you’ve ever taken has been a frustrating struggle, if you’re toast after two laps, if you always feel as if your toenails are in danger of scraping the pool bottom, Lesson One can give you an unprecedented feeling of basically being able to just lie there, kicking gently, while tension and discomfort melt away. Once you have that, you’ll immediately swim with far more ease, and the rest of the lessons will go much more smoothly.

先头？

HEAD FIRST?

多年来，我观看了数千名“人类游泳者”的水下视频，首先注意到的是他们的手臂和腿部完全忙于保持平衡，试图不沉下去。他们可能以为自己在“划水”，但实际上，他们几乎没有任何能量产生推进力。相反，大部分能量都用来对抗下沉的感觉。除非你学会不借助手臂的力量轻松保持平衡，否则根本不可能有效地进行练习或划水。因此，你的第一步是让水在没有手臂帮助的情况下支撑你。在“头部引导”练习中，由于你无法用手臂支撑身体，你将学会通过正确的头部位置和重量分布来完全平衡身体。

In watching underwater video of thousands of “human swimmers” over the years, what I notice first is how completely their arms and legs are occupied with trying not to sink. They may think what they’re doing is “stroking,” but virtually none of their energy is producing propulsion. Instead, most of it goes into fighting that sinking feeling. Until you learn to balance effortlessly without your arms helping, it is simply impossible to drill or stroke efficiently. Thus, your first step is to get the water to support you without help from your arms. In “head-lead” drills, because you’re unable to use your arms for support, you’ll learn to balance your body entirely through proper head position and weight distribution.

 

 

成功的四个简单秘诀

FOUR SIMPLE SECRETS TO SUCCESS

1.练习时，想象自己被一根系在头顶的绳索牵引着。保持头部与脊柱的连线保持伸直。

1. As you practice, imagine being towed by a line attached to the top of your head. Keep your head-spine line long and straight.

2.练习放松。尽量保持安静和节制，不要扰动水面。力求达到一种近乎禅宗般的宁静感。

2. Practice ease. Move as quietly and economically as you can, trying not to disturb the water. Strive for an almost Zen-like sensation of stillness.

3.用伸直、柔韧的长腿，轻柔地、安静地打水。保持双脚与身体的“尾迹”或“影子”同步。如果感觉打水速度慢，不要用力过猛；相反，试着通过改善平衡和身体姿势来减少阻力。

3. Kick silently and gently with a long, straight, supple leg. Keep your feet inside your body’s wake, or “shadow.” If you feel slow, don’t kick harder; instead, try to reduce resistance by improving your balance and alignment.

4.最重要的是，第一次练习第一课时，要选择浅水区，这样你随时都可以站起来。做头部引导练习时，尤其是如果你的打腿能力较弱，即使游25码也会很累。在你能够毫不费力地游5到10码之前，不要再游太远了。（后院和汽车旅馆的泳池通常非常适合练习第一课！）如果你感到疲倦或用力过猛，不要继续用力。相反，站起来，深呼吸几次，放松一下，然后再继续练习。

4. Most important, when practicing Lesson One for the first time, use a shallow pool section, where you can stand up at any time. When doing head-lead drills, especially if you have a weak kick, even 25 yards can be tiring. Until you can do just five or ten yards effortlessly, don’t go farther. (Backyard and motel pools are often perfect for Lesson One practice!) If you feel tired or are working too hard, don’t push on. Instead, stand up, take a few deep breaths, and relax before resuming.

练习 1：背部基本平衡

DRILL 1: BASIC BALANCE ON YOUR BACK

我们这样做的原因：这是放松身心、享受水的支撑最简单的方法。你不用担心呼吸问题，所以你可以躺在那里，感受平衡。轻松和稳定是平衡的关键感觉；在这里学习这些感觉，然后在其他姿势下保持平衡。

Why We Do It: This is the easiest way to relax and enjoy the support of the water. You don’t have to worry about breathing, so you can just lie there and experience balance. Effortlessness and stability are the key sensations of balance; learn them here then maintain in other positions.

 

 

按照这个顺序（每一步轻轻踢腿）

Follow This Sequence (Kicking Gently at Each Step)

1. 遮住头部。你的脸应该与水面平行，水会润湿你的额头顶部、下巴底部以及泳镜的两角。稍微收起下巴，保持头部与水面平行。如果其他游泳者溅到你脸上，你可以戴上鼻夹，尽量减少这种干扰。花五到十分钟调整头部位置，或者让同伴照着图示练习并提供帮助。耐心练习，直到感觉更自然，并且对水面的贴合度感到舒适。在之后的每次练习中，在做其他事情之前，都要先遮住头部。

1. Hide your head. Your face should be parallel to the surface, with water wetting the top of your forehead, the bottom of your chin, and the corners of your goggles. Tuck your chin slightly to keep your head aligned. If other swimmers splash waves in your face, you can minimize this distraction by wearing nose-clips. Spend five to ten minutes simply getting your head position right or have a partner check the illustration and help. Patiently practice until it feels more natural and you’re comfortable with the water that close. In every subsequent drill, hide your head before doing anything else.

 

 

2. 背部呈“船形”。肩膀向后、胸部向前挺起时，保持平衡会比较困难。稍微拱起肩膀，让背部呈船形。在所有平衡练习中，保持肩膀处于这个中立位置。

2. Make a “hull shape” with your back. It’s harder to balance with your shoulders back and your chest thrust forward. Round your shoulders slightly and shape your back like the hull of a boat. Keep your shoulders in this neutral position for all balance drills.

 

 

3. 压住你的“浮标”。保持平衡的方法是“趴在肺上”，也就是身体最容易浮起的部位。保持头部隐藏，躯干呈船形，上背部向后倾斜，直到臀部感觉轻盈。保持平衡后，每次踢水时，你的大腿都会露出一块“干燥的部位”。但不要让踢水溅起水花；你的膝盖和脚趾应该只是轻轻触碰水面。在接下来的练习中，以同样的方式“趴在肺上”。

3. Press your “buoy.” You achieve balance by “lying on your lungs,” which are the most buoyant part of your body. Keeping your head hidden and your torso hull-shaped, lean on your upper back until your hips feel light. When you’re balanced, you’ll show a “dry patch of thigh” on each kick. But don’t let your kick become splashy; your knees and toes should just ruffle the surface. In subsequent drills, “lie on your lungs” in the same way.

 

 

4. 就躺在那儿。平衡的真正考验是你的手臂什么都做不了。如果你需要用手臂支撑自己或划桨，那你就没有保持平衡。当你真正被水支撑时，你可以用手臂把自己塑造成鱼雷的形状。

4. Just lie there. The true test of balance is being able to do nothing with your arms. If you need to brace yourself or scull with them, you aren’t balanced. When you are really supported by the water, you can use your arms just to help shape yourself into a torpedo.

 

 

5. 练习时间到了。限制重复距离在25码或更短。一旦你开始失去轻松和放松的感觉，就休息一下，直到恢复。

5. Time to practice. Limit repeats to 25 yards or less. As soon as you begin losing your sense of ease and relaxation, rest until you regain it.

为“沉没者”提供特别帮助

Special Help for “Sinkers”

体型瘦削、肌肉发达或腿较长的运动员（尤其是同时具备上述两种或两种以上特征的运动员）通常会发现，无论怎么调整姿势，在鼻上平衡练习（练习1至3）中都无法真正感到舒适。这些练习对于教授你在第三课、第四课和第五课的“切换”练习之间使用的恢复姿势至关重要，但你将在练习4及以后的练习中学习在鼻下姿势下完成整个划水动作时所需的平衡感。

Athletes who are lean, densely muscled, or long-legged (and particularly those with two or more of these traits) commonly find that no amount of position adjusting allows them to achieve real comfort in the nose-up balance drills (Drills 1 through 3). These drills are important in teaching the recovery position you’ll use between cycles of the “switch” drills in Lessons Three, Four, and Five, but you’ll learn the sense of balance you’ll use while swimming the whole stroke in nose-down positions in Drill 4 and beyond.

我建议你在最初学习平衡练习时请朋友或游泳伙伴来帮助你，而不是费力地让“沉重”的腿漂浮起来。在完全沉浸式“伙伴系统”中，你的伙伴可以在练习1和2中从你的头部或肩部轻轻拖拽，在练习3中从你伸出的手部轻轻拖拽。当你的伙伴拖拽时，你要完全专注于放松；使用轻柔、紧凑的踢腿；从水中最小的“洞”中滑过；并记住你获得的轻松支撑感。

Rather than struggle to float those “heavy” legs, I recommend that you ask a friend or swim partner to help you as you learn balance drills initially. In the Total Immersion “buddy system,” your partner can tow gently from your head or shoulders in Drills 1 and 2, and from your extended hand in Drill 3. As your partner tows, put your focus entirely on relaxing; using a gentle, compact kick; slipping through the smallest “hole” in the water; and memorizing the sense of easy support you gain.

提供一些动力后，你的同伴可以放开你，继续在前面向后走，如果发现你开始挣扎，就准备继续牵引。同伴的“牵引”应该会让你更容易独立继续。你要专注于感受——以及踢腿——就像被牵引时一样。重复牵引和放开几次，试着保持独立的动力，每次只持续稍长一点。（附录中介绍的《自由式轻松滑行》 DVD/视频详细介绍了学习平衡和其他技能的“伙伴系统”。）

After providing some momentum, your partner can release you and continue walking backward in front, ready to resume towing if he or she sees you begin to struggle. Your partner’s “draft” should make it a bit easier for you to continue independently. You focus on feeling—and kicking—the same as when you were being towed. Repeat tow-and-release several times, trying to sustain independent momentum, for just a bit longer each time. (The “buddy system” for learning balance and other skills is illustrated in detail in the Freestyle Made Easy DVD/video described in the appendix.)

一般来说，“下沉型”在前三个练习中会比较吃力，所以我的建议是不要为了掌握它们而忍受挫折。快速地练习，并保持一定的耐心，在合理的范围内尽可能多地学习，然后再进行练习4——滑行。在这一步，下沉型开始理解平衡的感觉。你也可以使用脚蹼进行单独练习，详情请见本课末尾的方框。

In general, “sinkers” struggle more with the first three drills, so my advice is not to endure frustration while trying endlessly to master them. Do them expeditiously and with a degree of patience to learn as much as a reasonable effort with allow, then move on to Drill 4, Skating. This is the step where sinkers begin to understand how balance should feel. You can also use fins for solo practice, as detailed in the box at the end of this lesson.

专注于那种静谧的感觉，当你躺在那里，轻轻地踢腿，让水来做功时，你会感到无比平静。想象一下，你如此稳定，以至于可以把香槟酒杯放在额头上。这种感觉正是平衡的标志！在进行其他平衡练习时，也要保持这种感觉。

Focus mainly on the sense of stillness produced when you can just lie there, kicking gently, and let the water do the work. Imagine being so stable that you could carry a champagne glass on your forehead. This feeling is a hallmark of balance! Keep it as you progress to other balance drills.

练习2：找到你的“最佳点”

DRILL 2: FIND YOUR “SWEET SPOT”

我们为什么这样做：你主要会侧身游泳，并且每个练习都是侧身开始和结束的，但“侧平衡”几乎从来不会完全侧身。“最佳平衡点”是你找到真正平衡点的地方，它会受你的体型影响。如果你体型偏瘦或肌肉发达，侧平衡很可能几乎是仰卧的。找到你的最佳平衡点至关重要，因为你的每个练习都是从这里开始和结束的。当你掌握了“最佳平衡点”后，你的练习就会轻松流畅；如果你不花时间去掌握它，你反而会很吃力。

Why We Do It: You’ll swim mainly on your side and start and finish every drill on your side, but “side balance” is almost never exactly on the side. The Sweet Spot is where you’ll find true equilibrium and balance and is influenced by your body type. If you’re lean or densely muscled, side balance will probably be almost on your back. Finding your Sweet Spot is critical because you’ll start and finish every drill here. When you master Sweet Spot, you’ll drill with ease and fluency; if you don’t take time to master it, you’ll struggle instead.

 

 

遵循此顺序

Follow This Sequence

1. 像练习1一样开始，手掌放于身体两侧，轻轻踢腿。保持仰卧，直到你检查头部位置，感觉轻松保持平衡。

1. Start as in Drill 1, palms at your side and kicking gently. Remain on your back until you check your head position and feel effortlessly balanced.

 

 

2. 头部不动，转动身体，使一只手的指关节刚好露出水面即可。目标是找到一个手臂从肩膀到指关节都干燥的姿势，并且感觉和仰卧时一样舒服。如果感觉不适，请恢复仰卧姿势，并减少旋转幅度，再试一次。

2. Without moving your head, roll just enough for the knuckles of one hand to barely clear the water. Your goal is to find a position where one arm is dry from shoulder to knuckles and you’re just as comfortable as you were on your back. If you feel any discomfort, return to your back and try again with less rotation.

 

 

3. 检查您的头部是否仍处于练习 1 中的位置，水位位于护目镜的角部。

3. Check that your head is still positioned as in Drill 1, with the water at the corners of your goggles.

 

 

4. 注意观察身体是否出现不适：抬头、伸长脖子、弓背、用小臂支撑。如果感到任何紧张，请恢复仰卧姿势，并减少旋转幅度，重新开始。

4. Watch for signs of discomfort: lifting the head, craning the neck, arching the back, helping with the lower arm. If you feel any tension, return to your back and start over with less rotation.

 

 

5. 一旦你在 Sweet Spot 中感到自在，就集中精力保持身高并从水中的一个小洞中滑过，然后让静止、安静和轻松的感觉变得自然。

5. Once you feel at home in Sweet Spot, focus on staying tall and slipping through a small hole in the water, then on making stillness, quiet, and effortlessness feel natural.

 

 

6. 换另一侧重复。你可能会觉得一侧比另一侧更舒服。我把这种情况称为“巧克力”（平衡性更好）和“香草”侧。香草侧的平衡改善通常会带来更大的收益。一侧练习一个长度或一分钟，另一侧练习相同的距离或时间。

6. Repeat on your other side. You may feel more comfortable on one side than the other. I call this having a “chocolate” (better balance) and “vanilla” side. Balance improvements on your vanilla side will usually bring greater dividends. Alternate one length or minute on one side with a similar distance or time on the other side.

 

 

7. 当你开始感觉两侧都舒服时，开始练习主动平衡。在一侧轻松打水，保持三次瑜伽呼吸，然后轻轻翻滚，露出另一侧手臂，保持三次呼吸。主动平衡的两个关键技巧是：(1) 翻滚时保持平衡；(2) 轻松转移重心，开始身体翻滚。翻滚时不要用手臂，不要用力打水，也不要搅动水面。保持头部稳定，左右翻滚时，泳镜角处有水，就像额头上顶着一个香槟杯一样。

7. When you begin to feel comfortable on each side, begin practicing Active Balance. Kick easily on one side for three yoga breaths, then roll gently to show the other arm for three breaths. The two key skills in Active Balance are: (1) maintain constant equilibrium as you roll, and (2) use effortless weight shifts to initiate body roll. Roll without using your arms, without kicking harder, and without disturbing the water. Keep your head in a steady position, with water at the corners of your goggles as you roll from side to side, as if carrying a champagne glass on your forehead.

你最重要的任务是学习正确的方法——耐心而专注地——练习所有技能。给自己无限的时间，让自己轻松自如。你没有计划提前进入第二课。如果你在第一课中培养了这些态度和习惯，你的技能在接下来的每个阶段都会更加强大、更加扎实：

Your most important task here is to learn the right way—patiently and mindfully—to practice all skill drills. Give yourself unlimited time to acquire effortless ease. You are not on a schedule to advance to Lesson Two. If you cultivate these attitudes and habits in Lesson One, your skills will be stronger and sounder at each subsequent stage:

踢腿、脚蹼、钻水和游泳：完整的故事

Kicking, Fins, Drilling, and Swimming: The Whole Story

为什么我在踢腿和练习时会向后退？脚踝僵硬是最常见的原因，“成年后发病”的游泳者是典型案例。随着年龄的增长，我们都会失去灵活性（除非你进行专门的拉伸或瑜伽训练），如果你不是从小就开始游泳，那么你可能会在20到40年的时间里逐渐失去脚踝的灵活性。多年的跑步通常会加速脚踝的僵硬。如果你从小就开始游泳并坚持下去，通常足以保持脚踝的灵活性。

Why do I go backward when kicking and drilling? Inflexible ankles are the most common cause and the “adult-onset” swimmer is the classic case. We all lose flexibility as we age (unless you follow a dedicated stretching or yoga program), and if you didn’t start swimming young you may spend twenty to forty years gradually losing ankle flexibility. Years of running usually accelerates the stiffening. If you started swimming young and continued, that’s usually sufficient to maintain ankle flexibility.

第二个原因很简单，就是缺乏协调性。正确的蝶泳打腿动作是违反直觉的。你其他的打腿经验（比如踢足球、轮胎、你弟弟）教会你以大约90度的膝关节屈曲度来打腿。但有效的蝶泳打腿只用到大约30度；打腿主要依靠髋屈肌和股四头肌。孩子们学得比较自然；而成年后才开始学习游泳的人往往需要有意识地摒弃其他的打腿习惯，才能学会正确的方法。

The second cause is simple lack of coordination. The correct flutter-kicking action is counterintuitive. Your other kicking experiences (soccer balls, tires, your kid brother) teach you to kick with about 90 degrees of knee flexion. But an efficient flutter kick uses only about 30 degrees; the kick happens mostly from the hip flexor and quadriceps. Kids learn it fairly spontaneously; the adult-onset swimmer often has to consciously unlearn the other kicking habits in order to learn the right way.

我该如何解决这个问题？以下四种方法已被证明最有效：

How do I fix it? Four ways have proven to work best:

垂直打腿。这对柔韧性帮助不大，但对学习协调性很有效。如图所示，双臂交叉抱在胸前，嘴巴略高于水面，垂直漂浮。如果感觉自己在下沉，可以在腋下夹一个浮标，或者把一块浮板抱在胸前。打腿时，注意保持从臀部到脚趾的直线。你的腿要修长而灵活，不要僵硬。利用大腿上部的肌肉，像钟摆一样摆动整条腿。（对于真正的初学者来说，一个好的练习是简单地坐在泳池边，双腿悬在水中，试着用几乎伸直的腿来回拨动水流。试着用踝关节屈伸来推动水流前后移动。试着用一只脚“搅动”水，以更好地理解如何用脚感受水流。）练习垂直打腿几次，每次十五秒或更长时间，休息相同的时间。然后用同样的感觉在下面的侧身位置踢腿。

VERTICAL KICKING. This won’t do much for flexibility but it is effective for learning coordination. Float vertically with arms folded across your chest, mouth just above the water, as shown in the illustration. If you feel yourself sinking, tuck a pull buoy under each armpit, or hug a kickboard to your chest. Focus on keeping a long line from hip to toes as you kick. Your leg should be long and supple, never rigid. Using the muscles at the top of your thigh, move your whole leg like a pendulum. (A good exercise for the true beginner is simply to sit on the edge of the pool with your legs dangling in the water and try to move the water solidly back and forth with an almost-straight leg. Try to use ankle flexion and extension to move the water forward and back. Try “stirring” the water with one foot to develop a bit more awareness of how to feel the water with your feet.) Practice vertical kicking for several periods of fifteen or more seconds, resting for a similar amount of time. Then kick with the same feeling in the side position below.

拖曳。第113页描述的TI“伙伴系统”的拖曳-释放练习也有助于纠正低效的习惯。对非推进性打腿最无效（但最本能）的反应是更用力地打腿。被伙伴拖曳时，更容易专注于轻柔打腿；保持从臀部到脚趾的长而柔韧的线条；并将双脚保持在躯干的“阴影”内。释放后，保持被拖曳时的打腿姿势。拖曳和垂直打腿在Freestyle Made Easy DVD/视频中有详细说明。

TOWING. The TI “buddy system” of tow-and-release described on page 113 can also be helpful in correcting inefficient habits. The least effective (but most instinctive) response to a nonpropulsive kick is to kick harder. While being towed by a partner, it’s much easier to focus on kicking gently; maintaining a long, supple line from hip to toes; and keeping your feet inside your torso’s “shadow.” After release, keep your kick as it was while being towed. Towing and Vertical Kicking are illustrated in the Freestyle Made Easy DVD/video.

侧踢。这可以帮助你提高协调性和灵活性，也是练习TI训练的另一个好处。我们序列中的每个练习都以甜蜜点开始和结束。任何时候你踢腿侧身时，你更有可能使用30度屈曲踢腿。像玩浮板一样俯卧踢腿，你更有可能做出自行车式踢腿，因为重力会促使你这样做。侧身时，由于你的膝盖不会顺着重力方向弯曲，所以你不太可能做出“自行车式”踢腿。

SIDE KICKING. This can help you with both coordination and flexibility and is one more benefit to practicing TI drills. Each drill in our sequence starts and finishes in Sweet Spot. Any time you’re kicking on your side, you’re a lot more likely to use the 30-degree flexion kick. Kicking on your stomach—as with a kickboard—makes it far more likely that you’ll do the bicycling kick, because gravity encourages it. On your side, because your knees don’t flex in the direction gravity is working, you’re far less likely to “bicycle.”

拉伸。这对协调性没有任何帮助。它可能会改善适度地调整脚踝的活动范围。这样不会让你突然变成一个快速、轻松的踢球者。

STRETCHING. This won’t do anything for coordination. It may improve the range of motion in your ankles moderately. It won’t suddenly turn you into a fast, easy kicker.

脚蹼有帮助吗？脚蹼的主要好处是叶片可以轻松弯曲，弥补脚踝的不足。为了使打腿有推进力，一些东西可以弯曲，以便移动水，类似于螺旋桨的倾斜叶片。当你的脚踝拒绝时，你的膝盖自然会代替你。但这只会使问题变得更糟。首先，因为直角膝盖会导致你的小腿从尾流中伸出——将腿变成另一个阻力源。这就是你不能向前移动的原因。其次，它会触发跑步者打腿时的抓地动作。这会导致你向后退。如果你的脚上戴上脚蹼——并且你的身体侧卧——很快你就能提高灵活性和协调性。

Will fins help? The primary benefit of fins is that the blade will flex easily, compensating for the ankle that won’t. In order for the kick to be propulsive, something has to flex, in order to move the water, similar to the pitched blades of a propellor. When your ankle refuses, it’s only natural for your knee to substitute. That only makes the problem worse. First, because a right-angle knee causes your lower leg to protrude from your slipstream— turning the leg into another source of drag. That’s why you don’t move forward. Second, it triggers the pawing action of a runner’s kick. That causes you to go backward. With fins on your feet—and your body on its side—pretty soon you’re helping both flexibility and coordination.

我应该在训练中使用脚蹼吗？每个TI训练中的“甜蜜点”暂停有助于提高你的放松度和协调性。这很好。但是，如果你的打腿姿势不正确，每次回到“甜蜜点”时，你的身体可能会停止移动。这很糟糕。如果你的身体在每个循环后都停下来，你最终会在泳池里蹒跚而行，耗费精力去克服惯性，而不是有效地保持动量。所以，合理的打腿至关重要。而且，由于训练的重点是教你轻松和经济地进行，如果使用脚蹼能让你练习轻松，那真的会是一个巨大的好处。

Should I use fins in drills? The Sweet Spot pause in every TI drill helps your ease and coordination. Good. But if you have a poor kick, each time you return to Sweet Spot, your body may stop moving. Bad. If your body comes to halt after each cycle, you end up lurching down the pool, spending energy trying to overcome inertia rather than efficiently conserving momentum. So a reasonable kick is essential to efficient drill practice.
