And because the main point of drills is to teach you ease and economy, it really is an enormous benefit if using fins allows you to practice ease as you drill.

但我建议你尝试不穿脚蹼完成第一课。这有助于确保你主要使用脚蹼来保持动力，而不是为了掩盖你的平衡问题。如果你在练习时确实使用脚蹼，那就让它们发挥作用。保持双腿伸直、灵活、放松。打腿动作尽量轻柔，这样脚蹼就不会影响你正在学习的核心发力动作。

But I recommend that you try to complete Lesson One without fins. That helps to ensure that you’re using the fins mainly to help conserve momentum, not to mask your balance problem. And if you do use fins while practicing drills, let them do the work. Keep your legs long and supple and relaxed. Kick as gently as possible, so the fins don’t overwhelm the core-generated movement you’re trying to learn.

游泳时应该使用脚蹼吗？除非你的目标是快速游短距离，否则我建议你使用非明显打腿——也就是你几乎意识不到的打腿。如果你的训练教你平衡，那么让你的腿跟随你的核心身体应该更容易。我不鼓励游泳者在游泳时经常使用脚蹼。这容易导致你打腿过度，很容易让你失去平衡感、流畅性以及全身协调的游泳感觉。所以……如果脚蹼在训练中能极大地提升你的轻松度，那就一定要使用。但不要犹豫尝试一些不带脚蹼的训练。开始游泳时，一定要脱掉脚蹼。

Should I use fins while swimming? Unless your goal is to swim short distances fast, I advocate a non-overt kick—i.e., one you’re hardly aware of. If your drills teach you balance, it should be much easier to just let your legs follow your core body. I don’t encourage swimmers to use fins very often while swimming. It tends to encourage you to overkick, and you can easily lose your feel for balance, fluency, and for swimming with a seamless whole-body harmony. So … do use fins if they contribute dramatically to your ease while drilling. But don’t be reluctant to try some drilling without them. And take the fins off when you start swimming.

• 练习每个训练时无需考虑时间限制或重复次数。

• Practice each drill with no set time limit or number of repetitions in mind.

• 坚持下去，直到毫不费力。

• Stay with it until it becomes effortless.

• 然后继续一段时间，直到你感到“无聊”为止（你不需要花费脑力就能做到）。

• Then continue a bit longer until you are “bored” (you can do it without mental effort).

• 只有这样，您才可以进行下一个训练或技能。

• Only then should you progress to the next drill or skill.

在任何阶段都要承诺避免“练习挣扎”。每当你感觉自己失去控制时，就停下来休息，重新回到之前的训练或技能，或者两者兼而有之。如果不这样做，你最终只会把挣扎铭刻在肌肉记忆中，每当你感到有点累的时候，你的身体就会自然而然地回到低效的模式。

Make a commitment to avoid “practicing struggle” at any stage. Any time you feel yourself losing control, stop and rest, regroup at the prior drill or skill, or do both. If you don’t, you’ll simply end up imprinting struggle in your muscle memory and your body will naturally revert to inefficient patterns whenever you get a bit tired.

第一课的完整练习系列包括仰卧25码、右侧25码、左侧25码以及主动平衡25码。每完成25码后休息3到5次瑜伽呼吸。随着你的最佳平衡点（Sweet Spot）的提高，你可以减少练习1的次数，专注于侧向平衡和主动平衡的练习。随着你逐渐掌握其他技巧，训练时，在进行更高级的训练之前，花五到十分钟的时间调整你的 Sweet Spot 总是有益的。

A comprehensive series for Lesson One practice is 25 yards on your back, 25 on your right side, 25 on your left side, and 25 of Active Balance. Rest for three to five yoga breaths after each 25. As your Sweet Spot balance improves, you can do Drill 1 less often, focusing your practice on side balance and active balance. As you progress to other drills, a five- to ten-minute tune-in with your Sweet Spot before tackling more advanced drills will always be beneficial.

第二课：变得失重和滑溜

Lesson Two: Becoming Weightless and Slippery

在第一课中，我们运用头部引导练习，轻松保持水平，并解放了手臂，不再依赖手臂的平衡。现在，我们可以伸展“无重力手臂”，让你的“船”更滑。正如我在第三章中解释的那样，当你的身体线条变长时，阻力会减小，让你无需费力就能游得更快。本课将帮助你打造一艘更长、更滑的平衡船。

After using head-lead drills in Lesson One to become effortlessly horizontal—and to free your arms from helping with balance—we can now extend a “weightless arm” to make your “vessel” more slippery. As I explained in chapter 3, when your body line becomes longer, drag is reduced, allowing you to swim faster without working harder. This lesson will give you a balanced vessel that is longer and more slippery.

成功的三个简单秘诀

THREE SIMPLE SECRETS TO SUCCESS

1.当你从伸出的手到脚趾延伸身体线条时，重要的是要尽可能保持这条线长、直、流畅，但不要过度拉伸到绷紧的程度。从身体后部开始拉伸，而不是从前部开始，以保持身体的平衡。

1. As you extend your body line from your outstretched hand to your toes, it’s important to keep that line as long, straight, and sleek as possible, but don’t overstretch to the point of tension. Lengthen from the back of your body, not from the front, to stay aligned.

2.任何时候您感到不舒服或不平衡 - 或者感到需要用手臂支撑（在第一次进行第二课时并不少见） - 请将伸出的手臂放回身体一侧，并在头部主导的最佳位置重新保持平衡。

2. Any time you feel uncomfortable or unbalanced—or feel the need to use your arm for support (not uncommon when doing Lesson Two for the first time)—return your extended arm to your side and rebalance in Head-Lead Sweet Spot.

3.正如我们鼓励学生不穿脚蹼掌握第一课一样，我们也鼓励他们在第二课中随意使用脚蹼来提升学习的轻松度。如果你已经保持平衡，但仍然需要用力打腿，脚蹼可以帮助你减轻疲劳，节省体力，以便更好地练习。练就更强的打腿能力并不重要，重要的是找到更省力的动作方式。

3. Just as we encourage students to master Lesson One without fins, we also encourage them to feel free to use fins to increase their ease in Lesson Two. If you are balanced but still have to kick too hard, fins can help reduce fatigue and save energy for refinement. Developing a stronger kick is unimportant; a more economical movement style is all-important.

练习 3：手动引导甜蜜点——延长你的“血管”

DRILL 3: HAND-LEAD SWEET SPOT—LENGTHEN YOUR “VESSEL”

我们这样做的原因：体验手臂伸展时的平衡感，并记住你最滑的身体姿势。手部引导最佳位置也是你每次练习的开始和结束位置。最后，它是练习蝶泳踢腿的两个最佳位置之一。（另一个是滑冰姿势——练习4。）

Why We Do It: To experience how balance feels with an arm extended and to imprint your most slippery body position. Hand-Lead Sweet Spot is also the position in which you’ll start and finish every drill. Finally, it’s one of the two best positions for practicing flutter kick. (Skating Position—Drill 4—is the other.)

 

 

遵循此顺序

Follow This Sequence

1. 像练习1一样开始，保持平衡，仰卧，轻轻地踢水。水是否淹没了你的泳镜角？你是否感觉轻松支撑？（花点时间感受一下。）然后，稍微翻滚，露出一只手臂。你仍然感觉舒服吗？你的头部和脊柱之间的连线是否清晰、长长？你上面的那只手臂从肩膀到指关节是否干燥？如果不是，请恢复仰卧姿势，重新开始。如果是，那么……

1. Start as in Drill 1, balanced on your back, kicking gently. Is the water at the corners of your goggles? Do you feel effortlessly supported? (Take all the time you need to feel this.) Then roll just enough to show one arm. Do you still feel comfortable? Do you have a long, clean head-spine line? Is your top arm dry from shoulder to knuckles? If not, return to your back and start over. If yes, then …

 

 

2. 将小臂“潜入”水中，完全伸展。你的手应该在水面以下一两英寸处。你的手掌可以向上、向下或向侧面。你的手臂应该感觉就像向前漂浮一样。

2. “Sneak” your lower arm to full extension. Your hand should be an inch or two below the surface. Your palm can be up, down, or sideways. Your arm should feel as if it’s just floating forward.

 

 

3. 接下来，让自己像针一样。当你的手臂伸展且没有重量时，检查后脑勺和肩膀之间的间隙。如果可能的话，缩小间隙，但要避免拉伤或不适。最后，确保你的头部与脊柱对齐，水位于两个泳镜的角部，并且你的上臂可以轻松地侧放，并且从肩膀到指关节的皮肤保持干燥。

3. Next, make yourself needlelike. Once your arm is extended and weightless, check the gap between the back of your head and your shoulder. Narrow the gap if possible, but avoid strain or discomfort. Finally, make sure your head is aligned with your spine, that water is at the corners of both goggles, and that your top arm lies easily on your side with a dry strip of skin from shoulder to knuckles.

 

 

4. 不断练习，直到你能在这个姿势下无限次地左右滑动。花点时间，让你“香草”的一侧和“巧克力”的一侧感觉一样好；耐心等待，以后会有巨大的回报。

4. Practice until you could glide blissfully in this position on either side indefinitely. Take the time to make your “vanilla” side feel as good as your “chocolate” side; patience here will pay big dividends later.

练习方法：当你感到两侧肌肉放松时，开始练习一个长度的重复动作（中间休息三次或以上瑜伽呼吸），持续七到十分钟，左右两侧交替练习。每个长度的练习点可以从以下几个方面中选择：

How To Practice: Once you feel “bliss” on either side, practice 1-length repeats (resting for three or more yoga breaths between) for seven to ten minutes, alternating sides. Choose one of these focal points for each length:

 

 

1. 从伸展的指尖到脚趾，画一条修长、清晰的线条。伸展手臂时，注意从身体后侧拉长，而不是前侧。

1. Create a long, clean line from your extended fingertips to your toes. As you extend your arm, focus on lengthening from the back of your body, not the front.

 

 

2. 尽量从水中最小的洞里滑过去。确保你的头部和身体滑过的洞是同一个。

2. Slip through the smallest possible hole in the water. Make sure your head slips through the same “hole” that your body is traveling through.

 

 

3. 滑行时安静且轻松。轻轻打水，保持双腿伸直、柔韧，并保持在身体的“阴影”范围内。（如果无法做到这一点，可以使用脚蹼。）

3. Glide silently and effortlessly. Kick gently, keeping your legs long, supple, and within the “shadow” of your body. (Use fins if this is impossible.)

 

 

4. 如果您在任何时候失去平衡或感到不舒服，请将手臂放回身体一侧并重新开始。

4. If at any time you lose balance or comfort, put your arm back to your side and start over.

练习 4：滑冰姿势的平衡

DRILL 4: BALANCE IN THE SKATING POSITION

我们为什么这样做：这是你第一次体验平衡感，就像你刚开始游泳时那样。这也是所有后续换位练习的第一个动作。最后，但同样重要的是，这是你练习正确呼吸技巧的第一个练习，养成良好的习惯，让你能够一直保持到整个划水过程。在这里，你将学习通过将身体滚动到空气中来呼吸——而不是抬起或转动头部。滚动身体换气的动作会培养一个关键的习惯（在练习中），即在“甜蜜点”完成每个滚动动作。

Why We Do It: This is your first opportunity to experience balance as it should feel when you begin swimming. This is also the first movement in all the Switch drills that follow. Last, but not least, this is the first drill in which you practice the proper technique for breathing, developing good habits now that you can maintain right through to whole-stroke. Here you’ll learn to breathe by rolling your body to where the air is—rather than lifting or turning your head. The act of rolling your body to breathe imprints the critical habit (when drilling) of finishing every rolling movement in Sweet Spot.

 

 

遵循此顺序

Follow This Sequence

1. 像练习3一样开始，轻轻地踢腿。保持平衡，仰卧并遮住头部，然后轻轻翻滚露出一只手臂，最后伸展另一只手臂。在进行下一个动作之前，让每个姿势都感觉舒适。

1. Start as in Drill 3, kicking gently. Balance on your back and hide your head, then roll gently to show one arm, and finally extend the other arm. Allow each position to feel great before you move to the next.

 

 

2. 把手臂“悄悄”抬起来后，停下来检查：水还在泳镜两角吗？你感觉自己像一根长长的、平衡的针，正从一个小孔里滑出来吗？然后……

2. After “sneaking” your arm up, pause to check: Is the water still at the corners of both goggles? Do you feel like a long, balanced needle slipping through a small hole? Then . . .

 

 

3. 转动头部，直视底部，同时身体向侧面滚动。向下看后，暂停并检查：你的视线是否直视下方？你的侧身是否保持平衡，肩膀是否朝上？你伸出的手是否在头部下方？（放得比你认为的要深！）你是否感觉平衡良好——甚至有一种下坡滑行的感觉？

3. Swivel your head and look directly at the bottom, rolling to your side as you do. After you look down, pause and check: Are you looking directly down? Are you balanced on your side with your shoulder pointing directly up? Is your extended hand below your head? (Put it deeper than you think you should!) Do you feel great balance—even a downhill gliding sensation?

 

 

4. 保持一段舒适的间歇，然后一路滚回起始位置。教学中，我们始终指导学生滚过最佳位置，以便舒适地呼吸。如果在滚起呼吸后感到不平衡或不舒服，则说明滚得还不够远。

4. Stay for a comfortable interval, then roll all the way back to where you started. When teaching, we always instruct our students to roll past their Sweet Spot in order to breathe comfortably. If you feel unbalanced or uncomfortable after you roll up to breathe, you haven’t rolled far enough.

 

 

5. 在再次向下滚动之前，在 Sweet Spot 重新调整至少三次瑜伽呼吸；避免感到呼吸困难或匆忙。

5. Regroup in Sweet Spot for at least three yoga breaths before rolling nose-down again; avoid feeling breathless or rushed.

第二课练习计划

Lesson Two Practice Plan

让我们回顾一下你目前学到的内容：平衡和头脊对齐。如何让自己更滑。刚开始游泳时应该如何保持平衡。如何在将针形体旋转到空气流动的位置时进行呼吸。这些见解对于让你成为更像鱼的游泳者都具有非凡的价值，所以你应该充分利用第二课的练习来改进你的划水动作，即使你的划水动作已经相当高效。现在花点时间耐心地打磨所有细节。

Let’s review what you’ve learned so far: Balance and head-spine alignment. How to make yourself more slippery. How balance should feel when you begin swimming. How to breathe while rolling your needle shape to where the air is. These insights will all be of extraordinary value in making you a more Fishlike swimmer, so you should make extensive use of Lesson Two drills in refining your stroke, even after it has become quite efficient. Take time now to patiently polish all the fine points.

与第一课一样，有一个简单的 100 码序列用于练习第二课技能：以机头朝上姿势滑行50码（右侧25码，左侧25码），再以滑行姿势滑行50码（右侧25码，左侧25码）。每滑行一段距离后休息至少三次“瑜伽”呼吸，并练习七到十分钟。为每段距离选择一个焦点。机头朝上姿势，请从练习三中提到的姿势中选择。滑行姿势，请从以下姿势中选择：

As with Lesson One, there’s a simple 100-yard sequence for practicing Lesson Two skills: 50 yards in the nose-up position (25 on your right side, 25 on your left) plus 50 yards in the Skating Position (25 right, 25 left). Rest for three or more “yoga” breaths after each length and practice for seven to ten minutes. Choose a focal point for each length. For the nose-up position, choose from among those mentioned for Drill 3. For the Skating Position, choose from among the following:

 

 

1. 头部位置。始终与脊柱对齐。抬头时，水位应位于泳镜角。低头时，鼻子正对泳镜底部，头部位置应确保水流能轻松流过背部。从一个位置翻滚到另一个位置时，头部紧贴伸展的手臂。

1. Head Position. Aligned with your spine at all times. Water at the corners of your goggles while looking up. Nose pointed directly at the bottom while looking down with your head positioned so water can easily flow over the back. Head tucked against the extended arm as you roll from one position to the other.

 

 

2. 保持平衡。尤其是在船头向下时，要专注于感觉完全被水支撑，就像在滑下山坡一样。要做到这一点，请确保你的头部隐藏在水中，手放在头下，并且身体靠在肺部。

2. Balance. Particularly when nose-down, focus on feeling completely supported by the water, almost as if you’re sliding downhill. To get this, make sure your head is hidden, that your hand is below your head, and that you lean on your lungs.

 

 

3.真正平衡。当你能毫不费力地——几乎是懒洋洋地——滑行，看着池底的瓷砖在你身下滑过，你就知道自己已经达到了这种状态。

3. Really balanced. You’ll know you’ve reached this state when you can glide effortlessly—almost lazily—watching pool tiles slide by underneath you.

 

 

4. 滑溜。我们称之为滑冰姿势，因为这种感觉就像用身体的延伸侧——从指尖到脚趾——就像用冰刀一样。能够侧身保持平衡——肩膀直立——是你在水中能达到的最滑的姿势。通过滑动你的身体在水中通过尽可能小的空间，以尽量减少身体表面的形状阻力。

4. Slippery. We call this the Skating Position because the sensation should be of using the extended side of your body—from fingertips to toes—as if it were a skate blade. Being able to balance right on your side—shoulder pointed straight up—is the most slippery position you can achieve in the water. Enhance this by slipping your body through the smallest possible space in the water, to minimize form drag on body surfaces.

 

 

5. 呼吸。在旋转并向下滚动到滑行位置时，保持针形——特别是当你旋转回最佳位置呼吸时，如果滚得太远。

5. Breathing. Maintain your needle shape as you swivel and roll nose-down to the Skating Position—and particularly as you roll “too far” when you swivel back to Sweet Spot to breathe.

第三课：

从你的动力链中轻松获取力量

Lesson Three:

Tapping Effortless Power From Your Kinetic Chain

前两课教你如何保持平衡和滑行的身体姿势。在第三课中，你将学习如何利用平衡且滑行的核心身体旋转来轻松产生推进力。第三课还将介绍我们三个“Switch”练习序列中的第一个。这将是你迄今为止练习过的最有活力、最有力的动作。

The first two lessons have taught you balance and slippery body positions. In Lesson Three, you’ll learn to use rotation of your balanced and slippery core body to generate effortless power for propulsion. Lesson Three also introduces you to the first of our three Switch drill sequences. These will be the most dynamic and powerful movements you have yet practiced.

 

 

练习 5：内溜冰

DRILL 5: UNDERSKATE

我们为什么这样做：你在滑冰姿势中学习了最有价值的平衡技巧。这个姿势将成为其他平衡练习的基础，为你的平衡练习带来不同的活力。这个练习也是练习6：UnderSwitch的预演。最后，它强化了游泳时保持侧身以及通过将平衡、对齐、滑溜的身体翻滚到空中来呼吸的关键技巧。

Why We Do It: You learned the most valuable form of balance in the Skating Position. That position becomes the basis for other ways of practicing balance that bring a different dynamic to your balance practice. This drill is also a rehearsal for Drill 6: UnderSwitch. Finally, it reinforces the key skills of staying on your side as you swim and of breathing by rolling a balanced, aligned, slippery body to the air.

 

 

遵循此顺序

Follow This Sequence

1. 像练习 4 一样开始，耐心地完成之前练习的所有四个位置或动作，同时轻轻地、无声地踢腿：保持背部平衡；然后稍微旋转到最佳位置，露出一只手臂，然后将另一只手臂完全伸展；最后到达滑冰姿势。

1. Begin as in Drill 4, moving patiently through all four positions or movements practiced previously, kicking silently and gently as you do: Balance on your back; then rotate slightly to Sweet Spot, showing an arm, then sneak your other arm to full extension; and finally arrive in the Skating Position.

 

 

2. 向下看后，停下来检查：你的头部是否隐藏且保持水平？伸出的手是否在头下方？你是否感觉平衡良好——甚至有种下坡滑行的感觉？

2. After you look down, pause and check: Are you looking down with your head hidden and aligned? Is your extended hand below your head? Do you feel great balance—even a downhill gliding sensation?

 

 

3. 如果是，就将拖在后面的手悄悄地伸入水下（擦过腹部，越过下巴），直到看到手正对着鼻子。确认你仍然侧卧，肩膀并拢，然后将手滑回身体一侧。最后，将针形的按摩棒滑过你的“甜蜜点”。

3. If so, then sneak the trailing hand forward under water (wipe it across your belly and past your jaw) until you see the hand right under your nose. Check that you’re still on your side with your shoulders stacked, then slide the hand back to your side. Finish by rolling your needle shape past your Sweet Spot.

 

 

4. 至少进行三次瑜伽呼吸，然后重复以上步骤。每25码大概可以完成三个循环。下次练习时换边。

4. Take at least three yoga breaths, then repeat the sequence. You’ll probably fit in three cycles in each 25 yards. Switch sides on the next length.

底板位置还说明了所有底板开关练习的开关时机。

THE UNDERSKATE POSITION ALSO ILLUSTRATES SWITCH-TIMING FOR ALL UNDERSWITCH DRILLS.

练习方法：重点与练习4相同，但更加强调在将手举至脸部时保持身体侧卧，并同时努力从水中最小的空隙中滑过。单独练习UnderSkate，左右两侧交替练习。或者将其与第二课的一系列练习结合起来：练习2、3、4和5，每次50码（右手25码，左手25码）。有些运动员只需练习不到10分钟就能掌握这个练习。如果你觉得已经掌握了，那就继续学习。如果没有，请投入尽可能多的时间，因为在UnderSkate中学习的技能是后续所有练习的关键。

How to Practice: Your key focal points are the same as for Drill 4, but with added emphasis on remaining on your side as you bring your hand to your face and on slipping through the smallest hole in the water as you do it. Practice UnderSkate by itself, alternating sides. Or practice it in a series with Lesson Two drills: 50 yards each (25 right, 25 left) of Drills 2, 3, 4, and 5. Some athletes can master this drill after no more than ten minutes of practice. If you feel you’ve got it, move on. If not, spend as much time as you need because the skills learned in Under-Skate are key to every drill that follows.

练习 6：开关下方

DRILL 6: UNDERSWITCH

我们为什么这样做：这是第一个利用动力链力量的练习，教你如何将划臂动作与核心身体旋转联系起来，从而轻松获得推进力。它还能通过视觉提示何时切换，简化学习前象限划臂时机的过程，从而保持身体线条的长长。

Why We Do It: This is the first drill to tap the power of the kinetic chain by teaching you how to link an armstroke to core-body rotation for effortless propulsion. It also simplifies the learning process for learning the front-quadrant stroke timing that keeps your body line long, by giving you a visual cue for when to make the switch.

 

 

遵循此顺序

Follow This Sequence

1. 当 UnderSkate 的动作看起来自然（几乎“不费脑筋”）后，开始进行完整的练习。像练习 5 一样开始，但当你看到你的手在鼻子下方时，继续向前移动，直到完全伸展，同时滚动（切换）经过另一侧的 Sweet Spot。

1. After the movements of UnderSkate seem natural (almost a “nobrainer”), move to the full drill. Start as in Drill 5, but when you see your hand under your nose, keep moving it forward to full extension as you roll (switch) past Sweet Spot on the other side.

 

 

2. 至少进行三次瑜伽呼吸（放松，调整呼吸，找准方向），同时检查平衡，确保再次回到最佳位置。然后，旋转至滑冰姿势（头部向下，双肩并拢）……暂停……然后换方向重复。

2. Take at least three yoga breaths (relax, normalize your breathing, and get your bearings) as you check your balance and make sure that you are in Sweet Spot again. Then, swivel to the Skating Position (nose down and shoulders stacked) … pause … and repeat in the other direction.

 

 

3. 基本动作简单，但改进的空间很大。请逐一练习以下重点：

3. The basic movements are simple, but the opportunities for refinement are many. Practice these focal points, one at a time:

 

 

• 要有耐心。直到你看到你的手在鼻子下面时才切换。

• Be patient. Don’t switch until you see your hand under your nose.

• 当你滚过时，用伸出的手“抓住你在水中的位置”。

• Switch by using the extended hand to “hold on to your place in the water,” as you roll past it.

• 通过滚过您的甜蜜点来完成切换。

• Finish the switch by rolling past your Sweet Spot.

• 另一种强化这种呼吸的方法是，假设你打算用肚脐呼吸。当你看到你的手后，把肚脐抬到空中；你的头也会跟着一起动。

• Another way to reinforce this is to switch as if you were planning to breathe with your belly button. After you see your hand, take your belly button to the air; your head just goes along for the ride.

• 切换时保持连接：当您看到手时，将手臂、头部和躯干作为一个整体移动。

• Stay connected as you switch: When you see your hand, move arm, head, and torso as a unit.

• 保持滑溜：通过水中尽可能最小的孔洞切换。

• Stay slippery: Switch through the smallest possible hole in the water.

• 专注于尽可能安静地进行练习。这将帮助你更流畅、更经济地完成任何练习。

• Focus on doing the drill as quietly as possible. This will help you do any drill more fluently and economically.

• 最后一步：看到手的瞬间暂停踢腿，然后换手。回到最佳位置后，继续轻柔踢腿。

• Final step: Pause your kick at the moment you see your hand and switch. Resume gentle kicking once you’re back in Sweet Spot.

练习 7：双下开关

DRILL 7: DOUBLE UNDERSWITCH

我们为什么这样做：切换练习可以训练核心身体进行有力、协调且轻松的运动。多重切换（两次或两次以上切换）练习可以引入游泳节奏（稳定、有节奏的核心身体旋转），但会在最佳位置保留停顿，以便有时间重新调整、评估练习效果并进行微调。

Why We Do It: Switch drills teach powerful, coordinated, effortless movement of the core body. Multiswitch (two or more switches) drills introduce swimming rhythms (steady, rhythmic core-body rotation) to these movements but retain pauses in Sweet Spot, to allow time to regroup, evaluate your practice, and make fine adjustments.

 

 

遵循此顺序

Follow This Sequence

1. 像练习 6 一样开始，但在再次在 Sweet Spot 暂停之前，您将进行两次切换。

1. Start as in Drill 6 but you’ll do two switches before pausing in Sweet Spot again.

 

 

2. 转至滑行姿势后，停下来检查平衡。身体前倾，感受水的支撑，然后把手悄悄地向前伸。

2. After you roll to the Skating Position, pause to check your balance. Lean in to feel the support of the water, then sneak your hand forward.

 

 

3. 等到两个开关都打开之前，你的手才能看到。保持头部“隐藏”状态，并通过两个开关直视底部。

3. Wait to see your hand before both switches. Keep your head “hidden” and look directly at the bottom through both switches.

 

 

4. 完成甜蜜点并呼吸三次，然后再次翻滚至机头向下。

4. Finish in Sweet Spot and breathe three times before rolling to nose-down again.

 

 

5. 从另一侧开始下一个长度：向下看...看到你的手...切换...滑动片刻...看到你的手...切换...在你的最佳位置呼吸。

5. Start the next length on your other side: Look down … see your hand … Switch … glide a moment … see your hand … Switch … Breathe in your Sweet Spot.

 

 

6. 左右两侧都练习，直到你感觉自己能够毫不费力地保持平衡地滑行……并且直到你的 Switch 时间保持一致。

6. Practice on both right and left sides until you feel yourself gliding effortlessly in balance … and until your Switch timing is consistent.

练习 8：三重下开关

DRILL 8: TRIPLE UNDERSWITCH

我们为什么这样做：这个练习将为您提供更多的空间，让您变得更像鱼，并学习游泳节奏的感觉。

Why We Do It: This drill will give you even more space to make yourself more Fishlike and learn the feel of a swimming rhythm.

 

 

遵循此顺序

Follow This Sequence

只需在上一个练习中添加一个切换即可。利用额外的节奏时间来感受以下所有内容：

Just add one switch to the previous drill. Use the extra rhythm time to feel all of the following:

放松你的踢腿：

如何让它变得经济又轻松

Let Go of Your Kick:

How to Make It Economical and Relaxed

大多数成年游泳者打腿过多，并非出于自愿，而是因为他们感觉腿在下沉。这种打腿不仅缺乏推进力、浪费能量，还会破坏你的节奏，让你无法达到流畅的游泳水平。对大多数人来说，理想的打腿方式是平直且几乎不费力的。你的练习是帮助你用更经济的打腿方式（称为两次打腿，每个划水周期打腿两次）取代浪费能量的打腿的完美工具。

Most adult swimmers kick too much, not because they want to but because they feel their legs sinking. This kicking is not only nonpropulsive and energy-wasting, it also wrecks your rhythm and any chance of achieving fluency. The ideal kick for most people is one that is nonovert and nearly effortless. Your drills are the perfect device for helping you replace an energy-wasting kick with an economical kick, called a two-beat kick (for two kicks in each stroke cycle).

训练过程中唯一应该进行的明显踢腿动作是在“甜蜜点”轻轻踢腿，以便在训练周期之间保持动力。但是，当身体旋转提供动力时，让你的腿休息一下。你可以使用“换腿”练习来训练双腿，学习双拍踢腿的时机。这种踢腿动作非常有效地帮助身体左右摇摆，从而产生充足的推进力。你几乎可以整天用这种踢腿方式游泳而不会感到疲倦。

The only overt kicking that should happen as you drill is a gentle kick in Sweet Spot to maintain momentum between drill cycles. But when your body rotation is providing momentum, let your legs take a rest. You can train them for this by using Switch drills to learn the timing of the two-beat kick. This kick does a wonderfully efficient job of helping the body roll from side to side, which generates ample power for propulsion. You can swim with this kick virtually all day without tiring.

学习过程相当简单。进行任何“切换”练习时，切换时都要停止踢腿。尝试在“甜蜜点”状态下保持平衡滑行片刻，无需踢腿，然后恢复轻柔稳定的踢腿。在旋转至机头朝下姿势时，保持轻松踢腿，但当你的手向前划动以启动切换时，再次暂停踢腿，让你的身体借助重心转移和身体旋转产生的动量向前滑行。在“甜蜜点”状态下重新平衡后，再次开始踢腿。

The learning process is fairly simple. Whenever you do any of the Switch drills, stop kicking as you make the switch. Try to glide in balance without a kick for a few moments in Sweet Spot, then resume gentle, steady kicking. Keep kicking easily as you swivel to the nose-down position, but as your hand slices forward to initiate the switch, pause your kick again and let your body glide forward on the momentum from your weight shift and body rotation. After you rebalance in Sweet Spot, pick up the kick again.

多开关练习也一样。和单开关练习一样，在最佳位置以及旋转到滑行姿势时，保持轻柔的打腿，但当你的手在第一个开关处切入时，让你的腿暂停。它们实际上不会保持静止。相反，当每只手入水时，一条腿应该用力向下。右手入水时，左腿打腿；左手入水时，右腿打腿。

It’s the same with the multiswitch drills. As in the single-switch drills, maintain a gentle kick while in Sweet Spot and when you swivel to the Skating Position, but once your hand slices in on the first switch, let your legs pause. They won’t actually remain motionless. Instead, one leg should beat down as each hand enters the water. As your right hand enters, your left leg kicks; as your left hand enters, your right leg kicks.

无需耗费过多脑细胞来协调。相反，专注于让双腿自然地运动，就像你暂停换腿前一直在进行的稳定踢腿一样。你的手臂和双腿已经非常熟悉如何以平衡的方式移动。无论是跑步还是行走，它们都会做同样的事情：右臂和左腿一起向前摆动，然后左臂和右腿一起摆动。

Don’t use too many brain cells trying to coordinate this. Instead, focus on letting the legs do what comes naturally when you just pause the steady kick you’d been using prior to the switch. Your arms and legs already are well acquainted with moving in a counterbalancing fashion. Running or walking, they do the same: Right arm and left leg swing forward together, then left arm and right leg.

• 保持头部隐藏。三次切换过程中，水应流过您的后脑勺。

• Keep your head hidden. Water should flow over the back of your head during all three switches.

 

 

• 保持时间的一致性。当你看到手在鼻子下方时，立即切换。

• Keep your timing consistent. Switch at the exact moment you see your hand under your nose.

 

 

• 双手向前和向后充分伸展，然后滑动片刻，然后恢复进行下一次切换。

• Extend both hands fully, front and back, then glide just a moment before recovering for the next switch.

 

 

• 滑行时，感觉自己就像躺在水面上一样，被水支撑着。这就是极佳的平衡感。

• During your glide, feel yourself just lying there supported by the water. That’s the feeling of great balance.

 

 

• 集中精力刺入水中，特别是在潜行和切换手臂时。

• Maintain a focus on piercing the water, particularly while sneaking your arm and switching.

 

 

• 当所有这一切开始感觉有些自然时，看看你是否可以在三次切换期间暂停你的踢腿……在 Sweet Spot 再次拿起它。

• When all of that begins to feel somewhat natural, see if you can pause your kick during the three switches…. Pick it up again in Sweet Spot.

 

 

• 最后，减少换位之间的滑行。在三次换位过程中，身体的转动幅度要小一些，以增加节奏感。

• Finally, reduce the glide between switches. Roll your body a bit less during the three switches, to increase rhythm.

第三课练习计划

Lesson Three Practice Plan

前两课的动作和协调性相对简单。第三课涉及更复杂的动作，但我们的呈现方式旨在简化您的学习曲线。动作越复杂，就越容易让人感到困惑。您可以通过以下两点来简化：(1) 在进入第四课之前，为第三课留出更多练习时间；(2) 在按照以下建议的顺序组合练习之前，花更多时间对第三课中的每个练习进行集中练习。

The movements and coordination were relatively simple in the first two lessons. Lesson Three involves more complex movements, though we’ve presented them in a way designed to ease your learning curve. More complexity brings more opportunity for confusion. Simplify by doing two things: (1) Allow more practice time for Lesson Three before advancing to Lesson Four; and (2) spend a bit more time on focused practice of each of the Lesson Three drills by themselves before combining them in the sequences suggested below.

以下是一些建议的序列（务必至少花十分钟复习练习 2、3 和 4 来进行热身）。

Here are some suggested sequences (always warm up with at least ten minutes refresher practice of Drills 2, 3, and 4).

 

 

200码重复

200-YARD REPEATS

• 练习 2、3、4 和 5，每项 50 码（右 25 码、左 25 码）。

• 50 yards each (25 right, 25 left) of Drills 2, 3, 4, and 5.

 

 

100码重复

100-YARD REPEATS

• 右侧 25 UnderSkate，25 UnderSwitch，左侧 25 Under-Skate，25 UnderSwitch。

• 25 UnderSkate on your right side, 25 UnderSwitch, 25 Under-Skate left, 25 UnderSwitch.

 

 

150码重复

150-YARD REPEATS

• 50 UnderSkate（右 25，左 25），50 UnderSwitch，50 Double UnderSwitch（右 25 平衡，左 25）。

• 50 UnderSkate (25 right, 25 left), 50 UnderSwitch, 50 Double UnderSwitch (25 balance on right, 25 on left).

• 25 UnderSkate 右，25 UnderSwitch，25 Double Under-Switch 右，25 UnderSkate 左，25 UnderSwitch，25 Double UnderSwitch 左。

• 25 UnderSkate right, 25 UnderSwitch, 25 Double Under-Switch right, 25 UnderSkate left, 25 UnderSwitch, 25 Double UnderSwitch left.

在第三课的练习中累计练习几个小时之前，每次练习后至少休息三次瑜伽呼吸。同样，在每次练习的循环之间，在你的最佳练习点进行三次瑜伽呼吸。

Until you have put in a cumulative total of several hours practice in Lesson Three drills, rest for at least three yoga breaths after each length. Similarly, take three yoga breaths in your Sweet Spot between cycles of each drill.

第四课：掌握紧凑、放松的恢复

Lesson Four: Mastering a Compact, Relaxed Recovery

掌握了第三课后，你应该已经体验到了鱼式游泳的两个重要要素：首先，如何用手简单地抓住水中的某个点，同时通过动态的身体翻滚越过该点，从而毫不费力地产生推进力。其次，如何保持身体线条较长，并有节奏地“俯卧”。我们的下一步将让你拥有更强的平衡感，并开始为你紧凑、放松的移臂打下肌肉记忆。我们煞费苦心地为划水建立了平衡、对齐的基础，我们不想让手臂摆动的移臂破坏这一点。本课将教你一种节省能量、保持身体对齐、减少阻力的移臂方法。

Having mastered Lesson Three, you should now have experienced two important elements of Fishlike Swimming: First, how to generate effortless propulsion by using your hand to simply hold on to a spot in the water while dynamic body roll takes you past that spot. Second, how to keep your body line long and to “lie on your lungs” while doing that rhythmically. Our next step will give you an even stronger sense of balance and start imprinting the muscle memory for a compact, relaxed recovery. Having painstakingly developed a balanced, aligned foundation for stroking, we don’t want to let an arm-swinging recovery upset that. This lesson teaches you an energy-saving, alignment-preserving, drag-reducing recovery.

练习 9：拉链溜冰鞋

DRILL 9: ZIPPERSKATE

我们为什么这样做：我们用 UnderSkate（练习 5）作为 UnderSwitch（练习 6）的动觉练习，并练习一种稍微更动态的平衡方式。ZipperSkate 可以以同样的方式帮助你为 ZipperSwitch 做好准备。但它在你准备全程游泳时更有价值，因为它是获得“俯卧”最强烈感觉的理想方式。一旦你深入骨髓地感受到这种感觉，你就会知道如何真正放松、从容地划水。

Why We Do It: We used UnderSkate (Drill 5) as kinesthetic rehearsal for UnderSwitch (Drill 6) and to practice a slightly more dynamic form of balance. ZipperSkate will prepare you for ZipperSwitch in the same way. But it can be even more valuable in preparing you for whole-stroke swimming because it’s the ideal way to gain the most powerful sense of how to “lie on your lungs.” Once you feel that in your bones, you’ll know how to have a truly relaxed, unhurried stroke.

 

 

遵循此顺序

Follow This Sequence

1. 按照练习5的步骤开始。当你回到滑行姿势时，不要在水下恢复，而是慢慢地将手沿着身体两侧拉动（就像拉拉链一样）。保持手在水面以下，如图所示。

1. Begin as in Drill 5. When you arrive at the Skating Position, rather than recover under water, drag your hand slowly along your side (as if pulling up a zipper). Keep your hand under the surface, as shown in the illustration.

 

 

2. 尽可能长时间地用肘部引导，手部跟随，直到肘部和手部位于耳边。（提示：侧卧在泳池边或家中地板上练习这个动作非常有帮助。）

2. Lead with your elbow for as long as possible, with your hand trailing until elbow and hand are alongside your ear. (Tip: It can be extremely helpful to practice this movement while lying on your side on the pool deck or on your floor at home.)

ZIPPERSKATE 位置还说明了所有 ZIPPERSWITCH 练习的切换时机。

THE ZIPPERSKATE POSITION ALSO ILLUSTRATES SWITCH-TIMING FOR ALL ZIPPERSWITCH DRILLS.

 

 

3. 当你的手臂呈“鲨鱼鳍”状时，短暂检查肩膀是否仍然保持水平，然后将手向下滑动。最后，将针状体式一直滚动到最佳位置。进行三次瑜伽呼吸，然后重复。

3. Once your arm is in the “shark-fin” position, briefly check that your shoulders are still stacked, then slide your hand back down. Finish by rolling your needle shape all the way back to Sweet Spot. Take three yoga breaths, then repeat.

 

 

练习方法：随着时间的推移，这很可能成为你最有价值的平衡训练，也是你应该最常练习的。它能让你清晰地了解：(1) 你对平衡的掌握程度；(2) 你的支撑“浮标”在哪里；以及 (3) 如何运用这种意识稳步提升你的平衡能力。在你学会了基本动作（尤其是肘部引导手部以及手部保持在水下）之后，我建议你运用“练习到厌倦”的理念，充分培养你的动觉平衡意识，并将其深深地植入你的神经系统。在接下来的一两个月里，你可以每周不间断地练习这个训练，每次十五到三十分钟，并在每一圈都学到宝贵的经验。以下是一些重点：

How to Practice: Over time this will probably be your most valuable balance drill and the one you should practice most often. It will give you a clear picture of: (1) how well you’ve mastered balance; (2) where your supporting “buoy” is; and (3) how to use that awareness to steadily improve your balance. After you’ve learned the basic movements (particularly the elbow leading the hand and the hand remaining underwater), I recommend you use the practice-’til-you’re-bored philosophy to fully develop your kinesthetic balance awareness and burn it into your nervous system. You could easily practice this drill nonstop for fifteen to thirty minutes once a week for the next month or two and learn valuable lessons on every lap. Here are a few focal points:

 

 

1. 你的身体稳定吗？还是手臂向前时会立即下沉？如果你立即开始下沉，请确保身体重心前倾，并将伸出的手臂置于头部下方。如果你下沉，你的目标是保持水平下沉，使腋窝与臀部和双脚处于同一水平。这对于学习平衡至关重要。如果你下沉，请将手放在肩膀上，然后立即将其滑回身体两侧。

1. Are you stable or do you immediately begin to sink as your arm comes forward? If you begin to sink right away, make sure you keep your weight forward and the extended arm below your head. Your goal—if you sink—is to sink in a horizontal position with your armpit at the same level as your hips and feet. This is enormously valuable to learning equilibrium. If you’re a sinker, bring your hand to your shoulder and immediately slide it back to your side.

 

 

2. 如果你在向前拉手臂时身体姿势保持相当稳定，可以“滑行”几秒钟，肘部静止在肩膀上方。手臂在空中的重量应该能让你清楚地感觉到如何通过“俯卧”来保持平衡。如果你在这样做时感觉平衡，可以练习非常缓慢地移臂。这是目前为止最接近你开始进行全程游泳后想要的感觉。

2. If your body position remains fairly stable as you draw your arm forward, “skate” for a few seconds with your elbow motionless above your shoulder. The weight of your arm in the air should give you a clear sense of how to balance by “lying on your lungs.” If you feel balanced while doing this, practice doing the recovery super slowly. This is the nearest sensation thus far of how you’d like to feel once you begin whole-stroke swimming.

 

 

3. 移水时，专注于感受水对你手的阻力。不要对抗。相反，要通过放松手和手臂来克服阻力。你的移水动作能紧凑、轻柔到什么程度？

3. Focus on sensing the water resistance against your hand on recovery. Don’t fight it. Instead, yield to the resistance by softening your hand and arm. How compact and gentle can you make that recovery action?

 

 

4. 如果您在这个练习中属于“下沉”组，脚蹼将让您在进行这个练习时感受到平衡游泳者所感受到的稳定支撑。

4. If you’re in the “sinkers” group on this drill, fins will allow you to sense the stable support a balanced swimmer feels when doing this drill.

练习 10：拉链开关

DRILL 10: ZIPPERSWITCH

我们为什么这样做：你正在学习的紧凑、放松、从容的移臂动作，将是有效地将手臂划水与核心身体旋转力量联系起来的关键。这个练习还会教你如何掌握前象限的节奏，让你的身体在整个划水周期中保持较长的线条。这个练习特意夸张地将手在耳边切入，然后在水下向前切入。这可以纠正几乎普遍存在的移臂过度伸展的倾向。

Why We Do It: The compact, relaxed, unhurried recovery you are learning will be an important key to effectively linking your arm-stroke to the power of core-body rotation. This drill will also teach you the front-quadrant timing that keeps your body line long throughout the stroke cycle. The purposeful exaggeration on this drill is to slice your hand in alongside your ear, before slicing it forward underwater. This corrects the nearly universal tendency to overreach on the recovery.

 

 

遵循此顺序

Follow This Sequence

1. 按照练习 9 开始。从最佳位置有意识地移动到滑冰位置，然后检查您是否保持平衡——感觉到很好的支撑——伸出的手放在头下。

1. Begin as in Drill 9. Move deliberately from Sweet Spot to the Skating Position, then check that you are balanced—feeling great support—with your extended hand below your head.

 

 

2. 做“拉链式”移水，手部入水，肘部尽可能向前。感受水对手部的阻力，但不要抵抗。放松手臂和手部，使其靠近肩膀和耳朵。

2. Do a “Zipper” recovery with your hand under water, elbow leading as far forward as possible. Feel water resistance on your hand but don’t fight it. Soften your arm and hand and keep them close to shoulder and ear.

 

 

3. 当你的手追上肘部时，立即将其向内向前切，同时切换并滚动到另一侧的甜蜜点。

3. As soon as your hand catches up to the elbow, slice it in and forward as you switch and roll to Sweet Spot on the other side.

 

 

4. 放松并在“甜蜜点”处滑行，时间随意（三次瑜伽呼吸），然后换方向重复。练习时，注意以下几点：

4. Relax and glide in Sweet Spot for as long as you want (three yoga breaths), then repeat in the other direction. As you practice, emphasize the following:

• 紧凑而从容地恢复。继续专注于在尽可能小的空间内切换，但现在这个空间是在水面之上和之下。

• A compact and unhurried recovery. Continue to focus on switching through the smallest possible space, but that space is now above and below the surface.

• 手入水过早，且靠近头部。将手伸入水中，直至耳边，以纠正过度伸手的倾向。

• Hand entry that is exaggeratedly early and close to your head. Drive your hand into the water alongside your ear to overcorrect the tendency to overreach.

•默默练习，花所有时间去感受康复过程中进行转换的正确时机。

• Practice silently, taking all the time you need to feel in your bones the right moment in your recovery to make the switch.

• 在切换时继续感觉与核心身体“连接”。

• Continue to feel “connected” to your core body as you switch.

练习 11：双拉链开关

DRILL 11: DOUBLE ZIPPERSWITCH

我们为什么这样做：就像“双下换”一样，“双拉链”将游泳节奏融入你刚刚学到的动作中。让你更接近真正的游泳。

Why We Do It: As in Double UnderSwitch, Double Zipper introduces swimming rhythms to the movements you’ve just learned. You’re coming ever closer to actual swimming.

 

 

遵循此顺序

Follow This Sequence

像 ZipperSwitch 一样开始，但在 Sweet Spot 再次暂停之前进行两次切换。

Start as in ZipperSwitch, but do two switches before pausing in Sweet Spot again.

 

 

1. 转至滑冰姿势后，检查你的平衡。感受水在支撑你，然后将手向前伸。始终感受水在对你的手施加阻力。

1. After you roll to the Skating Position, check your balance. Feel the water supporting you, then draw your hand forward. Feel the water resisting your hand at all times.

 

 

2. 当你的手放在耳朵旁边时切换。

2. Switch when your hand is alongside your ear.

 

 

3. 将头部“隐藏”起来，并通过两个开关直视底部。

3. Keep your head “hidden” and look directly at the bottom through both switches.

 

 

4. 在 Sweet Spot 处结束，呼吸三次后再向下滚动。

4. Finish in Sweet Spot and take three breaths before rolling nose-down again.

 

 

5. 从另一侧开始下一个长度。

5. Start the next length on your other side.

练习 12：三重拉链开关

DRILL 12: TRIPLE ZIPPERSWITCH

我们为什么这样做：我们正处于全程游泳的边缘。多做 ZipperSwitches 能让你从熟练的练习过渡到优美的游泳。

Why We Do It: We’re right on the verge of whole-stroke swimming. Doing more ZipperSwitches primes you to transition from skillful drilling to beautiful swimming.

 

 

遵循此顺序

Follow This Sequence

1. 当你感觉平衡感和节奏感良好，并且能够从容放松地进行移臂时，可以进阶到三重拉链式。练习要点与三重下式相同：头部隐藏，保持稳定、从容的核心身体节奏，以及保持一致的“切换”节奏。以下是一些你可以给出的具体指导：

1. When you feel good balance and timing and have an unhurried, relaxed recovery, progress to Triple Zipper. Focus on the same points as in Triple Under: head hidden, steady unhurried core-body rhythm, consistent “switch” timing. Here are some specific instructions you can give:

•藏起你的头……水应该大部分时间从你的后脑勺流过……直视下方，看着自己毫不费力地滑过泳池底部的瓷砖。

• Hide your head… Water should flow over the back of your head much of the time … Look straight down and watch yourself slide effortlessly past tiles on the pool bottom.

•保持低调……贴着水面，就像在很低的天花板下游泳一样。

• Keep a low profile…Hug the surface, as if you were swimming under a very low ceiling.

•刺穿水面...从水面上和水面下尽可能最小的空间中滑过。

• Pierce the water… Slip through the smallest possible space both above and below the surface.

•放松你的手臂和手...感觉水对你的手有阻力，但试着恢复而不溅起水花或湍流。

• Soften your arms and hands… Feel the water resist your hand but try to recover without splash or turbulence.

•感受水的完全支撑，并利用水的支撑尽可能缓慢地将手向前移动。

• Feel the complete support of the water and use it to bring your hand forward as slowly as you can.

•最后，钻孔时不要发出声音。

• And finally, drill without making a sound.

第四课练习计划

Lesson Four Practice Plan

从练习到游泳的过渡从这里开始。第四课教你的动作和协调性几乎与流畅游泳时完全相同。我建议你不要把时间平均分配在这节课的三个练习上。正如建议的那样，花大量时间练习 ZipperSkate 来培养良好的平衡感。这将有助于你在接下来的训练中取得成功。练习 ZipperSwitch 的时间要足够掌握换水时机。随着技能的提升，可以花更多时间练习 Triple Zipper，因为它能教会你一系列宝贵的经验，而且比任何其他训练都更能让你成为一名真正经济的游泳者——能够在任何距离的游动中几乎不费力地漂浮，甚至不需要大口喘气。以下是一些建议的顺序：

The transition from drilling to swimming starts here. Lesson Four teaches you movements and coordination almost exactly the same as you’ll use in fluent swimming. I’d suggest you don’t divide your time equally among all three drills in this lesson. As suggested, spend lots of time practicing ZipperSkate to develop the great balance sense that will make you successful in the drills that follow. Spend just enough time practicing ZipperSwitch to master the switch timing. As your skills develop, spend more of your time with Triple Zipper because it teaches a range of valuable lessons and can do more than any other drill to make you a truly economical swimmer—able to practically float through a swim of any distance without even breathing hard. Here are some suggested sequences:

 

 

100码重复

100-YARD REPEATS

• 右侧有 25 个 ZipperSkate，25 个 ZipperSwitch，左侧有 25 个 ZipperSkate，25 个 ZipperSwitch。

• 25 ZipperSkate on your right side, 25 ZipperSwitch, 25 ZipperSkate left, 25 ZipperSwitch.

• 25 UnderSwitch、25 Triple Under、25 ZipperSwitch、25 Triple Zipper。

• 25 UnderSwitch, 25 Triple Under, 25 ZipperSwitch, 25 Triple Zipper.

 

 

150码重复

150-YARD REPEATS

• 练习 3、4 和 9，每项 50 码（右 25 码、左 25 码）。

• 50 yards each (25 right, 25 left) of Drills 3, 4, and 9.

• 50 ZipperSkate（右 25、左 25）、50 ZipperSwitch、50 Multi-Zipper。

• 50 ZipperSkate (25 right, 25 left), 50 ZipperSwitch, 50 Multi-Zipper.

• 25 ZipperSkate 右、25 ZipperSwitch、25 Triple Zipper、25 ZipperSkate 左、25 ZipperSwitch、25 Triple Zipper。

• 25 ZipperSkate right, 25 ZipperSwitch, 25 Triple Zipper, 25 ZipperSkate left, 25 ZipperSwitch, 25 Triple Zipper.

额外练习：更多拉链开关

EXTRA PRACTICE: MORE ZIPPERSWITCHES

通过长时间、专注地、耐心地重复练习三重拉链，可以极大地提升你的轻松度和流畅度。主要进行25码的重复练习，每次练习之间休息三到五次瑜伽呼吸。参考练习13的重点菜单，每次重复只选择一个重点。持续专注于体验的这一方面。直到你感觉它融入你的动作模式。随着你的动作变得更加放松和流畅，在回到最佳位置之前，可以进行更多次换位——最多五六次。但不要把它变成个人屏气比赛。真正高效的游泳者会发现，他们可以轻松地、从容地进行近25码的拉链换位，因为这种换位非常省力，几乎不需要氧气就能游完整个泳池。

You greatly enhance your ease and flow with long, concentrated sessions of nothing but patient repetition of Triple Zipper. Do mainly 25-yard reps, resting between each for three to five yoga breaths. Referring to the menu of focal points for Drill 13, choose just one focal point for each repetition. Keep focusing on that aspect of the experience until you feel it becoming “grooved” into your movement pattern. As your movements become more relaxed and flowing, do more switches—as many as five or six—before returning to the Sweet Spot. But don’t turn it into a personal breath-holding contest. Truly efficient swimmers find they can do effortless, unhurried ZipperSwitches for nearly 25 yards because they are so economical they use little oxygen to do a full pool length.

第五课：迎接你的新击球

Lesson Five: Meet Your New Stroke

第五课虽然简单易学，但却能教会你如何精准地掌握划水姿势，并最终影响你的一生。对一些人来说，练习12和13至少在一段时间内是他们“游泳”的方式。第五课，尤其是练习12和13的伟大价值在于，它几乎能让任何人，即使是处于学习初期的人，也能轻松地练习像鱼一样游泳。

Lesson Five, though simple to master, will teach you precisely how your stroke will feel for the rest of your life. For some, Drills 12 and 13 are their form of “swimming,” at least for a while. The great value of Lesson Five, particularly Drills 12 and 13 is that it gives almost anyone, even someone in the very early learning stages, an easy way to practice Fishlike Swimming.

练习 14：过度切换

DRILL 14: OVERSWITCH

我们为什么这样做：我们的最后一步是一个练习，教你如何感受新的“鱼式”划水姿势。事实上，你会在最佳位置的停顿之间用新的划水姿势游泳。这个练习可以强化你最初通过“下划”和“拉链式”划水练习掌握的节奏。这种节奏可以帮助你游得更高。它还能让你练习灵巧、刀子般的入水……这两项技巧都有助于将你的手臂与核心旋转带来的轻松力量联系起来。

Why We Do It: Our final step is a drill that teaches you how your new “Fishlike” stroke will feel. In fact, you’ll be swimming with your new stroke between pauses in your Sweet Spot. This drill reinforces the timing you began imprinting with Under- and ZipperSwitch. That timing helps you swim taller. It also allows you to practice a deft, knife-like entry … Both of these skills help connect your arm to effortless power from core-body rotation.

 

 

遵循此顺序

Follow This Sequence

1. 此练习是拉链练习系列中相应练习的自然延伸。从至少一段三拉链练习开始。确保你以紧凑、放松——几乎是懒散的——移臂动作进行。在进行第二段时，抬起你的移臂手，使其刚好离开水面，然后立即重新入水。在进入甜蜜点之前，每个循环进行三次或更多次“切换”。

1. This drill is a natural extension of the corresponding drill in the Zipper drill series. Start with at least one length of Triple Zipper. Make sure you’re recovering with a compact, relaxed—almost lazy— recovery. On the second length, raise your recovery hand so it barely clears the water and immediately reenters. Do three or more “switches” on each cycle before going to Sweet Spot.

 

 

2.练习时应注意以下几个重点：

2. Practice with the following focal points:

• 保持头部隐藏且稳定。切换时，请持续观察泳池底部的瓷砖。水流应大部分时间从您的后脑勺流过。

• Keep your head hidden and stable. Keep watching the tiles on the pool bottom during the switches. Water should flow over the back of your head much of the time.

• 换臂时要“耐心”：等到移臂的手臂够到耳边后，再开始用伸出的手“划”。在手入水前换臂。

• Be “patient” on your switches: Wait for the recovering arm to reach your ear before you start to “pull” with your extended hand. Make the switch just before your hand enters the water.

• 将手伸入泳镜前方的水中。用手指剪开一个洞，然后将手臂干净利落地穿过那个洞。

• Put your hand into the water just in front of your goggles. Cut a hole with your fingers and slip your arm cleanly through that hole.

过度切换时间。

OVERSWITCH TIMING.

• 逐渐将注意力从切换时间转移到核心身体滚动节奏。

• Gradually shift focus from the timing of your switches to your core-body-rolling rhythm.

• 一旦感觉到身体节奏，调整身体滚动以实现流畅、有节奏和无缝的运动，没有犹豫或中断。

• Once you feel body rhythm, adjust body roll to allow for fluid, rhythmic, and seamless movement with no hesitation or interruptions.

 

 

3. 如果你感觉良好，而且不需要特别用力呼吸，可以增加换挡次数。大多数TI学生可以轻松完成四到六次换挡。关键在于保持轻松、轻松的换挡和滚动节奏。你可能会发现自己能够在“甜蜜点”不停歇地完成整整25码。

3. If you feel good and don’t particularly need to breathe, add switches. Most TI students can do four to six switches with ease. The key is to sustain a relaxed, effortless, switching-and-rolling rhythm. You may find yourself able to complete a full 25 yards without pausing in Sweet Spot.

第五课练习计划

Lesson Five Practice Plan

除了“甜蜜点”中的停顿之外，你在这里要练习的就是游泳，而且要进行多次切换。基于练习的练习有助于最大限度地减少可能导致你恢复到以前“人类游泳”习惯的压力或情况。尤其是在早期阶段，用第四课的练习来“调整”第五课的练习会很有帮助。以下是一些建议的150码序列（每25码继续休息两到三次瑜伽呼吸）：

Except for the pauses in Sweet Spot, what you’ll be practicing here with multiple switches is swimming. Drill-based practice helps minimize the pressures or situations that might cause you to revert to your old “human-swimming” habits. Particularly in early stages, it will be helpful to “tune up” for Lesson Five practice with Lesson Four drills. Here are some suggested 150-yard sequences (continue to rest for two to three yoga breaths each 25):

 

 

150码重复

150-YARD REPEATS

• 右侧 25 ZipperSkate、25 ZipperSwitch、25 Double Zipper 右侧（向左侧呼吸）、25 ZipperSkate 左侧、25 ZipperSwitch、25 Double Zipper 左侧（向右侧呼吸）。

• 25 ZipperSkate on your right side, 25 ZipperSwitch, 25 Double Zipper right (breathing to your left), 25 ZipperSkate left, 25 ZipperSwitch, 25 Double Zipper left (breathing to your right).

• 25 ZipperSkate 右、25 Triple Zipper、25 Triple OverSwitch、25 ZipperSkate 左、25 Triple Zipper、25 Triple Over。

• 25 ZipperSkate right, 25 Triple Zipper, 25 Triple OverSwitch, 25 ZipperSkate left, 25 Triple Zipper, 25 Triple Over.

• 50 ZipperSkate（25 右、25 左）、25 ZipperSwitch、25 Triple Zipper、25 OverSwitch、25 Triple Over。

• 50 ZipperSkate (25 right, 25 left), 25 ZipperSwitch, 25 Triple Zipper, 25 OverSwitch, 25 Triple Over.

通过 Triple Overswitch 找到你的幸福

FIND YOUR BLISS WITH TRIPLE OVERSWITCH

专注练习“三重练习”（Triple Over）可以让你进入心流状态。每次练习25码（中间休息两到四次瑜伽呼吸），持续七到十五分钟。尝试做4到6次切换，然后在“甜蜜点”（Sweet Spot）暂停三次瑜伽呼吸。以下是一些重点练习：

Concentrated practice of Triple Over can put you into a Flow state. Do 25-yard reps (resting for two to four yoga breaths) for seven to fifteen minutes. Try to do 4 to 6 switches before pausing in Sweet Spot for three yoga breaths. Here is a menu of focal points:

 

 

•向下看，让水流过你的后脑勺。

•Look down so water flows over the back of your head.

 

 

•身体前倾（顺坡游），这样你的臀部和腿部就会感觉轻松。

•Lean in (swim downhill) so your hips and legs feel light.

 

 

• “紧贴”水面。尽可能短时间地将手从水中移开，然后将其放回泳镜旁边。

•“Hug” the surface. Take your hand out of the water for the briefest possible period; put it back in right beside your goggles.

 

 

• “刺穿”水面。在水面上和水面下尽可能狭小的空间内滑行。

•“Pierce” the water. Slip through the smallest possible space above and below the surface.

 

 

•放松恢复动作并尽可能缓慢地将手向前伸。

•Soften your recovery and bring your hand forward as slowly as you can.

 

 

•用指关节（如果戴着拳套）或指尖切开一个洞，然后将整个手臂干净利落地滑进去，直到低于头部。

•Cut a hole with your knuckles (if wearing fistgloves®) or fingertips and slip your entire arm through cleanly and steeply until it’s below your head.

 

 

•拉长你的船。感受你的手不慌不忙地向前漂浮。

•Lengthen your vessel. Feel your hand just float forward with no hurry.

 

 

•保持开关时间的一致性。

•Time your switches consistently.

 

 

•移动时尽量保持安静。

•Move as silently as you can.

第六课：过渡到游泳

Lesson Six: Making the Transition to Swimming

你的游泳动作现在都到位了。剩下的就是取消“甜蜜点”暂停，用有节奏的呼吸来代替。你的目标是让呼吸与身体旋转的节奏无缝衔接。（次要目标可以是两侧呼吸顺畅。）让我们回顾一下你是如何为此做好准备的。

Your swimming movements are all in place now. All that remains is to take out the Sweet Spot pauses and replace them with rhythmic breathing. Your goal here is to make breathing a seamless part of your body-rolling rhythm. (A secondary goal can be to breathe smoothly on either side.) Let’s review what has prepared you to do this.

 

 

1. 你已经学会了在三种滑冰变式中，通过身体向空中滚动（而不是转动头部）来呼吸。使用滑冰、UnderSkate 和 ZipperSkate 来强化这个习惯。

1. You learned to breathe by rolling your body to the air (rather than turning your head) in all three variations of Skating. Use Skating, UnderSkate, and ZipperSkate to reinforce that habit.

 

 

2. 你在 UnderSwitch 和 ZipperSwitch 中学会了在空中翻滚时保持头部连接和对齐。利用这些练习来强化这个习惯。

2. You learned to keep your head connected and aligned as you rolled to the air in UnderSwitch and ZipperSwitch. Use those drills to reinforce this habit.

 

 

3. 你在 Triple Zipper 和 Triple Over 中培养了核心-身体-滚动的节奏感。利用这些练习来强化你的节奏感。

3. You developed your sense of core-body-rolling rhythms in Triple Zipper and Triple Over. Use those drills to reinforce your rhythm awareness.

 

 

4. 你已经完成了全部十四个练习中的平衡训练。平衡能力的提升将使你能够呼吸，而无需将前臂推向底部。呼吸时，注意保持平衡，保持“挺直”。在练习中（包括钻井和游泳）大量使用拳套（参见第13章），对练习“无重臂”尤其有帮助。

4. You’ve worked on balance in all fourteen drills. Improved balance will allow you to breathe without driving your lead arm toward the bottom. Focus on balance to “stay tall” as you breathe. Extensive use of fistgloves® (see chapter 13) in your practice—both drilling and swimming—can be particularly helpful in developing the “weightless arm.”

我们将使用三重过度切换练习来过渡到游泳。进行一系列25码的重复练习。每次练习之间根据需要休息（五次或更多瑜伽呼吸），以便每次练习都完全恢复状态。每次练习都以正常（但具有穿透力）的蹬水动作开始，并在第一次呼吸前至少进行四次切换。这并非屏住呼吸，而是衡量你放松程度和轻松程度的标准。从几次不间断的切换开始，目的是通过核心身体旋转而不是手臂来建立节奏。一旦你感觉到轻松自在的节奏，就可以开始不间断地将呼吸融入其中。方法如下。

We’ll use Triple OverSwitch for the transition to swimming. Do a series of 25-yard repeats. Rest as much as needed (five or more yoga breaths) between reps to start each completely fresh. Start each rep with a normal (but water-piercing) pushoff and begin stroking with at least four switches before your first breath. This should not be a breath-holding effort, but a measure of how relaxed and effortless you are. The purpose of beginning with several uninterrupted switches is to establish your rhythm with core-body rotation and not with your arms. Once you feel an effortless, relaxed rhythm, you are ready to fit a breath into that rhythm with no interruption. Here’s how.

 

 

1. 第一次呼吸时，只需滚动到有空气的地方，然后立即向另一个方向滚动即可。

1. Take your first breath simply by rolling right to where the air is and immediately back in the other direction.

 

 

2. 尝试这样做，不要打断你在呼吸之前在开关上建立的滚动节奏。

2. Try to do that with no interruption of the rolling rhythm you established on your switches before the breath.

 

 

3. 如果这次呼吸顺畅，就用同样的方法再做一次，间隔几次。如果感觉节奏稍微中断，试着在下一个划水周期中将其调整顺畅。

3. If that breath goes smoothly, do another the same way, several strokes later. If you sense a slight interruption in your rhythm, try to smooth it out on the next stroke cycle.

 

 

4. 如果失去控制，请在下一次呼吸时回到最佳位置，并思考如何在接下来的 25 分钟内改善您的呼吸技巧。

4. If you lose control, go back to Sweet Spot on the next breath and think about how to improve your breathing technique on the next 25.

要有耐心。有些游泳者可以立即无缝衔接呼吸。其他人，尤其是那些平衡感极其脆弱的人，可能需要花费数周时间才能学会有节奏的呼吸，并且不破坏他们在训练中刻苦练习掌握的控制力和协调性。以下是一些可能有帮助的技巧：

Be patient. Some swimmers will fit breathing in seamlessly right away. Others, particularly those who have the most delicate sense of balance, may need to spend weeks learning to fit in a rhythmic breath without breaking down the control and coordination they have worked so diligently in drills to develop. Here are some tips that may help:

 

 

1. 手臂无重感很重要。在进行多向切换练习时，重点是入水至泳镜旁后，手臂向前漂浮。第一次呼吸时，尤其要注意保持手臂无重感。呼吸时，手应该保持向前微微移动。Fistgloves®会有所帮助！

1. A weightless arm is important. During multiswitch drills focus on having your arm float forward after entering next to your goggles. When you take your first breath, put particular focus on keeping that weightless-arm sensation. Your hand should keep inching forward while you breathe. Fistgloves® will help!

 

 

2. 每次换气的时间要完全一致。保持这个时间与你第一次呼吸的时间一致。

2. Keep the timing of every switch exactly the same. Maintain that timing as you fit in your first breath.

 

 

3. 尽可能地滚到合适的高度。旧习惯可能会导致你抬起或转动头部。保持头部、颈部和躯干连成一体，向空中滚动时，保持身体各部分连接一致。尽量向空中滚动。如果难以顺利出气，可以滚得更远一些。

3. Roll as far as necessary. Old habits may be causing you to lift or turn your head. Keep everything connected and aligned as you roll your head, neck, and torso as one unit to air. Roll all the way to the air. If you’re having difficulty getting air easily, roll farther.

 

 

4. 放慢速度。每当你感到失控时，就放慢一切节奏。保持安静，更加温柔。不要让自己感到匆忙。最后，我有没有提到过，Fistgloves®会有所帮助？

4. Slow down. Any time you feel a loss of control, slow everything down. Be quieter and more gentle. Don’t let yourself feel hurried. And finally, did I mention that fistgloves® will help?

9

9

培训（以及如何获得培训）

Training (and How to Get It)

“健身是当你练习良好的技巧时发生在你身上的事情。”

“Fitness is something that happens to you while you’re practicing good technique.”

如果我的训练营里的游泳运动员几乎什么都没带回家，我希望他们能记住这一点。这是整个“全浸式”游泳项目的基石，虽然我接下来要说的话听起来可能有些重复，但无论如何强调也不为过：游泳速度的70%来自你的划水技巧，只有30%来自肌肉、心脏——所有为划水提供动力的系统。在训练营里，我重复了两三遍之后，就能看到一些运动员眼中涌现出兴奋的神色。“哇！这家伙告诉我，我不需要训练就能游得好！真是省时间！”

If the swimmers in my camps go home with little else, I want them to go home remembering that. It’s the cornerstone of the whole Total Immersion program, and though I may sound repetitious with what I’m about to say, it can hardly be overstressed: 70 percent of your swim speed comes from your stroke mechanics and only 30 percent from the muscles, the heart—all the systems that power that stroke. After the second or third time I repeat it at a camp, I can see an excited idea forming in some of the athletes’ eyes. “Wow! This guy tells me I don’t have to be trained to be good! What a time saver!”

唉，我不是这个意思。我们是在调整优先事项，而不是提倡懒惰。首先，30% 的练习量没什么可放弃的。然而，更重要的是，如果你在泳池中途耗尽体力，即使是一次非常高效的划水也于事无补。训练在全浸式系统中确实有其地位，你对训练效果了解得越多，就越能知道如何规划自己的训练计划。

Alas, that’s not what I meant. We’re adjusting priorities, not advocating sloth. In the first place, 30 percent is nothing to walk away from. More important, however, even a brilliantly efficient stroke won’t do you much good if you run out of gas halfway down the pool. Training does have its place in the Total Immersion system, and the more you know about what the training effect is, the better you’ll know how to plan your own.

我的定义很简单：训练效果可以概括为几乎无限地锻炼、深度、满足的感觉呼吸顺畅，锻炼时感觉神清气爽，而且几乎可以一直持续下去。这其实与衰老截然相反——要求我们（以及我们的细胞）做得更多而不是更少。这就是为什么我直到开始经历衰老才充分享受它。看看发生在我身上的事情是否听起来很熟悉。

My definition is simple: The training effect can be summed up as the feeling of nearly limitless capacity to exercise, take deep, satisfying breaths, feel fresh throughout a workout, and go on practically forever. It’s really the opposite of aging—asking ourselves (and our cells) to do more rather than less. That’s why I didn’t savor it fully until I’d begun to experience aging first. See if what happened to me sounds familiar.

大学四年游泳课上，我的身材达到了人生中最好的状态。每天两小时的高强度训练让我能够不知疲倦地游上一英里又一英里。我精力充沛，可以做任何我想做的事情。不过，二十岁应该就有这种感觉吧。

I was in the best shape of my life during four years of college swimming. Rigorous daily two-hour workouts gave me the ability to tirelessly swim mile after hard mile. I had energy to burn for anything I wanted to do. But you’re supposed to feel that way when you’re twenty years old.

或许正因如此，我才如此轻易地放弃了游泳，甚至还没满21岁就退出了竞技游泳。那时候，大师级游泳比赛根本不可能，而且没有比赛可训练，训练还有什么意义呢？

That must have been why I gave it up so casually, retiring from competitive swimming before I’d even turned twenty-one. Masters swimming wasn’t an option back then, and without races to train for, what was the point in working out?

接下来的十六年，我久坐不动。当年那个瘦削结实的大学生，如今却变成了如今养家糊口的爸爸，松弛的身躯，光是耙树叶就很容易气喘吁吁。我对此并不高兴，但我已经习惯了这种轻松自在的生活方式。

Sixteen sedentary years followed. The lean and hard undergraduate’s body softened into the daddy-and-breadwinner’s flabby frame, easily winded from just raking leaves. I wasn’t happy about it, but I’d grown comfortable with my undemanding lifestyle.

三十七岁生日刚过，警钟就敲响了。我伸手到汽车后座去拿一个轻便的包裹，却再也直不起身子。三天后，我第一次能够下床，我向自己承诺，要恢复正常的游泳训练。

Soon after my thirty-seventh birthday, the wake-up call came. Reaching into the backseat of my car for a light package, I couldn’t straighten up again. Three days later, able to get out of bed for the first time, I promised myself I would return to regular swim training.

不出所料，最初的几个月既艰难又令人沮丧，因为我努力克服疏忽对肌肉、心脏和肺部造成的累积影响。大学里，四英里的艰苦训练轻而易举。现在，我连一英里都跑不了。但我坚持了下来，改为游短距离、轻快的间歇跑。我只是不停地进行马拉松训练，直到它变得更容易，我可以跑得更远。

Predictably, the first months were difficult and discouraging as I struggled to overcome the accumulated effects of neglect on my muscles, heart, and lungs. A hard, four-mile training session had been a cakewalk in college. Now, I could barely struggle through one mile. But I kept at it, swimming the short, brisk lengths of intervals instead of just plowing up and down in nonstop marathon workouts, until it got easier and I could go farther.

接下来的几年里，我的能力日复一日、周复一周地增长。第二年，我可以轻松地完成3000码的训练，就像前一年完成2000码的训练一样。到了第三年，我熟练地将距离提升到了4000码；第四年，在为世界大师锦标赛的5000米（3.1英里）项目进行训练时，我可以轻松地完成5000码甚至更长的训练，甚至连气喘吁吁都没有。最棒的是，当我年满40岁时，我感觉自己比十年前年轻多了。

Day by day, week by week, for the next several years, my capacity grew. In year two I could knock off 3000-yard practices as easily as the 2000-yard workouts of the year before. By the third, I had deftly upped it to 4000 yards and in the fourth, as I trained for a 5000-meter (3.1-mile) event at the World Masters Championships, I could sail through sessions of 5000 yards and more without even breathing hard. Best of all, as I turned forty, I felt much younger than I had ten years earlier.

那么，除了能让时光倒流的灵丹妙药之外，训练还有什么效果呢？通过压力来增强力量。哲学家弗里德里希·尼采在宣称“那些杀不死我的，终将使我更强大”时，可能就在思考我们从锻炼中获得的益处。给生物体施加压力，它会稍微衰弱，然后会比以前更好地自我修复。给肌肉施加比它习惯的更重的重量，它就必须更加努力。哎哟。然而，让它定期进行这样的训练，它就会自我增强，从而轻松满足新的需求——只要它在训练之间得到足够的休息来修复和增强自身力量。这是一个循序渐进的过程：退一步，休息一下，再进两步。

So, besides an elixir for turning back the clock, what is the training effect? Building strength through stress. Philosopher Friedrich Nietzsche might have been thinking of the benefits we get from our workouts when he declared, “That which does not kill me makes me stronger.” Stress an organism and it breaks down a little, then builds itself up slightly better than before. Give a muscle a heavier weight to lift than it’s used to and it has to work harder. Ouch. Put it on a regular program of such work, however, and it builds itself up so it can meet that new demand easily—as long as it gets enough rest between workouts to repair and strengthen itself. It’s a ratcheting process: one step back, rest, two steps forward.

训练的起点并非像某些追求“好身材”的人误以为的那样，是镜子，而是心脏——一块我们可以像其他肌肉一样锻炼的肌肉。心脏所能做的工作量称为心输出量，即它在给定时间内能够循环的血液量。训练的目标是增加心输出量，这决定了你的肌肉能够做多少工作。

The starting point for training is not the mirror, as some people looking for “good bodies” mistakenly believe, but the heart—a muscle we can develop just like any other. The amount of work your heart can do is called cardiac output—the volume of blood it can circulate in a given period of time. The goal of training is to increase cardiac output, which determines how much work your muscles can do.

心输出量是心率（脉搏，或每分钟心跳次数 [BPM]）乘以每搏输出量（每次心跳可以泵出的血量）。通过规律的运动给心脏施加压力，它会像其他肌肉一样变得更大、更强壮。这会增加每搏输出量。随着心脏每次收缩泵出更多血液的能力增强，完成这项工作所需的收缩次数就会减少。因此，随着训练的进行，您可以更轻松地以相同的速度完成相同的工作（例如游一英里）（感觉更好），也可以像以前一样努力，但速度更快（表现更好）。曾经40分钟就能游一英里的努力，现在可能只需要35分钟。这是大多数人的选择。

Cardiac output is the product of heart rate (pulse, or beats per minute [BPM]) multiplied by stroke volume (the amount of blood it can pump with each beat). Stress the heart regularly through exercise and it will grow bigger and stronger just as other muscles do. This increases stroke volume. As your heart gets better able to pump more blood with each contraction, it takes fewer contractions to do the job. So as your training takes hold, you can either do the same work (like swimming a mile) at the same speed more easily (you feel better), or you can work just as hard as you used to but go faster (you do better). The same effort that once produced a 40-minute mile may now drive you through the mile in 35 minutes. That’s the choice most people make.

当然，其他肌肉也会对训练做出反应。它们学习如何更好地从血液中提取氧气来为自己提供能量，并排出废物，从而可能增大肌肉体积。

The other muscles, of course, also respond to training. They learn how to better extract oxygen from the blood to fuel themselves and flush out waste products, and they may increase their size.

几乎所有的训练都能锻炼心脏。但它循环的大部分血液都流向骨骼肌，而骨骼肌正是身体在跑道上或泳池中运动的真正动力来源。例如，由于游泳和跑步使用的肌肉群不同，游泳训练对肌肉的锻炼方式也与跑步不同。而且你不能仅仅通过增加训练量来解决这个问题，我每年都会被提醒这一点。如果我整个冬天都在雄心勃勃地备战春季的地区或全国大师赛，那么到四月份，我的状态就会达到最佳，可以游三英里快节奏的间歇跑——相当于跑十二英里。甚至不会出一滴汗。但大约在同一时间，我第一次春季跑步时，轻松跑完三英里就筋疲力尽了。心输出量充足；然而，跑步肌肉已经失去了有效利用这些心输出量的能力。但如果我坚持度过那个令人沮丧的阶段，几周之内我就会开始感觉更强壮——比我的心血管系统尚未处于“游泳状态”时要快得多。

The heart gets its training from most any workout. But most of the blood it circulates goes to the skeletal muscles doing the actual work of moving the body around the track or down the pool. Since swimming uses different muscle groups from running, for example, swim training builds you differently from running. And you can’t get around that by just pouring more work on, as I’m reminded every year. If I’ve spent all winter prepping ambitiously for a springtime Regional or National Masters championship, by April I’ll be in prime shape for swimming three miles of brisk interval repeats—the equivalent of twelve running miles. Won’t even break a sweat. But on my first spring run about the same time, I’m shot after three easy miles. Plenty of cardiac output; however, the running muscles have lost the ability to use it well. But if I persevere through that discouraging phase, within weeks I’ll begin to feel stronger—much more quickly than if my cardiovascular system wasn’t already in “swimming shape.”

这就是交叉训练的价值。

That’s the value of cross-training.

这也体现了针对性。例如，不要为了成为更好的游泳运动员而训练你的骑行肌肉。事实上，正如我在之前的章节中提到的，针对性的意义远不止将大部分训练内容缩小到你想擅长的运动项目上。你甚至可以在单项运动的不同时间使用专门的肌肉群，比如当你游不同的泳姿时。如果我进行自由泳训练，然后在蛙泳比赛中全力以赴，我可以肯定我的肌肉会在比赛中途开始停止工作。蛙泳肌肉还没有达到比赛状态。尽管我游泳很多，但它们并没有经过专门的训练。

That’s also a lesson in specificity. For example, don’t train your cycling muscles to become a better swimmer. In fact, as I mentioned in an earlier chapter, specificity goes even deeper than just narrowing most of your training to the sport you want to excel at. You even use specialized muscle groups at different times within that single sport, such as when you swim different strokes. If I train with freestyle sets, then race breaststroke with all I’ve got, I can count on my muscles starting to shut down midway through the event. The breaststroke muscles aren’t in racing shape. As much swimming as I’ve done, they haven’t been specifically trained.

最后，即使你每次都训练正确的肌肉，它们对不同训练强度的反应也会有所不同。有氧训练（含氧）是指肌肉燃烧燃料产生能量，并且可以持续很长时间。还有无氧训练（不含氧），这种训练强度更高，依赖于一种储存的肌肉燃料，这种燃料不需要氧气，但供应总是有限的，很容易让你感到疲劳。

And finally, even if you train exactly the right muscles every single time, they respond differently to different workout intensities. There’s aerobic (with oxygen) training, where the muscles burn fuel to produce energy and can go on doing that for a long time. And there’s anaerobic (without oxygen) training, which is more intense, relies on a kind of stored muscle fuel that doesn’t require oxygen but that’s always in limited supply, and makes you tired quickly.

有氧健身和无氧健身不仅由不同的能量来源提供能量，而且它们的能量消耗时间也不同。有氧能量来源提供能量的速度适中，但持续时间较长，正如我们所说。这有助于提高耐力。无氧能量来源提供能量的速度更快，非常适合爆发式速度训练，但很快就会耗尽。这就像有两个油箱，一个装了很大的阀门，另一个装了很小的阀门。巨大的阀门可以为同样巨大的八缸发动机提供动力——但不会持续太久。油箱很快就会空。小阀门或许只能驱动一台不起眼的四缸发动机，但足以让它全天运转。

Aerobic and anaerobic fitness are not only powered by different energy sources, they are used at different times. The aerobic source provides energy at moderate rates, but for a long time, as we said. This promotes endurance. The anaerobic source provides energy faster, perfect for bursts of speed, but the well goes dry quickly. It’s like having two fuel tanks, one with a huge valve and one with a tiny one. The huge valve will power an equally huge eight-cylinder engine—but not for long. The tank empties quickly. The small valve may run only a meager four-cylinder engine but will keep it going all day long.

如果你喜欢快速游泳，尤其是在比赛时，训练的挑战就是确保无氧燃料箱充满。即使你每天游10000码，你的“另一个燃料箱”里仍然只剩下一点点油。唯一的补充方法就是无氧训练。

If you like to swim fast, and especially if you race, the training challenge is to make sure the anaerobic fuel tank is topped off. You could swim 10,000 aerobic yards a day and still have little but fumes in that other tank. The only way to fill it is anaerobic training.

说起来容易，做起来难。无氧训练很痛苦！而且，你的无氧训练越多，你的肺部燃烧得越厉害，你的胸腔就越沉重，你的肌肉就越抽痛。这就是为什么它很容易被一再推迟。但如果你想参加比赛——而不是仅仅为了塑形——你就不能只靠有氧健身。

Easy to say, not so easy to do. Anaerobic hurts! And the more anaerobic your training is, the more your lungs burn, your chest pounds, and your muscles throb. That’s why it’s so easy to put off over and over again. But if you want to race—as opposed to just get in shape—you can’t make it purely on aerobic fitness.

比赛距离越短，无氧代谢就越旺盛。50码的比赛可能需要30到40秒，大约90%的能量来自无氧燃料箱。但在通常需要20到30分钟的英里比赛中，超过90%的能量将来自有氧燃料箱。

The shorter the race, the more anaerobic it will be. In a race of 50 yards, which might take between 30 and 40 seconds, about 90 percent of your energy comes from the anaerobic fuel tank. But in the mile race, which usually takes between 20 and 30 minutes, more than 90 percent of the energy will come from your aerobic tank.

方便的是，你应该为每项赛事进行训练的方式和你比赛的方式一样。耐力训练（组数更长、休息时间更短、节奏更轻松）可以锻炼“呼吸”能力。短跑训练（组数更短、休息时间更长、节奏更快）可以锻炼“速度”能力，因为它让你游得足够快、足够用力，让你的肌肉发出“呼啸”的呼喊，需要更多的氧气。如果它们需要“呼啸”得足够频繁，最终就能学会从血液中获取更多的氧气。

Conveniently, the way you should train for each event is much the same as the way you race it. Endurance training (longer sets, shorter rest, easier pace) develops the “wind” tank. Sprint training (shorter sets, longer rest, faster pace) develops the “speed” tank by making you swim fast enough and hard enough so your muscles scream for more oxygen. If they have to scream often enough, they eventually learn to extract more oxygen from the blood.

这被称为更高的最大摄氧量（经验丰富的运动员行话叫VO2max ），但这并非超越有氧/无氧速度的唯一方法。另一种方法是——我相信你现在应该不会感到惊讶——更好的划水姿势。由于游泳速度的70%来自于划水姿势，这一点我当然会不厌其烦地强调，良好的划水姿势能让你无需做太多功或消耗更多能量就能达到更高的速度。经济地游泳，用流畅平衡的身体最大限度地减少阻力，你就能自然而然地在跨越可怕的无氧阈值之前游得更快。

That’s called higher maximal oxygen uptake (the VO2max of seasoned athlete’s lingo), but it’s not the only way to skin the aerobic/anaerobic speed cat. The other way is—no surprise to you by now, I’m sure—a better stroke. Since 70 percent of your swim speed comes from your stroke, as I obviously never tire of saying, great stroke mechanics let you reach much higher speeds without doing much more work or using more fuel. Swim economically, minimizing drag with a sleek and balanced body, and you’ll automatically be able to go faster before crossing the dreaded anaerobic threshold.

可是，如果你训练的方式和比赛的方式不一样，会发生什么呢？难道这两种训练方式真的足够接近，能够取得不错的成绩吗？不，并非如此。我自己也经历过痛苦的教训。

Still, what happens if you train one way and race another? Aren’t the two really close enough to give decent results? No, they’re not. I learned that myself the hard way.

1992年，在备战大师世界锦标赛5公里（3.1英里）比赛时，我理所当然地采用了长组训练、短休息的训练方式。毕竟，一场持续一个多小时的比赛，大概只有一两成的能量来自无氧系统。何必费心训练呢？

In 1992, getting ready for the 5-kilometer (3.1-mile) race in the Masters World Championships, I logically used long sets on very short rest for my training. After all, a race lasting over an hour would probably draw maybe a percent or two of its energy from the anaerobic system. Why bother training it?

但我却迫不及待地想利用这些训练成果做点什么。所以，早在大赛开始前，我就参加了一场当地的大师赛。100码自由泳是我的第一项比赛，我自信地冲上起跑线，因为高强度、短休息的训练让我保持了大学以来的最佳状态，所以今天会是非常棒的一天。

But I was getting antsy to do something with all this conditioning. So, long before the big race, I entered a local Masters meet. The 100-yard freestyle was my first event, and I mounted the block confident that since my high-volume/short-rest training sessions had me in the best shape since college, this would be a very good day.

一开始确实如此。一开始我一头扎进去，奋力游完了前50码。但当我转过第二个弯时，感觉不对劲。我怎么可能累呢！已经累了吗？

At first, it was. At the start I dove in and swam strongly through the first 50 yards. But as I came off that second turn, something was wrong. I couldn’t possibly be tired! Already?

哦，是的，我可以。到了75码的转弯处，我的肌肉已经僵硬得打结了，感觉就像穿了件大衣而不是Speedo泳裤。我费力地完成了那场短暂的比赛，这让我有充分的理由反思，如果至少进行一点速度训练该有多好。我的有氧状态可能非常好，但厌氧池早已干涸了。

Oh yes, I could. By the time I came to the 75-yard turn, my muscles were tying up into knots and I felt as if I were wearing an overcoat instead of my Speedo. My struggle to finish that brief race gave me plenty of reason to reflect on how nice it would have been to have done at least a little speed training. I may have been in fantastic aerobic shape, but the anaerobic tank was long dry.

那么你的训练目的是什么？

So What Are You Training For?

如果你不知道自己训练的初衷，就无法充分利用训练时间。你想拥有健康的身体吗？想在水中游得更顺畅？想练就更强壮的体魄？想赢得比赛？这些都是你踏入泳池的充分理由，而且都需要不同的准备工作。

You can’t make the most of your training time if you don’t know why you’re training in the first place. Do you want to be fit and healthy? Become smoother in the water? Build a more powerful body? Win races? They’re all good reasons for getting into the pool, and they all take different kinds of preparation.

当然，在我刚当教练的时候，主要受自身游泳经历的影响，我对这些一无所知。其他人也一样。我们对训练的目标只有一个既定的理念：坚持不懈，直到成为一名成功的运动员。如果你能一直保持压力，直到隔壁泳道的选手突破，你就赢了。所以教练的工作很简单：保持压力，不断加大难度，不断提升每个人对痛苦的承受力。

Of course, in my earliest days as a coach, influenced mainly by my own experiences as a swimmer, I knew none of that. No one else knew it either. We had a tried-and-true notion of what training sessions were supposed to accomplish: grind it out until you became a successful racer. If you could just keep the pressure on until the guy in the next lane broke, you won. So the coach’s job was simple. Keep the pressure on, keep making it harder, keep increasing everyone’s tolerance for misery.

然而，我与游泳运动员合作的时间越长，我就越明白真正的训练难题实际上有多么复杂，肌肉需要休息才能恢复，因为休息是它们重建的时间，而且训练神经系统使其更高效地运作远比折磨身体更有效。突然之间，训练变成了各种各样的选择，任何人都可以参与。你不再需要二十多岁就成为大学运动员才能被视为“在训练”，也不必每天都拼命训练才能达到目标。因为你的目标可以是以下任何一项：

The longer I worked with swimmers, though, the more I understood how complex the real training puzzle actually is, how desperately muscles need rest to improve since that’s when they do their rebuilding, and how training the nervous system to swim more economically is far more useful than beating up the body anyway. Suddenly, training split into a whole range of choices anyone could fit into. You no longer had to be a college jock in your twenties to be considered “in training,” and you didn’t have to destroy yourself every day to get where you were going. Because you could be working toward any of the following:

基础健身：你的目标仅仅是享受有氧健身，感觉强壮健康，精力充沛地度过每一天吗？每周进行三到四次，每次30到40分钟的游泳训练就能达到这个目标。除非你正在备战游泳比赛，否则基本的低强度训练组就能满足你的所有需求。如果你只是在其他运动项目进行高强度训练后休息一下，那么这种训练就能满足你对肌肉放松的需求。

BASIC FITNESS: Is your goal to simply enjoy aerobic fitness, to feel strong and healthy with plenty of energy to get through the day? You can achieve that with regular 30- to 40-minute swim workouts, three or four times a week. Unless you’re gearing up for a swimming race, basic low-intensity sets will give you everything you want. And if your swimming is a break from hard training in another sport, you’ll get all the muscle soothing you need from this kind of workout.

训练体能：填写比赛报名表时，无论你是否意识到，基本的体能已经远远不够了。无论你最终计划参加一场轻松的大师赛、一场艰苦的公开水域游泳，还是第一次参加铁人三项比赛，你的训练计划都需要更有针对性。训练体能指的是应对高难度和高强度训练的能力。

TRAINING FITNESS: Fill out a race entry form, and whether you know it or not, basic fitness is no longer enough. No matter whether you plan to eventually suit up for a casual Masters meet, tough open-water swim, or first triathlon, your training program needs to become more ambitious. Training fitness is the ability to handle difficult and demanding workouts.

在真正做好比赛准备之前，你必须先达到训练体能。你必须做好准备，为比赛训练打下基础，而不是一头扎进去。成功的训练是循序渐进的一系列小调整，而不是突然超负荷，让你筋疲力尽。你需要慢慢地“加大训练量”，增加组数、延长训练时间，以及更频繁的训练。你还需要提高训练强度。也需要进行一些我在本章前面提到的无氧训练。你参加的比赛越长——从一分钟左右的100码自由泳，到三个多小时的奥运铁人三项——你对身体的准备要求就越高。你不可能一夜之间就从每周训练两小时变成每天训练两小时。

Training fitness is what you have to achieve before actually getting yourself race-ready. You must prepare to prepare, laying the groundwork for your race training, not just plunging into it. Successful training is a gradual series of small adaptations instead of a sudden overload that puts you down for the count. You’ll need to slowly “turn up the volume” with longer sets, longer workouts, and probably more frequent training sessions. And you’re going to have to turn up the intensity too, with some of that anaerobic work I spoke of earlier in the chapter. The longer the event you’re entering—from the minute or so of a creditable 100-yard freestyle to the three-hours-plus of an Olympic-distance triathlon—the more you’ll ask of your body getting ready. You don’t go overnight from training two hours a week to as much as two hours a day.

竞速健身：比赛和训练完全不同。我们大多数人比赛时都会全力以赴（毕竟这是比赛！），但我们训练时的速度会比较轻松。

RACING FITNESS: Races are simply different from workouts. Most of us go all out when we race (after all, it’s a race!), but we train at a less punishing pace.

从技术层面上讲，需要澄清的是，“竞赛体能”根本不存在，因为它太宽泛了，没有任何实际意义。你需要的体能不仅仅是比赛，还包括100码自由泳、200码蛙泳或400码个人混合泳。如果你还没有让你的身体做好准备，以应对你即将参加的具体比赛项目，那么它就无法胜任这项任务。

Technically, to set the record straight, there is no such thing as “racing fitness” because it’s too broad a term to have any meaning. What you need to be fit for is not just a race but a 100-yard freestyle, or 200 breaststroke or 400 individual medley. If you haven’t prepared your body for how—and how hard—it will work in the specific event you’re entering, it won’t be up to the task.

这条规则很容易被忘记。还记得我那场臭名昭著的比赛吗？几个月来，我把自己打造成了一台强大的有氧机器，为3.1英里（5000米）公开水域比赛（一个多小时）的稳定而快速的冲刺做好准备。但在那场重要的比赛几个月前，我却在100码自由泳比赛中掉线了，这应该只需要58秒。然而，在我最终的60多秒的考验中，不到一半就出现了肌肉叛变，这提醒我，如果你的训练不能在某个时刻达到比赛所需的氧气量，你的身体就会反抗你。它喜欢熟悉的感觉，而不是惊喜。

This is an easy rule to forget. Remember my own minute of race infamy? I’d turned myself into one mean aerobic machine over months of prepping for the steady and brisk clip of a one-hour-plus open-water race of 3.1 miles (5000 meters). But several months before the big one, I dropped into that 100-yard freestyle event which should have taken me about 58 seconds. Instead, the muscle mutiny that struck barely halfway through my ultimate 60-seconds-plus ordeal was a humbling reminder that if your training doesn’t at some point duplicate the oxygen demands of your race, your body will simply turn on you. It likes familiarity, not surprises.

如果你参加不同距离的比赛，不可能专注于所有距离，那么就决定哪一个对你来说最重要，然后集中精力主要还是靠这个。剩下的就只能靠自己了。即使是教练也没有灵丹妙药。我最擅长的比赛是英里跑，但偶尔也忍不住要来个短跑。所以我会进行足够的有氧训练，争取跑出不错的英里成绩，同时也会挤出时间进行足够的无氧训练，这样至少我的百米跑成绩不会让人尴尬。

If you compete at different distances and can’t possibly specialize in all of them, just decide which one means the most to you and focus mainly on that. The rest will have to take care of themselves. Even coaches have no magic solution to this. My best race is the mile, but I can’t resist a sprint now and then. So I do enough aerobic training to turn in decent mile times and squeeze in enough anaerobic work so at least my 100s aren’t embarrassing.

致胜体能：通过打造竞赛体能，保持“满载而归”的状态，让你能够顺利完成比赛，高高兴兴地回家。在此基础上，再加之力量和速度，则能让你顺利完成比赛，最终登上领奖台领取奖牌。不过，游泳运动中力量和速度的获取方式与其他运动略有不同。

WINNING FITNESS: “Full tanks” from building racing fitness let you finish your event and go home happy. Putting power and speed on top of that lets you finish your event and go up to the awards stand for your medal. But power and speed are achieved a little differently in swimming than they are in other sports.

这就是为什么有些教练称游泳为“力量受限”的运动。速度越快，阻力就越大。速度加倍，水的阻力就会加倍。所以，如果你想快速游动，你需要足够的力量。但你不能仅仅去力量训练室就能练出这种力量，因为它必须完全遵循你的划水规律——甚至速度也要一致。再次强调，这是“特异性”。

That’s one reason some coaches call swimming a power-limited activity. Drag increases exponentially as you speed up. Go twice as fast, the water fights you four times as hard. So you need plenty of power if you want to move quickly. But you can’t just go to the weight room to build this kind of power, because it has to follow the exact pattern of your stroke—and even be at the same speed. Specificity again.

游泳运动员必须通过超短、超快的重复训练来建立这种能力，这样他们的肌肉才能学会调动所有可用的肌纤维来参与这项运动。由于高速等于高阻力，这有助于肌肉建立比赛所需的力量。这就像在健身房里把最重的杠铃片放在杠铃上，只不过你只能在泳池里做。

Swimmers must build this with ultrashort, ultrafast repeats so their muscles learn to throw every available fiber into the job. Since high speed equals high resistance, that’s what helps the muscles build the power you’ll need them to deliver in a race. It’s like loading the heaviest plate on the bar in the weight room, only you get to do it in the pool.

“超短”也不是比喻。短跑运动员在12码的短距离内进行全力力量训练，很少超过25码，尽管他们有时会用管子和桨来增加比水流冲击更大的阻力。长距离选手只需游得更快就能积累所需的力量。比他们的比赛速度更快。计算起来并不复杂。假设你在1500米比赛中平均每100米游1分20秒（相当于20分钟的完成时间）。以1分10秒完成100米循环——甚至以0分35秒完成50米循环——将提高你在1500米比赛中的游泳能力。

“Ultrashort” is no figure of speech either. Sprinters do their all-out power training in lengths as short as 12 yards and seldom go more than 25, though they sometimes pile on even more drag than the water throws at them by using tubes and paddles. Longer-distance competitors build the kind of power they need just by swimming faster than their race pace. The math is not complicated. Let’s say you average 1:20 per 100 meters in a 1500-meter race (equals a 20-minute finishing time). Doing 100-meter repeats in 1:10—or even 50-meter repeats in 0:35—will improve your swimming power for the 1500.

当然，力量并不等同于速度，正如我在本书前面所解释的那样。如果一名实力强劲的游泳运动员效率平平，那么他仍然只能算是中游选手。还记得亚历山大·波波夫吗？他可能是世界上最伟大的游泳运动员。他之所以能赢得比赛，是因为即使在最高速度下，他的划水时间也比其他任何人都要长。当你慢速移动时这已经够难的了，当你冲刺时则几乎不可能。一英里的典型划水频率约为每分钟 70 次。在 100 米比赛中，它可以飙升到 110。而且，由于每次划水的距离（划水长度）会随着你每分钟的划水次数（划水频率）的微小增加而迅速下降，所以你很容易开始原地踏步而不是加速。所以，不要认为开始你的比赛生涯最容易的地方可能是一段短暂而美好的时光。 （200到500码的比赛或许能提供最佳的平衡，既能满足必要的训练准备，又能让你通过练习本书中教授的智能游泳策略取得好成绩。）成功的短跑运动员会投入大量时间，耐心地训练肌肉，不仅要快速，还要游得长、流畅。学得最好的肌肉才能获胜。

Power, of course, is not speed, as I explained earlier in this book. A powerful swimmer with lackluster efficiency will remain a powerful swimmer stuck in the middle of the pack. Remember Alexander Popov, possibly the world’s greatest competitor? He wins races because his stroke stays longer than anyone else’s, even at top speed. Hard enough when you’re moving slowly, almost impossible as you sprint. A typical stroke rate in the mile is about 70 per minute. In the 100-meter, it can zoom to 110. And since the distance you travel with each stroke (stroke length) falls off rapidly with even small increases in the number you take per minute (stroke rate), it’s easy to start spinning your wheels instead of speeding up. So don’t think the most forgiving place to launch your racing career is probably something nice and short. (A race of 200 to 500 yards probably offers the best balance between necessary training preparation and a race duration that allows you to do well by practicing the smart-swimming strategies we teach in this book.) Successful sprinters invest a lot of time in patiently teaching their muscles how to move not just fast but long and smooth too. The muscles that learn best win.

无论你处于训练金字塔的哪个位置，或许还在打基础，或许已经爬到顶端，正在磨练力量和速度，你都会面临一个不可避免的问题：“我下一步能做到多少？”大多数没有教练指导的运动员会认为他们深谙训练的秘诀：“如果一些训练是好的，那么更多的训练肯定更好。所以我会尽我所能，尽快地进行训练。”而在这项相对不易受伤的运动中，他们或许可以侥幸逃脱。

No matter where you are on the training pyramid, perhaps putting down your base or already way up at the top and sharpening your power and speed, the inevitable question is, “How much can I do next?” Most athletes without a coach to hold them on course think they know the secret principle of training: “If some is good, more must be better. So I’ll do as much as I can, just as soon as I can.” And in this comparatively injury-free sport, they may get away with it.

但这并非通往成功的必经之路。循序渐进——通过逐渐要求身体做更多事情来增强体能——是有效训练最重要的基本原则之一（参见第167页“简化训练”）。但在游泳方面，由于你的成功很大程度上来自于技术上的提升，而非身体上的进步，因此需要采取一些不同的方法。

But it’s not the path to success. Progression—strengthening your body by gradually asking it to do more—is one of the most important fundamentals of effective training (see “Training Made Simple” page 167). But in swimming, with so much of your success coming from technical improvements instead of physical ones, it needs to be handled a little differently.

传统的进步是这样的：由于肌肉只有在被要求做比以往更多的事情时才会持续适应，所以我可以用10磅的重量做我想做的所有二头肌弯举，我的肌肉会变得非常擅长。但是，除非我强迫它们，否则它们无法举起15磅的重物。同样，如果你每天以35分钟的速度游一英里，你的生理机能就会完美地适应这种特定速度的能量需求。就是这样。要想有任何提高，你必须增加训练负荷，要么增加训练量（游泳超过一英里），要么以更高的速度训练（通常将一英里分成更短、更快的几段），要么减少重复训练之间的休息间隔。

Conventional progression goes like this: Since a muscle continues to adapt only so long as it’s asked to do more than it’s used to, I can do all the biceps curls I want with a 10-pound weight and my muscles will get very good at that. But they won’t be able to lift 15 pounds until I push them. Similarly, if you swim a 35-minute mile every day, your physiology becomes perfectly adapted to the energy requirements for that specific speed. Period. To improve in any way, you must raise the training load either by increasing the volume (swimming more than a mile) or training at higher speeds (usually by breaking the mile into shorter, faster pieces) or decreasing the rest interval between repeats.
