聪明的游泳者需要知道如何以及何时控制进步。在力量训练室里，进步可能等于进步，但在水中并非总是如此。能够不断游得更远或更快的兴奋感必须被这样的认知所抵消：在大多数情况下，你可能正在牺牲自己的体型来证明自己在进步。如果真是这样，那你就没有进步。你在体能上获得的任何提升，都被效率更低的划水动作所抵消。我再怎么强调也不为过：要想游得比你想象的更好，请遵循我们在我的训练营和本书中教授的方法。它们以建立高效的划水习惯为基础，然后以你能承受的速度增加训练量或强度，同时不影响效率。

The smart swimmer needs to know how and when to rein in progression. In the weight room progression might equal progress, but that’s not always true in the water. The thrill of being able to constantly swim farther or faster must be tempered by the knowledge that, in most cases, you’re probably sacrificing your form to prove that you’re progressing. If that’s true, you’re not. Whatever you’re gaining in fitness is being taken away by the cost of a less effective stroke. I can’t say it often enough: To swim better than you ever thought you could, follow the method we teach in my camps and in this book. They’re based on establishing efficient stroke habits as a foundation, then adding volume or intensity only as quickly as you can handle them with no loss of efficiency.

如果这实际上需要更多的耐心和毅力，而不是像以前那样，每两次训练都多游几圈，请不要感到惊讶。为了提高一英里游泳成绩，您的挑战是只增加您可以以与最佳圈数（通常是前几圈）相同的效率（划水次数）完成的圈数或次数。一种方法是将一组 100 码的重复次数增加到 15 次，或者保持重复次数为 10 次，但将每次重复增加到 150 码，同时保持相同的平均划水次数。另一种技巧是保持组内总码数相同，但将重复次数之间的间隔从 30 秒减少到 15 秒，同时不降低任何效率。

Don’t be surprised if it actually takes more patience and persistence than just throwing a few more laps into the mix every workout or two, as you probably used to do. To beef up your mile swim, your challenge is to add only laps or repetitions you can do with the same efficiency (stroke count) as your best laps, usually your first few. One way is to increase a set of 10 repetitions of 100 yards to 15 repetitions, or keep the number of repetitions at 10 but increase each repeat to 150 yards, while holding the same average stroke count. Another technique is to keep the total yardage of your set the same but cut the rest between reps from 30 seconds to 15, without giving up any efficiency.

对于短距离游泳运动员来说，数字方面的问题就稍微复杂一些。如果你在40秒内游完50码自由泳，每划30次，你能在38秒内游完30次吗？或者假设当你加速到35秒时，你的划水次数增加了4次。你能找到办法保持这个速度，但只多划2次吗？你在和水做交易，你想确保自己总是赢。有效地用划水换取速度，正是亚历山大·波波夫和他之前的马特·比昂迪成为他那个时代最具统治力的游泳运动员的原因。

For shorter-distance swimmers, the numbers are just a little more involved. If you do 50 yards freestyle in 40 seconds and 30 strokes, can you do it in 38 seconds and 30 strokes? Or let’s say your count goes up by four strokes when you speed up to 35 seconds. Can you find a way to hold that speed but have it cost you only two additional strokes? You’re making bargains with the water, and you want to make sure you always win. Effective trading of strokes for speed is what made Alexander Popov the most dominant swimmer of his time, and Matt Biondi before him.

因此结果显然是值得的。

So the results are clearly worth it.

让培训变得简单

Training Made Simple

游泳或其他耐力运动健身的基本知识

The Basic Facts of Getting Fit for Swimming or Any Other Endurance Sport

1. 压力：压力并非指发现支票被拒付或与脾气暴躁的老板发生冲突而产生的压力。在训练中，压力仅仅意味着施加于身体的负荷。谨慎而有选择地施加压力，会引发积极的反应：身体会变得更强壮。但如果负荷过重，身体就无法适应。结果就是：受伤、疲惫、沮丧。

1. Stress: Not the kind caused by discovering a bounced check or having a run-in with your abrasive boss. In training, stress simply means a workload imposed on the body. Carefully and selectively applied, it elicits a positive response: The body grows stronger. But if the workload is too heavy, the body can’t adapt. The result: injury, exhaustion, frustration.

 

 

2. 渐进式超负荷：随着身体对训练的反应增强，增肌速度会越来越慢。因此，我们需要增加负荷，前提是要明智且系统地进行。更高的频率或更高的强度——或者两者兼而有之——都能刺激身体进步。在你训练的第一个月（甚至第一年）里，合适的训练负荷可能太小，无法让你在第三个月（甚至第一年）获得更大的进步。

2. Progressive Overload: As the body grows stronger in response to training, gains come more slowly. So we need to increase the load, as long as we do it judiciously and systematically. More frequency or more intensity—or both—stimulate the body to improve. The right training overload for your first month (or even year) of training probably will be too little to build you up more by the time the third month (or year) comes along.

 

 

3. 针对性：身体会适应施加的特定压力。因此，你的训练应该在类型、距离和强度上尽可能地与你正在准备的活动相匹配。

3. Specificity: The body adapts to the specific stress imposed. So your training should be as much as possible like the activity you’re preparing for in type, distance, and intensity.

 

 

4. 坚持：即使你每天只能抽出30分钟进行训练，只要坚持锻炼，你仍然可以获得相当好的健身效果。生理学家告诉我们，我们每天至少需要训练3分钟每周最多四天，全年无休，才能保持基本体能。（显然，更佳的体能需要更多训练。）体能很容易在几周的空闲时间里就消失殆尽，而且恢复所需的时间总是比失去时更长。所以，当你的训练时间即将完全枯竭时，请记住，即使只是一点点，也比完全没有要好得多。

4. Consistency: Even if you can spare as little as thirty minutes a day for training, you can still achieve reasonably good fitness by being regular about it. Physiologists tell us that we need to train at least three to four days a week, year-round, to maintain basic fitness. (More fitness obviously takes more work.) Fitness can be easily lost in a few idle weeks, and it always takes longer to regain than it did to lose. So during a period when your training time threatens to dry up altogether, remember that even a little is far better than none at all.

 

 

5. 进阶：你越接近攀登的顶峰，山势就越陡峭。你进步越大，保持同样的速度进步就越困难。只需适度的努力，你就能发挥出90%的潜力，而之后即使是微小的进步也得不偿失。当你达到那个阶段时，明智的做法是增强体质，而不是强化。精益求精。游得更聪明，而不是更卖力。好消息是：你已经赢得的健身场地将相对容易守住。

5. Progression: The nearer you get to the top of the mountain you’re trying to climb, the steeper it grows. The more you improve, the harder it becomes to keep improving at the same rate. You’ll reach 90 percent of your potential with a moderate amount of effort, and beyond that even small gains will come grudgingly. When you reach that point, you’re smarter to buff, not build. Polish technique. Swim smarter, not harder. The good news: The fitness ground you’ve already won will be relatively easy to hold.

 

 

6. 恢复：工作和休息如同阴阳，是同一个等式中不可分割的两个部分。你需要从高强度训练中恢复，让你的身体适应并成功应对更高的训练负荷——无论是在一组训练、一次训练还是一个训练周期中。除非你的心率在两次训练之间恢复到接近静息水平，否则你不可能在一段时间内反复将心率推到接近最大值。同样，高强度训练也必须与恢复性训练保持平衡。

6. Recovery: Work and rest are yin and yang, inseparable halves of the same equation. You need to recuperate from hard training, to allow your body to adapt and successfully handle harder workloads— during a set, a workout, or a training cycle. You can’t push your heart rate near its maximum in a set time and again unless it recovers nearly back to its resting level between efforts. Similarly, intense workouts must be balanced with recovery workouts.

现在来谈谈完全不同的事情

And Now for Something Completely Different

（中风，其他三种，以及它们对你的好处）

(Strokes, That Is. The Other Three, and the Good They Can Do You)

这或许会让那些以里程为重的骑行者和跑步者感到惊讶，但游泳运动员也可能像其他人一样痴迷于距离。而这种痴迷对他们来说同样有害。

It may surprise mileage-based athletes like cyclists and runners, but swimmers can be as obsessed with distance as anybody else. And the obsession is just as bad for them.

“可我只有45分钟的训练时间，仅此而已，”时间紧迫的运动员们抱怨道，我警告他们，如果他们能打破惯常的训练模式，开始尝试更多不同的训练方式，效果会更好。“如果我把其他事情都安排进去，我就无法积累保持体形所需的训练距离了。”

“But I have forty-five minutes to work out, period,” time-pressed athletes grumble when I warn them they’d be better off if they left their comfortable workout ruts and started using more variety. “If I try to fit in all that other stuff, I won’t be able to rack up the yardage I need to stay in shape.”

但他们可以，他们的身体也知道这一点——只是他们的大脑还需要进一步证实。大多数人在泳池里训练的肌肉量是现在的两到三倍，而且无论他们投入多少时间，都能从锻炼中获得同样多的锻炼效果。

But they can, and their bodies know it—only their brains still need convincing. Most people can train two to three times as many muscles in the pool as they do now, in whatever time they have to spend, and get just as much conditioning from their workout.

在45分钟内，一位意志坚定的游泳者可以游完2000到2500码的自由泳。由于这是最快、最轻松的泳姿，因此总成绩最令人满意。如果混合其他泳姿，可能会让这个令人欣慰的数字少几百码。游泳者们和其他人一样，相信距离的神奇力量可以衡量“良好”的体能训练。距离越远，身体素质就越好。

In 45 minutes, a determined swimmer can cover 2000 to 2500 yards of freestyle. Since it’s the fastest and easiest stroke, it gives the most satisfying total. Mixing in other strokes could chop that comforting number by several hundred yards, and swimmers believe as much as anyone else in the magical power of distance to measure a “good” physical workout. Farther equals fitter.

只是你最关注的肌肉并不知道这一点：心脏不理解也不关心你游了什么泳姿，也不关心你在游多少码。它只知道两件事——如何它的效果有多强，持续了多久？让我们比较一下两种不同的20分钟锻炼方式对心脏健康的影响。

Except that the muscle you’re targeting the most doesn’t know that: The heart doesn’t understand or care what strokes you’re swimming or how many yards you write in your log. It knows only two things—how hard it has worked and for how long. So let’s compare the heart-health effect of two different 20-minute workout sets.

第一组： 1000码自由泳（每组100码，重复10次），每2分钟出发一次。约翰是一位56岁的大师级游泳运动员，他每组平均游1分35秒，心率保持在120左右。

Set #1: 1000 yards freestyle (10 repeats of 100 yards), leaving every 2 minutes. John, a fifty-six-year-old Masters swimmer, averages 1:35 for each repeat of the set and keeps his heart rate around 120.

第二组：后来，约翰决定游一组20分钟的个人混合泳（四种泳姿全部用到），但现在他只能在同样的时间内完成8组100码的游程，因为他必须将游程间隔增加到每100码2分30秒（游泳2分钟，休息30秒）。他的心率仍然保持在120次/分左右。

Set #2: Later John decides to swim a 20-minute individual medley set (all four strokes), but now he can complete only eight repeats of 100 yards in the same time, since he has to increase his interval to 2 minutes 30 seconds per 100 yards (2 minutes swimming, 30 seconds rest). Once again his heart rate stays around 120 BPM.

他在第二组比赛中丢掉了20%的码数，这有什么损失呢？当然，这损失的不是体能。在第一组和第二组比赛中，他的心脏跳动了大约2400次。它根本不在乎它所服务的身体游了多远。对于坚持低强度训练（最大心率的60%到75%）的健身游泳者和交叉训练者来说，情况尤其如此。

What did he lose by dropping 20 percent of his yardage on the second set? No fitness, certainly. His heart pumped about 2,400 times in #1 and #2. It didn’t care how far the body it was servicing traveled. And that would be especially true of the lower-intensity workout levels (60 percent to 75 percent of MHR [maximum heart rate]) fitness swimmers and cross-trainers stay on.

更好的是，即使游码数减少，你的体型也能变得更好。秘诀很简单：多样化。心脏可能不在乎你用哪种泳姿，但你的肌肉非常在意。自由泳、蝶泳、蛙泳和仰泳这四种泳姿，不同的肌肉群负责锻炼，因为这些泳姿本身就有很大不同。一套自由泳动作能锻炼你的自由泳肌肉，但会忽略其他肌肉。想要锻炼到最多的肌肉组织？那就游完所有泳姿。你将获得交叉训练的双重好处：更好的体能，更少的受伤几率。

Better yet, you can actually get in better shape even as your yardage goes down. The secret is simple: variety. The heart may not care whether you’re swimming one stroke or another, but your muscles care very much. Different muscle groups do the work in each of the four swimming strokes—freestyle, butterfly, breast, and back—because the strokes themselves are so different. A freestyle set helps your freestyle muscles but neglects others. Want to work the greatest amount of muscle tissue? Swim all the strokes. You’ll be getting the classic double-barreled benefit of cross-training: better conditioning with less chance of injury.

 

 

7. 周期：稳定的“次极量”训练就像把钱存入银行，建立我们的基础，保障我们的安全。我们用高强度训练的需要来开支票。开太多支票，你很快就会破产，你的身体会反抗，根本不会适应（参见第175页）。训练速度越快、强度越大，你就越快收到身体“资金不足”的通知。这适用于个人训练，也适用于以月为单位或以年为单位的训练周期。成年游泳者尤其应该记住：你的“职业生涯”可以用四分之一世纪甚至半个世纪来衡量，这确实令人羡慕。如果你主要追求的是健康和快乐，那么稳定的低压力训练将使你远离伤病，保持身体活力，并为长期训练做好准备，周复一周，年复一年。

7. Cycles: Steady, “submaximal” training is like putting money in the bank, establishing our base, our security. We write checks on that account with the demands of intensive training. Write too many and you’ll soon be bankrupt, your body will rebel and simply refuse to adapt (see page 175). And the faster and harder you train, the sooner you’ll get your body’s “insufficient funds” notice. This applies to individual workouts as well as training cycles of months and years. Adult swimmers especially should remember: Your “careers” may be measured in quarter- or even half-centuries, enviable to be sure. If you mainly want health and happiness, steady low-stress training will keep you injury-free, physically fresh, and fit for the long haul, week in and week out, year in and year out.

10

10

轻松游泳（为什么慢游能让你游得更快）

No-Sweat Swimming (Why Going Slow Will Get You There Faster)

让我们放慢速度。尽管我们在上一章讨论了大量的快速训练，但速度并非游泳的关键。事实上，有时速度甚至不是一个好主意，实际上弊大于利。按照我教游泳的方式，如果没有相当多的慢速——我更喜欢称之为有效——游泳练习，你就无法真正精通游泳。

Let’s slow down for just a minute. Despite all our talk in the last chapter about fast training, speed isn’t everything when it comes to swimming well. There are times, in fact, when it’s not even a very good idea and can actually do you more harm than good. The way I teach swimming, you can’t become really proficient without a fair amount of slow—I prefer to call it effective —swimming.

这引起你的注意了吗？确实如此。这不仅是个好消息，而且恰好是正确的，尽管正如我在上一章所说，如果你想在比赛中发挥出自己的极限，有时需要让自己喘口气来补充无氧能量。此外，正如我们将在下一章中看到的，你必须愿意一只眼睛盯着时钟，另一只眼睛盯着泳道线。但在完全沉浸式系统中，没有什么比以能够让你有效划水和高效移动的节奏进行仔细、周到的练习更有益于你的划水。学会做到这一点，速度自然会更快。

Does that get your attention? It should. It’s not only good news, it happens to be correct despite the fact that, as I said in the last chapter, you sometimes need to get yourself good and winded to fill up your anaerobic fuel tank if you expect to be able to take it to the limit in a race. Also, as we’ll see in the next chapter, you must be willing to swim with one eye on the clock and the other on the lane lines. But in the Total Immersion system, nothing does as much for your stroke as careful, thoughtful practice at a pace that lets you stroke effectively and move efficiently. Learn to do that and speed will come more easily anyway.

这在体育界并不流行，你很容易就能找到不同意我观点的游泳教练。可惜的是，有太多人坚信你必须刻苦训练。是时候提高游泳水平了，那些帮助建立流行训练信条的人。当顶级游泳运动员被记录下来时，他们的实力不可避免地要归功于一系列非凡的牺牲和刻苦训练的习惯。

That’s not a popular notion in the athletic profession, and you’ll have no trouble finding swim coaches who disagree with me. Too bad there’s such an abundance of people convinced you must train hard all the time to improve at swimming, people who have helped establish popular training gospel. When top swimmers get written up, their prowess is inevitably credited to a litany of extraordinary sacrifices and ferocious work habits.

但教练们并非无所不知。事实上，他们可以从游泳界科学家的研究成果中学到越来越多的东西。他们正在逐渐认识到的一件事——尽管他们正在拼命争取——是轻松游泳是一种非常有效的训练工具，即使对顶级运动员来说也是如此。

But coaches don’t know it all. In fact, there’s more and more they can learn from the work of the swim community’s scientists. And one of the things they’re gradually learning—though they’re fighting it tooth and nail—is that easy swimming is a formidably effective training tool, even for top racers.

还是以亚历山大·波波夫为例。如果你不了解一些技巧，也不知道如何掌握，就无法成为无可争议的世界顶尖选手。那么，尽管波波夫最擅长的项目是所有游泳项目中最短、最快、最无氧的项目，但他近70%的训练码数都低于所谓的无氧阈值，我们该如何理解呢？如果你说这一定是因为波波夫知道这样对他更有益，那你是对的。他呼吸顺畅，耐心地在神经系统中铺垫着超高效的划水轨迹，这种划水姿势能够让他在精准控制的高强度快速训练中保持稳定并有效地向前推进。

Take Alexander Popov—again. You don’t get to be indisputably the best in the world without knowing a thing or two about technique and how to get it. So what can we make of the fact that even though Popov’s best events are the shortest, fastest, most anaerobic in all of swimming, nearly 70 percent of his training yardage is below the so-called anaerobic threshold? If you said it must be because Popov knows it does him more good, you were right. He was breathing comfortably, patiently laying down tracks in his nervous system for an ultra-efficient stroke that will stand firm and propel him effectively during the precisely administered hard, fast work he also does.

教练们也不能再固守“一分耕耘，一分收获”的铁律了。虽然他们一直信奉“越多越好”的信条，但生理学家至少让他们承认，加入一些更容易的训练才能产生更好的效果。直到最近，尤其是在游泳训练中，恢复期一直是训练中保守得最好的秘密。你应该还记得，从上一章开始，恢复期就是你想要的适应过程——比如肌肉变得更强壮——真正发生的时候。可惜的是，这么多年来，大多数教练都认为工作时间才是最好的休息时间，不愿冒险尝试……定期给游泳运动员放松训练。训练政策就像谚语里的那条线：受不了热？就离开泳池。教练们一致认为，哲学家尼采深谙如何塑造游泳运动员：“那些杀不死你的，终将使你更强大。”

Coaches can’t cling to the “no pain, no gain” defense anymore either. While they have always followed the gospel that more and harder are better, the physiologists have at least gotten them to admit that adding in some easier produces superior results. Until recently, in swimming especially, the recovery period was the best-kept secret in training. Recovery, you’ll remember from the last chapter, is when the adaptations you want—like your muscles growing stronger—actually take place. Too bad that for so many years most coaches, believing the only good time was work time, were reluctant to take a chance by taking it easy on their swimmers at regular intervals. Training policy was like the proverbial line in the sand: Can’t stand the heat? Get out of the pool. Philosopher Nietzsche, coaches agreed, knew how to shape a swimmer: “That which doesn’t kill you makes you stronger.”

除非它让你精疲力竭、更加虚弱。过度训练会导致科学家所说的适应失败综合症。身体在艰难/更艰难/最艰难的隧道尽头看不到一丝曙光，放弃了任何适应的机会，最终慢慢崩溃。运动员会变得疲惫、迟缓、虚弱……如果他们没有先生病或受伤的话。一些游泳教练对这种衰退视而不见，指望赛前减量训练能让他们摆脱困境。狠狠地打击他们，然后让他们好好休息，你的游泳运动员就能克服重重困难，不是吗，大个子？

Unless it makes you exhausted and weaker. Too much hard work results in what scientists call failing adaptation syndrome. The body, seeing no glimmer of light at the end of the hard/harder/hardest tunnel, gives up on ever getting a chance to adapt and just slowly collapses. Athletes grow tired, slow, and weak … if they don’t get sick or injured first. Some swim coaches accept this decline with their eyes open, counting on a precompetition taper to pull everything out of the fire. Beat ’em up bad, then rest the dickens out of them, and your swimmers will come through big time, eh, big guy?

他们或许真的会成功。他们的身体非常感激终于有机会喘口气（无论是比喻还是字面意义上），以至于他们“超级适应”，正如科学家们所说，取得了巨大的进步。不幸的是，教练们随后把所有的功劳都归功于他们的努力，尽管这实际上可能把游泳运动员逼到了崩溃的边缘。作为传统的教练，他们永远不会承认，正是休息最终让运动员发挥出了真正的潜力。

And so they might. Their bodies are so grateful for finally getting a chance to catch their breaths (figuratively and literally) that they “superadapt,” as the scientists say, taking a big leap forward. Unfortunately, the coaches then give all the credit to the hard work, even though it may have actually pushed the swimmers perilously close to coming apart. And as traditional coaches, they’d never admit it was the rest that finally allowed the athletes to reach their true potential.

但最近科学家们的声音越来越大，他们开始有所行动了。“呃，教练，让你的运动员循序渐进地提高训练水平不是更合理吗？先训练一会儿，休息一会儿，然后再加把劲？让他们一个个级别晋升到下一个级别？”这比让每个人都沉浸于训练，让他们陷入一段漫长的沉闷期，然后在最后让他们奇迹般地恢复过来更有意义。

But the scientists have been talking a little louder lately, and they’ve begun to get through. “Uh, Coach, wouldn’t it make more sense to build your athletes up in a series of small steps? Work a little, rest a little, then work a little harder? Kind of ratchet them up from each level to the new one?” Makes more sense than drowning everybody in training, triggering a long stale period, then turning them loose with one big miraculous recovery at the end.

“哦，是的，你的游泳者可能会更喜欢它。”

“And oh yes, your swimmers might enjoy it more.”

因此，教练们不得不勉强接受更科学训练运动员的明智之举，允许运动员有更多轻松的日子，甚至——颠覆性的想法！ ——偶尔进行一整周轻松低调的训练。不过，他们抱怨这违反了他们最珍视的训练戒律。有些人甚至轻蔑地称之为垃圾码数。大多数游泳运动员喜欢这样（其他一些坚定的传统主义者，仍然更喜欢尼采式的跑步训练），但许多人并没有获得应有的收益，因为教练们仍然把轻松游泳日视为一种令人遗憾的必要“退让”。他们不明白这是一个重要的机会。

So coaches have grudgingly begun to accept the wisdom of training their athletes more scientifically, permitting more easy days, maybe even—subversive thought!—a whole week now and then of relaxed and low-key training. They grumble, mind you, over violating their dearest training commandment. Some even disdainfully call it garbage yardage. Most swimmers like it (others, the bedrock traditionalists, would still rather have Nietzsche running workouts), but many aren’t benefiting as much as they could because the coaches still see a day of easy swimming as a regrettably necessary “backing off.” They don’t understand it’s a major opportunity.

但冠军亚历山大·波波夫的教练很早就明白这一点。他知道，这不仅仅是恢复，这是一种让你已经获得的有氧适应——你的身体状况——最终发生的方式。这也是训练你的神经系统以最有效的方式利用这种条件的唯一好方法。当你的心率达到 130 或 140 BPM 时，你可以练习在心率达到 180 BPM 时无法做到的精确技能和技巧。比如划水训练、感官游泳、限制划水次数的游泳，以及没有“划水成本”的速度。而且，由于你的身体以最高效率游泳的能力远比以最大努力游泳的能力重要，很明显，花在轻松游泳上的时间可能不仅同样重要，而且更为重要。

But champion Alexander Popov’s coach understood this long ago. It’s not just recovery, he knew, it’s a way to allow aerobic adaptations you’ve already earned—your very conditioning—to finally happen. It’s also the only good way to train your nervous system to use that conditioning in the most efficient possible way. When your heart’s humming along at 130 or 140 BPM, you can work on precise skills and techniques that are impossible when it’s pounding at 180. Things like stroke drills, sensory swimming, stroke-limited swims, and speed without “stroke cost.” And since your body’s ability to swim with maximum efficiency is far more critical than its ability to swim with maximum effort, it’s clear the time spent on easy laps is probably not just as important but more important.

当轻松训练的新闻最终传播开来时，波波夫的言论将被证明只是冰山一角。20世纪90年代中期，俄罗斯游泳运动员包揽了从50米到400米的所有自由泳世界纪录。美国顶尖运动员的教练们自然也接受了这种想法。

And Popov will prove to be just the tip of the iceberg when the easy-training news finally gets around. In the mid-1990s, Russian swimmers held every freestyle world record from the 50 through the 400 meters. Inevitably, the coaches of America’s elite athletes got the idea too.

但前沿培训通常需要更长的时间才能普及对于自学成才的成年人来说。如果说有哪一类运动员比其他任何群体更需要这样的建议，那一定是铁人三项运动员。想想看：这三种运动都能让你精疲力竭！再加上那种奇特的交叉训练理念，认为一项运动的刻苦训练在某种程度上可以作为另一项运动的恢复。所以他们拼命地跑步、骑车、游泳，然后却不明白为什么自己要用半生的时间去养伤。

But cutting-edge training usually takes much longer to filter down to the self-coached adult. And if any one group of athletes needs the advice more than any other, it’s triathletes. Just think: three sports to push yourself to exhaustion in! Plus the fanciful cross-training notion that hard work in one sport somehow qualifies as recovery from hard work in another. So they hammer in running, hammer in biking, and hammer in swimming, then wonder why they spend half their lives nursing injuries.

刻苦训练跑步和骑自行车可能会有好处，因为这些技术性较低的运动从基本体能的提升中获得更大的提升。但对于普通的铁人三项运动员来说，艰苦的游泳训练毫无意义，因为他们最好的选择是永远、永远、永远不要努力游泳。想想看。在比赛本身中，胜利永远属于最快的自行车手或跑步者，而永远不会（永远、永远）属于最快的游泳者。甚至有一个词来形容在游泳比赛中努力工作的铁人三项运动员。他们被称为失败者。这些认真的人努力在水中取得一点点领先，而其他所有人都坐在后面，舒服地跟在他们后面，被拉着走。挣扎的人很快就会在自行车上被吞没，最终在跑步时完全崩溃。每个轻松完成游泳的人都会继续骑行和跑步以获得荣耀。

Grinding out run and bike miles may do some good, since those less technical sports get a bigger boost from gains in basic physical prowess. But hard swim training makes no sense at all for the average triathlete whose best bet is to never, never, never swim hard. Figure it out. In the race itself, victory always goes to the fastest biker or runner, never (never, never) to the fastest swimmer. There’s even a word for triathletes who work hard during the swim leg. They’re called losers. These earnest types struggle to a small lead out of the water while everybody else sits back and comfortably drafts behind them, getting pulled along. The strugglers quickly get swallowed up on the bike and finally collapse altogether on the run. Everyone who coasted through the swim goes on to ride and run to glory.

所以，对于你们当中的多项运动爱好者来说，底线是：既然在铁人三项比赛中，最明智的做法是在整个游泳过程中将心率保持在130到140次/分之间，那么任何更高的心率训练都是浪费时间和精力。只要你遵循以下两点，你轻松的训练就能获得巨大的回报：

So for the multisport among you, the bottom line is this: Since your smartest move in a triathlon is to keep your heart rate at 130 to 140 bpm for the entire swim, training at anything higher is a waste of time and energy. Your take-it-easy work will pay big dividends if only you follow these two points:

 

 

1. 记住我们熟悉的70法则（表现的70%取决于划水效率，只有30%取决于体能），并利用它与对手较量。只有一小部分很多铁人三项运动员都有竞技游泳的背景。他们大多是前跑步运动员，通常体格健壮，但游泳技能也只是些皮毛。这就是你的机会，而且是一个巨大的机遇。与其锻炼，不如练习，运用我在本书中介绍的“完全沉浸式”方法。

1. Remember our familiar rule of 70 (performance is determined 70 percent by stroke efficiency and only 30 percent by fitness), and take advantage of it against your competition. Only a tiny fraction of triathletes come from a competitive-swimming background. Most are former runners, who are generally very fit but who also have just rudimentary swimming skills. There’s your chance, and it’s a huge opportunity. Instead of working out, practice, using the Total Immersion methods I’ve covered in this book.

 

 

2. 还要记住，游泳是加速你从自行车和跑步等其他运动的高强度训练中恢复的最佳方式。减少游泳的强度，专注于微调你的神经系统训练，而不是浪费精力在你已经非常强大的有氧系统上，你就能恢复得更健康、更快。这反过来会让你成为一个更强大的跑步者和自行车运动员，因为这些运动不再需要与游泳分享稀缺的有氧适应资源。这并非痴心妄想或巧妙的文字游戏。铁人三项运动员一次又一次地告诉我，一旦他们调整训练方式，适应完全沉浸式训练法，他们就会恢复到以前的状态。我有没有教过他们跑步或骑自行车的秘诀？当然没有。我是游泳教练。但我仍然可以帮助他们在其他运动中成为更聪明的游泳教练。

2. Remember too that swimming is the best way to speed up your recovery from hard work in other sports like biking and running. Dial down the swimming effort, concentrate on fine-tuning your nervous-system training instead of wasting work on your already superb aerobic machinery, and you’ll bounce back fitter and faster. That in turn will make you a stronger runner and cyclist, since those sports no longer have to share scarce aerobic-adaptation resources with swimming. This is not wishful thinking or clever wordplay. Triathletes have told me over and over that it happens to them once they adjust their training to the Total Immersion method. Did I give them secret tips about running or biking? Of course not. I’m a swim coach. But I could help them in those other sports nonetheless by making them smarter swim trainers.

那么，另一群竞技水平的游泳运动员，大师级选手（严格来说是19岁以上，但实际上大多是30到90多岁的选手）又如何呢？他们也知道，更好的游泳成绩来自于提升有氧能力。只有一个问题。他们大多数都在40岁以上，有充足的时间来锻炼心血管系统。而且，由于身体状况开始逐渐降低上限，推动心血管系统除非你只是久坐不动，否则不太可能达到更高的训练水平。所以，未来的个人最佳成绩都将来自更好的划水技巧，而不是攀升到新的训练高度。

And what about that other competitive group, Masters swimmers (technically anyone over nineteen, but in practice mostly swimmers from thirty to ninety-plus)? They too know that better swim times come from punching up their aerobic powers. Only one problem with that. Most are forty and over, and they’ve had plenty of time to work on their cardiovascular conditioning. And with nature beginning to lower the ceiling just a little anyway, pushing cardiovascular conditioning any higher—unless you’ve just been sitting around for a long time—is unlikely. So any future personal bests will come from better stroke mechanics, not from scaling some new training heights.

如果你一开始就对比赛毫不在意，那会怎样？你是试图从泳池的一端猛冲到另一端，还是精心策划、循序渐进地练习，真的有什么区别吗？确实如此。而且，数百万人确实需要知道这一点。考虑到大约有5万名比赛选手和400万到500万名健身游泳者，大约99.9%的游泳者更关心的是自己是否保持健康强壮，以及是否在过程中享受乐趣，而不是自己游得快慢。他们需要知道，自己无需流汗就能获得100%的益处和乐趣。

What if you couldn’t care less about racing in the first place? Does it really make any difference whether you try to blast from one end of the pool to the other or plan careful, measured practices? Indeed it does. And there are literally millions of people who need to know that. Considering that there are maybe 50,000 racers and somewhere between 4 million and 5 million fitness swimmers, about 99.9 percent of all swimmers have less interest in whether they’re swimming fast or slow than in whether they’re staying healthy and strong and having fun along the way. They need to know they can get 100 percent of the benefits and enjoyment they seek without ever breaking a sweat.

即使是赛车手也普遍知道，身体的大部分变化，也就是让你成为运动员的变化，都发生在心率远低于所谓的无氧阈值（也就是你会严重喘不过气的阈值）的时候。在较低的心率下，你的心输出量会更有效地提高，燃烧更多脂肪，基础耐力也会更强。如果这听起来像是最重要的抗衰老功效的完整列表，那是因为它确实如此。你的肌肉也会因此变得更强壮。

Why, even racers generally know that most of the changes in your body that transform you into an athlete occur at heart rates well below the so-called anaerobic threshold, the point where you get seriously out of breath. Your cardiac output improves more efficiently, you burn more fat, and you build more basic endurance at lower heart rates. And if that sounds like a complete list of the most important antiaging effects, that’s because it is. Your muscles get stronger in the bargain.

那么，你缺什么呢？就是比赛所需的无氧训练。但如果你本来就不打算比赛，谁还需要它呢？你仍然可以稳步提升，因为轻松的有氧训练能让你越来越高效地发挥。你受伤或感到疲惫的可能性更小，也更容易坚持训练，因为你不需要艰苦训练所要求的休息和恢复期，您会发现让游泳更容易融入您的日常生活安排。

So what’s missing? Just the anaerobic training you need for racing. But if you’re not going to race anyway, who needs it? You can still steadily improve because your easy aerobic training will let you maximize your efficiency more and more and more. You’re less likely to suffer injuries or staleness and more apt to train consistently, since you don’t need the periods of rest and recovery demanded by hard training, and you’ll find it’s easier to make swimming match the schedules of your everyday life.

对于我们当中除了精英之外的所有人，我想说欲速则不达。放慢训练速度，才能加速你的游泳水平提升。

For all but the elite among us, I say haste makes waste. Speed up your swimming improvement by slowing down your training.

11

11

组织起来的时间——按时钟游泳

Time to Get Organized— Swimming by the Clock

你是泳池机器人吗？泳池机器人就像一个刚装好电池的大玩具，跳进去就能游，像个机械的“游泳高手”，上上下下地来回走动。这就像加了点氯气的“职业道德”。虽然这种训练效率最低，但我们很多人却心甘情愿地浪费训练时间。所以，我们接下来要讨论的是间歇训练——一种更好的锻炼方式。

Are you a pool robot? Pool robots are swimmers who just jump in and start swimming, like a big toy with fresh batteries, plodding mechanically up and down and up and down. It’s the work ethic with a dash of chlorine. And even though training like this is the least effective, it’s how too many of us willingly squander our training time. That’s why we’re about to discuss intervals—a much better way to work out.

与此同时，如果上面的描述听起来像你，也别尴尬。你身边还有很多人。你或许会开怀大笑，因为在你看来，上一章关于慢速游泳的内容终于证明了你那些令人麻木、节奏感十足的训练是合理的。事实上，它并没有做到这一点。没错，你需要一定量的有目的、有深度的游泳来提升技能，但无休止、没有目标的训练是没有出路的。

Meantime, if the description above sounds like you, don’t be embarrassed. You have plenty of company. You may also be smiling broadly because it seems to you like that last chapter on slow swimming finally justified your mind-numbing, metronomic workouts. In fact, it did no such thing. Yes, you need a certain amount of purposeful, thoughtful swimming to build skills, but endless workouts with no objective are dead-end exercise.

在“全浸式”项目中，我们希望确保你不会把速度置于良好的技术之上，所以我们不会在早期强调大量的计时游泳。但停留在二档也不是重点。要想取得进步，你需要一个计划，你需要一个结构，你或许还需要一些加大力度的训练。

In the Total Immersion program we want to be sure you don’t put speed before good technique, so we don’t stress a lot of timed swimming early on. But staying in second gear is not the point either. To get ahead, you need a plan, you need structure, and you probably need some workouts where you push the throttle a bit harder.

你需要间歇训练。在本章中，你将体验到间歇训练。但不是那种大多数人都会觉得累到精疲力竭的、令人恐惧的、游到筋疲力尽的训练。当他们听到这个词时会想到什么。完全沉浸式间歇训练是一种科学的游泳方式，它能让你充分利用时间，而不会让你感到疲惫。

You need intervals. And in this chapter, you shall have them. But not the scary, swim-’til-you-drop exercises in exhaustion most people think of when they hear the word. Total Immersion intervals are scientific swimming that make the most of your time without asking you to beat yourself up.

虽然我们很多人可能都知道，一直保持中等速度，直到体力或时间耗尽，是不会走远的，但大多数健身游泳者却是这样打发时间的。在两圈之间抓住他们——如果你能让他们停下来的话——你就会听到他们说：“我想游一英里。”就像跑步中的10公里一样，它是每个人都想用来衡量自己的黄金标准距离。

Although many of us probably know that hanging out on medium-throttle autopilot until our energy or time runs out won’t take us far, it’s how most fitness swimmers spend their time. Grab them between laps—if you can get them to stop at all—and you’ll hear why: “I want to swim a mile.” Like the 10K in running, it’s a kind of gold-standard distance against which everyone wants to measure him- or herself.

没有人比泳池救生员更了解这一点，他们从经验中知道，几乎每个游泳新手都会不时地问：“这里的一英里是多少圈？”现在大多数泳池都只是张贴数字让所有人都能看到。有了这种认知（顺便说一下，在25码的泳池里，这个神奇的数字是70.4），他们开始尝试一点一点地向这座大山发起挑战。如果他们不能马上做到不间断，他们就会选择分段完成。先完成三组20圈，然后轻松完成10或12圈。目标必然是游得更久，休息得更少，直到最终能够将所有这些努力拼凑成一次不间断的胜利。他们会为自己感到庆幸，当然，他们也会这样做，但这种喜悦不会持续太久。因为明天，他们当然必须回来游得更快。然后，这个新的挑战会让他们感到有趣一段时间，直到时间趋于平稳，不再有任何进展。显然剩下的就是继续坚持下去，因为“这对你有好处”。

Nobody understands this better than pool lifeguards, who know from experience that nearly every new swimmer will come up at one time or other asking, “How many laps to the mile here?” Most pools now simply post the number for all to see. Armed with that intelligence (in a 25-yard pool, by the way, the magic figure is 70.4), they begin trying to chip away at the mountain. If they can’t make it non-stop right away, they’ll settle for doing it piecemeal. Knock off three sets of 20, then finish up with an easy 10 or 12. The goal is inevitably to go longer and rest less until they can finally patch it all together into one nonstop triumph. They congratulate themselves, as well they might, but the glow doesn’t last long. Because tomorrow, naturally, they’ve got to come back and swim it faster. Then that new challenge remains interesting for a while until the times simply level off and go nowhere. All that’s apparently left then is to soldier on because “it’s good for you.”

那不是你吗？首先，你没时间浪费在那种距离上？好吧，也许你是那种午休时间冲进健身俱乐部，只剩下40分钟空闲时间的人。第一天，你可能跑了10到20个来回就累得筋疲力尽了（到顺便说一下，对于教练和竞技游泳选手来说，游一程和一圈是一样的），即使两者之间有一两分钟的休息时间。但你还是像任何想成为一英里赛跑者的选手一样，不断削减进度，增加圈数，减少休息时间，急于提高 40 分钟的圈数分数。确实，过一段时间你大概就能一口气游完 40 分钟，加起来甚至可以达到一英里（70 个程）。如果幸运的话，你甚至可以再多游几个程，以达到更好的效果。但最终你也会达到你的游泳平衡点（我的一个营员称之为“终极平庸”），你的训练也将不再有任何有趣的感觉。

That’s not you? For one thing, you don’t have the time to squander on that kind of distance? Well, then, maybe you’re the clock-watching type who dashes into the health club at lunchtime with 40 minutes to spare. On day one, you probably peter out after 10 or 20 lengths (to coaches and competitive swimmers, by the way, a length and a lap are the same), even with a minute or two of rest between each. But you keep whittling away just as any would-be miler would, adding laps, subtracting rest, anxious to pump up that 40-minute lap score. And true enough, after a while you’ll probably be able to swim the full 40 minutes without stopping, which may even add up to a mile (70 lengths). With luck, you’ll even be able to pile on a couple more lengths just for good measure. But eventually you too will reach your swimming equilibrium (“terminal mediocrity,” one of my campers called it) and the end of anything remotely interesting about your workouts.

这就是将圈数统计作为游泳目标的结果。你浪费时间担心游了多少圈或游得有多快，而不是担心游得有多正确。相反，你应该担心停滞不前。身体已经习惯了你正在做的事情，以至于没有任何刺激来提高。适应和超负荷的原则会让你在开始时坚持一段时间，因为如果你从未游过一英里，那么为它做准备就是一种超负荷，它确实可以训练你的身体。但是一旦你游完一英里并再次游完，你会去哪里？世界上最优秀的游泳运动员，那些与教练一起训练的人鱼，总是对圈泳运动员的死胡同式训练感到困惑。“这不无聊吗？”他们会问，因为他们知道有更好的方式来利用他们的时间。“嗯，是的，”圈泳运动员回答。“但这对我有好处。”

That’s what always comes of making the lap tally the holy grail of your swimming. You waste time fretting over how many or how fast—instead of how right—you are doing each one. Instead, you should be fretting about stagnation. The body gets so used to what you’re doing that there’s no stimulus to improve. The principles of adaptation and overload will see you through for a while in the beginning since, if you’ve never swum a mile, the preparation for it is an overload that does train your body. But once you’ve done the mile and done it again, where do you go? The world’s best swimmers, the human fish who train with coaches, are always baffled by the lap swimmer’s dead-end routine. “Doesn’t it get boring?” they ask, since they know there’s a much better way to invest their time. “Well, yes,” answers the lap swimmer. “But it’s good for me.”

嗯，如果你换成间歇训练，或者换成我所谓的“有计划地、有目的的停顿”，对你来说会更好，也更有趣。你需要知道如何让时间为你运转。所以，让我们用“完全沉浸式”的方式进行间歇训练吧。

Well, it could be a lot better for you and a lot more fun too if you’d switch to intervals or, for the less technical, to what I call stopping-on-purpose-with-a-plan. You need to know how to make the clock work for you. So let’s do some interval training the Total Immersion way.

为什么那个钟缺少一根指针？

Why Is That Clock Missing a Hand?

几乎在美国，每个游泳池的尽头附近的墙上都挂着一个带有秒针的八角形白色大月亮，它是让你从无意义的游泳过渡到智能间歇训练的关键。由于游泳者以分和秒来衡量成绩，因此节奏时钟有分针和秒针，但没有时针。一分钟（秒针绕钟面一圈）分为 12 个五秒间隔。五秒间隔（:05-:10、:10-:15 等）用红色标记和大黑色数字表示。它们之间的四个标记（秒）是黑色标记。游泳者通常从红色（五秒）标记开始重复训练。

The pace clock—that big, octagonal, white-faced moon with the sweep hand on the wall near the end of virtually every lap pool in America—is the key to your graduation from pointless swimming to smart interval training. Since swimmers measure performance in minutes and seconds, the pace clock has a minute hand and a sweep hand, but no hour hand. One minute—one sweep of the second hand around the clock face—is divided into 12 five-second intervals. The five-second intervals (:05–:10, :10–:15, etc.) are shown with both a red mark and large black numbers. The four marks (seconds) between them are black marks. Swimmers usually start their repeats on a red (five-second) mark.

无论您是否接受过教练指导，配速钟都能帮您掌握有效间歇训练所需的几乎所有信息。阅读配速钟，您可以了解：(1) 每次重复训练的速度；(2) 下次重复训练前还剩多少休息时间。

The pace clock tells you nearly everything you need to know for effective interval training, whether you’re coached or uncoached. Read it to find out: (1) how fast you’ve swum each repeat, and (2) how much rest remains before your next one.

把它当作工具，而不是暴君。过于沉迷于计时钟，它就会变成一个无情的监工。那些一丝不苟地只关注游速，而不考虑效率代价（划水次数、心率高低）的游泳者，他们的游泳水平其实很差。但要把计时钟当作一个有价值的工具，帮助你提升技术，它会让你的所有练习更有价值，也更有趣。

Use it as a tool, not a tyrant. Become too absorbed with the pace clock and you’ll allow it to grow into an unforgiving taskmaster. Swimmers who meticulously focus only on how fast they’re swimming and never mind the efficiency price (how many strokes, how high a heart rate) are really practicing sloppy swimming. But use the clock as a valuable tool to help build up your technique, and it will make all your practices more valuable. And more fun.

完全沉浸式间歇训练与你习惯的训练略有不同。大多数运动员用“i”这个词来泛指任何艰苦的、重复的训练，让你气喘吁吁，然后准备比赛。训练，呕吐，回家。

Total Immersion intervals are a little different from what you may be used to. Most athletes use the “i” word to broadly describe any training that’s tough, repetitive, leaves you out of breath, and gets you ready for a race. Work out, throw up, go home.

我使用它们的方式不同。没错，有些间歇训练可以让你为全力以赴的比赛做好准备。但还有很多其他的间歇训练方法。我最常被问到的问题，以及你需要的完全沉浸式训练方法的答案是：

I use them differently. Yes, there are intervals that can prepare you for an all-out race. But there are dozens of others as well. The questions I get most often, and the answers you need to train the Total Immersion way, are:

 

 

1. 我能期待什么效果？在完全浸入式游泳中，我们所做的一切（包括间歇训练）的目标都是为了提高技术，无论你是学习新技能，通过练习巩固技能，还是测试在游得更远更快时你能多好地保持这些技能。

1. What Effect Can I Expect? In Total Immersion swimming, the objective of anything we do—intervals included—is improvement of technique, whether you’re learning new skills, consolidating them through practice, or testing how well you can hold on to them as you swim farther and faster.

增强耐力、提升速度、提高对无氧训练的耐受力，以及练习竞速或配速策略，这些都是你在间歇训练中应该期待的次要目标。但这些都只是次要的。

Building endurance, increasing speed, improving your tolerance for anaerobic training, and practicing racing or pacing strategies are worthwhile secondary objectives that you should expect from your intervals. But they are secondary.

 

 

2. 我应该做多少组？这样决定：做足够的组数，让自己获得充分的有氧训练（每组至少持续10到15分钟，包括游泳和休息时间，共进行4到5组）。但不要做太多，以免影响你的技术或注意力。

2. How Many Should I Do? Decide this way: Do enough to give yourself adequate aerobic conditioning (a set lasting at least ten to fifteen minutes—including swim and rest time—in a workout of four or five sets). But don’t do so many that your technique or concentration suffers.

 

 

3. 我应该游多远？理论上，重复距离可以是从25码到800码甚至更长的任何距离，但为了提高划水技巧（这也是我们这项运动的宗旨），短距离几乎总是更好。虽然长距离重复有助于培养耐力和节奏感，但通常会削弱速度和技巧。较短的重复跑（通常200码或更短）没有这个缺点，而且几乎可以满足你的所有需求。为了提高耐力，可以增加重复跑次数和/或减少休息时间。为了提高速度，可以选择更少、更快的重复跑次数和更多的休息时间。

3. How Far Should I Go? Repeats can technically be any distance from 25 yards to 800 yards or more, but for stroke improvement, which is the name of our game, shorter ones are nearly always better. While longer repeats help develop endurance and pace sense, they generally undermine speed and technique. Shorter repeats (generally 200 yards and less) don’t have this disadvantage and can give you virtually everything you want. For greater endurance, increase the number of repeats and/or decrease the rest. For more speed, choose fewer, faster repeats and more rest.

 

 

4. 我必须全力以赴吗？当然不是。首先，你可以用几种方法来衡量强度：最大心率百分比、最大速度百分比或自觉用力程度（感觉有多难？）。更高的强度可以提高速度和无氧体能。较低的强度更有利于发展技术、提高有氧体能，以及练习节奏：学会长时间以相同的速度游泳，即使你越来越累。

4. Must I Swim All-Out? No indeed. First of all, you can measure intensity in several ways: percent of maximum heart rate, percent of maximum speed, or perceived exertion (how hard does it feel?). Higher intensity develops more speed and anaerobic fitness. Lower intensity is better for development of technique, for improving aerobic fitness, and for practice of pacing: learning to swim at the same speed for a long time, even as you grow more tired.

 

 

5. 休息多久才够？当两次游泳之间的休息时间少于或等于游泳时间的一半时，你的体能（有氧耐力）提升最快，通常表现为2:1的训练休息比。3:1到10:1的训练休息比在提升耐力方面很常见，在游泳训练书籍中也经常看到。如果你遇到这种情况，一定要小心。在完全沉浸式训练中，技术和效率绝对高于一切，所以要注意你的间歇训练要足够有挑战性，以促进体能提升，但又不能太紧凑，以免为了对抗疲劳而牺牲效率。

5. How Much Rest Is Enough? Your fitness (aerobic endurance) goes up fastest when the rest period between swims is one-half or less of the swim time, usually shown as a work:rest ratio of 2:1. Ratios of 3:1 all the way up to 10:1 are common in building endurance, and you’ll see them often in swim-training books. When you do, watch out. In Total Immersion, technique and efficiency come before absolutely everything else, so be careful that your intervals are challenging enough to promote fitness, yet not so tight you have to throw away efficiency as you fight fatigue to do them.

训练休息比为1:1、1:2等（休息时间等于或多于训练时间），可以提高速度和无氧体能，因为较长的休息时间能让你游得更快。短暂的休息时间无法让你有足够的恢复时间进行全力冲刺。

Work:rest ratios of 1:1, 1:2, etc. (equal or more rest than work), develop speed and anaerobic fitness, since the longer rest lets you swim them much faster. A short rest interval doesn’t allow enough recovery for an all-out push.

 

 

6. 所有重复动作都是直线游泳吗？并非如此。游泳的种类是无限的。你可以练习、练习游泳，或者只是游泳。使用你想练习的四种泳姿中的任何一种。练习划水和踢腿，无论是否使用浮板和/或浮板。（更多关于这些和其他训练工具的使用，请参见第13章。）甚至可以让每个间歇都与前一个不同——下降组、金字塔组、梯子组等等。（更多内容见下文。）

6. Are All Repeats Straight Swimming? Not at all. The variety is limitless. You can drill, drill-swim, or just swim. Use any of the four strokes you want to practice. Work on pulling and kicking with or without a pull buoy and/or kickboard. (More on use of these and other training tools in chapter 13.) Even make every interval different from the one before—descending sets, pyramids, ladders, etc. (More on this below.)

基本间隔：四种观察时钟的好方法

Basic Intervals: Four Good Ways to Watch the Clock

1. 固定休息组

1. FIXED-REST SETS

例如：4 × 200码，休息60秒

Example: 4 × 200 yards on 60 seconds rest

重复次数：4

Number of repetitions: 4

每次距离：200码

Distance of each rep: 200 yards

开始每次重复：完成上一次重复后 60 秒

Start each repetition: 60 seconds after finishing the last one

没有比这更基础的间歇训练了，所以如果你是新手，这绝对是入门之选。无论你游得快还是慢，都能保证相同的休息时间。比如，第一个200米用时3分00秒，第二个200米从4分00秒开始。如果第二个200米跑得慢到3分20秒，第三个200米从4分20秒开始，无论如何都要保持这一分钟的休息时间。

You don’t get intervals more basic than this, so it’s the place to start if you’re new. You’re guaranteed the same amount of rest, no matter how slowly or how fast you swim. For instance, do the first 200 in 3:00 and you start the second at the 4:00 mark. If your second 200 slows to 3:20, you start the third at 4:20, holding your minute’s rest no matter what.

为了更容易记录，大多数游泳运动员会把剩余的成绩四舍五入，在时钟上留下一个红色标记。在3分17秒游完200米后，他们可能会在4分15秒或4分20秒再游一次，而不是4分17秒。

To make it easier to keep track, most swimmers round off the rest to leave on a red mark on the clock. After a 200 at 3:17, they’d probably go again at 4:15 or 4:20, not 4:17.

2. 固定间隔集

2. FIXED-INTERVAL SETS

例如：8 × 100码，2:00

Example: 8 × 100 yards on 2:00

重复次数：8

Number of repetitions: 8

每次距离：100码

Distance of each rep: 100 yards

每次重复开始时间：2:00（包括游泳时间加上休息时间）

Start each repetition on: 2:00 (includes swim time plus rest time)

这也是相当基础的，但比第 1 条更难一些，也更具策略性。无论中间休息多少，你都要在开始前一次 100 码的两分钟后开始下一次 100 码的重复。在 1 分 30 秒内完成第一个 100 码，你就可以获得 30 分的休息时间。第二次的配速降低到 1 分 35 秒，在开始第三次重复之前的休息时间也会降低到 25 分。防止坡度越来越陡（并且每次重复都可能变得越来越难）的唯一方法是跟上，这意味着在所有八码处都要以接近相同的速度游泳。由于你的体力每次都会下降，你必须想办法分配工作（我们将在下一章关于比赛的章节中解释），每次都做得更好一些，这样你最终就能以相同的速度游第一名和第八名。

This is fairly basic too, but it’s a little tougher and more strategic than #1. You start each 100-yard repeat two minutes after starting the previous one, regardless of how much or little rest that gives you. Finish the first 100 in 1:30 and you get :30 off. Slip to a 1:35 pace on the second and your rest before you start your third repeat slips too: to :25. The only way to keep the slope from getting steeper and steeper—and each repeat from probably getting harder and harder—is to keep up, which means swimming close to the same pace on all eight. Since your tank gets lower each time, you have to figure how to parcel out the work (we explain this in our next chapter on racing) a little better each time so you end up swimming numbers one and eight at the same speed.

3. 递减区间集

3. DECREASING-INTERVAL SETS

例如：5 × 50码，间隔1:00–:55–:50–:45

Example: 5 × 50 yards on intervals of 1:00–:55–:50–:45

重复次数：5

Number of repetitions: 5

每次距离：50码

Distance of each rep: 50 yards

每次重复的开始时间：减少休息

Start each repetition on: decreasing rest

递减间隔组比第二个组更难，因为在每次连续重复中，随着你变得越来越累，你自动得到的休息就会减少。

Decreasing-interval sets are tougher yet than #2 because on each successive repeat, as you’re growing more tired, you automatically get less rest.

以上面的例子为例。第一个间隔（第二次循环之前）是 1 分 0 秒，下一个是 55 分，最后一个是 45 分。所以，如果你每次循环的游时长是 40 分，那么在第二次循环之前你会休息 20 分，在开始第三次循环之前休息 15 分，在第四次循环之前休息 10 分，在第五次循环之前休息 5 分。

Take the example above. The first interval (preceding the second repeat) is 1:00, the next is :55, and the last is :45. So if you swam each repeat in :40, you’d rest :20 before swimming the second, :15 before starting the third, :10 before the fourth, and just :05 before the fifth.

胆小鬼可不行。但信不信由你，一位经验丰富的重复游泳运动员实际上可以在每次重复游泳时游得更快一些，弥补失去的一点点休息时间。

Not for sissies. But believe it or not, an accomplished repeat swimmer can actually swim slightly faster on each succeeding repeat, regaining a sliver of lost rest.

教练经常使用减少间隔的方法来让你适应比赛中保持速度的艰难挑战，此时你的身体开始说：“嘿，放轻松，好吗？”

Decreasing intervals are often used by coaches to get you used to the tough challenge of holding your pace in a race, when everything in your body is beginning to say, “Hey, take it easy, will you?”

4. 递增区间集

4. INCREASING-INTERVAL SETS

例如：8 × 50（1-4 在 1:00，5-8 在 1:30）

Example: 8 × 50 (1–4 on 1:00, 5–8 on 1:30)

重复次数：8

Number of repetitions: 8

每次距离：50码

Distance of each rep: 50 yards

每次重复的开始时间：前半程 1:00，后半程 1:30

Start each repetition on: 1:00 for first half, 1:30 for second

这看起来像是让你得到了休息，因为后半程每次重复之前你都比前半程多休息了30秒。但有一个问题：有了额外的休息时间，你应该游得更快。（而且，正如我们现在所知，如果你像这样以固定间隔游，你还能得到更多的休息。）

This seems like it gives you a break, since you get :30 more rest before each repetition in the second half than in the first. But there’s a catch: With that extra rest, you’re supposed to swim faster. (And if you do, as we now know, you get still more rest if you’re swimming fixed intervals like these.)

教练通常会使用增加间歇时间来加快你的速度，因为增加的休息时间可以让你在间歇中游得更快、更卖力。这就像是为了强势完成一组（最好是一场比赛）而进行的预演。

The increasing interval is usually used by coaches to speed you up as the set progresses, since the added rest makes the intervals easier to swim harder and faster. It’s a kind of rehearsal for finishing a set (and hopefully a race) strongly.

间歇设计仅受教练创造力的限制，多年来我们许多人都变得非常有创造力。事实上，仅是阐述那些精心设计的方案，你就可以写一整本书，这些方案是为了在你盯着时钟的情况下安排你的泳池时间而制定的。“降序组”是逐组增加速度的组别，“梯子”和“金字塔”要么增加每次重复的长度，要么增加一半组的时长，然后在另一半组中再次缩短。如果这还不足以追踪，休息时间也会变化，因为它通常是根据你刚刚完成的腿的长度来计算的。在混合距离组中，一切都在变化，距离和休息间隔不断变化。

Interval design is limited only by a coach’s creativity, and over the years many of us have gotten pretty creative. In fact, you could probably write a whole book just on the elaborate schemes that have been devised to organize your pool time with your eye on the pace clock. “Descending sets” are sets that grow faster one by one, “ladders” and “pyramids” either increase the length of each rep or increase it for half the set and then shorten it again on the other half. If that’s not enough to keep track of, rest changes too, since it’s usually calculated from the length of the leg you’ve just done. And in mixed-distance sets everything is in play, with distances and rest intervals changing and changing again.

但上面四种常用的间歇训练模式能为你提供最直接的提升途径，而且无需防水计算器即可记录。此外，真正决定结果的是你在每个间歇训练中投入了多少，而不是你的整个训练计划安排得多么精巧。

But the four bread-and-butter interval formats above will give you the most direct route to improvement, and they don’t take a waterproof calculator to keep track of. Besides, it’s what you put into each length—not how elaborately your whole program is organized—that gets results.

对面的“入门套件”用到的只是固定休息组，没什么特别之处。但它能帮助你实现任何目标，从基础体能训练到让你引以为豪的比赛成绩。只需确保遵循每周的码数指南即可。为了比赛准备和速度，更艰苦的训练就像一剂强效良药。为了达到最佳效果，你应该只服用规定剂量。剂量过大并不一定更好，反而可能有害。

The “starter kit” opposite uses nothing fancier than fixed-rest sets. But it will groom you for any goal from basic fitness to a race time you’ll be proud of. Just make sure you follow the weekly yardage guidelines. The tougher work, for race-readiness and speed, is like a powerful medicine. You should take just the prescribed amount for best results. More is not better—and can be harmful.

准备，设置，重复！

Ready, Set, Repeat!

1. 健身间歇训练

1. FITNESS INTERVALS

（占总训练码数的 60% 至 100%）

(60 PERCENT TO 100 PERCENT OF TOTAL TRAINING YARDAGE)

这是一种相对较慢、轻松的游泳方式，旨在增强有氧耐力。其目标是广泛训练而非高强度训练。速度（或心率）通常仅为您最大重复距离的65%到75%（例如，如果您100码的最佳成绩是1分20秒，那么您在健身间歇组中的重复距离应为1分45秒到2分00秒）。此外，较短的休息时间也会抑制速度。为了达到效果，每组训练至少应持续20分钟。如果您正在准备一项超长距离的比赛（例如，铁人三项长距离游泳），可以通过增加重复次数将训练时间延长至1小时。

This is relatively slow, easy swimming that builds aerobic endurance. The aim is extensive rather than intensive training. Speed (or heart rate) is only 65 percent to 75 percent of your maximum for the repeat distance (i.e., if your best time for 100 yards was 1:20, you would repeat at 1:45 to 2:00 in a fitness interval set). Besides, speed is also held down by short rest periods. To work, the set should be at least 20 minutes. If you’re prepping for an extremely long event (e.g., an Iron-man distance swim), it can be made as long as an hour by adding more repeats.

示例：

EXAMPLES:

16-30 × 50（休息10-20秒）

16–30 × 50 (10–20 seconds rest)

10-20 × 75（休息10-20秒）

10–20 × 75 (10–20 seconds rest)

8-15 × 100（休息10-30秒）

8–15 × 100 (10–30 seconds rest)

5-10 × 150（休息15-30秒）

5–10 × 150 (15–30 seconds rest)

4-8 × 200（休息15-40秒）

4–8 × 200 (15–40 seconds rest)

还记得“全浸式”训练计划的根本原则吗？“健身是你在练习良好技巧时自然而然发生的事情。”间歇训练就是一个很好的例子。你只需将你的健身计划调整到间歇训练可以分为：练习、游泳练习、感官技能练习或其他技能培养技巧。尝试以下一些典型的组合：

Remember the bedrock principle of the Total Immersion program? “Fitness is something that happens to you while you’re practicing good technique.” Fitness intervals are a perfect example. You can build fitness and efficiency at the same time simply by turning your fitness intervals into drills, drill-swims, sensory skill practice, or other skill-building technique. Try some of these typical combinations:

 

 

1. 练习： 16 × 50 滑行（或您选择的），休息 20 秒。

1. Drill: 16 × 50 slide & glide (or your choice) on 20 seconds rest.

2. 练习游泳： 12 × 75，休息 20 秒（50 秒练习，25 秒游泳）。

2. Drill-swim: 12 × 75 on 20 seconds rest (50 drill, 25 swim).

3. 感觉技能练习： 8×100，休息20秒（50秒下坡游泳，50秒无重量手臂游泳）。

3. Sensory skill practice: 8 × 100 on 20 seconds rest (50 swim downhill, 50 swim with a weightless arm).

4. 划水消除器： 8 × 100，休息 20 秒（保持每长度 17-18 次划水 [s/l]，假设“正常”s/l [每长度划水次数] 为 19-20）。

4. Stroke eliminators: 8 × 100 on 20 seconds rest (hold at 17–18 strokes per length [s/l], assuming a “normal” s/l [strokes per length] of 19–20).

5. 游泳高尔夫： 8×50，每组休息20秒。将每次划水次数和时间相加，得出每次的得分，并尝试在第一次到第八次之间降低你的得分。

5. Swimming golf: 8 × 50 on 20 seconds rest. Add strokes and time for each repeat to get score for each repeat, and try to reduce your score between reps one and eight.

2. 比赛准备间隔

2. RACE READINESS INTERVALS

（占总训练码数的 0% 至 30%）

(0 PERCENT TO 30 PERCENT OF TOTAL TRAINING YARDAGE)

为比赛做准备的最佳方式就是比赛，因此在这些间歇训练中，你可以模拟发令枪响后你将面临的速度和身体压力。通常的目标是让你的心血管系统和骨骼肌更能承受氧债。（肌肉需要的氧债超过了心血管系统所能提供的。）“完全沉浸式训练”的目标更进一步：让你练习在比赛速度下保持效率。你需要尽量减少体能间歇训练和速度间歇训练之间的时间差。你的总时间不应该增加。速度间隔的增加量超过 10%，因此，如果您在健身间隔上保持 18，那么速度间隔的增加量就不要超过 20。

The best way to get ready for a race is to race, so on these intervals you simulate the speeds and physical stresses you’ll face after the gun goes off. The usual goal is to make your cardiovascular system and skeletal muscles more able to tolerate oxygen debt. (Muscles need more than the CV system can deliver.) The Total Immersion goal goes a step further: to let you practice holding on to your efficiency at racing speeds. You do that by trying to minimize the difference in s/l between your fitness intervals and your speed intervals. Your total should not increase by more than 10 percent on speed intervals, so if you hold 18 on fitness intervals, don’t take more than 20 on speed intervals.

1:1 的工作：休息比例应该提供足够的恢复，让您在每次重复时达到最大速度（和心率）的 80% 或更多，这是您应该进行比赛准备间隔的时间。

A work:rest ratio of 1:1 should provide enough recovery to let you reach 80 percent or more of maximum speed (and heart rate) on each repeat, which is where you should do your race readiness intervals.

示例：

EXAMPLES:

（重复的总距离应等于比赛距离的 60% 到 100%。例如：为准备 1500 米，请进行 20-30 组× 50 次，或 10-15 组× 100 次。）

(Total distance of repeats should equal 60 percent to 100 percent of race distance. Example: To prep for 1500 meters, do sets of 20–30 × 50, or 10–15 × 100.)

8-30 × 50（休息30-60秒）

8–30 × 50 (30–60 seconds rest)

6-20 × 75（休息45-90秒）

6–20 × 75 (45–90 seconds rest)

4-15 × 100（60秒 - 休息2分钟）

4–15 × 100 (60 seconds–2 minutes rest)

（计算划水次数或进行游泳高尔夫运动。）

(Count strokes or play swimming golf on all.)

3. 速度间歇训练

3. SPEED INTERVALS

（占总训练码数的 0% 至 10%）

(0 PERCENT TO 10 PERCENT OF TOTAL TRAINING YARDAGE)

这些是你的比赛“精修学校”，因为它们通过让你以比赛速度或更快的速度游出比比赛更短的距离，锻炼你在比赛中所需的一切——无氧系统、游泳专项力量以及在比赛速度下保持高效的能力。你的“完全沉浸式”训练目标是以尽可能低的划数达到最高的速度。训练与休息的比例为1:2到1:3。组数和重复次数都很短，每周只进行一次或最多两次。

These are your racing “finishing school,” since they work on everything you need in a race—the anaerobic system, swimming-specific power, and your ability to stay efficient at race speeds—by letting you swim distances shorter than the race at race pace or faster. Your Total Immersion goal is to produce the most speed on the lowest possible stroke count. The work:rest ratio is 1:2 to 1:3. Sets and repeats are short and are done only once or, at most, twice a week.

示例：

EXAMPLES:

50至100码比赛，每组8次，每组25分钟（休息40至60秒）

8 × 25 (40–60 seconds rest) for 50- to 100-yard races

100-200码比赛，4-10组，每组50分钟（90秒，休息3分钟）

4–10 × 50 (90 seconds–3 minutes rest) for 100- to 200-yard races

100-200码比赛，4-8组，每组75分钟（休息2-3分钟）

4–8 × 75 (2–3 minutes rest) for 100- to 200-yard races

500至1650码比赛，每组3-8组100米（休息3-5分钟）

3–8 × 100 (3–5 minutes rest) for 500- to 1650-yard races

（计算划水次数或进行游泳高尔夫运动。）

(Count strokes or play swimming golf on all.)

用节奏钟游泳并不意味着要一直游到筋疲力尽，而是要用智慧游泳。任何人都可以一头扎进泳池，在泳池里来回翻腾，直到精疲力竭。很多人这样做，认为无论速度如何提升，速度都能让他们成为更优秀的运动员。但他们为此付出的代价是时间的浪费和效率的损失。间歇训练则能给你一个目标，以及一种结构化、有目的性的方法来衡量你在朝着目标前进的道路上取得的进步。

Swimming with the pace clock doesn’t mean swimming ’til you drop. It does mean swimming smart. Anyone can dive in and just churn up and down the pool until the gas runs out. Many do, thinking speed will make them better athletes regardless of how they get it. But the price they pay in wasted time and lost efficiency is high. Intervals give you a goal instead, and a structured and purposeful way of measuring your progress along the path toward it.

而完全沉浸式间隔会给你最直接的路径。

And Total Immersion intervals give you the most direct path of all.

12

12

比赛。

这只是一种训练而已

Racing.

It’s Just Training with a Twist

备受敬爱的跑步哲学家兼心脏病专家乔治·希恩医生曾被问及慢跑者和跑步者的区别。他的回答堪称医学界的简洁典范：“一张比赛报名表。”

The beloved running philosopher and cardiologist Dr. George Sheehan was once asked the difference between a jogger and a runner. His reply was a model of medical brevity: “A race entry form.”

诚然，这多少有点精英主义，但在一项拥有自身阶级体系和相应词汇的运动中，这却是一个聪明且必要的区分。我们不是。在泳池里，每个人都是游泳者，就是这样。

A trifle elitist, to be sure, but a clever and necessary distinction in a sport that has its own class system and a vocabulary to match. We don’t. In the pool, everyone is a swimmer, period.

但这并不意味着参加比赛的游泳运动员和我们这些每周训练的人没有区别。在计时器的注视下，与同龄人并肩作战，投入训练，这种感觉无与伦比，能让你集中注意力。我推荐这种训练方式。而且，几乎一年四季，全国各地都会举办数百场全民大师赛，即使你不是特别优秀的运动员，也能在赛后对自己的成绩感到满意。

But that’s not to say swimmers who race aren’t a little different from those of us who just do our workouts week in, week out. There’s something about putting your training on the line, side by side with your peers and in full view of the timers, that focuses you as nothing else can. I recommend it. And with the hundreds of all-comers Masters meets held around the country at practically any time of year, you don’t have to be an especially accomplished athlete to feel good about your results when you’re done.

如果你已经参加过一两场比赛，你就会明白我的意思。如果你还没有——或者你想在下一场比赛中运用一些“完全沉浸式”策略，更好地应对——请继续阅读。

If you’ve already got a meet or two behind you, you know what I mean. If you haven’t—or if you’d like to do your next one better armed with a little Total Immersion strategy—please read on.

顺便说一句，终身游泳者可能在几乎任何其他有氧运动中都比终身竞争对手具有竞赛优势：许多人实际上在成年后的表现比他们在高中或大学队。中年战胜青年？完全不是。没有人认为游泳可以推翻衰老规律。我们想再次强调的是，你的成功很大程度上源于良好的技术，而非纯粹的体能。“全浸式”训练计划将为你提供工具，让你在未来多年持续提升技术和成绩。因此，无论你从未参加过比赛，还是立志打破年轻时的个人最好成绩，持续进步的几率都非常高。

Lifelong swimmers, by the way, probably have a racing advantage over lifelong competitors in practically any other aerobic sport: Many can actually do better as adults than they did on their high school or college teams. The triumph of middle age over youth? Not at all. Nobody is suggesting that swimming repeals the laws of aging. What we are saying—again—is that so much more of your success comes from good technique instead of sheer fitness, and the Total Immersion program gives you the tools to keep improving your technique—and your times—for many years. So whether you’ve never raced before or are aiming to topple the personal bests of your youth, the odds of continued improvement are very high.

不要为了奖牌而比赛。至少一开始不要。参加比赛是因为提前做好准备就能产生一种期待感，这必然会让你所有的训练都更有目的、更有重点。参加比赛是因为在比赛中游得好，在比赛中你尽了全力，这比任何练习都更能带来满足感。最重要的是，参加比赛是对你练习水平的终极考验。

Don’t race for medals. Not at the beginning, at least. Do race because simply entering a competition well in advance creates an anticipation that inevitably gives purpose and focus to all your training. And do race because an event swum well, an event you’ve given your best, is more deeply satisfying than any practice. And do race, above all else, because it’s the ultimate test of how well you have practiced.

正如我们在第 9 章中所说，不存在所谓的“通用”比赛训练。你需要针对你的比赛项目，并为此进行专门的准备。大量的耐力训练会让你成为世界上最差的短跑运动员，反之亦然。就像路跑一样，你会发现适合任何个性的比赛长度——从短距离激烈的速度竞赛到长时间的耐力和持久力测试。每种比赛的训练组合都略有不同。所以，选择你的“长度”（短、中或长），继续阅读，了解你需要做些什么准备，然后开始吧。

And as we said in chapter 9, there’s no such thing as “generic” race training. You target your event, and you ready yourself specifically for it. Lots of endurance work will make you the world’s worst sprinter, and vice versa. Just as in road running, you’ll find event lengths to suit any personality—short and sharp speed contests to long tests of endurance and staying power. And the training mix for each is a little different. So pick your “size” (short, medium, or long), read on to find out what you need to do to prep for it, and get started.

比赛？有小型、中型和大型

Races? There’s Small, Medium, and Large

1.短跑：50-100码/米

1. SPRINTS: 50–100 YARDS/METERS

当被问及短距离比赛的制胜秘诀时，世界纪录保持者兼奥运冠军马特·比昂迪回答道：“四个：技术、技术、技术、速度。” 想要在20到90秒内尽可能快地游，并不需要太多的耐力。你需要的是一个极其高效的划水动作。只要确保在尽可能快地游动、心率飙升、乳酸涌入你无助而疼痛的肌肉时，你还能保持划水长度即可。

When once asked what wins sprint races, world record holder and Olympic champion Matt Biondi replied, “Four things: technique, technique, technique, and speed.” It doesn’t take much endurance to swim as fast as you can for twenty to ninety seconds. A deadly efficient stroke is what you need. Just make sure you can hold your stroke length when you’re going as fast as you possibly can, when your heart rate is crashing through the roof, and lactic acid is flooding into your hapless and hurting muscles.

效率在短跑比赛中至关重要，因为100米的速度可能比1500米快20%到25%，而阻力和克服阻力所需的力量差异巨大。在短跑比赛中，微小的效率低下会被放大。

Efficiency is so critical in short races because you’re probably going 20 percent to 25 percent faster in the 100 meters than the 1500, for example, and the difference in drag and the power needed to overcome it is enormous. Small inefficiencies become hugely magnified in a sprint.

但你也不能忽视为肌肉提供充足的能量和氧气，因为肌肉正在拼命地消耗能量和氧气，为你的身体提供动力，让你的身体完成这场超负荷的运动。你的身体系统还必须以肌肉产生乳酸的速度，尽快清除掉消耗能量的乳酸，这样才能让肌肉继续运转。

But you can’t overlook the need to supply enough energy and oxygen to muscles that are gulping it down for all they’re worth, powering your body through this over-the-top effort. Your system also has to whisk away all that energy-sapping lactic acid as fast as your muscles produce it if they’re to keep going.

当然，这一切都意味着无氧训练，在加快练习节奏的同时，你不能让你的划水动作变得马虎。

All that means anaerobic training, of course, and you can’t let your stroke get sloppy while pushing the practice pace.

最后，你需要通过训练神经肌肉系统来获得力量，调动所有可用的肌肉运动单元，克服划水效率尚未消除的阻力。这意味着游泳“力量组”，即以最大努力进行短时间的重复训练。（请参阅附录中的一些建议。）

Finally, you need the power that comes from training your neuromuscular system to fire up all available muscle motor units to overcome whatever drag your stroke efficiency hasn’t eliminated. That means swimming “power sets,” short reps at top effort. (See the appendix for some suggestions.)

 

 

2. 中距离：200-400码/米

2. MIDDLE DISTANCE: 200–400 YARDS/METERS

有时也被称为速度/耐力项目，因为它们需要两者兼顾，也是最难训练的项目之一。你没有休息时间。速度相当接近短跑，但你必须坚持十倍的时间。真正考验你技术和效率的并非短跑中更高的划水频率，而是这些比赛中令人惊讶的无氧运动量，即使它们比短跑更长更慢。如果没有足够的空气，很难在整整四分之一英里的比赛中保持对划水的精准控制。

Sometimes called speed/endurance events because they take both, these are among the most difficult to train for. You don’t get a break. Speeds are fairly close to the sprint, but you’ve got to hold on for up to ten times as long. It’s not the higher stroke rate of the shorter sprints that will crack your technique and efficiency but the surprising amount of anaerobic work in these races, even though they’re longer and slower than sprints. It’s hard to stay fussy about your stroke over an entire quarter mile without enough air.

当然，随着你的技术开始衰退，保持速度的“能量消耗”也会随之增加，即使你剩余的能量随着秒表的滴答声而越来越少。因此，中距离跑者需要双管齐下的训练策略：

Of course, as your technique starts to come apart, the “energy cost” of holding your speed inflates even as you have less and less left with every tick of the stopwatch. So middle-distance racers need a two-pronged training strategy:

 

 

1. 长时间的有氧运动组是为了提高耐力——如果这些运动组能够同时训练神经系统和有氧系统，并且也注重划水效率，那么效果会更好。

1. Long, aerobic sets for endurance—sets that will do far more good if they train the nervous system right along with the aerobic system, focusing on stroke efficiency too.

 

 

2. 比赛速度游泳，培养更高速度下的耐力，并让你习惯划水频率和无氧条件，这些距离对身体来说是一次全面的考验。

2. Race-pace swimming, to develop endurance at higher speeds and get you used to the stroke rate and anaerobic conditions that make these distances such a thorough test.

归根结底，关键在于找到并保持正确的节奏——避免氧债，尽可能长时间地进行有氧运动。（记住，你的划水效率越高，你就能坚持得越久。）达到那种有氧优雅的状态。）除非你以均匀的速度游完比赛的大部分时间，否则这个技巧很难掌握。前半程的火热通常意味着后半程的痛苦。这就是为什么世界上最好的中距离游泳运动员几乎总是能游出与前半程一样快甚至更快的后半程。掌握这个技巧需要练习。（请参阅附录中的一些建议。）

What it all comes down to is finding and holding the right pace—staying out of oxygen debt, operating aerobically for as long as you can. (The more efficient your stroke, remember, the longer you can hold on to that aerobic state of grace.) It’s a hard trick to pull off unless you swim most of the race at an even pace. A blazing first half usually guarantees a painful second half. That’s why the world’s best middle-distance swimmers almost always swim the second half as fast as or even faster than the first. And mastering that tactic takes practice. (See the appendix for some suggestions.)

 

 

3. 长距离游泳：800米及以上

3. DISTANCE SWIMMING: 800 METERS AND UP

对于每年成千上万的跑步爱好者来说，他们选择游泳来寻求不那么消耗体力的锻炼方式，认为两英里的竞走比赛与短跑比赛相差无几。然而，游泳比赛的距离如此之短，着实令人意外。1500米，顶尖选手可能只需要15到20分钟——几乎相当于5公里跑的时间——是大多数游泳运动员参加过的最长的比赛。而马拉松比赛的时长通常为3到5小时，这对跑步者来说相当常见，但在游泳比赛中却几乎闻所未闻。

For the thousands of runners who turn to swimming every year to find less body-punishing workouts and who think of a two-mile footrace as barely the far side of a sprint, the comparatively short distance–horizon in swimming comes as a surprise. The 1500 meter, which may take a top contender fifteen to twenty minutes—nearly the same time as a 5K run—is the longest event most swimmers ever enter. And the marathon’s time span of three to five hours, a fairly common experience for runners, is all but unheard of in swimming.

那么，为什么如此强调高码数训练呢？因为游泳教练认为，我们不仅要培养耐力，还要培养“对水的感觉”，这其实就是自然效率的另一种说法。他们认为，要培养这种感觉，需要多年的练习和数百万码的重复训练。

So why all the emphasis on high-yardage training? Because swim coaches believe we must not only develop endurance but also “feel for the water,” which is really just another way of saying natural efficiency. And they believe it takes years of practice and millions of yards of repetition to develop this.

并非如此。如果你能加速发展高效划水，这正是你在本书中学习的内容，那么你就能大幅减少准备耐力游泳所需的码数。相反，你应该努力发展我所说的效率耐力，即无论游多远都能保持划水节奏的能力。训练设定的距离是比赛距离的一半。如果您使用它们来练习并提高保持长距离和高效划桨的能力，请这样做，一圈又一圈。

It doesn’t. If you can accelerate the development of an efficient stroke, which is just what you’re learning to do in this book, then you can drastically reduce the yardage it takes to prep for an endurance swim. Instead, you work on developing what I call efficiency endurance, the ability to keep your stroke the same whatever distance you swim. Training sets up to half again the distance of your race will do this if you use them to practice and improve your ability to keep your stroke long and efficient, lap after lap after lap.

教练们如此强调游泳运动员进行大码数训练的第二个原因，是为了培养“头脑中的时钟”，即以恰当速度游泳的本能，这样他们就不会在一开始就因为过度游泳而葬送比赛。长距离游泳运动员会不断地练习速度控制，学习如何在疲劳加剧的情况下，一圈又一圈地保持相同的速度。缩短学习曲线的一个方法是采用我们在上一章中提到的递减次数游法，在长距离游组中，每次游速都会逐渐加快。（示例见附录。）

The second reason coaches push so much high-yardage training on swimmers is to develop the “clock in the head,” the instinct for swimming at just the right pace so they don’t kill the race by overswimming at the beginning. Distance swimmers practice pacing endlessly, learning how to keep going at the same pace for lap after lap even as fatigue mounts. One way to shorten the learning curve is by swimming descending reps, which we mentioned in the last chapter, in which each one gets progressively faster during a long set. (See the appendix for samples.)

如何做好准备。真正做好准备

How to Be Ready. Really Ready

良好的训练并不一定能保证比赛顺利。领先的位置属于那些做好充分准备的人，他们从确定需要多少热身，到了解比赛的走向，以及每个赛段的预期。

Good training doesn’t necessarily guarantee a good race. The lead spots go to those who’ve done their homework, from deciding how much warmup they’ll need to knowing how the event plays out, what to expect on every length.

如果你已经为1650码自由泳（相当于1500米）做好了准备，那么你几乎可以为任何项目做好准备。它被称为游泳界的公制英里，相当于在25码的泳池里游66个来回。虽然这是我个人最喜欢的项目，但我对待它总是抱着爱恨交加的态度。爱是因为这是我最擅长的距离，而且总能在这个距离上取得我最高的全国排名（只领先几秒）。恨是因为它会带给我巨大的痛苦。

If you’ve done the homework for a 1650-yard freestyle (the equivalent of the 1500-meter event) you can get yourself ready for most anything. Otherwise known as swimming’s metric mile, it’s 66 lengths of a 25-yard pool, and though it’s my personal favorite, I always approach it with a love-hate attitude. Love because it’s my best distance and the one in which I’ve always reached my highest national rankings (a couple of seconds). Hate because it promises lots of pain.

我参加过感觉更轻松的长距离游泳比赛。我参加过感觉更轻松的长距离跑步比赛，尽管我的游泳水平比跑步高得多。45到50分钟的10公里赛跑似乎远不如在泳池里游1650码，我大概18到19分钟就能完成。即使是5公里公开水域游泳，我也花了68分钟，但这比我在泳池里游过的任何1650码比赛都要轻松。

I’ve swum longer races that felt easier. I’ve run longer races more comfortably, even though I’m a much better swimmer than runner. A 45- to 50-minute 10K footrace doesn’t seem anywhere near as long as a 1650 in the pool, which I can knock off in maybe 18 or 19 minutes. Even a 5K open-water swim, which took me 68 minutes, was easier than any 1650-yard race I’ve ever swum in a pool.

或许是因为需要高度集中精力保持高效的划桨效率，每一圈都感觉比上一圈更难。或许是因为随着圈数增加，大量的回转弯道让你难以保持有氧。但无论原因如何，这场比赛考验着你的一切：你的精神集中力、效率的持久力以及你的体能素质。所以，为这场比赛做准备实际上是所有赛前准备工作的清单。根据个人经验，以下是我在准备和应对1650米比赛时的建议。如果你准备的是短距离比赛，只需调整我的训练计划即可。

Perhaps it’s because of the need for such fierce concentration on keeping your stroke efficient, with every lap feeling harder than the last. Perhaps it’s all the flip turns that make it hard to stay aerobic as the laps mount. But whatever the reason, this race tests it all: your mental focus, the staying power of your efficiency, and the quality of your conditioning. So getting ready for it is a virtual punch list for all prerace preparation. Based on personal experience, here’s how I advise leading up to and handling a 1650. If you’re prepping for a shorter distance, just adapt my routine to suit.

几天前，我开始思考，如果我愿意全力以赴，在比赛中身体开始恳求我放弃的时候不退缩，那会是什么感觉。这会是极限努力吗？还是更难？当然是极限努力。

Several days before, I begin to think about what it will feel like if I’m willing to take it to the limit and not back off in the race when the body starts imploring me to. Will this be a redline effort or something less? Redline, of course.

比赛日到来时，我会进行长时间、轻松的赛前热身——通常至少40到45分钟，而比赛时间却不到比赛时间的一半。这样做有几个好处。首先，轻松流畅地游动可以缓解紧张情绪。其次，你可以利用热身时间，让自己的划水速度达到教练所说的轻松速度，一种轻松、熟悉的节奏，一种在预计的比赛速度下可以掌控、毫不费力的感觉。要达到这种感觉至少需要几分钟，但我不想把1650米的前500米都用来摸索，所以我现在就开始练习这种感觉。

Come competition day I get in the mood with a long, easy, pre-event warmup—typically at least forty to forty-five minutes for a race that takes less than half as long. This does several things. First, just swimming smoothly and easily takes the nervous edge off. Second, you can use the warmup to groove your stroke into what coaches call easy speed, a relaxed, familiar rhythm, a feeling of being controlled and effortless at your projected race pace. It takes at least several minutes to get that, but I don’t want to spend the first 500 of my 1650 groping around for it, so I rehearse the feeling now.

我会反复练习，直到完全掌握，大概要跑六到八次100码——几乎是比赛距离的一半——每次都努力精准地达到目标配速，保持轻松奔跑的那种轻松感。为了参加第16场比赛以相同的节奏跑100米，每次都要更卖力一些，因为肌肉会逐渐感到新的疲劳。前几个感觉毫不费力，但最后几个感觉就像在举钢琴。如果我能完成6到8个这样的项目，中间休息15到20秒，我就更有信心，一旦发令枪响，我就能以同样的节奏，不休息地连续完成16个。

And I rehearse until it’s right, maybe six or eight 100-yard repeats—nearly half the distance of the race itself—trying to hit target pace precisely on each with that buoyant feeling of easy speed. To race sixteen identically paced 100s, you have to go a little harder on each as a new layer of fatigue settles into your muscles. The first few will feel nearly effortless, the last ones will feel like you’re lifting a piano. If I can hit six or eight of these with 15 to 20 seconds of rest between, I’m more confident that once the gun goes off, I’ll be able to reel off sixteen in a row, with no rest, at the same pace.

如果你在长距离比赛开始前完成热身/练习，你可能会在比赛初期感觉更好。从热身池到起跑器，你的肌肉已经准备好，比赛节奏也已经设定好，这是很有道理的。如果做得正确，像这样在比赛前进行长时间的热身会让你的体能得到净增长，因为你一直在练习的是能量守恒。

You’ll probably feel better in the early stages of a distance race if you finish your warmup/rehearsal just before your heat starts. There’s something to be said for going right from the warmup pool to the starting blocks, with your muscles prepared and your race rhythms all set. Done correctly, a long warmup like this right before the race gives you a net gain in the gas tank, since what you’ve been practicing is energy conservation.

你也一直在脑中设定那个建立自信的“时钟”，教练用这个词来形容你对速度的精准把握。泳池比赛是一对一，所以不存在跟在别人后面的情况。即使你能尝试，你也可能不想尝试。1650米太长了，不适合尝试代替别人比赛。按照你训练的方式进行，你的表现会更好。这意味着要有一个目标时间，并制定一个达到目标的速度计划。

You’ve also been setting that confidence-building “clock in the head,” the coach’s term for an unerring sense of pace. Pool racing is done one to a lane, so there’s no such thing as drafting behind anyone. And you might not want to try even if you could. The 1650 is too long to try to swim someone else’s race. You perform far better when you do it the way you’ve trained for it. That means having a goal time in mind and a pace plan for reaching it.

终于到了比赛时间。枪声响起，做好这些准备工作后，你就会全身心投入，变得非常平静。从一开始，你的划桨感觉就恰到好处。现在需要耐心。前400到500码（16到20个桨位）的距离，避免比赛。你处于跟踪状态。尽可能保持划桨距离，尽可能降低划桨频率，并与对手保持一定距离。一切都与效率有关，因此效率会深深地印在你的神经系统上，即使即将到来的疲劳和比赛压力也无法将其摧毁。

Finally it’s time to race. When the gun goes off and you dive in after this kind of prep work, you’ll become quite calm. From the first, your stroke feels just the way you want it to. Now’s the time to be patient. For the first 400 to 500 yards (16 to 20 lengths), avoid racing. You’re stalking. Keep your stroke as long as possible and your stroke rate as low as possible, and stay within striking distance of your rivals. Everything goes into efficiency, so it’s indelibly imprinted onto your nervous system and the coming fatigue and racing pressures can’t break it down.

无论你做什么，都要避免氧债。你很兴奋，可能正在努力跟上。任何比赛的前半段都很容易游过头，然后滑过无氧阈值。一旦滑过，唯一的恢复方法就是放慢速度，而一旦你放慢了速度，就几乎不可能再把速度完全拉上来。哦，最终你得进入无氧状态才能保持速度，但你最好尽可能在比赛快结束时进行。在比赛的四分之三时间里保持有氧状态，这样你就能为最后几百米的比赛做好准备。

Whatever you do, stay out of oxygen debt. You’re excited. You may be trying to keep up. It’s too easy to overswim the first part of any race and slip across the anaerobic threshold. Once you do, the only way to recover will be to slow down, and once you’ve slackened the pace, it’s nearly impossible to push it all the way up again. Oh, eventually you’ll have to go anaerobic just to hold on to your pace, but you want that to come as near the end of the race as possible. Stay aerobic for three quarters of the race, and you’ll have what it takes in the tanks for the last few 100s.

最终，你会和疲劳玩一场猫捉老鼠的游戏。你完全凭意志力，努力保持划桨长度，但随着你越来越累，你唯一的办法就是小心地提高划桨频率。用臀部转动来做，而不是肌肉力量。（反正你的肌肉现在已经没有那么多多余的力量了。）试着每划100米就稍微提高一点，正好抵消疲劳。这是一场微妙的游戏，但如果你练习得足够多，你就能成功。

Eventually, you’ll be playing a cat-and-mouse game with fatigue. In a sheer act of will, you try to keep your stroke long, but as you get a little more tired your only recourse is to increase stroke rate—carefully. Do this with hip rolling, not muscle power. (Your muscles don’t have that much to spare by now anyhow.) Try to dial it up just a little on each 100 to exactly offset fatigue. It’s a delicate game, but if you’ve practiced enough, you can play it successfully.

你现在已经游了大约1200码，但谁在数呢？答案是，朋友们在数。在起跑器对面的泳池尽头，每次转身前都会有一张写着圈数的卡片塞到你面前。这场比赛需要高度集中注意力，根本记不住你的圈数，所以会有一个朋友跪在你的泳道尽头，热情地把那些写着圈数的卡片塞进水里，并在你转身时大声鼓励你。

You’re up to about 1200 yards now, but who’s counting? The answer is, friends are. At the end of the pool opposite the starting blocks, a card showing the lap number is shoved in front of your face just before every turn. This race takes so much concentration that it’s impossible to keep track of your lap count, so a friend kneels at the end of your lane and obligingly shoves those numbered cards into the water, shouting encouragement as you turn.

你现在快追上来了。最后16到20个马身，是时候真正发力了。开始数数。计分卡显示51，你即将进入第52圈，你心想：只剩14个马身了——我一定能赢。

You’re closing in now. The last sixteen to twenty lengths, and it’s time to really bear down. Begin to count. The card reads 51, you’re headed into lap 52, and you’re thinking, Only fourteen to go—I can bring this home.

是时候看看你是由什么组成的了。无论你多么容易一开始就游，无论你中间的配速多么合理，最后几百码你都会全身缺氧。每次翻身转身都像是一记有氧耳光，因为翻身转身会在每一面墙切断你的氧气供应几秒钟。太好了，正是你需要的。脸露出水面的开放式转身固然很好，但每面墙都要耗费宝贵的时间，你游到现在可不是来浪费时间的。可惜的是，每次转身后你似乎都需要游完全程才能恢复呼吸，而刚好恢复呼吸，你又会被打回原形。

Time to find out what you’re made of. No matter how easily you swam the beginning, no matter how intelligent your pace in the middle, your whole body will start to ache for oxygen over the last few hundred yards. Every flip turn seems like an aerobic slap in the face, since the flip turn cuts off your oxygen for a few seconds at each wall. Great. Just what you need. An open turn with your face above water would be so nice, but it costs precious fractions at each wall and you didn’t come this far to throw time away now. Too bad it seems like you need the whole length to get your breath back from every turn and just when you have, you get slapped down again.

还剩八圈。现在六圈。现在只剩四圈了。每游50圈都更难，但也让你更接近解脱。最后，你把剩下的力气都用在最后两圈上，把手放在触摸板上，比赛结束了！

Eight lengths to go. Now six. Now just four. Each 50 gets harder, but each brings you closer to relief. Finally, you pour everything you have left into the last two lengths, thrust your hand to the touch pad, and it’s over!

哪怕是精疲力竭地挂在排水沟里几分钟，也会很疼，因为乳酸会在产生乳酸的肌肉里积聚。所以，蹬水后，游几圈轻松的仰泳，把乳酸排出来。你完成了。你已经把全浸式训练运用到了比赛中，并证明了即使身体其他部位出现问题，只要训练得当，你的肌肉也能“自动运转”。

For a couple of minutes even hanging exhausted on the gutter will hurt, as lactic acid pools in the muscles that generated it. So push off and swim a few massaging laps of easy backstroke to wash some of it out. You’re finished. You’ve taken your Total Immersion training into the contest and proven that even when the rest of the body falters, your muscles can go on autopilot if you’ve trained them well.

至少对我来说，像这样的比赛是一场自我探索的练习。我感兴趣的不是最终成绩，而是更广阔的视角，看看我的训练如何为今天的比赛做好准备。我更感兴趣的是检验自己执行良好比赛计划的能力，而不是我可能赢得什么颜色的奖牌。我参加的每一场比赛都蕴含着独特的经验教训，每当我回到泳池进行下一次练习时，我总是渴望将这些经验教训付诸实践。

And for me at least, racing like this is an exercise in self-discovery. My final time interests me less than the broader revelation of how well my training has prepared me to race on this particular day. I’m more curious about testing my abilities to execute a good race plan than in what color medal I may have won. And every race I swim presents its own set of lessons, which I am always eager to apply when I return to the pool for my next practice.

十三

13

泳池工具：

少即是多

Pool Tools:

Less Is More

别误会，你只需拥有自己的身体、泳衣和一些专业的教练，就能成为一名优秀的游泳运动员。无需任何辅助工具。

Make no mistake about it. You can become an excellent swimmer with nothing more than your own body, a swimsuit, and some smart coaching. No accessories necessary.

但其实有很多可用的训练器材。其中一些确实很有帮助。浮板可能是最常见的，其次是脚蹼。手桨、浮标、弹性系绳——所有这些都能带来更大的力量或更快的速度。据说它们的工作原理就像水中的负重器械，可以让你单独锻炼需要锻炼的肌肉，然后通过集中训练来强化它们。

But there are plenty available. Some of them are actually helpful. Kickboards may be the most familiar, followed closely by fins. Hand paddles, pull buoys, elastic tethers—all beckon with the promise of greater strength or more impressive speed. They supposedly work like weight machines of the water, letting you isolate muscles you need to work on, then bear down on them with concentrated training.

有些是有益的，有些至少不会对你造成特别的伤害。还有一些听起来不错，但往好了说是浪费时间，往坏了说是对你的游泳造成实际损害。诚然，几乎每个人都在使用它们，但这种情况表明，大多数人对这些训练辅助工具的真正作用存在误解。所以，让我们对它们进行批判性分析。

Some are beneficial. Others at least won’t do you particular harm. And still others sound good but are a waste of time at best and an actual detriment to your swimming at worst. It’s true that virtually everyone uses them, but this is one of those cases where most folks just have the wrong idea about what these training aids really do. So let’s give them a critical analysis.

在构成“游泳天赋”这一难以界定的天赋的所有要素中，最有价值的是非凡的动觉意识——有天赋的游泳者比任何人都更懂得如何与水互动，从而减少阻力，实现更流畅的动作。但正如我所提到的，教练们所说的“游泳天赋”中，令人惊讶的是“天赋”是可以学习的。 “普通”游泳运动员毫无疑问可以提高自己的动觉意识，这总是比任何“训练”都能带来更快、更大的进步。

Of all the elements that make up the hard-to-define gift known as “swimming talent,” the most valuable is extraordinary kinesthetic awareness—gifted swimmers just know how to work with the water better than anyone else to achieve less resistance and more fluid movement. But, as I’ve suggested, a surprising amount of what coaches call “talent” is learnable. “Average” swimmers can unquestionably heighten their own kinesthetic awareness, which will always produce more improvement, more quickly, than anything under the heading of “work.”

最常用的训练工具有两个缺点：(1) 它们鼓励你专注于努力，而不是效率；(2) 它们会主动干扰你提高动觉意识的能力。最后，对于正在发展中的游泳运动员来说，还有一个问题是如何优先安排宝贵的时间用于最有价值的活动。TI 方法能帮助你立即提高游泳水平。而浮标、冲浪板和桨则根本做不到。

The most commonly used training tools have two drawbacks: (1) they encourage you to focus on effort, rather than efficiency; and (2) they actively interfere with your ability to improve your kinesthetic awareness. Finally, for developing swimmers there is also the issue of prioritizing precious time for activities that have the largest value. TI methods help you swim better immediately. Buoys, boards, and paddles simply don’t.

拒绝浮板

Just Say No to Kickboards

浮板训练的主要目的是让你的腿部保持良好状态，以便更用力地打腿。你为什么要用力打腿呢？(1) 因为你感觉你的腿在下沉，(2) 为了游得更快，或者 (3) 为了燃烧更多的卡路里或脂肪。但是 (1) 平衡——由 TI 训练所教授——是让你的腿保持漂浮的关键。(2) 快速流畅游泳的理想打腿方式是与身体整体运动无缝衔接。最后，(3) 正如下一章将解释的那样，燃烧卡路里和脂肪的最佳方式是更轻松的游泳方式。关于浮板的真相是，无论你是刚开始学习还是正在为全国锦标赛训练，它们对你提高自由泳水平的努力都毫无帮助。在浮板上使用的扑水动作——手臂、躯干和臀部严格锁定——与你在游泳时使用的打腿动作截然不同，因此浮板训练对发展打腿能力毫无价值。这有助于你的身体在水中高效移动。“锻炼腿部”也是如此。

The main idea of kickboard training is to get your legs in shape for kicking harder. And why would you want to kick harder? (1) Because you feel your legs sinking, (2) to swim faster, or (3) to burn more calories or fat. But (1) balance—taught by TI drills—is what keeps your legs afloat. And (2) the ideal kick for fast, fluent swimming is one that harmonizes seamlessly with overall body movement. Finally, (3) as the next chapter will explain, the best way to burn calories and fat is with easier swimming. The truth about kickboards is they will contribute absolutely nothing to your efforts to improve your freestyle, whether you’re just learning or are training for a national championship. The flutter used on a kickboard—with arms, torso, and hips rigidly locked in place—is so different from the kick you’ll use when swimming that kickboard sets have zero value for developing a kick that helps your body move efficiently through the water. Ditto for “conditioning your legs.”

由于在浮板上打水和游泳时腿部动作截然不同，浮板真正能训练的就是用浮板打水。如果你计划参加需要在泳池中推动浮板上下运动的比赛，那么浮板训练就很有意义；否则，完全是浪费时间！如果你想让你的腿“达到”游泳的“最佳状态”，那么在练习TI训练时放松的打水动作，就能让你的腿在比赛中保持最佳状态：保持放松。从此以后，你就不用再使用浮板了。

Because your legs move so differently when kicking on a board than while swimming, the only thing a kickboard really trains you for is kicking with a board. If you ever planned to enter a race that involved pushing a kickboard up and down the pool, then kickboard sets would make sense; otherwise, it’s a total waste of time! If you want your legs to be “in shape” for swimming, the relaxed kicking you do while practicing TI drills conditions your legs to do exactly what they need to do when you race: stay relaxed. You are dispensed from using a kick-board ever again.

失去浮标

Lose the Buoy
