拉浮标有一个主要缺点：它们会欺骗你，让你以为自己已经保持平衡。它们之所以受到成千上万游泳者的欢迎，是因为平衡能力差是一个常见问题。只要你戴着浮标，它就会支撑你的臀部和腿部。你会感觉更好，游得更快。问题是，使用它之后似乎并没有教会你如何保持平衡。一旦你取下浮标，那种下沉的感觉就会立刻回来，而且你的情况不会比以前好。想要永远在没有浮标的情况下感觉更好吗？平衡训练、保持头部与脊柱成一线、顺坡游泳以及戴着 fistgloves® 游泳，这些都能让你在游泳时保持平衡，并产生持久的教训。

Pull buoys have one central drawback: They fool you into thinking you’re balanced. They’re so popular with thousands of swimmers because poor balance is such a common problem. So long as you have a buoy on, it supports your hips and legs. You feel better and swim faster. The problem is that using it never seems to teach you how to stay balanced after you use it. As soon as you remove the buoy, that sinking feeling is right back and you’re no better off than before. Want to feel better without the buoy—permanently? Balance drills, keeping your head in line with your spine, swimming “downhill,” and swimming with fistgloves® produce lasting lessons in how to stay balanced while you swim.

至于用浮标训练可以增强你的拉力事实上，它通过超负荷和孤立你的手臂，适得其反。浮标的人工浮力会让你的身体在水中抬高，而它却让你的手臂负重不足——这对训练没有任何好处。此外，使用浮标实际上会损害你的划水力量，因为力量并非来自手臂，而是来自核心身体的旋转。浮标可能会抑制你的身体滚动，干扰你的节奏和力量。幸运的是，一旦你学会了平衡，戴上浮标就会感觉完全不对劲，这很快就会让你打消使用浮标的念头。

And as for the idea that training with a buoy strengthens your pull by overloading and isolating your arms, in fact, it does just the opposite. The artificial buoyancy of the buoy raises your body in the water; it underloads your arms—no training benefit at all. Moreover, using a buoy can actually hurt your stroking power, because power doesn’t come from the arms; it comes from core-body rotation. Buoys are likely to inhibit your body roll, interfering with your rhythm and power. Fortunately, once you do learn balance, putting on a buoy should feel all wrong, which will soon discourage you from using one.

使用浮标可能有一些价值的唯一情况是：如果你是那些非常瘦或肌肉密集的运动员之一，似乎永远都无法保持平衡，如果你在做平衡练习时感觉像是在做最后的挣扎，如果你的踢腿“疯狂”，你也许可以选择性地使用浮标作为打破挣扎循环的一种方式。使用一个相当小的浮标，轻松地游一圈。保持头部在一条直线上，尽可能安静地游。当你这样做的时候，调整到被支撑的感觉，能够从容不迫地向前滑动手臂，游得“更高”一点，能够放开你的踢腿。游一个圈后还没有感觉？用这种方式再游几个 25 秒。当这些感觉出现时，捕捉并记住它们。然后取下浮标，游两个 25 秒。保持头部在一条直线上，顺势游下坡。尽可能轻柔安静地游。你的目标只有一个：让你的无浮标游泳圈感觉尽可能接近有浮标游泳圈。耐心地重复这个模式十到十五分钟。当你的无浮标游泳圈感觉像有浮标游泳圈一样轻松时，再增加更多无浮标25圈。

The sole circumstance in which there might be some value in using a buoy is this: If you are one of those extremely lean or densely muscled athletes who seems permanently balance-challenged, if you experience what feels like terminal struggle while doing balance drills, if you have a “frantic” kick, you may be able to selectively use a buoy as one way to break the cycle of struggling. Using a fairly small buoy, swim a relaxed pool length. Keep your head in line and swim as silently as you can. As you do, tune in to how it feels to be supported, to be able to glide an unhurried arm forward and swim a little “taller,” to be able to let go of your kick. Can’t feel it after one length? Do a few more 25s that way. When those sensations come, just capture and imprint them. Then remove the buoy and swim two 25s without it. Keep your head in line and swim downhill. Swim as gently and quietly as possible. You have just one goal: to get your no-buoy laps to feel as much like the buoy lap as possible. Patiently repeat this pattern for ten or fifteen minutes. As your no-buoy laps begin to feel as relaxed as the buoyed laps, add more unbuoyed 25s.

智能手比愚蠢的塑料更好

Smart Hands Are Better Than Dumb Plastic

手划桨的妙处很简单：戴上它，突然感觉自己仿佛真的能抓住水面，有力地划动它。桨通常被强调为一种动力工具（理论上桨越大越好）。你利用额外的表面积来推动水流。但除非你的划桨技术完美，否则用桨推动水流只会增加肩部受伤的风险。而且，即使你足够幸运地避免受伤，一旦脱下桨，你也会感觉自己像是在用冰棍棒划船。这有什么好处呢？

The rap on hand paddles is pretty simple: You put them on and suddenly feel as if you can really grab the water and move it powerfully. Paddles are usually emphasized as a power tool (and the bigger the paddle, the better—or so the theory goes). You use the extra surface area to muscle the water. But unless you have a perfect stroke, muscling the water with paddles is mainly a good way to improve your chances of shoulder injury. And if you’re lucky enough to avoid injury, once you take them off, you feel like you’re trying to row with a Popsicle stick. What could be good about that?

和浮标一样，有一个小例外。你可以偶尔戴上小桨，用超慢的速度游几圈，专注于如何帮助你的手学会划破水面……或者无重力地向前滑很远……或者在抓水时保持稳定。然后取下桨，按照上面关于浮标使用的建议，试着在不使用桨的情况下重现那种感觉。除非你能在戴着桨的情况下减少至少两次划水，否则它们对你没有任何帮助。

As with pull buoys, there is one small exception. You might occasionally don small paddles for a few superslow laps with a narrow focus on how they may help your hand learn to pierce the water … or slide weightlessly forward a looong way … or anchor for the catch. Then remove them and, as suggested above for buoy use, try to recreate that sensation without the paddles. Unless you can subtract at least two strokes with the paddles on, they’re not helping you at all.

想要一双能教你像艺术家一样与水共舞的灵巧双手，不妨考虑一下拳套®。拳套已被证明是教授TI式游泳的必备辅助工具，因此我们会在TI周末工作坊为每位学员提供一副。我们喜欢拳套，因为它能让任何游泳者都变成问题解决者，而你提出的解决方案将帮助你以前所未有的方式控制水流。

For intelligent hands that can teach you to work with water like an artist, consider fistgloves®. Fistgloves have proven so indispensable as an aid to teaching TI-style swimming that we give a pair to every student at TI Weekend Workshops. We like them because they turn any swimmer into a problem solver and the solution you come up with will help you hold the water like never before.

Fistgloves® 带来的问题是：当你没有东西可以抓握时，如何抓住水？通过将双手握紧，用乳胶包裹，Fistgloves® 可以将宽阔平坦的表面变成一个橡胶块。在最初几圈，你的手在水中无助地滑动。但渐渐地，你会找到一个可以抓住的水分子，一部分是通过使用你的前臂来支撑身体，一部分是简单地学会更有耐心。只要以极大的耐心和注意力去抓水，你最终就能学会让水对你戴着手套的手产生一点点阻力。通过练习，你可以学会在最轻微的阻力下做出非凡的事情。通过继续耐心地划水，戴着手套游泳的感觉会逐渐变得几乎“正常”。过了一会儿，你甚至会怀疑自己是否戴着手套。通过计算每圈的划水次数和玩游泳高尔夫来衡量你获得了多少控制力。

The problem fistgloves® present is: How do you hold on to the water when you have nothing to hold on with? By squeezing the hands into a tight, latex-wrapped fist, fistgloves® turn a broad, flat surface into a rubber nub. On the first few lengths, your hands slip helplessly through the water. But gradually, you find one molecule of water to hold on to, partly by using your forearm for purchase, partly by simply learning to be more patient. Just by making the catch with exquisite patience and attention, you will eventually learn to get the water to resist your gloved hands just a little bit. With practice you can learn to do remarkable things with the slightest resistance. So much so that by continuing to stroke patiently, the gloved-swimming sensation will gradually come to feel almost “normal.” After a while, you may even wonder if you’re wearing a glove. Measure how much control you’re gaining by counting strokes per length and playing Swimming Golf.

当然，真正的魔力发生在你脱下手套的时候。突然间，你原本平凡的手变得无比巨大，仿佛手臂末端插着一把餐盘大小的桨，抓住水面变得轻而易举。

The real magic, of course, happens when you peel the gloves off. Suddenly, your previously ordinary-feeling hand seems huge, as if you had a dinner-plate-sized paddle at the end of your arm and holding on to the water turns out to be a piece of cake.

为什么 fistgloves® 比桨更适合用来训练对水的感觉？因为桨的作用恰恰相反。游泳者认为他们会学会拥有“大手”的感觉，而一旦桨脱落，他们就会记住他们想要的感觉。当桨戴着时，你当然会感觉更能控制水。但是当桨脱落时？你会感觉就像有人用冰棍棒划船。你的手看起来很笨，没有用。所以我们有时把 fistgloves® 称为“非桨”，因为使用 fistgloves® 之后，你的手似乎更聪明，而不是更笨。

Why are fistgloves® better than paddles for teaching feel of the water? Because paddles do exactly the opposite. Swimmers figure they’ll learn how it feels to have “big hands,” and that once the paddles come off they’ll remember the sensation they’re aiming for. While the paddles are on, you do of course feel much more able to hold the water. But when the paddles come off? You feel like someone rowing with a Popsicle stick. Your hands seem dumb, ineffectual. So we sometimes call fistgloves® the “unpaddles,” because after using fistgloves® your hands seem smarter, not dumber.

使用 Fistgloves® 最简单、最好的方法是每次练习的前 20 到 25 分钟都戴上，无论你在这段时间里做什么。每圈都会帮助你提高平衡感和技巧。当你脱下它们时，你会游得更加直觉。或者，在 60 分钟的练习中，你可以戴 20 分钟，取下 10 分钟，再戴上 20 分钟，最后再不戴游泳 10 分钟。

The simplest and best way to use fistgloves® is to wear them for the first twenty to twenty-five minutes of every practice, whatever you may be doing during that time. Every lap will help your balance and finesse. When you take them off you’ll swim with far more intuition the rest of the way. Or, during a 60-minute practice, you might wear them for 20 minutes, remove them for 10, put them on again for 20 minutes and swim without them for 10.

脚蹼是学习辅助工具，不是为了暂时提高速度

Fins as a Learning Aid, Not for Temporary Speed

我见过最常见的使用脚蹼的人是那些想要瞬间加速的人。所以他们戴上脚蹼，立刻就能游得更快。但是，就像浮标和桨一样，这正是脚蹼的问题所在。它们只是暂时的、人工的辅助工具，在你戴上它们的时候能让你游得更轻松或更快，但一旦你脱下它们，效果就会消失。没有任何学习。一点儿也不。为了更快而戴脚蹼就像是为了更高而穿厚底鞋一样。

The most common use of fins I’ve seen is by those who want a dose of instant speed. So they put on fins and instantly can swim much faster laps. But, as with buoys and paddles, that’s precisely the problem with fins. They’re a temporary and artificial aid that helps you swim easier or faster while you have them on, but the effect disappears as soon as you take them off. No learning happens. None. Wearing fins to be faster is like wearing platform shoes to be taller.

以这种方式使用脚蹼可能会妨碍您养成流畅、放松、高效的划水习惯。短叶脚蹼尤其适用于帮助您比使用全叶脚蹼时更快地打腿。您的腿移动得越快，您的手臂就必须移动得越快才能跟上。更快的周转率（即更高的 SR）不正是我们想要避免的吗？短脚蹼最初的设计目的是帮助短距离游泳运动员在借助脚蹼加速游泳时实现高划水率，并使游泳者的腿部适应短距离游泳时典型的用力打腿。同样，这正是 TI 游泳者想要避免的事情。

What fins might do, when used this way, is interfere with your ability to develop a fluent, relaxed, efficient stroke into a reliable habit. Short-blade fins, in particular, are specifically designed to help you kick faster than you could with full-blade fins. And the faster your legs move, the faster your arms have to move to keep up. Isn’t faster turnover (i.e., higher SR) precisely what we’re trying to avoid? Short fins were designed originally to help sprint swimmers achieve high stroke rates while swimming with fin-aided speed—and to condition a swimmer’s legs for the hard kicking that is typical when sprinting. Again, that’s precisely the kind of thing a TI swimmer wants to avoid.

脚蹼也有例外。正如我在第8章中解释的那样，对于那些脚踝僵硬、训练困难的人来说，脚蹼非常有帮助。使用脚蹼可以保存能量，让你专注于流畅、更可控的动作，有助于掌握技能。大多数情况下，即使你明智地使用脚蹼来提高你的训练技巧，最好在你切换到全程游泳时就把它们脱掉。

There are exceptions with fins as well. As I explained in chapter 8, they can be very helpful to anyone whose rigid ankles make drill practice an ordeal. Using fins to preserve your energy and allow yourself to focus on smooth, more controlled movement is an aid to mastering skills. For the most part, even if you use fins judiciously to improve your drill practice, it’s best to take them off as soon as you shift to whole-stroke swimming.

游泳长凳

Swim Benches

游泳凳在某些方面被宣传为比在泳池里游泳更好。制造商承诺，它们能完美训练你的划水动作，让你在家就能获得与在泳池里一样好的“游泳”锻炼效果，等等等等。事实上，这些凳子确实能增强你的手臂力量，让你得到某种程度的锻炼，但我对它们能否提高你的游泳水平持高度怀疑态度。在水中运动的身体和躺在凳子上的身体行为方式完全不同。不同的凳子，其生物力学（肌肉群相互作用的方式）和运动知觉（你的“肌肉感觉”）也截然不同。游泳凳训练最适合训练你进行游泳凳训练。如果你打算参加游泳凳比赛，那么一定要在凳子上训练。如果你必须在家里准备一些东西来补充你的游泳能力，你可以买一个售价仅为最便宜游泳凳5%的器材，却能提供其90%的益处。它叫做弹力绳。

Swim benches have been promoted as better, in some ways, than actually swimming in a pool. Their manufacturers promise they’ll perfect your stroke and allow you to get as good a “swim” workout at home as you could going to the pool, et cetera, et cetera. The fact is that these benches will make your arms stronger and give you a work-out of sorts, but I’m highly skeptical that they’ll improve your swimming. A body moving through water and a body lying on a bench behave in entirely different ways. The biomechanics (the way muscle groups interact) and the kinesthetics (your “muscle sense”) are dramatically different from bench to pool. Swim bench workouts train you best to do swim bench workouts. If you’re planning to enter swim bench competition, then by all means train on one. If you must have something at home to supplement your swimming, you can get a device that sells for about 5 percent of what the least expensive swim bench costs, yet will provide 90 percent of its benefit. It’s called a stretch cord.

弹力绳

Stretch Cords

弹力绳是一截乳胶管，两端带把手，中间有一个尼龙环，可以固定在各种固定物体上。二十多年来，弹力绳一直是我最喜欢的训练辅助工具之一，因为它是所有力量训练工具中价格最实惠、用途最广泛的，值得推荐给游泳运动员。事实上，新不伦瑞克大学的一项研究发现，每天进行20分钟的弹力绳训练（12到14分钟运动，6到8分钟休息），几乎可以帮助游泳运动员在三周的休赛期保持所有体能状态。

Stretch cords are lengths of latex tubing with handles at each end and a nylon loop in the middle that can anchor to a wide variety of fixed objects. Cords have been one of my favorite training aids for over twenty years because they’re the most affordable and versatile of any strength-building tool that can legitimately be recommended for swimmers. In fact, a study at the University of New Brunswick found that a daily stretch cord workout of 20 minutes (12 to 14 minutes of exercise, 6 to 8 minutes of rest) helped swimmers hang on to virtually all of their conditioning during a three-week layoff.

弹力绳能给你和水一样稳定、流畅的阻力。它们还能让你在几乎无限的运动范围内锻炼，只受关节和锻炼空间的限制。如果你使用重量来增强游泳力量，你也可以使用弹力绳作为力量训练室中非特定力量训练和泳池中游泳专项动作之间的“桥梁”。重量训练可以锻炼与你举重时所使用的动作最相关的肌肉。游泳对这些肌肉的使用方式不同，并且总是在低负荷的情况下进行。弹力绳训练有助于将你在力量训练室的力量转化为泳池力量，通过让你的肌肉进行游泳专项动作，但负荷比水能提供的要高得多。

Stretch cords give you the same steady, fluid resistance that water does. They also let you work through a virtually endless range of motion, limited only by your joints and your workout space. If you use weights to build swimming strength, you can also use cords as a “bridge” between nonspecific strength work in the weight room and swim-specific movement in the pool. Weight training builds muscles that are most specific to the movements you use while lifting the weights. Swimming uses those muscles differently and always in a low-load situation. Stretch cord training helps translate your weight room strength to pool strength by working your muscles in swimming-specific motions, but under much higher loads than water could provide.

最后，绳索可以轻松用于“赛前康复”训练，以纠正游泳造成的肌肉不平衡，并增强肩关节，防止肌腱炎和其他损伤。事实上，身体治疗师建议进行拉伸绳练习来康复许多肩部损伤。

Finally, cords can be easily used for “prehab” exercise to correct muscle imbalances caused by swimming, and to strengthen the shoulder joint to protect against tendinitis and other injuries. In fact, physical therapists prescribe stretch cord exercises to rehab many shoulder injuries.

游泳水槽

Swim Flumes

写这篇文章的时候，我正在地下室准备安装一台无边际泳池 (Endless Pool)，这是一种水槽式泳池，水流从前端循环，从后端流出。在本书的早期版本中，我曾担心，在原地游泳时，水流经过你的身体时，动态变化可能会损害完全沉浸式练习所要达到的效率。但在过去几年里，凭借着使用无边际泳池 (Endless Pool) 的经验，我改变了想法。

As I write this I’m having my basement prepared for the installation of an Endless Pool, a flume pool that circulates a water current in the front end and out the back. In an earlier edition of this book, I described concerns about how the dynamics of swimming in place while water moves past you could hurt the efficiency that Total Immersion practice is designed to build. In the last few years, with experience in an Endless Pool, I’ve changed my mind.

事实证明，对于越来越多的TI教练来说，将水流速度调低后，无边际泳池（Endless Pool）是教授和练习TI训练和技能的便捷高效场所。但如果水流速度过快，最终导致的划水效果与持续用力游泳一样糟糕。水流适中的水槽泳池主要有以下优点：

With the current set at slower speeds, the Endless Pool has proven, for a growing number of TI coaches, to be a convenient and effective place for both teaching and practicing TI drills and skills. But if you keep the current cranked up high, the resulting stroke will be just as bad for you as swimming hard all the time. The primary virtues of a flume pool with a moderate current are these:

 

 

• 因为没有“墙”，你无需中断游泳，也无需转身返回，你实际上拥有一个无边际泳池。在25码泳池中练习TI练习或技能的一个干扰是，你经常会发现自己在接近墙时才进入节奏或调整到你想要的感觉。墙会打断你的注意力，你必须重新开始才能“找到”动作的节奏。在水槽泳池中，一旦你建立了动作质量或感觉，你就可以继续前进进行任意多个循环，这是建立正确肌肉记忆的强大辅助手段。

• Because there is no “wall” and no need to interrupt your swimming and head back the other way, you quite literally have an endless pool. A distraction of practicing TI drills or skills in a 25-yard pool is that you often find yourself just getting into the rhythm, or tuning into the sensation you’re after as you approach the wall. The wall interrupts your concentration and you have to start all over again to “groove” the movement. In a flume pool, once you establish the movement quality or sensation, you can just keep going for as many cycles as you like, a powerful aid to building the right kind of muscle memory.

 

 

• 在水槽泳池中，无需计算圈数或重复次数，也无需关注计时器，你更容易将注意力集中在真正重要的事情上：你的动作是否流畅，以及当你像鱼一样划水时的感觉。因此，在流动的水流中练习，可以达到近乎禅宗般的纯粹。

• With no laps or repeats to count or pace clocks to focus on, in a flume pool, it’s far easier to give all your attention to what really matters: how smooth and fluent your movements are and how you feel when your stroke is Fishlike. Thus, there’s the potential of an almost Zen-like purity to the practice one can do in a moving current.

 

 

我计划用我的无边际泳池（Endless Pool）来教学，也用它来练习游泳。我期待着以后能随时游泳，无论是早上5点还是晚上11点，都无需出门，尽情享受一次又一次优美的划水体验。

I plan to use my Endless Pool both for teaching and as a way of practicing my own swimming. I’m looking forward to being able to swim anytime I like, whether at 5 a.m. or 11 p.m., without leaving the house, and to enjoying the nirvana of one beautiful stroke after another for as long as I like.

游泳绳

Swim Tethers

游泳绳是一种灵活的绳索，系在你和泳池壁之间。有些绳子的长度只够让你游几码就停下来。然后，你就可以在超大橡皮筋的末端原地划水，想划多久就划多久——有些人觉得，这非常适合在后院或酒店的短泳池里训练。

A swim tether is a flexible line that you attach between yourself and the pool wall. Some are only long enough to allow you to move perhaps a few yards before halting your progress. Then you stroke in place at the end of your oversized rubber band for however long you want— perfect, some people feel, for training in a short backyard or hotel pool.

这个想法听起来很合理，让你在很小的空间里就能锻炼。但不幸的是，由于系绳很短，你的脚或脚踝向后的张力非常不自然，几乎不可能做任何事，除了游泳姿势笨拙，这对任何追求技巧的人来说都是适得其反的。另一方面，一条足够长的游泳绳可以让你一直游到泳池尽头（对于25码的泳池来说，这相当于大约30英尺长的相对较轻的游泳圈），可以让你学到一些有用的经验。这样的游泳绳可以让你克服逐渐增加的阻力——最后5码可能非常艰难——稳步前进。

The idea sounds reasonable enough, letting you do your workout in a fraction of the space. But unfortunately, with a very short tether holding you in place the backward tension on your feet or ankles is so unnatural that it becomes almost impossible to do anything other than swim awkwardly, which is counterproductive for anyone working on skill. On the other hand, a swim tether that’s long enough to let you swim all the way to the end of the pool (for a 25-yard pool this would be about 30 feet of relatively light tubing) can yield some useful lessons. Such a tether lets you swim against gradually increasing resistance—the last 5 yards can be very tough—as you move steadily forward.

佩戴游泳绳时，你能做的最好的事情就是计算划水次数，努力减少每段游泳的划水次数（划水次数的总数显然会比畅游时更多），并打打游泳高尔夫。用运动手表计时，将划水次数加到成绩上，就能得到分数。之后再游几段，努力减少划水次数。

The best thing you can do while wearing a swim tether is count your strokes, work on reducing your strokes per length (the total will obviously be higher than when swimming unimpeded), and play swimming golf. Use a sports watch to time yourself, add your stroke count to your time, and you have a score. On subsequent lengths, work on reducing it.

你甚至可以练习冲刺。游到最远端后，靠墙休息一会儿（抓紧！），然后转身尽可能快地游回来，让腰带拉着你游得比你独自游泳的速度更快。这被称为冲刺辅助训练，它能教会你的肌肉以比你最好的比赛速度更快的速度移动。

You can even practice sprinting. After you get all the way to the far end, rest at the wall (hang on tight!) for a moment, then turn around and swim back as fast as you can, the belt pulling you along faster than you could ever swim all by yourself. This is called sprint-assisted training, and it teaches your muscles to move faster than your best race pace.

但如果你在练习划水次数或高尔夫成绩，那就懒洋洋地游回起始端，让绳子帮你完成所有动作。过一会儿，你就会用上省下来的能量，再次奋力游回泳池。

But if you’re working on your stroke count or your golf score, just float lazily back to the starting end, letting the cord do all the work. In just a minute, you’ll need the energy you’re saving to fight your way back down the pool again.

关于游泳训练辅助工具，有两点需要注意：一分价钱一分货；纸面上或广告文案上看起来不错的想法，不一定适合你的身体。最简单的“泳池工具”似乎效果最好。永远不要忘记，最简单的还是你自己的身体。

Two things you can say about swim training aids: You don’t necessarily get what you pay for, and an idea that sounds good on paper or in ad copy doesn’t necessarily make sense to your body. The simplest “pool tools” seem to work the best. And never forget that the simplest of all remains your own body.

14

14

游泳减肥

Swimming the Pounds Away

“游泳？绝对是最好的全能运动。但如果你想减肥，你得跑步。”

“Swimming? Absolutely the best all-around exercise. But if you want to lose weight, you need to run.”

很多人至今仍相信这一点，但很多人错了。对于任何想减掉几磅体重，并且喜欢把大部分可用锻炼时间花在泳池里的人来说，这绝非昙花一现。实际上，没有科学依据可以让我们灰心丧气，我们完全有理由为此感到振奋。

A lot of people still believe this, and a lot of people are wrong. It’s an issue of more than passing interest to anyone who wants to shed a few pounds and prefers to spend most of his or her available exercise time in the pool. Actually, there’s no scientific reason to be discouraged, and there’s every reason to take heart.

游泳长期以来在体重控制方面名声不佳——尤其是与跑步和骑自行车相比——怀疑论者反复强调“很棒的运动，但不能燃烧脂肪”，这迫使人们不必要地走上人行道，追求更苗条的身材。你也能理解，一个不科学的抽样调查似乎就能证明这一点。看看周六早上有多少憔悴的跑步者在街上慢跑。他们都是普通的运动员，甚至算不上顶尖冠军。

Swimming has long suffered from a bad rep—especially compared to running and cycling—when it comes to weight control “Great exercise but no fat burner,” repeat the skeptics, driving people unnecessarily onto the pavement in search of trimmer bodies. And you can understand how an unscientific sampling could seem to prove this. Just look at the number of gaunt runners slipping through the streets on a Saturday morning. Everyday athletes, not even elite champions.

但让我们先从科学角度来思考一下。真正的问题是，游泳运动燃烧的卡路里和脂肪真的和跑步或骑自行车一样多吗？一些研究表明并非如此。但每种研究的结论都是基于实验。所有研究的共同缺陷在于，游泳和与之对比的跑步运动的强度并不相同。游泳的速度太慢，无法提供可靠的对比结果。

But let’s get scientific for a minute. The real question is, do swimming workouts burn as many calories—and as much fat—as running or biking? Several studies have suggested that they do not. But in each case the deck was stacked experimentally. The flaw common to all the studies was that the swimming, and the running to which it was compared, were not done at the same intensities. The swimming paces were far too slow to provide a reliable comparison.

1989年，加州大学戴维斯分校的一项研究最终比较了跑步和游泳对两组人的减肥效果。两组受试者的运动强度相同：两项运动中，每个人的运动量都达到了最大负荷的75%。你猜结果如何？游泳运动员不仅减重效果与跑步者一样好，实际上减重效果甚至略微更好。

Then, a 1989 study at the University of California at Davis finally compared the weight-loss effects of running and swimming on two groups, both of whom exercised at identical intensities: 75 percent of maximum capacity for every subject in both sports. And what do you suppose happened? The swimmers not only lost as much weight as the runners, they actually lost slightly more.

四年后，新泽西州普林斯顿的游泳运动员、同时也是统计学家的霍华德·韦纳（Howard Wainer）计算出，游泳冠军每小时比跑步冠军多燃烧约25%的卡路里。韦纳的这项研究发表在美国统计协会期刊《机会》 （Chance）上。该研究表明，游泳消耗更多能量，因为水的阻力远大于陆地上的空气阻力，而且游泳运动员锻炼的肌肉也比跑步运动员多得多。

And four years later, Howard Wainer, a Princeton, New Jersey, swimmer who also happens to be a statistician calculated that champion swimmers burn about 25 percent more calories per hour than champion runners. Wainer’s study, published in Chance, the journal of the American Statistical Association, suggested that swimming takes more energy because the drag forces of water are so much greater than air resistance on land, and also because swimmers work so many more muscles than runners.

当然，游泳运动员对此并不感到意外。了解这项运动的人都知道，顶尖游泳运动员和其他任何运动项目的顶尖运动员一样精瘦。他们看起来比顶尖跑步运动员更壮，只是因为他们体型更大。快速游泳需要强大的上肢力量，因此游泳运动员的手臂、胸部和背部肌肉通常比跑步运动员甚至自行车运动员的肌肉发达得多。

Swimmers, of course, found none of this surprising. People who know the sport realize that elite swimmers are just as lean as elite athletes in any other sport. They simply look bigger than top runners, for example, because they are bigger. Fast swimming requires a powerful upper body, so swimmers’ arm, chest, and back muscles are typically far more developed than those of runners or even cyclists.

所以，在游泳和其他运动项目中，认真的运动员在同等训练下也能拥有同样精瘦的身材。但是，业余游泳者和业余跑步者之间明显的体重差异又该如何解释呢？我相信，在某种程度上，这只是一个简单的心理问题。由于人在水中的体重只有陆地上的10%，所以体重超标的跑步者每走一步都会感到每一磅体重的增加，而体型魁梧的游泳者却能轻松应对。那么，谁更有动力去关注最终的结果呢？

So equal work produces equally lean bodies among serious athletes in swimming and other sports. But what about the obvious weight differences between casual swimmers and casual runners? In part, I’m convinced, it’s a matter of simple psychology. Since your body weight in water is only 10 percent of what it is on land, an overweight runner feels every extra pound with every single step, while a chunky swimmer can be supremely comfortable. So, who has more motivation to watch what goes onto the plate?

研究人员对同样的饮食行为有了更科学的解释。加州大学欧文分校医学中心的格兰特·格温纳普博士的一项研究表明，游泳运动员通常体重更重，并非因为他们消耗的热量比其他运动员少，而是因为他们摄入的热量更多。格温纳普的推理是：假设78华氏度（约24摄氏度）的水比同温空气吸收的热量多得多。游泳运动员的身体会通过增加保护性隔热层来应对这种情况，而这当然需要食物来积累。我的亲身经历让我相信格温纳普博士是对的。跑步后我从来不想吃东西，但游泳后我却总是迫不及待地想吃东西。

Researchers have a more scientific explanation for the same eating behavior. Swimmers usually weigh more not because they burn fewer calories than other athletes, but because they consume more, says a study done by Dr. Grant Gwinup at the University of California at Irvine Medical Center. Gwinup’s reasoning: Water at, say, 78 degrees Fahrenheit draws much more heat from the body than air at the same temperature. And swimmers’ bodies react to that by adding protective insulation, which of course requires food to build up. My personal experience convinces me Dr. Gwinup is right. I never feel like eating after a run, while after swimming, I’m always primed to strap on the feedbag.

然而，无论你是不是顶尖运动员，有几种策略可以帮助你在游泳时燃烧更多脂肪，并在游泳结束后抑制食欲。首先，保持充足的水分就能保持饱腹感（参见第220页的“补水：游泳者缺水时”）。在锻炼期间补充充足的水分，这是你应该做的。其次，游泳训练后，允许自己适量吃一些饱腹感强但低脂的食物（例如水果或无花果棒）。这既能抑制你过强的食欲，又不会增加体重。

However, elite athlete or no, several strategies can help you both burn more fat while swimming and depress your post-swim-workout appetite when you’re done. First, stay full-feeling simply by staying well hydrated (see “Hydration: When Swimmers Run Out of Water” on page 220). Drink ample fluids during the workout, which you should be doing anyway. Second, allow yourself some judicious snacking on filling but low-fat foods (such as fruit or fig bars) immediately after your swimming workout. That will tame your stoked-up appetite without piling on pounds.

游泳的方式，甚至游泳的时间，都会影响最终燃烧的脂肪量。在剧烈运动中，肌肉必须依赖非常有限的储存能量。但如果以中等强度游泳，情况就会完全不同。虽然以较慢的速度燃烧相同数量的卡路里需要更长的时间，但消耗的能量中脂肪的比例更高。

How—and even when—you swim can affect the amount of fat you end up burning. During intense exercise, your muscles must rely on a very limited supply of stored energy. But swim with or using moderate effort and that all changes. Though it takes longer to burn the same number of calories at a slower pace, a greater percentage of the fuel being used is fat.

生理学家现在相信，我们实际上可以训练身体在更高强度下燃烧更多脂肪。交叉点通常是大约相当于全力以赴的60%——实际上相当低——之后，随着我们更加努力，我们的燃烧器就会转向碳水化合物。但是，通过正确的训练，我们可以在全力以赴达到最高水平的70%甚至80%时，继续燃烧脂肪。

And physiologists now believe we can actually train our bodies to burn more fat even at higher intensities. The crossover point is usually somewhere around 60 percent of an all-out effort—fairly low, actually—after which our burners switch over to carbohydrates as we work harder. But with the right training we can keep fat going into the furnace at efforts as high as 70 percent or even 80 percent of maximum.

这样做：在停止摄入碳水化合物八到十二小时后，安排一次长时间的游泳练习（六十到九十分钟，甚至更长时间）。最简单的方法是将训练安排在早餐前。轻松游六十到九十分钟，可以燃烧更多储存的脂肪（完全浸入式间歇训练和不间断游泳一样可以达到同样的效果——只是必须是轻松的间歇训练）。你重复这个训练的次数越多，你的身体就越能适应使用脂肪而不是储存的肌肉能量（称为糖原）作为燃料。

Do this: Schedule a long swim practice (sixty to ninety minutes or even more) after eight to twelve hours of carbohydrate deprivation. The easiest way is to plan your workouts for the morning, before breakfast. By swimming easily for sixty to ninety minutes you’ll burn more stored fat (Total Immersion intervals can do this as well as non-stop swimming can—they just have to be easy intervals), and the more you repeat this routine, the more you’ll condition your body to use fat rather than stored muscle energy (called glycogen) as fuel.

空腹状态下，需要更多胡萝卜才能完成这么多运动吗？答案是：加州大学戴维斯分校的这项研究还表明，长时间、轻松的有氧训练能带来令人印象深刻的后燃效应，促进新陈代谢，让你在训练结束后长达12个小时内继续燃烧多余的卡路里。

Need more of a carrot to do that much work on an empty stomach? Here it is: That University of California at Davis study also showed that prolonged, easy aerobic training sessions give you an impressive after-burn, boosting your metabolism so you continue burning extra calories for up to twelve hours after you finish your workout.

总结：你可以在泳池里减肥。任何体重增加的游泳者都应该怪他的游泳叉，而不是他的运动。

Bottom line: You can lose weight in the pool. Any swimmer having trouble with the pounds ought to blame his fork, not his sport.

补水：当游泳者缺水时

Hydration: When Swimmers Run Out of Water

在本书前面，我曾承诺，你只需一套泳衣、一顶泳帽和一副泳镜，就能成为一名非常优秀的游泳运动员。无需任何额外的装备。

Earlier in this book, I promised you could become a very good swimmer with nothing more than your suit, cap, and goggles. No added equipment necessary.

不完全是。应该始终有一件设备放在泳道尽头的甲板：你的水瓶。人们很容易误以为，因为你的汗水不明显，所以游泳训练就没发生。但游泳训练不仅会出汗，而且会大量出汗。

Not quite. One piece of equipment should always be sitting on the deck at the end of your lane: your water bottle. It’s easy, and common, to mistakenly figure that because your sweat isn’t obvious, it’s not happening. But you not only sweat during a swim workout, you sweat copiously.

通过在锻炼前后称重来证明这一点。你当然瘦了，而且都是水。即使只流失体重的2%（对于一个150磅的游泳运动员来说，流失的体重也只有3磅），也会显著影响你的运动表现。事实上，脱水比肌肉能量耗尽更容易减慢你的速度，因此“补充水分”比补充碳水化合物更重要。

Prove it by weighing yourself before and after a workout. You’ve lost weight, of course, and it’s all water. Sweat losses of as little as 2 percent of your body weight (just 3 pounds for a 150-pound swimmer) can cut dramatically into your performance. In fact, dehydration is far more likely to slow you down than running out of muscle energy, making “water loading” even more important than carbo loading.

但白开水并非总是最佳选择。德克萨斯大学运动生理学家杰克·威尔莫尔博士的一项研究发现，对于少于一小时的锻炼来说，没有什么比水更好的了。如果锻炼时间更长，含有电解质（盐）的补液运动饮料比水更快地被血液吸收，这意味着运动表现更好，运动后恢复也更快。

But plain water is not always the liquid of choice. A study by Dr. Jack Wilmore, an exercise physiologist at the University of Texas, found that for workouts of less than an hour, nothing beats water. If you’re going longer, fluid replacement sports drinks that contain electrolytes (salts) are absorbed into your bloodstream faster than water, which means better performance and a faster recovery when you’re done.

他们的配方都略有不同，所以我只能重复标准教练的建议：多尝试。有些人可能同意，有些人可能不同意。我找到了一种味道好，而且对我的胃很友好的配方。自从我开始使用它以来，我注意到在任何75分钟的锻炼后半段，我都感觉有明显的提升。

Their formulas are all slightly different, so I can only repeat the standard coach’s advice: experiment. Some may agree with you and others may not. I found one that tastes good to me and sits well in my stomach, and I’ve noticed a marked boost during the second half of any seventy-five-minute workout since I’ve started using it.

 

 

聪明游泳者的饮酒规则

The Smart Swimmer’s Drinking Rules

1. 每十五分钟，你就能出汗流失6到8盎司（约175到227毫升）的水分——没错，即使在泳池里也是如此。这相当于你每十五分钟喝一口水，对健康有益。

1. You can sweat off 6 to 8 ounces of fluid every fifteen minutes—yes, even in the pool. That’s a healthy swig from your water bottle every quarter hour.

 

 

2. 想要更精确？锻炼前后都称一下体重。每减掉一磅体重，就意味着流失了1品脱（16盎司）的水。下次，记得把这个量装进你的水瓶里。

2. Want to be more precise? Weigh yourself before and after a work-out. Each pound lost is a pint (16 ounces) of water gone out of you. Next time, bring that much in your water bottle(s).

 

 

3. 提前补充水分。游泳前两小时喝2到3杯水（16到24盎司），游泳前15分钟再喝2杯水。

3. Prehydrate. Drink 2 to 3 cups of water (16 to 24 ounces) about two hours before swimming and another 2 cups fifteen minutes before your workout.

 

 

4. 口渴前喝水。口渴意味着你的身体已经需要水分，所以再想防止脱水就太晚了。对于年纪较大的游泳者来说尤其如此，因为中年之后，随着身体水分的流失，我们感觉不那么口渴，身体发出的警告信号也容易被忽视。

4. Drink before you’re thirsty. Thirst means your body already needs water, so it’s too late to prevent dehydration. This is especially true for older swimmers, since after middle age we feel less thirsty as we dry out and the body’s warning signals can be overlooked.

在泳池里减肥：

如何游泳才能燃烧最多脂肪

Shedding Pounds in the Pool:

How to Swim to Burn the Most Fat

游泳真的能有效减肥吗？答案是肯定的，尽管各种理论都站不住脚。现在我们知道了：如果你消耗的热量比摄入的多，你就能减肥——无论是在健身车上、在跑道上，还是在游泳池里。而游泳是你所能找到的最舒适的燃脂方式之一。

Is swimming an effective exercise for losing weight? It certainly is, despite all the theories to the contrary that have come and gone. We now know this: If you burn more calories than you eat, you will drop pounds—on an exercise bike, at the track, or in the pool. And swimming is one of the most comfortable ways to burn calories you’ll ever find.

所以，如果通过减少体脂来减肥、改善胆固醇水平以及帮助降低血压是你锻炼计划的重要目标，那么你选择的运动就对了。信不信由你，实现所有这些目标并提高划水技术的最佳方式是轻松游泳，这是完全沉浸式游泳的基石。

So if slimming down by reducing body fat, improving your cholesterol count, and helping lower blood pressure are important goals for your exercise program, you’ve come to the right sport. And believe it or not, the best way to do all of that, plus improve your stroke technique, is with easy swimming, the keystone of Total Immersion swimming.

研究证明，只要游同样的距离，适度运动（心率仅为最大心率的60%）就能带来与高强度训练相同的健康益处。需要注意的是，这里说的健康，与运动表现无关。当然，如果你想游得比别人快，赢得冠军，你仍然需要高强度训练。但这并非保持心血管系统健康的关键。

Research has proven that exercising moderately (at just 60 percent of your maximum heart rate) provides the same health benefits as hard work-outs as long as you cover the same distance. That’s health, mind you, in contrast to performance. Obviously, if you want to win a championship by swimming faster than everyone else, you’ll still have to do intense work. But it’s not an essential ingredient to keeping your cardiovascular system tuned up.

在达拉斯库珀有氧运动研究所进行的一项为期六个月的研究中，一组每天慢速步行三英里的女性获得了与另一组以更快速度步行相同距离的女性相同的健康益处。事实上，步行每英里燃烧的卡路里与跑步一样多，只是需要更长的时间才能走完相同的距离。

In a six-month study at the Cooper Institute for Aerobics Research in Dallas, a group of women who walked three miles daily at a slow pace gained the same health benefits as a group that walked the same distance much faster. In fact, walking burns just as many calories per mile as running. It just takes longer to cover the same distance.

佛罗里达大学人类表现实验室主任迈克尔·波洛克博士发现，慢走在减少体脂、高血压和胆固醇方面与快走一样有效。库珀研究所的研究也表明，推车式步行实际上比快走式步行更能减掉体脂。

Michael Pollock, Ph.D., director of the Human Performance Laboratory at the University of Florida, found that slow walking was also just as effective as fast walking at reducing body fat, high blood pressure, and cholesterol. And at the Cooper Institute, the strollers actually lost more body fat than the power walkers.

这一切都不足为奇，因为研究人员早就知道，燃烧脂肪的最佳方法是长时间低强度运动。我们的身体主要依靠两种燃料来提供能量：脂肪（我们希望燃烧更多）和碳水化合物（如果任由身体自行燃烧，我们当然希望燃烧更多；毕竟，碳水化合物的效率更高）。相比加速训练，长时间轻松的训练是让身体从脂肪中获取更大比例能量的一种方法。

None of this is surprising, since researchers have long known the best way to burn fat is to exercise at lower intensities for longer periods of time. Our bodies use two main fuels to supply energy: fats (which we’d like to burn more of) and carbohydrates (which our bodies, left to their own devices, would like to burn more of; carbohydrates are more efficient, after all). Long, easy practices are one way to get the body to draw a greater percentage of the energy it needs from fats than it would if you sped things up.

“最终，你所做的工作总量才是最重要的因素，”波洛克说。“人们可以放慢速度，但他们需要付出更多才能获得同样的结果。”

“The total amount of work you do ends up being the important factor,” says Pollock. “People can go slower. They just need to go longer to get the same results.”

嗯，这当然很容易。如果你以平均每100码1分30秒的速度游一英里，你只需27分钟就能完成练习。如果以每100码2分00秒的速度游，你只需要36分钟就能完成。但显然你不能同时降低速度和距离。少即是少。即使是美国运动医学会，现在也建议以低于最大能力的60%的强度进行训练是可以的，但它也规定，为了获得益处，你必须进行足够长的时间和足够频繁的训练。对于成年游泳者来说，这意味着每周要游泳6000到8000码，分三到四次在泳池里训练。

Well, that’s certainly easy enough. If you swim a mile at an average pace of 1:30 per 100 yards, you’ll finish the practice in only 27 minutes. At 2:00 per 100 yards, you’ll be done in 36 minutes. But you obviously can’t cut back both pace and distance. Less is less. Even the American College of Sports Medicine, which now advises that it’s okay to work at less than 60 percent of maximal capacity, stipulates that you must still do it long enough and frequently enough to get the benefit. For adult swimmers, this would mean about 6000 to 8000 yards of swimming a week, in three to four pool sessions.

所以，发现稍微放慢节奏就能更容易地到达游泳池，这本身并没有错。高强度的锻炼项目不可避免地会面临更高的退出率，因为人们不喜欢，而且一旦“达不到标准”就会感到沮丧。“通过鼓励更慢、更舒适的锻炼，”波洛克博士说，“我们给人们一个锻炼的理由，而不是一个不锻炼的借口。”

So there’s nothing wrong with discovering that easing your pace a little makes it easier to get to the pool in the first place. Higher-intensity exercise programs inevitably suffer from higher dropout rates because people just don’t enjoy them and get frustrated when they can’t “measure up.” “By encouraging slower, more comfortable exercise,” says Dr. Pollock, “we’re giving people a reason to exercise rather than an excuse not to.”

我对此没有异议。毕竟，轻松游泳也是完全沉浸式练习的完美节奏。相比在泳池里拼命游动，低强度下你可以更有效地进行练习和技巧练习，并计算每段划水的次数。

No argument from me. After all, easy swimming is also the perfect pace for Total Immersion practice. You can do your drills and technique work and count your strokes per length much more effectively at low intensity than when you’re trying to burn up the pool.

即使是间歇训练，通常需要更高强度的训练，也能成为“燃脂良方”。只需采用更放松的节奏即可。每次训练之间不需要太多休息，因为你的心率会保持在中等水平。速度很重要，但即使是短暂的休息也是有益的——尤其是对成年游泳者来说——因为它们可以控制积聚在肌肉和血液中、导致疲劳的乳酸水平。这反过来意味着锻炼后肌肉僵硬和酸痛感会减少。间歇训练及其内置的休息时间有助于心脏为关节和肌肉输送更多的血液、氧气和营养，从而降低受伤的风险。

Even interval training, normally done with a little more gusto, can become a “fat burner.” Just use a more relaxed pace. You won’t need much rest between repeats because your heart rate will stay fairly even at moderate paces, but even brief rests are beneficial—especially for adult swimmers—since they control the levels of fatigue-producing lactic acid that accumulates in muscles and the bloodstream. That in turn means less stiffness and soreness after your workout. And interval repeats with their built-in rest periods help the heart supply more blood, oxygen, and nutrients to joints and muscles, reducing your chance of hurting something.

但是多快才算“够慢”呢？要计算你轻松自在、减重、强身健体的间歇训练速度，可以将你最好的100码成绩乘以1.25到1.5之间的任意数字。所以，如果你的最佳成绩是1分20秒，那么每100码1分40秒到2分00秒之间的配速就刚好达到目标。计划在两次游泳之间休息10到20秒。如果你进行划水练习而不是直接游泳，你的成绩自然会落在这个范围的上半部分。使用相同的公式来计算你重复其他距离的配速。或者直接遵循附录中的“完全沉浸式”练习。按照建议进行，它们既可以锻炼划水能力，又可以燃烧脂肪。

But how fast is “slow enough”? To calculate your easygoing, pound-dropping, health-building clip for intervals, multiply your best 100-yard time by anywhere from 1.25 to 1.5. So if your best time is 1:20, you’ll be right on target at a pace between 1:40 and 2:00 per 100. Plan on ten to twenty seconds of rest between swims. And if you’re doing stroke drills rather than straight swimming, your times will naturally fall in the upper part of the range. Use the same formula to figure your pace for repeats of other distances. Or just follow the Total Immersion practices in the appendix. Done as suggested, they work well as both stroke builders and fat burners.

为了获得最佳的燃脂效果，只需增加足够的次数或组数，确保至少在泳池中游一个小时。但这样做时，请记住，延长训练时间（燃烧更多脂肪）和提高技能（成为更好的游泳运动员）之间存在潜在冲突。如果您无法保持良好状态一小时或更长时间，则可能必须选择一项优先顺序。如果您的目标是成为更好的游泳运动员，请不要为了多燃烧一些卡路里而将训练延长到疲劳损害身体的程度。相反，可以增加三十分钟的步行、骑自行车、跑步机、健身车或任何仅燃烧卡路里和脂肪但不依赖于保持良好状态的运动。

To enjoy the optimum fat-burning benefit, just add enough repeats or sets to allow for at least an hour in the pool. But as you do so, keep in mind the potential conflict between longer sessions (to burn more fat) and quality skill work (to become a better swimmer). If you can’t maintain good form for an hour or more, you may have to choose one priority over another. If it’s becoming a better swimmer, don’t stretch the practice to the point where fatigue hurts your form, just so you can burn a few more calories. Instead add thirty minutes of walking or biking or treadmill or exercise bike or anything that simply burns calories and fat but doesn’t depend on maintaining good form.

15

15

保持强壮、柔韧、避免受伤：全浸式“陆上训练”

Staying Strong, Supple, and Injury-Free: “Dryland Training” the Total Immersion Way

我写这本书的目的是指导你在泳池里应该做什么，所以我不会试图对教练们所说的“陆上训练”做出最终的定论。但“完全沉浸”不仅是一种游泳方式，也意味着一种明智而实用的锻炼理念。此外，如果你是刚接触游泳，并且是新手，你至少应该得到一本像新电脑那样的“快速入门指南”。因此，我将推荐一系列锻炼方案，并围绕三个目标：

My goal with this book has been to guide you on what to do in the pool, so I won’t attempt to provide the last word on what coaches call “dryland training.” But Total Immersion, as much as a way of swimming, also means a philosophy of intelligent and practical exercise. Plus, if you have come to this book as a relatively new swimmer, you deserve at least a “quick-start guide” of the sort that comes with a new computer. So I will suggest a range of exercise options with three goals:

 

 

• 陆地训练是对水中无重力训练的补充，对强健的肌肉骨骼系统至关重要

• Dryland supplements to the gravity-free exercise of water, essential to a strong musculoskeletal system

 

 

• “预防性”锻炼可以保持肩膀（游泳者最脆弱的关节）健康，避免疼痛

• “Prehab” exercises to keep your shoulders—a swimmer’s most vulnerable joint—healthy and pain-free

 

 

• 有关合理力量训练的基本指导，可帮助您的身体在进行游泳动作时发挥最佳表现。

• Basic guidance on sensible strength training that will help your body perform optimally while doing swimming movements.

虽然我在这里只介绍基础知识，但我会在附录中建议更深入研究的资源。

And while I’ll just present the basics here, I’ll suggest resources for deeper study in the appendix.

预防肩部损伤：快速简单的计划

Preventing Shoulder Injury: A Quick and Simple Plan

游泳以剧烈和轻柔而闻名。但“轻柔”并不保证“不受伤”，尤其是对肩膀而言，肩膀几乎是天生容易受伤的。肩膀的结构看起来就像一个壁球（上臂骨的头部）平衡地放在瓶盖（肩胛骨窝）上。球由十七块肌肉组成的网络固定在瓶盖上。这对于灵活性很有帮助，但不利于手臂向后加速以抵抗阻力。“游泳肩”在游泳者中很常见，因为“人类游泳者”会本能地尝试用力划水，而不是用手固定并让核心身体完成大部分工作。结果，肩袖肌肉过度拉伸会使臂骨（又称肱骨）在窝内摇晃。这会挤压稳定肩膀的肌肉和肌腱，引起炎症和疼痛。

Swimming deserves its reputation for being both vigorous and gentle. But “gentle” doesn’t guarantee “injury-free,” particularly when it comes to your shoulder, which is almost ideally built for trouble. Shoulder anatomy looks like a racquetball (the head of your upper arm bone) balanced on a bottle cap (the socket of the scapula). The ball is held on the bottle cap by a network of seventeen muscles. This is great for mobility, but terrible for accelerating your arm rearward against resistance. “Swimmer’s shoulder” is common among swimmers because “human swimmers” instinctively try to muscle the water— rather than anchor the hand and let their core body do most of the work. The resulting overstretched rotator cuff muscles allow the arm bone (a.k.a. the humerus) to wobble in its socket. This pinches the muscles and tendons that stabilize your shoulder, causing inflammation and pain.

由于游泳运动员每游一英里，肩部旋转 1,200 到 1,500 次，因此制定预防计划至关重要。需要加强的最重要的肌肉是肩袖肌肉，它稳定肱骨头，使其他肩部肌肉能够有效地发挥作用，以及肩胛骨稳定肌，它可以防止肌腱挤压和肩袖压力。这个训练计划的主要优点是它只需要很少的时间（每周三次，每次十分钟）和很少的器材。对于需要使用阻力的练习，你只需要弹力绳、弹力带或轻重量——保持足够轻的阻力，每个练习至少重复 10 到 15 次。练习到感到疲劳为止；休息一下，然后再做第二次每组至少做20到30次。逐渐增加到每组30次或更多（达到这个数量后无需再做第二组），直到疲劳为止。

Because a swimmer’s shoulder rotates 1,200 to 1,500 times every mile, a prevention plan is clearly in order. The most important muscles to strengthen are the rotator cuff muscles, which stabilize the head of the humerus, allowing the other shoulder muscles to perform effectively, and the scapular (shoulder blade) stabilizers, which protect against pinched tendons and rotator cuff stress. The primary virtue of this routine is that it requires little time (ten minutes, three times per week) and little equipment. All you need for those exercises specifying the use of resistance is stretch cords, a Thera-Band, or light weights—keep resistance light enough to do at least 10 to 15 repetitions of each exercise. Work until you feel fatigue; rest and do a second set, for a total of at least 20 to 30 reps of each. Over time, try to build to 30 or more repetitions in a single set (no second set necessary when you do) before fatigue.

增强肩袖肌肉

STRENGTHEN YOUR ROTATOR CUFF MUSCLES

练习1.站立，双臂放于身体两侧，每只手握一个哑铃。将肩膀向前、向上向耳朵方向转动，向后，然后再向下，尽可能地进行最大幅度的运动。前后旋转和反方向旋转交替进行。

EXERCISE 1. Stand with arms at your sides, a dumbbell in each hand. Roll your shoulders forward, up toward your ears, back, then down again, moving through the greatest possible range of movement. Alternate one front-to-back rotation with one in the opposite direction.

练习2.侧卧，用手撑住头部，上臂贴在身体两侧，弯曲成直角，指关节向前，手掌向下，握住一个轻物。保持上臂贴着身体，慢慢旋转前臂，直到指关节指向天空，然后以相同的速度收回。您也可以站着做这个练习，用弹力绳或弹力带增加阻力。双臂靠近身体，呈“握手”姿势，肘部抵住肋骨。（在肘部和肋骨之间放一个薄垫子或枕头，以增强稳定性。）双手抓住弹力绳或弹力带的两端。慢慢将前臂向外旋转至一侧，然后以相同的速度收回。

EXERCISE 2. Lie on your side with your head propped on your hand and your top arm against your side, bent at a right angle with knuckles forward and palm down, holding a light weight. Keep the upper arm against your body as you slowly rotate your forearm until your knuckles point to the sky then return at the same speed. You can also do this exercise while standing, with stretch cords or a Thera-Band for resistance. Hold your arms close to your body in a “shake-hands” position with your elbows held into your ribs. (Place a thin cushion or pillow between elbow and ribs for greater stability.) Grasp the ends of the cords or Thera-Band in your hands. Rotate your forearms slowly out to the side, then return at the same speed.

练习3：坐姿或站姿，双臂伸直，垂于身体两侧。以拇指为引导，慢慢将双臂抬至略低于肩部前方，稍停片刻，然后以相同速度收回。使用5至8磅（约2.5至3.4公斤）的轻重量、弹力带或绳索作为阻力。

EXERCISE 3. Sit or stand with your arms straight and hanging at your side. Leading with your thumb, slowly raise your arms to just below and just in front of your shoulder, pause for a moment, then return at the same speed. Use a light weight of 5 to 8 pounds, a Thera-Band, or cords for resistance.

练习4.弯腰，双臂伸直从肩膀开始。（放松膝盖以避免下背部拉伤。）以指关节和略微弯曲的肘部为主导，慢慢地将手臂抬到肩膀的高度，稍停片刻，然后以相同的速度返回。

EXERCISE 4. Bend at the waist, with your arms hanging straight from your shoulders. (Soften your knees to avoid lower-back strain.) Leading with your knuckles and slightly-bent elbows, raise your arms slowly to shoulder level, pause for a moment, then return at the same speed.

加强肩胛骨稳定肌

STRENGTHEN YOUR SCAPULAR STABILIZERS

练习1.坐在带扶手的椅子上，双脚平放在地板上。双手放在扶手上。伸直肘部，向下用力，臀部抬离椅子。（如有必要，可以用脚稍微用力；随着你的力量增强，可以多用手臂发力。）你可以在工作时练习这个动作！

EXERCISE 1. Sit on a chair with armrests and with your feet flat on the floor. Place your hands on the armrests. Straighten your elbows and push down, lifting your hips off the chair. (If necessary, help by pushing a bit with your feet; as you get stronger let your arms do more of the work.) You can do this one at work!

练习2.将双手放在稳定的表面上（柜台、桌子、沙发靠背，几乎任何三到四英尺高的东西）。双脚保持半站立的“俯卧撑”姿势，头部与脊柱对齐，双手与肩同宽，手臂伸直。慢慢地做一个俯卧撑，但不要弯曲肘部。保持手臂伸直，胸部下沉几英寸，肩胛骨向内收拢。然后，利用肩部肌肉，向后撑起，拱起肩膀，并尽可能地展开肩胛骨。随着力量的增强，逐渐转向更水平的姿势，最终以俯卧撑或“平板支撑”的姿势完成。

EXERCISE 2. Place your hands on a stable surface (counter, desk, the back of a couch, almost anything that’s three to four feet high). Position your feet so that you are in a semistanding “push-up” position with your head and spine aligned, hands at shoulder width, and arms straight. Do a slow push-up— but without bending your elbows. Keep your arms straight, and lower your chest a few inches as your shoulder blades pinch together. Then, using shoulder muscles, press back up, rounding your shoulders and spreading your shoulder blades as much as possible. As you grow stronger, move toward a more horizontal position, eventually doing it in a push-up or “plank” position.

练习3.将Thera-Band或绳索绑在腰部或胸部高度的稳定物体上。抓住两端，双臂向前伸直，肩膀向下，远离耳朵，将肩膀向后拉（肩胛骨并拢），然后向前拉回。以相同的速度，直到感觉肩胛骨伸展开来。动作要慢，直到感觉到背部中部肌肉收缩和放松。

EXERCISE 3. Attach a Thera-Band or cords to a stable object at waist or chest height. Grasp the ends and with your arms straight in front and your shoulders down away from your ears, pull your shoulders back (pinching shoulder blades together), then return them forward at the same speed, until you feel your shoulder blades stretch wide. Move slowly enough to feel the muscles in the middle of your back contract and relax.

练习4：俯卧，额头下垫一条卷起的毛巾，臀部下垫一个枕头。双臂从肩膀向前伸展（二头肌距离耳朵两英寸），肘部伸直，拇指向上。尽可能抬起双臂，不要弯曲肘部；在最高点保持片刻，然后慢慢放下。感受从肩膀到背部中部的力量。开始时不负重；逐渐增加到2到5磅。

EXERCISE 4. Lie on your stomach, with a rolled towel under your forehead and a pillow under your hips. Extend your arms forward from your shoulders (biceps two inches from your ears), elbows straight and thumbs up. Raise your arms as far as possible, without bending your elbows; hold them at their highest point for a moment, then lower slowly. Feel the effort from your shoulders to the middle of your back. Start with no weight; work up to 2 to 5 pounds.

练习5：俯卧，额头下垫一条卷起的毛巾，臀部下垫一个枕头。双臂向两侧伸展，与肩同高，掌心向下或向前（拇指向上）。保持肘部伸直，抬起双臂时肩胛骨收拢；在最高点稍作停留，然后缓慢放下。练习时，可以使用或不使用轻重量。

EXERCISE 5. Lie on your stomach, with a rolled towel under your forehead and a pillow under your hips. Extend your arms to the sides at shoulder level with palms down or forward, (thumbs pointing up). Keeping elbows straight, pinch your shoulder blades together as you lift your arms; pause at the highest point for a moment, then lower slowly. Do this with or without light weights.

拉伸肩部肌肉

STRETCH THE MUSCLES UNDER THE SHOULDER

游泳比其他任何运动都能更好地促进自然的柔韧性，对抗衰老带来的僵硬，但仅靠游泳是不够的。事实上，即使是在“对身体更友好”的TI游泳中，你的肩部肌肉仍然发挥着重要作用，它能让你的手/手臂保持杠杆位置，这样你才能游过那个位置。反复收缩一小时左右后，对肩部肌肉进行拉伸，对它们会有好处。这里介绍的六个拉伸动作，针对你最常用的肌肉，能让你保持放松和柔韧。每组练习中选择一个或两个都做。游泳后淋浴时，保持每个姿势约十次瑜伽呼吸。

Swimming promotes natural flexibility and fights the stiffness of aging better than any other sport, but it’s not enough by itself. In fact, even in “body-friendly” TI swimming, your shoulder muscles still do an important job holding your hand/arm in a leveraged position so you can move past that spot. They’ll benefit from being stretched after contracting repetitively for an hour or so. The six stretches described here, which target the muscles you use most, will keep you feeling loose and supple. Do one or both of each pair of exercises while in the shower after swimming, holding each for about ten yoga breaths.

拉伸1.举起一只手臂，置于肩后。将肘部靠在墙角，用力按压，直到感觉到从肘部到腋窝及下方有拉伸感。

STRETCH 1. Raise one arm above your head, dropping your hand behind your shoulder. Lean the back of your elbow against a corner of a wall and press until you feel a stretch from the elbow down to your armpit and below.

拉伸2.双臂高举过头，呈流线型。先尽量向左侧倾斜，然后向右侧倾斜。感受身体从侧面向下拉动。

STRETCH 2. Put both arms overhead in the streamlined position. Lean first to the left side as far as possible, then to the right. Feel the pull all the way down your side.

伸展肩部前方的肌肉

STRETCH THE MUSCLES IN FRONT OF THE SHOULDER

伸展1.一只手臂向身体两侧伸直，与身体成直角；弯曲肘部，手指向上，手掌向前，呈90度角。将手掌、前臂和肘部的内侧抵住门口，肘部与肩同高。将手臂抵住门口的同时，将另一侧臀部向后转动，直到感觉到肩前侧和上胸部有拉伸感。重复此动作，将肘部抵住耳朵高度。

STRETCH 1. Hold one arm out to your side at a right angle; bend your elbow 90 degrees with fingers up and palm forward. Brace the inside surface of your hand, forearm, and elbow against a doorway with your elbow at shoulder height. As you press your arm against the doorway, turning your opposite hip back until you feel a stretch across the front of your shoulder and upper chest. Repeat with your elbow braced at ear level.

伸展2.双臂置于身后。双手十指交叉，握拳抵住臀部，肩胛骨收紧。缓慢地将手臂尽可能向上抬起。当你无法再抬起时，从腰部向前弯曲，继续向上抬起，尝试将其向上抬起至垂直。

STRETCH 2. Put both arms behind your back. Grasp your hands together with fingers interlaced, fists resting against your buttocks and shoulder blades pinched. Slowly raise your arms upward behind you as far as possible. When you can’t raise them any further, bend forward from the waist and continue, trying to raise them toward vertical.

拉伸肩部后部的肌肉

STRETCH THE MUSCLES IN BACK OF THE SHOULDER

伸展1.将手背放在下背部（手掌朝后），肘部向外伸展。指尖指向另一侧臀部。将肘部内侧抵住门口，同时将另一侧臀部向前转动。让肘部向前移动，直到感觉到肩部后侧有拉伸感。

STRETCH 1. Place the back of your hand on your lower back (the palm of your hand facing back) with your elbow out to the side. Your fingertips point toward the opposite hip. Brace the inside of your elbow against a doorway, while turning your opposite hip forward. Allow your elbow to move forward until you feel a stretch across the back of your shoulder.

拉伸2.将右臂横过身体，使肩膀位于下巴下方，右手、前臂和上臂与地面平行。将左臂绕过右臂，使左手腕位于右肘后方。左臂稳稳收紧，右臂尽可能贴近胸部。然后换边。

STRETCH 2. Put your right arm across your body so that the shoulder is under your chin and your right hand, forearm, and upper arm parallel to the ground. Wrap your left arm outside the right, so your left wrist is behind your right elbow. Pull in steadily with the left arm, pressing the right as close to your chest as possible. Then switch.

功能性力量训练

Functional Strength Training

许多游泳者总想着通过增肌来克服水流阻力。但水作为一种流体，对纯粹的力量毫无反应。水的阻力总是超过你所能施加的任何力量，而且，需要一种特殊的力量，并且要精准地运用，才能克服水的阻力。

Many swimmers are tempted to think they can overpower the water by bulking up. But water, being a fluid medium, just doesn’t respond to sheer power. The water’s resistance will always surpass any strength you can apply and, besides, it takes a special kind of strength, accurately applied, to overcome the water’s resistance.

世界上最优秀的游泳运动员并没有庞大或轮廓分明的肌肉。创造世界纪录的力量，以及帮助人们高效、流畅、愉悦地游泳的力量，更像是支撑布鲁克林大桥的纤细优雅的钢缆所展现的力量，而不是那些在举重比赛中举起重物的巨大力量。这并不是说传统的举重对游泳运动员毫无价值。任何超过三十五岁的人都应该这样做。根据美国运动医学会的建议，每周进行两次纯粹为了健康而进行的阻力训练。如果你确实要去健身房，与其专注于“游泳专用肌肉群”，不如请教练帮你制定一个复合/复杂训练计划，以增强整体力量。

The world’s best swimmers don’t have bulky or highly defined muscles. The strength that produces world records, as well as helping anyone to swim efficiently, fluently, and enjoyably is more like that exhibited by the slim, graceful cables that hold up the Brooklyn Bridge than by the brutes who heft enormous poundage in weight-lifting competitions. Which is not to say that conventional weight lifting has no value for swimmers. Anyone beyond their middle thirties should do some form of resistance training twice a week, purely for health, according to the American College of Sports Medicine. If you do go to a gym, rather than focus on “swimming-specific muscles,” ask a trainer to help plan a program of compound/complex exercises for general strength development.

对你的游泳来说，最有价值的或许是“功能性力量”，这种力量能让我们在各种活动中都更加强健，从铲花园的土到铲人行道上的泥，再到游1500米。这意味着训练肌肉和关节，让它们像我们运动时那样运作——多个肌肉群、多个关节和复杂的运动平面同时运作。这是因为快速游泳不是靠肌肉在水中前进来实现的，而是靠保持身体姿势，最大限度地减少阻力，并将推进的划臂动作与核心身体“动力链”的力量联系起来。这种力量是通过练习具有挑战性的动作来发展的，这些动作可以训练躯干和手臂/肩部肌肉协同工作。从四十多岁开始，我开始定期练习瑜伽，我发现瑜伽是一种比其他各种侧重不同方面的活动（比如举重、仰卧起坐和伸展运动）更具综合性的锻炼方式。

What is probably of greatest value to your swimming is “functional strength,” the kind that makes us more robust in everything from spading the garden to shoveling the walk to swimming 1500 meters. And that means training muscles and joints to work as they do when we move—multiple muscle groups, multiple joints, and complex planes of movement, all at once. This is because fast swimming isn’t produced by muscling your way through the water, but by maintaining body positions that minimize drag and connect the propelling armstrokes to the power of the core body’s “kinetic chain.” That kind of strength is developed by practicing challenging movements that teach torso and arm/shoulder muscles to work together. Since my mid-forties, I’ve begun the regular practice of yoga, which I’ve found to be a more integrated form of exercise than a myriad of other activities each focused on something different, like, say weight lifting, situps, and stretching.

我觉得瑜伽练习对游泳非常有效，因为它教会我将身体作为一个系统，协调所有肌肉群，克服重力和自身柔韧性的阻力，在每个动作中增强力量和柔韧性。俯卧撑、引体向上、屈伸、台阶练习和深蹲等仅靠自身体重完成的动作，也能增强肌肉感知和关节稳定性，让肌腱和韧带适应，而不是像有时被器械或外部重量压垮。

My yoga practice feels utterly functional for swimming because it teaches me to use my body as a system, working all muscle groups in unison, against the resistance of gravity and my own inflexibility to build strength and flexibility with each movement. Exercises such as push-ups, pull-ups, dips, step-ups, and squats, done with just the weight of your own body, also develop muscle sense and joint stability, letting tendons and ligaments adapt rather than being overwhelmed as they sometimes are by machines or external weight.

对功能性力量尤为关键的是“核心力量”，它指的是腹肌、脊柱旋转肌群、竖脊肌、髋屈肌、臀大肌等肌肉的力量。如果你的核心力量不足，那么你也同样缺乏力量，因为你的躯干是将力量从腿部传递到上半身的力耦合器。各种腹部运动，尤其是普拉提运动，都能增强核心力量。我参加认证教练的普拉提课程，也会借助书籍进行自学。（更多瑜伽和普拉提信息，请参阅相关资源。）

Especially critical to functional strength is “core strength,” which means strength in the abdominal muscles, spinal rotators and erectors, hip flexors, the glutes, and more. If your core isn’t strong, then neither are you, because your torso is the force coupler that transmits power from legs to upper body. Abdominal exercises of all sorts, and particularly Pilates exercises develop core power. I take Pilates classes with a certified instructor and practice on my own with the aid of a book. (See resources for more information on yoga and Pilates.)

在球上

On the Ball

稳定球训练是培养功能性力量和核心力量的最佳方法之一。而且，稳定球训练也是最令人愉悦的锻炼方式之一，因为它几乎能为任何锻炼程序增添童趣。但这并不意味着它没有真正的益处，因为它确实有。

One of the best developers of functional and core strength is stability ball exercise. And not incidentally, stability ball exercises are among the most enjoyable ways to get a workout because they lend almost any exercise routine a childlike sense of play. But that’s not to say they don’t offer serious benefits, because they do.

这些大型充气乙烯基球的主要优势在于，它们能为你在其上进行的任何运动增添一个关键维度：稳定性。由于球在你运动时容易摇晃或滚动，你的身体会调动从核心肌群向四肢辐射的肌肉带，以保持平衡和稳定。以下是一些例子：

The primary benefit of these large, inflatable vinyl balls is that they add a critical dimension to anything you do on them: instability. Because the ball tends to wobble or roll as you exercise on it, your body recruits bands of muscle radiating out from your core toward your extremities to keep you balanced and stable. Some examples:

 

 

• 当我将球放在膝盖下做俯卧撑时，除了通常在俯卧撑中做功的胸部和背部肌肉之外，我还能感觉到从肩膀到臀部的肌肉在发力，以防止我滚向一侧。

• When I do push-ups with the ball under my knees, in addition to the chest and back muscles that typically do the work in a push-up, I can also feel muscles from my shoulders to my hips working to keep me from rolling off to the side.

 

 

• 当我用哑铃做卧推时，上背部和肩膀靠在哑铃球上。我能感觉到腹肌支撑着躯干，大腿和髋屈肌也在稳定着我。

• When I do a “bench press” with dumbbells, resting my upper back and shoulders on the ball. I can feel my abdominals supporting my torso as well as my thighs and hip flexors stabilizing me.

 

 

• 当我做自重深蹲时，将球放在我的背部和墙壁之间，我的臀部肌肉会努力让我保持身体平衡。

• When I do a body-weight squat, with the ball between my back and a wall, my hip muscles are working to keep me aligned.

 

 

• 当我做腹部弯举时，用球支撑我的下背部，我意识到我的前腹肌和侧腹肌对我腹部的稳定作用比我在健身垫上做仰卧起坐时大得多。

• And when I do abdominal curls, with the ball supporting my lower back, I’m aware of my front and side abdominals stabilizing my midsection to a far greater degree than when I do sit-ups on an exercise mat.

圣地亚哥州立大学生物力学实验室最近的研究证实了我自身肌肉的反馈。研究发现，稳定球在功能性组合训练中尤其有效。这又是一个“功能性”的词。我几乎做过的每一个稳定球练习（它们功能多样，几乎可以与任何类型的运动结合）都让我感受到了与游泳时相同的肌肉功能——身体水平伸展，从指尖到脚趾的肌肉动态地工作，以抵消重力和阻力。稳定球可能是迄今为止最适合此类挑战的陆上模拟器。而且你永远不会觉得它无聊。

Recent research at the biomechanics lab at San Diego State University confirms what my own muscles tell me. Stability balls were found to be particularly effective at working torso muscles in functional combinations. There’s that word functional again. Virtually every stability ball exercise I’ve done (and they are versatile enough to integrate with almost any kind of exercise) has given me the same sense of muscle function that I feel when swimming—body extended in a horizontal position with muscles from fingertips to toes working dynamically to counteract the forces of gravity and drag. The stability ball may be the best dryland simulator yet for that kind of challenge. And you’ll never find it boring.

这是我最喜欢的系列之一。

Here’s one of my favorite series.

开始。保持水平平衡，球位于臀部下方，双手放在肩膀正下方，双腿向后伸直，与地面平行。

TO BEGIN. Balance in a horizontal position with the ball below your hips, hands directly under your shoulders, and legs straight behind, parallel to the floor.

动作一：双手向外伸展，直到球位于膝盖处。暂停，缓慢呼吸两次，然后向后伸展。重复5到10次。

ACTION. Walk your hands out until the ball is at your knees. Pause for two slow breaths, then walk back. Repeat 5 to 10 times.

要点：保持从肩膀到脚的直线、水平线。

KEY POINT. Maintain a straight, horizontal line from your shoulders to your feet.

“高级安置”：尝试以下任何一种方法：

“ADVANCED PLACEMENT”: Try any of the following:

 

 

1. 向外走动，直到球位于膝盖下方，然后暂停，做一个俯卧撑。胸部向下压向地板——双腿和双脚会抬起；保持从肩膀到双脚的直线。向后压至水平，然后向后移动至臀部。

1. Walk out until the ball is under your knees, then pause and do a push-up. Lower your chest down toward the floor—your legs and feet will rise; keep the line from shoulders to feet straight. Press back up to horizontal, then walk it back to your hips.

 

 

2. 向外走，直到球位于你的小腿或脚踝下方，然后将其带回臀部。不要让背部摇晃或弯曲；保持臀部与脊柱和双脚成一条直线。

2. Walk out until the ball is under your shins or ankles, then walk it back to your hips. Don’t let your back sway or bend; keep your hips in line with your spine and feet.

 

 

3. 将球放在膝盖下方，先将其滚到左膝下方，然后再滚到右膝下方。你会感觉到肩部和上背部的肌肉在发力，让你保持球不动。

3. With the ball under your knees, roll it under your left knee, then under your right. You’ll feel muscles in the side of your shoulder and upper back working to keep you on the ball.

在每一个练习中，你都会意识到从手到臀部的肌肉带在收缩——这正是你在游泳时感受到力量的方式。每个变式都会调动不同的稳定肌群参与动作。这项训练的游泳功能与你在陆地上进行的任何训练一样。

In each of these exercises you’ll be aware of contracting a connected band of muscle from your hands to your hips—exactly the way you should feel your strength while swimming. The variations will each recruit different stabilizer muscles into the action. This training is as swimming-functional as anything you can do on land.

16

16

你的朋友正在等待（“我可以和谁一起游泳？在哪里？”）

Your Friends Are Waiting (“Who Can I Swim With? And Where?”)

虽然长跑被认为是一项孤独的运动——至少短篇小说的标题是这么说的——但游泳也同样适合。想想看。你几乎听不到什么，除了自己的呼吸声，根本听不到谈话，视野也几乎仅限于泳池壁和池底。很难想象还有比这更孤独的锻炼方式了。

Though long-distance running is supposedly the sport of loneliness—at least the short-story title tells us so—a good case could also be made for swimming. Think about it. You can’t hear much but your own breathing, conversation is out of the question, and the view is pretty much limited to the pool walls and bottom. Hard to imagine a more solitary way to exercise.

或者说，更友好的氛围。或许是对我们每次游泳都身处其中的私密小天地的一种回应，但集体游泳的人相处起来非常融洽。这是一件好事，因为加入集体往往比独自一人更容易真正精通游泳。得益于地方、区域和全国性团体的广泛网络，几乎任何人都可以加入。

Or a more friendly one, either. Perhaps it’s a reaction to that private little cocoon we do all our laps in, but swimmers as a group are wonderfully congenial. And that’s a good thing, because it’s often easier to become truly proficient as a member of a group than alone. Thanks to the extensive network of local, regional, and national groups, nearly anyone can join.

即使你不是“加入者”，你也可能需要重新考虑纯粹的单人练习计划。我大部分时间也独自游泳，但当我能和朋友一起练习时，我会游得更快，并享受这种情谊。更快是因为即使是友好的竞争也会给你动力——当有人在你旁边的泳道上时，稍微争抢一下是一种良好、健康的本能。享受是因为无论我的单人练习多么快乐，我也喜欢与志同道合的游泳者一起练习。虽然加入大师级游泳是找到他们的好方法，只需召集一群朋友，就能确保最大程度的兼容性和亲和力。随着你的“全浸式”游泳技能不断提升，你会越来越享受游泳——或许这种感觉会持续很长时间。与那些同样以目标明确、专注的方式练习的人一起，你会成长得更快，也更享受这段旅程。

Even if you’re not a “joiner,” you may want to rethink a purely solo practice schedule. I swim alone most of the time too, but when I can practice with friends, I swim faster and enjoy the camaraderie. Faster because even friendly competition gives you a push—it’s just good, healthy instinct to race a little when someone’s in the lane next to yours. Enjoyable because no matter how blissful my solo practices are, I also enjoy the company of like-minded swimmers. And though joining Masters swimming is a good way of finding them, you can assure the maximum compatibility and congeniality by simply gathering a group of friends. As your Total Immersion skills grow, you’re going to enjoy swimming more and more—probably for a long time to come. You’ll grow faster, and enjoy the journey more, with the company of those who like to practice in a similarly purposeful and mindful way.

和朋友一起游泳/寻找一起游泳的朋友

Swimming With Friends/Finding Friends to Swim With

伙伴系统

THE BUDDY SYSTEM

找一个（或者两三个）合得来的训练伙伴，约定每周在泳池见面一到几次。这样你不仅会更有义务遵守约定，最终更规律地游泳，而且有同伴一起，你们俩都能游得更好。

Find a compatible training partner (or two or three) and make a pact to meet at the pool one or more times a week. Not only will you feel more obliged to keep the appointment and end up swimming more regularly, you’ll both swim better with company.

随着你的小团队不断壮大，你可能很快就会发现，你并不是唯一一个寻找训练伙伴的人。有一年冬天，我决定每天早上6:30约上几个朋友一起锻炼。我们的“锻炼圈”经常会新增五六个人，因为其他黎明前偶尔锻炼的人会问他们是否也能“加入我们”。像这样随意组建团队是获得与他人一起游泳益处的最便捷、最灵活的方式。你甚至可以得到一些即兴的指导，因为训练伙伴们总是很乐意观看你的划水或训练。只要告诉他们你在练习什么以及要注意什么，最好是在水下戴着泳镜练习。

You’ll probably soon find you weren’t alone looking for training mates, as your little band grows. One winter I decided I needed the push of meeting a couple of friends to work out at 6:30 each morning. Frequently, our “workout circle” grew by five or six people as other stray predawn exercisers asked if they too could “join up.” Casual team formation like this is the most convenient and flexible way to gain the benefits of swimming with other people. You can even get some impromptu coaching, since workout mates are always happy to watch you stroke or drill. Just tell them what you’re practicing and what to look for, preferably underwater through goggles.

加入大师游泳

JOINING MASTERS SWIMMING

别被“大师”这个词吓到。它的意思和你想象的不一样，我稍后会解释。

Don’t be put off by the word Masters. It doesn’t mean what you may think, as I’ll explain in a moment.

事实上，加入大师队可能是结识不同水平的朋友并结识新朋友的最佳方式。你还会有一位教练来规划你的训练，帮助你改进划水动作，不过大师队教练的专业素养、精力和专注力参差不齐。有些教练似乎很有天赋，能让每次训练都比上一次更好。而有些教练则不过是救生员而已。你只有亲自尝试才能知道结果，不过加入之前咨询一下队员通常能得到可靠的建议。加入大师队后，你安排游泳时间的灵活性会有所降低，但你总是可以在方便的时候和团队一起练习，不方便的时候自己练习。

Joining a Masters team, in fact, is probably the best way to swim with friends of all abilities and make new ones. You’ll also have a coach to plan your workouts and help you improve your stroke, though there’s a wide range of professionalism, energy, and attention levels among Masters coaches. Some seem to have a gift for making every practice better than the one before. Others are little more than lifeguards. You won’t know until you try, though asking members before you join usually produces reliable opinions. You do lose some flexibility in scheduling your swim with a Masters group, but you can always practice with the team when it’s convenient, and on your own when it’s not.

最重要的是，要知道“大师”并非“严肃”或“精英”的代名词。只有极少数大师级游泳运动员符合这一描述，但大多数人可能和你一样游泳——或者在加入大师级团队并开始进步之前也是如此。事实上，只有三分之一的大师级游泳运动员会参加比赛。大多数人加入时并没有打算参加比赛。他们纯粹是为了健身和休闲而游泳，热爱这项运动，希望结识其他热爱游泳的人，并寻求教练的帮助。

Above all, know that “Masters” is not a code word for “serious” or “elite.” A tiny percentage of Masters swimmers fit that description, but most probably swim just like you do—or they did until they joined a Masters team and jump-started their progress. In fact, only a third of Masters swimmers compete. Most join with no intention of ever racing. They’re strictly fitness and recreational swimmers who love the sport, want to meet other people who do too, and are looking for coaching to help them along.

这是一个亲切又亲切的组织。虽然美国大师游泳协会是国家行政机构，但其基层基础——大多数游泳运动员所能接触到的——是五十个地方大师游泳委员会 (LMSC)，负责监督各自地区的大师游泳团体。LMSC 负责注册、组织和批准比赛、与会员保持定期沟通，并且经常举办社交活动。国家办公室负责协调各LMSC，组织全国和邮政运动会（见方框），并为所有会员提供保险。欲了解更多关于美国大师游泳协会的信息，请访问www.usms.org，在那里您可以找到您所在地区LMSC的链接以及全国各地游泳场所的目录。

It’s a personal and personable organization. For though U.S. Masters Swimming is the national administrative body, the grassroots foundation—all most swimmers ever see anyway—are the fifty Local Masters Swim Committees (LMSC) that oversee Masters swimming groups in their areas. The LMSCs handle registration, organize and sanction meets, maintain regular communications with their members, and often have social activities as well. The national office coordinates among the LMSCs, organizes National and Postal meets (see box), and provides insurance for all members. For more information on U.S. Masters Swimming, visit www.usms.org where you’ll find a link for for your area’s LMSC and a directory of places to swim all over the country.

大师组的范围从松散非正式到高度结构化，应有尽有。大多数组员都包含这两种类型的游泳运动员，也有很多介于这两种类型之间的运动员，他们都在同一个屋檐下快乐地游泳。在一两条泳道中，你会发现一些曾经的竞技游泳运动员，他们为了比赛或健身而进行高强度的训练。在中级泳道中，你会发现一些较晚才开始游泳的游泳运动员，他们偶尔会穿上泳衣参加大师赛（还有一些铁人三项运动员，他们通常很有竞争力，但游泳经验不足）。在其余的泳道中，你会发现一些健身游泳运动员，他们加入的主要目的是获得教练的指导和增进友谊。如果你的技术过硬（例如，你可以持续平均每段20次划水），你几乎肯定能找到一条适合你的泳道。

Masters groups run the gamut from loose and informal to highly structured. Most groups include swimmers of both kinds and many in between, all swimming happily under the same roof. In one or two lanes, you’ll find former competitive swimmers who train intensely, whether for meets or for fitness. In the intermediate lanes, swimmers who came to the sport a little later, and who suit up for the occasional Masters meet (plus triathletes who are usually quite competitive but less experienced as swimmers). And in the rest, fitness swimmers who joined mainly for coaching pointers and camaraderie. If your skills are sound (i.e., you can consistently swim an average of twenty strokes per length), you will almost certainly find a lane that suits you.

规模较大的团队通常提供更多训练机会和更多教练。规模较小的团队可能训练时间较少，教练经验也不足，但提供一对一指导的机会更多。而且大多数团队都有一个共同点——泳池外的生活。大师级团队通常非常注重社交。最终，您可能会选择训练地点和时间安排最方便的团队。

Larger teams usually offer more practices and more coaches. Smaller groups may offer fewer practices and less experienced coaches, but more opportunity for one-on-one advice. And one thing most have in common—a life outside the pool. Masters teams tend to be quite social. In the end, you’ll probably choose the group that offers the most convenient practice location and schedule.

泳池规则

RULES OF THE ROAD IN THE POOL

泳池不像公园。你不能随便把一群运动员扔进去，让他们随心所欲地锻炼。空间太狭小，泳道也太局促。所以游泳者们要遵守一种不成文但绝非非正式的礼仪，这种礼仪不仅礼貌而且实用，尽可能地容纳更多的人，安全、流畅地进行他们需要的锻炼，避免碰撞。

Pools are not like parks. You can’t just throw a bunch of athletes in and let them work out any way they please. Space is too tight, lanes are too confining. So swimmers observe an unspoken but certainly not unofficial etiquette that is not only polite but practical, fitting in as many people as possible, doing the workouts they need safely, smoothly, and without collisions.

越早了解规则，你就能越快适应游泳环境。幸运的是，就像汽车的交通规则一样，美国各地的泳池规则也大同小异，这意味着你应该能够顺利适应任何地方。但为了确保万无一失，在任何不熟悉的泳池，最好咨询一下救生员。他们可能在那里发明了一些新规则。

The sooner you know the rules, the better you’ll fit in wherever you find yourself swimming. Fortunately, just like the rules of the road for cars, the conventions in pools are pretty similar all over the United States, which means you should be able to fit in smoothly anywhere. But just to be sure, check with the lifeguard at any unfamiliar pool. They may have invented something new there.

1. 选择你的泳道。在人流量大的泳池里，通常会为速度较快、中等和较慢的游泳者预留特定的泳道，这些泳道通常会在泳池壁、泳池甲板或起跑器上标示。当然，这些速度指标是相对的。“快”可能意味着在一个泳池里每100码游1分00秒，在另一个泳池里则为1分30秒。所以，你最好的选择是仔细观察每条泳道，选择一条最适合你的泳道。以后再考虑泳道标签的问题吧。

1. Picking your lane. In a busy pool, specific lanes are usually reserved for faster, moderate, and slower-speed swimmers, and are often identified by signs on the wall, deck, or starting block. Of course, those speed terms are relative. “Fast” could mean 1:00 per 100 yards in one pool, 1:30 in another. So your best bet is to eyeball each lane and pick the one that looks most like you. Worry about labels some other time.

如果没有标示指示，那就有点像边疆正义：控球权占了法律的十分之九。谁已经在那儿，谁就设定了球道的节奏。如果你比领跑者快，就后退。今天或许更适合练习你的击球动作，而不是速度。

If no directions are posted, then it’s kind of frontier justice: Possession is nine tenths of the law. Whoever’s already there sets the lane’s pace. If you’re faster than the pacesetters, back off. Today might be a good time to work on your stroke instead of your speed.

在热身的前五到十分钟，你的游速肯定会比较慢，所以你可能需要先从较慢的泳道开始，然后再换到较快的泳道。或者，如果你已经游了一段时间，决定进行一组会减慢速度的打腿练习，那么换泳道也是合理的。

You’ll certainly be swimming more slowly during the first five or ten minutes as you warm up, so you may want to start in a slower lane, then switch to a faster one later. Or, if you’ve been swimming for a while and decide to do a kicking set which will slow you down, it makes sense to switch lanes.

2. 入水。第一条规则：绝对禁止跳水。这不安全，即使你认为安全，泳池的保险公司也不同意。在任何有泳道的地方，都要脚先着地，轻轻地将身体放低。

2. Getting in. Rule one: No diving. Ever. It’s not safe, and even if you happen to think it is, the pool’s insurance company disagrees. Lower yourself down gently, feet first, anywhere lap swimming is going on.

然后，不要贸然闯入。你会和陌生人共享狭小的空间，而且如果你觉得推开泳道不利于表达善意和合作，就随时可能离开。如果有人显然正在游很长的距离，而且短期内不会停下来，那就潜入泳池，站在泳道边上一分钟左右，让他们看到你再开始游。切勿在别人前面或后面立即推开泳道。无论哪种方式，都要留出至少五到十秒的缓冲时间。

Then, don’t just barge in. You’ll be sharing tight space with strangers, and pushing off whenever you feel like it is no way to show goodwill and cooperation. If someone is obviously in the middle of a long swim and won’t be stopping anytime soon, slip into the pool and stand to the side of the lane for a minute or so, allowing them see you before you start. And never push off immediately in front of or behind someone else. Allow at least five or ten seconds of cushion either way.

3. 导航。如果泳道里只有另一位游泳者，你们俩可以随意分道，各占一边。先到先得，所以入道时问问你的泳道伙伴是想“绕圈”还是“分道”。如果是三人或三人以上，显然除了绕圈别无选择。所以，如果你是第三人，而前两位正在分道，就悄悄地入道，站在一边，直到他们都注意到你，然后问问他们是否介意换成绕圈的模式。

3. Navigating. If there’s just one other swimmer in the lane, you two can split it if you want, each taking a side. It’s first-come, first-served, so ask as you’re getting in whether your lane mate would prefer to “circle” or “split.” With three or more, there’s obviously no choice but to circle. So if you’ll be the third and the first two are splitting, slip in, stand to one side until they both notice you, and ask if they’d mind switching to a circle pattern.

绕圈几乎总是逆时针——至少在靠右行驶的国家是这样。在靠左行驶的国家，我发现人们也一样：顺时针。把底部的线想象成高速公路的分隔线，然后靠右行驶，尽可能靠近分道线。

Circling is nearly always counterclockwise—at least in countries where we drive on the right. In left-driving countries, I’ve found they swim the same way: clockwise. Think of the line on the bottom as the highway divider and stay to the right, as close to the lane rope as possible.

4. 超车。有时，即使同一条赛道上所有人的速度都一样，你也会被别人的脚掌追上。要超车，只需在一圈内轻轻敲击他的脚一次即可。当你到达下一堵墙时，他会向右移动，而你会从左侧超车。当然，如果你是“被超车者”，在遇到下一堵墙时，向右移动，以此让路。

4. Passing. Sometimes, even with everyone in a lane supposedly moving along at the same clip, you’ll come steaming up on someone’s soles. To pass, tap him on the feet only once during the lap. When you reach the next wall, he’ll move right and you’ll pass on the left. If you are the “passee,” of course, yield by moving to the right at the next wall.

做间歇训练时不要固执己见。每个人都有自己的泳池，为了保持节奏，你可能需要灵活地调整时间，给其他游泳者留出一些空间。在间歇倒计时快结束时，如果遇到游得慢的选手？那就缩短你的休息时间，在他们到达之前离开，而不是在他们经过时立即蹬水，然后立即超越他们。如果有更快的选手入水，请将你的间歇时间延长几秒钟，这样你就可以在他们身后蹬水，而不是挡住他们的路。

Don’t be stubborn when you’re doing intervals. It’s everyone’s pool, and to make that work you may have to be flexible enough to adjust your timing up or down to give other swimmers some space. Slower swimmer coming in toward the end of your interval countdown? Shave your rest a little and leave before they get there, instead of pushing off the instant they go by and immediately having to pass. If a faster swimmer’s coming in, extend your interval a few seconds so you push off behind them, rather than getting in their way.

常识和意识会让你在任何地方都受益。如果你身后的游泳者游得足够快，可以在下一个距离追上你，不要等她用脚轻点你。在下一个墙边停下来让她过去。礼貌总是值得赞赏的。而且几乎总是会得到回报。

Common sense and awareness will get you everywhere. If a swimmer behind you is coming up fast enough to catch you on the next length, don’t even wait until she taps your feet. Stop at the next wall and let her by. Good manners are always appreciated. And almost always reciprocated.

5. 休息。想要喘口气，就挤到右侧角落（游向池壁时，就在你右边）。想要长时间休息，比如几分钟以上，就坐在甲板上，完全不挡路。

5. Resting. To take a breather, squeeze into the right-side corner (your right as you swim toward the wall). To take a long breather, more than a couple of minutes, sit on the deck completely out of the way.

关于游泳的部分就到此为止。在甲板上：(1) 千万不要在计步器前徘徊。毕竟，别人看不透你。(2) 不要未经允许就借用泳道尽头的装备，即使它看起来好像没人用。

So much for the actual swimming part. On the deck: (1) Never loiter in front of the pace clock. After all, people can’t read through you. And (2) Don’t borrow the equipment sitting at the end of the lane without asking, even if it looks like it’s not being used.

大师游泳比赛：你不能输

Masters Swim Meets: You Can’t Lose

如今，每当有游泳新手提到有朝一日想参加大师赛或公开水域比赛时，我都会感到惊讶。跑步新手似乎一穿好耐克鞋就准备好填写他们的第一份公路赛申请表。游泳比赛究竟有什么特别之处，让那些泳道游泳运动员——即使是那些已经几十年的运动员——觉得这种比赛只是给高手玩的？如果跑步者都这么悲观，那么每场10公里比赛都会一眨眼就结束，可能不到40分钟。比他们跑得更久的人根本就懒得去参赛。

These days I’m actually surprised when a new swimmer even mentions wanting to enter a Masters meet or open-water race someday. New runners seem ready to fill out their first road race application the minute their Nikes are broken in. What is it about swim meets that makes lap swimmers—even those who have been at it for decades— think the contests are just for experts? If runners were such pessimists, every 10K race would be over in a blink, maybe under forty minutes. No one who took longer would bother showing up.

游泳运动员不知道自己错过了什么。当你练习了一段时间的“完全沉浸式”训练，你的划水动作开始感觉更流畅、更轻松、更快速时，检验你进步的最佳方法就是参加大师赛。

Swimmers don’t know what they’re missing. After you’ve been practicing your Total Immersion drills for a while, and your stroke has begun to feel smoother, easier, and faster, the best way to test your progress is swimming in a Masters meet.

“但我不是为了奖牌才参加的，”你说。好。其他大多数大师赛也一样。想要彻底打破大师赛是为那些渴望奖项的选手准备的神话，最好的办法就是亲眼见证。无论是草根娱乐还是全国锦标赛，你都能看到各个年龄段的选手，他们可能在任何基督教青年会（YMCA）的单圈训练中都显得微不足道。没错，那些神童们可能在50秒内完成100码自由泳，但其他人可能只需要3分钟……而且他们会因为出色的表现而获得热烈的掌声。

“But I’m not in it for the medals,” you say. Good. Neither are most other Masters. The best way to once and for all explode the myth that Masters meets are for bloodthirsty award hounds is to watch one. Grassroots pastime or National Championship, you’ll see competitors of all ages who might not stand out in any YMCA lap session. True, the whiz kids might knock off 100 yards of freestyle in under fifty seconds, but others may take three minutes … and they’ll get hearty applause for a job well done.

最让像我这样的大学游泳老手们惊讶的是，大师赛上那种轻松随意、轻松随意的氛围，那些人都记得，比赛就像高压锅一样，需要拼尽全力才能完成。享受快乐是第一位的，取得好成绩才是第二位的。比赛是分秒必争，而不是互相较量。

What most astonishes former college swimmers like me, people who remember meets as pressure-cooker contests of grim determination, is the relaxed, folksy feeling at Masters meets. Having a good time comes first, turning in a good time comes second. Competition is against the clock, not against each other.

大多数人不会谈论自己不愿参加比赛的原因。那些承认自己不愿参加大师赛的人常常表示，一想到要面对这些期望，他们就感到害怕：

Most people don’t talk about why they won’t race. People who admit their reluctance to enter Masters meets often describe feeling intimidated by the thought of facing these expectations:

 

 

1.你必须从高台出发。不可以。高手级游泳运动员可以自由地在水中出发——而且他们经常这样做，只是因为他们觉得这样更舒服。

1.You must execute a racing start off a high platform. No you mustn’t. Masters swimmers are free to start their races in the water—and often do, simply because they feel more comfortable that way.

 

 

2.你必须会竞速转身。又错了。这种容易学的开放式转身在大师赛上很常见。我见过年龄较大的游泳运动员用这种转身赢得全国冠军。

2.You have to be able to do racing flip turns. Wrong again. The easily learned open turn is common at Masters meets. I’ve seen swimmers in older age groups win national titles with them.

 

 

3.你将与前大学游泳明星同场竞技。简直是胡扯。首先，大师赛上只有三分之一的选手有过大师赛前的竞技游泳经验。其次，如果你是新手，你无论如何都会和其他新手一起游泳，因为预赛是按预估时间排序的。很多比赛甚至会设置新手赛，仅限从未参加过竞技游泳比赛的选手参加。你第一次参赛就有可能成为奖牌获得者。

3.You’ll be racing against former collegiate stars. Nonsense. First, only a third of the swimmers at Masters meets have had any pre-Masters competitive swimming experience. Second, if you’re new to this, you’ll be swimming with other new swimmers anyway since heats are seeded by estimated time. Many meets even offer novice-only races, restricted to those who have never swum the event competitively. You could be a medalist your first time out.

比赛通常如此：比赛时，男女选手按五岁为一个年龄组进行评分，从十九岁到二十四岁开始，一直到一百多岁。但预赛通常按时间排序，不考虑年龄或性别。如果预计成绩相近，一位二十四岁的女性可以和一位六十二岁的男性并肩游泳。

It generally works this way: At meets, men and women are divided into five-year age groups for scoring purposes, beginning with nineteen to twenty-four and continuing up to one hundred plus. But heats are normally seeded according to time, with no regard for age or sex. A twenty-four-year-old woman could be swimming next to a sixty-two-year-old man if their times are expected to be similar.

事实上，如果你能以良好的状态游完25码泳池的两圈（50码是大师赛的最低距离），你就已经准备好参加大师赛了。大多数人可以在30秒到1分钟内完成50码的比赛。自由泳和仰泳是技术含量最低的项目。对于现在先学蛙泳和蝶泳。正规的蛙泳需要像蛙泳一样的踢腿动作，这对很多新手来说感觉很笨拙；至于蝶泳，即使是游两个来回对任何人来说都是一个挑战。

In fact, you’re ready for a Masters meet if you can swim two lengths of a 25-yard pool in good form (50 yards is the minimum distance in Masters meets). Most people can finish off a 50-yard race in 30 seconds to a minute. Freestyle and backstroke are the least technical events. For get breastroke and butterfly for now. Legal breaststroke requires a frog-like kick that feels ungainly to many novices and as for butterfly, even two lengths is a challenge for anyone.

大师们说的自由泳，其实就是自由泳。自由选择你喜欢的任何泳姿。我们大多数人都选择所谓的爬泳，因为爬泳通常速度最快，但你才是真正的主人。1992年，我在大师世界锦标赛的200米自由泳比赛中，看到两位九十多岁的男士并驾齐驱。两人都使用初级仰泳，这完全符合规则。

And when Masters say freestyle, they mean free style. As in free to choose any style you like. Most of us use the so-called crawl because it’s generally fastest, but you’re the boss. In 1992, I watched two ninety-something gentlemen race neck-and-neck in a 200-meter freestyle contest in the Masters World Championships. Both were using an elementary backstroke, perfectly legal under the rules.

最后，选择任何你想参加的项目——最长的1500米自由泳，也就是一英里左右——只要你能在不站起来或不扶泳道线的情况下完成比赛即可。大师赛全国锦标赛甚至世界锦标赛都是全民参与的比赛，参赛者通常可以参加三项比赛，无需达到任何资格赛成绩。地方、州甚至地区比赛都不需要达到任何资格赛成绩才能参加任何项目的比赛。

Finally, pick any event distance you want—right up to the longest, which is the 1500-meter freestyle, just this side of a mile—so long as you can complete the race without standing up or holding on to lane lines. Masters National and even World Championships are all-comers meets, with competitors usually guaranteed the right to swim in three events without meeting any qualifying times. Local, state, and even regional meets never require qualifying times for entry to any number of events.
