不要误以为50码或100码的短距离比赛是轻松进入游泳比赛的最佳方式，因为它们速度很快。短距离比赛需要更多的技巧、力量和速度，才能避免落后。你最好参加500码的比赛，这样你就能有时间练习你一直在练习的东西，比如姿势和速度。此外，这感觉更像是练习游泳，而不是短距离冲刺的极速。

Don’t mistakenly think the best ways to ease into swim racing are the short 50- or 100-yard events because they’re over fast. Shorter races take more skill, power, and speed to avoid being left way behind. You’re better off going maybe 500 yards, which also gives you time to work on things you’ve been practicing, like form and pace. Besides, it will feel more like your practice swimming than the breakneck speed of a short sprint.

你也不需要拥有极佳的身体素质才能游完500码。记住我们的“70法则”：你的游泳表现70%取决于你的划水技巧，只有30%取决于体能。一旦你能在练习中不间断地游8分钟左右，你很可能就能参加500码的比赛了。

You needn’t be in superb shape to handle 500 yards, either. Remember our “Rule of 70”: 70 percent of your swim performance comes from your stroke mechanics and only 30 percent from fitness. Once you can swim for about eight minutes nonstop in a practice, you probably have a 500-yard event inside.

邮寄相遇：一流的邮票游泳测试

MAIL-IN MEETS: THE FIRST-CLASS STAMP SWIMMING TEST

想来一场完全属于自己的比赛吗？没有观众，没有特定的起跑时间，没有噪音，没有压力？邮寄比赛（你只需邮寄成绩，裁判负责计分）绝对是最轻松的。纽约州维克多市的贝蒂·巴里多年来一直指导着一项名为“健身挑战赛”的邮寄比赛。她说，她组织的参赛者中有三分之一从未参加过任何有组织的游泳比赛。“一位女士在参赛时给我发了一张纸条，上面写着：‘我不想上起跳台；我不想和任何人比赛；我很高兴你们给了我这个机会，让我在自己的泳池里做一些有意义的事情。’”

Want a race all your own? No spectators, no specific starting time, no noise, no pressure? Postal meets (you just mail in your results and officials handle the scoring) are as no-pressure as they get. Betty Barry of Victor, New York, directed a postal meet called the Fitness Challenge for several years and says a third of her entrants are people who have never been in any kind of organized swimming event before. “One woman sent me a note with her entry that said, ‘I don’t want to get up on the blocks; I don’t want to have to race anybody; I’m so happy that you’ve given me the opportunity to do something meaningful by myself in my own pool.’ ”

就像通过邮件进行的国际象棋比赛一样，在邮寄比赛中，你永远不会与对手面对面。你可以选择自己方便的泳池游泳，唯一需要的观众是你选择的计圈员/计时器。结束后，将结果写在报名表上，请见证人签字，然后邮寄给计分员。几周后，你会收到通知，告知你与其他所有参赛者的排名。这就像一个未公开的电话号码一样私密而文明。

Like a chess match played by mail, you never meet your rivals face to face in a postal event. Swim in whatever pool suits you, at your own convenience, the only required spectator being a lap counter/timer of your choice. When you’re done, write your result on the entry form, have your witness sign it, and mail it to the tabulator. A couple of weeks later, you’re notified how you placed against everyone else who did the same thing. It’s as private and civilized as an unpublished phone number.

而且比“真正的”比赛更加丰富多彩。有短距离比赛、长距离比赛，还有一项比赛是一小时内游泳的最大距离，还有一项是二月份游泳总码数的比赛。奖项总是按性别和五岁年龄组进行统计，就像常规大师赛一样。

And more varied than a “real” meet. Short events, long events, one for the maximum distance swum in one hour, another for the grand total of your February yardage. Awards are always tabulated by gender and five-year age group, as they are in regular Masters meets.

邮政游泳比赛能为你的训练注入活力，带来只有参加比赛才能带来的动力。而且，它还能帮你省钱。你可以与来自全国各地的同龄游泳选手一较高低，无需购买机票。请访问美国游泳协会 (USMS) 网站 ( www.usms.org )，查看邮政游泳比赛的时间表。

Postal events can juice up your training with the motivation that can come only from entering a race. And they’re real money savers. You can compare yourself to other swimmers your age from all over the country without ever having to buy a plane ticket. Check the USMS Web site (www.usms.org) for a schedule of postal events.

无泳道，无墙——宽阔水域游泳

No Lanes, No Walls—The Wide-Open-Water Swim

公开水域游泳不像大师赛那样“俱乐部式”，但也同样能让人放松身心。同样的原因也让公路赛在跑步者中比田径赛更受欢迎——在“开放道路”上自由驰骋，享受在数百人赛场上匿名竞技的快乐。

Open-water swims are not all as “clubby” as Masters meets, but they’re just as relaxing in their own way. And it’s for the same reason that road races are so much more popular than track meets among runners— freedom of the “open road” and the happy anonymity of competing in a field of hundreds.

正如成千上万的步行运动员永远不会考虑田径比赛的军事化纪律一样，公开水域比赛也吸引了从未在游泳池中比赛的游泳运动员。没有站在甲板周围警惕计时员的威胁，没有在邻近起跑器上挑战的对手，也没有坐满好奇粉丝的看台盯着水面——甚至可能看着你的人——公开水域赛事就像周末的10公里赛跑一样平淡无奇。证据：虽然美国大师游泳队拥有约4万名注册会员，但正如我们之前所说，只有三分之一的人参加比赛。然而，每年有6万人参加与铁人三项相关的公开水域比赛，还有成千上万的人在公开水域游泳时挤满海岸线。谁还需要被精心呵护的精确泳道？只需偶尔被其他不听话的人踢到脸或肘击耳朵，你就拥有了自由。

Just as thousands of foot-powered athletes would never consider the military regimentation of a track meet, open-water competitions draw swimmers who never race in a pool. Without the intimidation of timers standing watchfully around the deck, rivals challenging from neighboring starting blocks, and bleachers full of curious fans peering at the water—maybe even at you—open-water events are as matter-of-fact as a weekend 10K. Proof: Though U.S. Masters Swimming has some 40,000 registered members, only a third enter meets as we said earlier. Yet 60,000 people swim in open-water races connected with triathlons each year, and thousands more crowd the shorelines at open-water swims. Who needs the coddled precision of lanes? For the price of an occasional foot in the face or elbow in the ear from one of the other unguided bodies, you have freedom.

那么，为什么这么多游泳者从未踏出泳池，去体验在湖泊、河流和海洋中畅游的刺激呢？原因在于胆怯。游泳时没有绳索指引，看不到水底，也没有墙壁可以依靠。你得找到浮标才不会迷路，或许还要搏斗一番，而且谁知道水里除了游泳者还有什么呢？谢天谢地，别再说了。

So why is it many swimmers never venture out of the pool to explore the exhilaration of swimming in lakes, rivers, and oceans? Timidity. Swimming without a line to guide you, a bottom you can see, and a wall nearby for comfort? Buoys you have to find so you don’t get lost, perhaps surf to fight, and who knows what else in the water out there besides swimmers? No thanks.

所有风险都是可控的，当你最终从海滩跳入水中，你的身体会记起，在氯气、过滤器和水泵，甚至电灯出现之前，我们就是这样游泳的，显然这些风险是值得的。或许没有墙可以触及安全，但也没有墙可以限制你。

All manageable risks, and clearly worth the managing when you finally plunge in off the beach and your body remembers that before chlorine, before filters and pumps, even before electric lights, this is how we swam. There may be no wall to touch for security, but there’s no wall hemming you in either.

显然，如果没有传统的救生员、站立的裤子、以及可以扶住的墙壁或泳道标记等安全网，你就必须自己准备一张安全网。以下是如何安装它的方法。

Obviously without the customary safety net of lifeguards, bottoms to stand on, and walls or lane markers to hold on to, you’ve got to ready a safety net of your own. Here’s how to put it in place.

在海上感到宾至如归：策略

Feeling at Home at Sea: Strategies

回到泳池​​

BACK AT THE POOL

如果您首先在泳池中磨练一些技能，您将会更快地适应开放水域条件。

You’ll adapt to open-water conditions much faster if you first sharpen a couple of skills in the pool.

 

 

1. 练习双侧呼吸。在公开水域比赛中，你无法确定自己更舒服的一侧是否能呼吸到空气。风浪可能对你不利，你的地标也可能在你的“另一侧”，所以你需要能够随时将头转向另一侧。

1. Practice bilateral breathing. You can’t be certain of getting air on your more comfortable side during an open-water race. Wind and waves may be against you, and your landmarks may be on your “other” side, so you need to be able to roll your head either way at any time.

 

 

2. 练习游泳时，每游一圈抬头向前看两到三次。抬头前，先想象自己在寻找什么。这会教你立即找到自己的地标，并在过程中保持节奏和平衡。

2. Practice swimming and looking up and forward two to three times per pool length. Visualize what you’re looking for before you lift your head. This will teach you to spot your landmarks right away, holding on to your rhythm and balance as you do.

 

 

3. 闭上眼睛，重复游几圈25码，测试一下在水浑浊且没有引导线的情况下，你能否保持直线游动。慢慢游，以免撞到泳道线。除非你喜欢被人称为“无引导鱼雷”，否则要等到找到自己的泳道后再游。数划水次数，当你计算出距离泳道壁还有四划时，就睁开眼睛。千万不要发生意外。这将教会你在没有泳道线引导的情况下保持直线游动。

3. Swim some 25-yard repeats with your eyes closed to test your ability to swim straight when the water’s murky and there’s nothing to guide on. Do this slowly in case you run into a lane line, and wait until you have a lane to yourself unless you enjoy getting a reputation as an unguided torpedo. Count strokes and open your eyes when you calculate you’re still four short of the wall. No accidents please. This will teach you to swim straight without a lane line for guidance.

 

 

比赛前​​

BEFORE THE RACE

 

 

1. 显然，你首先想在湖里或海里游一会儿。你会习惯没有泳道线之类的便捷指引，并学会本能地利用岸上的地标导航。安全第一：与经验丰富的同伴或团队一起游泳，或者在独木舟或皮划艇的护送下游泳。在冷水中要小心，并靠近岸边。体温过低会影响你的协调性，并影响你的判断力。如果你有潜水服，它会起到很好的保暖作用。

1. Obviously you want to do some swimming in a lake or the ocean first. You’ll get used to the absence of convenient guides like lane lines, and will learn to navigate instinctively using on-shore landmarks. Safety first: Swim with an experienced partner or in a group, or with an escort canoe or kayak. Be careful in cold water and stay close to shore. Hypothermia (lowered body temperature) can impair your coordination and cloud your judgment. A wetsuit, if you have one, will be good insulation.

 

 

比赛日​​​​

ON RACE DAY

 

 

1. 如果你不能游出去查看赛道，至少要研究一下地图。想象一下从水里看重要的地标——尤其是终点线——会是什么样子。向救生员询问水温、当前洋流，如果是海上比赛，还要询问海浪条件。

1. If you can’t swim out and check the course itself, at least study a map. Picture how important landmarks—notably the finish line—will look from the water. Check with the lifeguards for water temperature, prevailing currents, and, if it’s an ocean race, surf conditions.

 

 

2. 计算你需要经过或转向多少个浮标，以及你需要从哪一侧经过它们。检查水底轮廓，确定你将要入水和出水的区域。你能跑多远并“海豚式”前进？你需要在哪里开始游泳？

2. Count how many buoys you have to pass or turn on, and on which side you need to pass them. Check bottom contours for the areas where you’ll be entering and leaving the water. How far can you run and “porpoise,” and where will you need to start swimming?

 

 

3. 如果比赛允许穿潜水服，那就穿一件吧。穿上它，你的游速会比穿潜水服快5%，而且不用费多大力气。

3. If wetsuits are allowed in the race, wear one. You’ll swim about 5 percent faster without working any harder for it.

 

 

比赛期间​​

DURING THE RACE

 

 

1. 公开水域比赛通常以集体（混乱）起跑开始。即使你需要游更长的距离才能到达第一个浮标，也要靠边游。这样你就会远离队伍的中间，因为如果手臂或腿不小心碰到了，可能会扰乱你的节奏，撞掉你的泳镜，或者在极少数情况下造成损伤。

1. Open-water races usually begin with a mass (confusion) start. Stay off to the side, even if you have to swim a slightly longer course to the first buoy. You’ll be out of the middle of the pack, where a collision with a stray arm or leg could ruin your rhythm, knock your goggles off, or in rare cases, do some damage.

 

 

2. 找一个比你游得稍快的人跟你一起游。跟船游可以让你游得更快，而且不用费力，更不用说让你不用经常抬头导航了。你只要把脸埋在水里，跟着队伍游就行了。当然，前提是你的跟船人知道自己要去哪里。

2. Look for someone slightly faster than you are to draft off. Drafting will let you swim a little faster with no more exertion, not to mention letting you get away with lifting your head for navigation much less often. You can just keep your face in the water and follow the pack. You can, that is, if your draftee knows where he’s going.

 

 

3. 在海里游泳时，你可能需要调整你的划水姿势。别担心。规律的泳池游泳者经常会发现海浪会打乱他们的节奏，所以不要强求。只要感受波浪，并顺势翻滚即可。在波涛汹涌的水中，高肘移臂也至关重要。而且，由于你在咸水中的浮力比在淡水中更大，你可以停止打腿，只需专注于速度即可。增强前象限游泳能力以及臀部有节奏的转动来获得力量。

3. You may need to adjust your stroke for ocean swimming. Don’t worry. Methodical pool swimmers often find waves upset their rhythm, so don’t fight it. Just feel the swells and roll with them. A high-elbow recovery is also essential in choppy water. And since you’re more buoyant in saltwater than fresh, you can lay off the kick and just focus on your speed enhancing front-quadrant swimming and the rhythmic rolling of your hips for power.

 

 

4. 如果是铁人三项游泳，最后不要冲刺。保持你的配速，保持低心率，为骑行和跑步保存体力。靠近岸边时，游到你的手触底，然后站起来，开始以高抬腿的步态跑向岸边。

4. If it’s a triathlon swim, don’t sprint at the end. Just hold your pace, keep your heart rate low, and save your energy for the bike and run. As you near shore, swim just until your hands touch bottom, then stand and begin running to shore with a high-knee gait.

— 后记 —

— Afterword —

专注游泳能丰富你的生活吗？

Can Mindful Swimming Enrich Your Life?

我在这里的任务即将完成。我希望这篇文章能成为一份实用且鼓舞人心的指南，帮助你更好地、更明智地游泳，尤其希望你能像我一样，享受每一圈的畅游。但在带你去泳池之前，我想分享一些最后的想法——不是关于如何打造更流畅的划水，而是分享我把游泳作为精通和流畅练习的经验教训。

My undertaking here is nearly complete. I’ve written what I hope you’ll find to be a practical and encouraging guide to better, smarter swimming, most especially so you might enjoy every lap you ever swim, just as I do. But before I point you to the pool, I’ll offer a few final thoughts—not on how to craft a smoother stroke, but to share lessons I’ve learned from using swimming as an exercise in Mastery and Flow.

2002年6月，我完成了28.5英里的曼哈顿岛马拉松游泳赛（MIMS）。这次游泳比赛有两个灵感。一是2001年我年满50岁，想要挑战一个我二十几岁时做梦也想不到的挑战。第二个灵感来自TI的大师级教练唐·沃尔什，他50岁时绕曼哈顿游了一圈，52岁时又游了一次。唐第一次把目光投向MIMS时，教练建议他连续几个月每周训练20个小时（或6万码）。但由于他有工作和家庭，这是不可能的，所以他决定成为一名更经济的游泳运动员，并证明自己只需适量的训练就能成功游完一场马拉松。

In June 2002, I completed the 28.5-mile Manhattan Island Marathon Swim (MIMS). I had two inspirations for this swim. One was turning fifty in 2001 and wanting to undertake a challenge I would never have dreamed of in my twenties. My second inspiration was TI Master Coach Don Walsh, who swam around Manhattan at age fifty and again at fifty-two. When Don set his sights on MIMS the first time, he was advised to prepare by training up to twenty hours—or 60,000 yards—per week for several months. With a job and family, that was out of the question, so he decided to become a more economical swimmer instead and prove he could successfully swim a marathon on a moderate amount of training.

唐在第一次参加曼哈顿游泳比赛前一年参加了TI的研讨会，之后他孜孜不倦地通过练习提高效率，每周最高游了25000码。比赛当天，唐享受了整个九个小时的旅程。正如他所描述的那样：“比赛结束后，其他人都痛苦不堪。但我感觉棒极了！如果比赛官员说，‘唐，你错过了一个弯道，你必须重新绕一圈’，我就可以轻松完成比赛了。”

Don took a TI workshop one year before his first Manhattan swim, then tirelessly improved his efficiency through practice, peaking at about 25,000 yards per week. On race day, Don enjoyed his entire nine-hour trip. As he described it, “When the race was over, everyone else was in severe pain. But I felt great! If a race official had said, ‘Don, you missed a turn and you have to go around again,’ I could have done it easily.”

唐的秘诀在于无与伦比的效率，而非超人的体能。他以TI风格游泳，保持着每分钟50次的悠闲划水速度，却能与划水速度更快的对手保持同步。如果将每分钟50次划水速度乘以9小时，你会发现唐需要划水27000次才能绕曼哈顿一圈。如果这个数字看起来很大，想想其他人每分钟的划水速度都在72到80次之间，总共需要划水41000次。唐省下的14000次划水，足以绕曼哈顿半圈！

Don’s secret was matchless efficiency, rather than superhuman fitness. Swimming TI-style, he maintained a leisurely rate of 50 strokes per minute yet kept pace with rivals who were stroking much faster. If you multiply 50 strokes per minute by nine hours, you’ll find it took Don 27,000 strokes to swim around Manhattan. If that seems a huge number, consider that everyone else was stroking between 72 and 80 times per minute, taking as many as 41,000 strokes. With the 14,000 strokes Don saved, he could have swum halfway around Manhattan again!

我想像唐那样训练——用更少的划水次数完成整个循环！2002年6月23日，我游了28.5英里，用时8小时53分钟，平均每分钟划水49次，总共划水次数略高于26000次，比我的任何竞争对手都少了至少11000次。和唐一样，我非常享受这次经历，以至于不到一个小时，我就决定再来一次。但我在MIMS训练中学到的经验和最终的体验一样宝贵。

I wanted to train just as Don had—and complete the circuit in fewer strokes! On June 23, 2002, I swam 28.5 miles in a time of 8 hours and 53 minutes, averaging 49 strokes per minute, for a total of just over 26,000 strokes, at least 11,000 fewer strokes than any of my competitors. And like Don, I enjoyed the experience so thoroughly that, within an hour, I had decided to do it again. But the lessons I learned while training for MIMS were just as valuable as the experience of doing it.

在应对MIMS的过程中，我也想证明，训练马拉松游泳也能做到一刻也不无聊。四个月里，我的游泳时间是平时的两倍，而且享受每一刻。当其他MIMS游泳运动员得知我是单独训练时（我和朋友一起训练过一次，和大师队一起训练过三次，但独自训练的时间超过一百小时），他们评论说，我肯定是疯了，非得游那么长时间。大部分时间都是我自己一个人。但我享受着，并且全身心投入到每一次划水之中。

In tackling MIMS, I also wanted to demonstrate that one could train for a marathon swim with not a moment of boredom or tedium. For four months, I swam twice as much as I usually do and enjoyed every moment. When other MIMS swimmers learned that I was training solo (I did one session with a friend and three sessions with Masters teams, but more than one hundred hours of training by myself) they commented that I must be going out of my mind having to swim that much by myself. But I enjoyed and was engaged by literally every stroke.

这不仅对保持理智很重要，还因为无聊会导致注意力不集中和效率低下。我需要全神贯注地投入训练中大约15万次的划水，以确保每一次划水都能帮助我养成流畅和经济的习惯，并使其足够强大，能够坚持九个小时不间断的游泳。最终，我的MIMS训练不再仅仅是为了游28多英里。它作为一项实现精通和流畅的练习，具有更长远的价值。我们先来看看精通。

Which is important not just for sanity, but because boredom leads to lack of attention and loss of efficiency. I needed to give full attention to each of the approximately 150,000 strokes I took in training, to ensure that each one helped imprint flow and economy as a habit strong enough to survive nine hours of nonstop swimming. My training for MIMS, ultimately, became far less a quest to swim 28-plus miles. It had far more long-term value as an exercise in achieving Mastery and Flow. Let’s look at Mastery first.

任何人都可以成为大师

Anyone Can Be a Master

2003年，我参加了杰夫·穆尔达尔（Geoff Muldaur）的演出，他是一位享誉盛名的布鲁斯和根源音乐音乐家，拥有四十多年的音乐经验。我坐在离他三十英尺远的狭小演出场地里，被他那浑然天成的吉他演奏深深吸引。他似乎完全放松，几乎无意识，但他的手指拨动琴弦的微妙之处，是我从未见过的，演奏出我从未听过的富有表现力的声音。

In 2003, I attended a performance by Geoff Muldaur, a noted blues and roots musician for more than forty years. Sitting just thirty feet away in the small performance space, I was mesmerized by the effortless genius of his guitar playing. He seemed utterly relaxed, almost unconscious, yet his fingers worked the strings with a subtlety I’d never seen to produce sounds of an expressiveness I’d never heard.

在歌曲之间，在讲故事的时候，他总是不停地演奏着美妙的乐曲，通常只用一只手，一切都带着一种令人惊叹的随意感。我对妻子爱丽丝说：“我感觉我们正在观看一位从未远离乐器的艺术家。” 在一次演出中场休息时，在户外露台上，我透过百叶窗看到他正在休息的房间……他一边在房间里踱步，一边继续演奏。我知道我很享受观看一位真正的大师演奏的特权。

Between songs, while telling stories, he never stopped producing beautiful sounds, often with just one hand, all with an amazing casualness. I remarked to my wife, Alice, “I get the feeling we’re watching an artist who is never far from his instrument.” During a midshow break, while on an outdoor deck, I could see through blinds into the room where he was relaxing … which he did by continuing to play as he paced around the room. I knew I was enjoying the privilege of watching a true Master at work.

每当我们见证某种令人难忘的高水平表演——无论是杰夫·穆尔达尔的音乐创作，还是泳池里的奥运选手——我们很自然地会认为，我们所看到的一定是某种与生俱来的天赋。事实上，任何追求个人意义重大挑战的人——无论起点多么卑微——都能体验到精通的回报。

Whenever we witness some form of memorably high-level performance—whether Geoff Muldaur making music or an Olympian in the pool—it’s natural to assume that what we’re seeing must require some kind of inborn genius. In fact, anyone who pursues a personally meaningful challenge—no matter how modest their starting point—can experience the rewards of Mastery.

精通是一个引人入胜的过程，最初困难重重、令人沮丧的事情，通过练习逐渐变得轻松愉快。或许没有比游泳更适合学习精通的媒介了，因为它与基因编程活动截然相反。然而，尽管人类DNA可能天生不适合游泳，但它却被编码为从生到死都在进行着大量的学习。

Mastery is the intriguing process through which something that is initially difficult and frustrating becomes progressively easier and more pleasurable through practice. There may be no better medium than swimming for learning about Mastery because it is the antithesis of a genetically programmed activity. Yet, while human DNA may be poorly wired for swimming, it is encoded to learn prodigiously from birth to death.

精通游泳并非指在一分钟内游完100米，甚至不仅仅是指达到划水效率。就像我为曼哈顿游泳赛训练一样，精通游泳需要身心合一，不受干扰和无聊，耐心、专注、甚至充满爱意地练习。这种练习可以教会你如何在许多其他方面取得优异成绩。

Mastery in swimming is not about swimming 100 meters in less than a minute nor even solely about achieving stroke efficiency. Like my training for the Manhattan swim, it’s about uniting mind and body, without distraction and boredom, in patient, focused, almost loving practice. Practice of this sort can teach you how to perform well in many other ways.

大师的根本信条是：坚守耐心与坚持的价值，而非追求快速轻松的结果。在学习过程中，保持适度的期望，每当你达到一个基准或突破，就享受它，然后继续练习，相信你总会有更进一步的平台值得追求。

The fundamental creed of the Master is dedication to the value of patience and persistence over the desire for quick and easy results. Cultivate modest expectations along the way and every time you reach a benchmark or breakthrough, enjoy it, then keep practicing, confident you will always have some further plateau to aim for.

练习的内在回报

The Intrinsic Rewards of Practice

掌握任何挑战性技能的一个关键洞见是，每一次短暂却激动人心的冲刺之后，都会经历一段比前一段略高、持续时间更长的平台期。真正的大师学会“热爱平台期”，即使表面上看起来停滞不前，也会继续热情地练习。你可能误以为偶尔的冲刺是唯一的进步时刻，但在深层细胞层面，每当你用需要高度集中注意力的任务挑战你的身体时，学习和适应都是持续不断的。

An essential insight for mastering any challenging skill is that every brief, but thrilling, spurt forward will be followed by a much longer plateau slightly higher than the previous one. True Masters learn to “love the plateau,” continuing to practice enthusiastically even as they seem, on the surface, to be stagnating. While you may mistake those occasional upward surges as the only time progress is occurring, on a deep cellular level, learning and adaptation are constant, whenever you’re challenging your body with tasks that require intense concentration.

真正的大师坚持练习，主要是为了获得练习本身的回报。与其因为看似缺乏进步而感到沮丧，不如学会欣赏你的日常生活，就像你为偶尔的突破而兴奋一样。就像禅修一样，游泳练习可以填补你通常被外部生活中的问题和干扰所占据的空间，从而带来平和与宁静。

And true Masters keep practicing primarily for the rewards of practice itself. Rather than becoming frustrated by your seeming lack of progress, learn to appreciate your daily routine, just as much as you are thrilled by the occasional breakthrough. Just as Zen practice does, your swimming practice can bring peace and serenity by filling the space usually occupied by the problems and distractions of your external life.

每次进入泳池，我都享受着一种幸福的幸福感，因为我总是能随心所欲地做自己想做的事。一年中或许会有那么一两次，我突然顿悟，顿悟的那一刻令人振奋，但这些时刻之间的“例行公事”仍然令人满足，因为我感觉自己从未像在“精通”时那样完全地展现自我。全浸式游泳带来的乐趣也吸引着我去尝试其他活动——划船、瑜伽、越野滑雪——它们也提供了类似的机会，让我通过专注的练习逐渐提升。这些活动让我感到鼓舞，即使到了五十多岁，我仍然在稳步提升自己的运动水平。

Every time I enter a pool, I enjoy a blissful sense of well-being, because I can always do exactly what I want. I may get an electrifying moment of new insight once or twice a year, but the “routine” between those moments is still satisfying because I feel I am never more fully myself than when working on Mastery. The pleasure I have gained from Total Immersion swimming has drawn me to other activities— rowing, yoga, cross-country skiing—that offer similar opportunities for incremental improvement through mindful practice. Together they provide an encouraging sense that, even in my fifties, I’m improving steadily as an athlete.

丰富的经验

Enriched Experience

正如第六章至第八章以及TI练习示例（参见第271页）所述，TI的游泳练习方式与传统的刻苦训练截然不同。TI教练更喜欢使用“练习”而非“训练”一词，因为它蕴含着截然不同的意识。对许多TI游泳运动员来说，“练习”不仅仅是你做的事情，而是你全身心投入其中，并将其作为生活中不可或缺的一部分的事情。你练习熟练的游泳技巧，不仅是为了游得更快，也是为了享受它带来的内在乐趣。

The TI way of practicing swimming, as outlined in chapters 6 through 8 and in the sample TI practices (see page 271) is radically different from conventional grind-it-out workouts. TI coaches prefer the term “practice” over “workout” because it implies a very different awareness. For many TI swimmers, the word practice is not just something you do, but anything you immerse yourself in as an integral part of your life. You practice skilled swimming, not just to swim faster, but for the intrinsic enjoyment it brings.

虽然有些游泳运动员可能急于从简单的训练过渡到高级训练，再到快速游泳，但真正的 TI 大师，例如唐·沃尔什 (Don Walsh)，已经练习了多年的训练，学会了欣赏即使是最基本的动作中所包含的微妙之处和无限的可能性。

While some swimmers may exhibit an impatience to move from simple drills to advanced drills to swimming to swimming fast, true TI Masters, like Don Walsh, who have been practicing the drills for years, have learned to appreciate the subtleties and endless possibilities contained within even the most rudimentary movements.

唐有时会重复一个动作——一个他很久以前就学会的、动作看似完美无瑕的动作——持续三十分钟甚至更久。这种不间断的冥想式重复练习极大地拓展了他的意识。起初几乎难以察觉的动作变化，如今却意义非凡，富有启发性，可以通过极其细微的调整进行调整。像唐这样的练习能带来令人难以置信的丰富体验。这种新奇感——新的见解，对“旧”技能和动作的新认识——将永远驱散无聊和不耐烦。

On occasion, Don may repeat a single drill—one that he long ago learned to do with what appears to be impeccable form—for thirty minutes or more. Such uninterrupted, meditative repetition expands his awareness significantly. What start out as barely noticeable variations in execution become significant and revealing and can be tweaked with great subtlety. Practice like Don’s offers an incredible richness of experience. This newness—new insights, new awareness in “old” skills and movements—banishes boredom and impatience forever.

掌握的三种工具

Three Tools for Mastery

正如我之前所说，精通的回报并非只属于那些拥有特殊天赋的人。像大师一样练习，将使你达到更高的卓越境界，并获得更深的满足感。以下是三个助你开启精通之旅的工具。

As I said earlier, the rewards of Mastery are not reserved only for those gifted with special talents. Practicing like a Master will enable you to achieve a higher level of excellence and a deeper sense of satisfaction. Here are three tools for your journey.

知识就是力量

KNOWLEDGE IS POWER

当你将宝贵的时间投入练习，并全身心投入时，务必确信自己走在正确的道路上。如果我做得不错，那么这本书——由你的身体反馈证实——可以成为你这份确定性的来源。虽然大多数读者都是自学成才，但一个用心学习、知识渊博的学生总比一个跟随糟糕老师的学生要好。即使你有教练，成功的最终责任也不在于你的老师，而在于你自己。

When spending your precious time at practice—and to commit yourself without reservation—it’s essential that you be confident you’re following the right path. If I have done my job well, this book— confirmed by your body’s feedback—can be your source of that certainty. While most of those who read this book are self-coached, a devoted student armed with knowledge is better off than a student with a poor teacher. And even if you have a coach, the ultimate responsibility for success lies not with your teacher but with you.

录像带可以成为指导和信息的来源。如果一张图片胜过千言万语，那么一张动态图片或许胜过万言。但学习离不开反馈的帮助。如果没有老师，你可以找个练习伙伴来为自己创造反馈。

Videotapes can be a source of guidance and information. If a picture is worth 1,000 words, then a moving picture is probably worth 10,000 words. But learning is immeasurably aided by feedback. And you can create feedback for yourself when a teacher isn’t available by finding a practice partner.

伙伴系统

THE BUDDY SYSTEM

你可以独自努力达到精通，但旅途中有一个同伴会很有帮助：经历过同样过程的人并能分享他们的智慧和见解。他们和你一样，都在学习中，你可以和他们交流学习心得。他们只是对你的成功感兴趣，并会给予鼓励。最好的办法是找一个练习伙伴。与他们分享你的热情，并邀请他们和你一起去泳池。如果你把学到的知识的一部分教给伙伴，你会更好地理解你所学的内容……然后他们也会更好地准备帮助你。

You can work toward Mastery on your own, but it helps to have company on the journey: People who have gone through the same process and can share their wisdom and insight. People who are engaged in the same learning quest as you, with whom you can compare notes. People who are simply interested in your success and will offer encouragement. Best of all is to recruit a practice partner. Share your enthusiasm with them and invite them to join you at the pool. You’ll gain a better understanding of what you have been learning if you teach some part of it to a partner … and they will then be better prepared to help you right back.

完美不是目标

PERFECTION IS NOT THE GOAL

尤金·赫里格尔在《弓箭艺术中的禅》一书中写道，禅弓射手的训练主要不是为了射中靶心，而是为了提升自我认知。同样，精通并非追求完美，而是自我认知——包括自身的缺点和局限性。只要你拥有人类的DNA，你就永远无法达到游泳的完美境界，所以庆幸的是，你永远可以追求更大的幸福。此外，偶尔感到笨拙或无能也很重要——当你感到笨拙或无能时，不妨自嘲一笑。大师级学习者的理解力取决于他们是否愿意放弃“已知”的知识，去学习新知识。

In Zen in the Art of Archery, Eugen Herrigel wrote that Zen archers do not train primarily to shoot bull’s-eyes, but to increase their self-understanding. Similarly, Mastery is not a pursuit of perfection, but of self-knowledge—including your flaws and limitations. So long as you have human DNA, you’ll never reach swimming perfection anyway, so happily you’ll always have some greater bliss to aspire to. Further, it’s essential to feel clumsy or incompetent at times—and to smile at yourself when you do. The understanding of a Master learner is measured by their willingness to surrender what they “know” in order to learn something new.

让通往精通的道路成为一种强大的习惯，将丰富你的人生体验。虽然你最初的目标只是游得更快或更高效，但你可以超越这个目标，让游泳成为一种令人深感满足的体验，甚至可能从中汲取人生经验，丰富几乎所有的事业。想了解更多关于精通的见解，请阅读乔治·伦纳德的《精通：成功与长期成就的关键》。

Making the path to Mastery a powerful habit will enrich the totality of your life experience. Though you began with the limited goal of swimming faster or more efficiently, you can go well beyond that to making swimming a deeply satisfying experience and perhaps to learning life lessons that can enrich nearly any undertaking. For more insights on Mastery, read the book Mastery: The Keys to Success and Long-Term Fulfillment by George Leonard.

从流畅的笔触到心流状态

From Fluid Strokes to a Flow State

1970年11月初的一个星期六，我经历了一次游泳经历，这件事让我困惑了好几年。当时我代表圣约翰大学参加一场游泳双人赛，和来自阿德菲大学的好友兼对手约翰·奎因在1000码自由泳比赛中较量。多年来，我和约翰一直在曼哈塞特游泳俱乐部的教练比尔·欧文麾下游泳，在夏季训练中日复一日地互相比赛，直到秋天我们各自前往各自的大学。训练中，约翰总是比我快一点，在我们大多数的比赛中都占据优势。

One Saturday in early November 1970, I had an experience in swimming that mystified me for years after. While swimming in a dual meet for St. John’s University, I raced John Quinn, a close friend and rival from Adelphi University, in the 1000-yard freestyle. For several years John and I had swum for Coach Bill Irwin on a club team, Manhasset Swim Club, racing each other day after day in summer training, before heading to our respective colleges in the fall. John was always a bit faster than me in training and held the edge in most of our meet encounters.

这一天，我并没有特别期待和他比赛。我们正处于高强度训练阶段，我已经感觉浑身酸痛疲惫好几天了。比赛前一天——也许是因为高强度的训练降低了我的抵抗力——我得了重感冒，晚上一直在喝橙汁和维生素C。比赛当天早上，热身时我感觉浑身无力，头脑也有些昏沉。400米混合泳接力赛结束后，我和约翰登上了1000米自由泳的中央起跑器，两队各有两名选手站在起跑器两侧。我知道，这是我本赛季参加的所有比赛中，个人对抗最激烈的一场。

On this day, I wasn’t especially looking forward to racing him. We were in a hard-training phase and I had felt sore and tired for days. The day before the meet—perhaps because grueling workouts had reduced my resistance—a nasty cold had reached full bloom and I spent the evening dosing myself with orange juice and vitamin C. The morning of the meet I felt sluggish and fuzzy-headed during warmup. Following the 400 medley relay, John and I mounted the center starting blocks for the 1000 free, flanked by two other swimmers from each team. I was aware that this was the most personal rivalry of all the races I would swim during the season.

发令枪响后，我们游了40圈，才游了不到四个圈，我就意识到自己游得比以往任何时候都快。我略微领先于其他选手——我几乎总是起跑落后，然后不得不迎头赶上——然而我游得毫不费力。接下来的36个圈，我继续毫不费力地领先。我只是感觉自己仿佛漂浮在远离赛场的地方——与比赛如此疏离，以至于我几乎觉得自己在观看比赛。从外部来看，我感觉不到一丝疼痛或疲劳。我既没有感觉自己跑得太猛，也没有感觉自己跑得太轻松。我几乎感觉不到自己在跑。然而，尽管感觉时间仿佛停滞，我却感觉自己完全掌控了一切。终点时，我超越了所有参赛选手，比我之前充分休息和精简后的最佳成绩快了惊人的15秒。

After the starter’s pistol went off, we had swum barely four lengths of that 40-lap race, when I realized that I was swimming as never before. I was slightly in front of the field—I almost always started races behind and then had to catch up—and yet I was swimming with no awareness of effort. Over the next thirty-six lengths, I continued to move effortlessly ahead. I simply felt as if I were floating away from the field—so detached from the race that I almost felt as if I was watching it from the outside. I never felt the slightest pain or fatigue. I never felt as if I was going too hard or too easily. I barely felt as if I was even doing it. Yet, despite feeling as if time was suspended, I felt perfectly in control. At the finish, I had lapped everyone in the field, finishing a stunning fifteen seconds faster than the best time I had previously recorded when fully rested and shaved down.

我再也没能追平那个成绩，也再也没能赢过奎因。之后的每场比赛，他都轻松击败了我。当我回到球队的替补席上时，我只是不停地摇头，心想：“如果我全力以赴，会怎么样？ ”我当时不明白，但现在我明白了，我经历了一种罕见而难以捉摸的体验，被称为“心流状态”——或许这是任何运动员都能拥有的最丰富、最难忘的体验，但却很少有人能体验到。

I never matched that time again and I never beat Quinn again. In every subsequent race, he beat me easily. When I sat back down on the team’s bench, I just kept shaking my head and saying “I wonder what I could have done if I’d gone hard?” What I didn’t understand, but realize now, is that I had experienced a rare and elusive experience known as a Flow State—perhaps the richest, most memorable experience any athlete can have, yet one that few ever experience.

如今，我对“心流”的理解已经足够深刻，能够在游泳时随时随地体验它。而且我知道，追求“心流”，比刻苦训练的意愿更能确保游出最佳水平。想想看，还有什么活动比游泳更适合“心流”状态的训练呢？TI 教授的一切都是为了让你在划水时更流畅地体验。将“心流”状态作为首要目标，你只是迈出了合乎逻辑的下一步。

Today, I understand Flow well enough to be able to experience it virtually at will, while swimming. And I know that pursuit of Flow, more than the willingness to train hard, is the surest path to swimming your best. When you think about it, what activity could be more perfectly suited to Flow State training than swimming? Everything TI teaches is about achieving more Flow in your stroke. By making Flow State the primary goal, you’re simply taking the logical next step.

将心流提升到意识层面

Bringing Flow to a Conscious Level

米哈里·契克森米哈赖博士在20世纪70年代采访艺术家（即那些“创造意义”的人）后，提出了“心流”的概念，并在《心流：最优体验心理学》一书中发表了他开创性的见解。他的创作对象描述了一种欣喜若狂的状态置身于创作之外的感觉。杰夫·穆尔达尔或许会描述自己沉浸在音乐之中，几乎感觉不到房间或观众的存在，甚至没有注意到自己的双手或乐器——至少在我看来是这样。

Mihaly Csikszentmihalyi, Ph.D., developed the concept of Flow in the 1970s after interviewing artists, or those who were “creating meaning,” and he published his groundbreaking insights in the book Flow: The Psychology of Optimal Experience. His creative subjects described an ecstatic sense of being outside of what they were creating. Geoff Muldaur might well describe moments of being so fully involved with his music that he barely notices the room or audience, or even his hands or instrument—or at least it appeared that way to me.

契克森米哈赖总结道，跳出日常的常规是“心流”的必要元素，因为它需要创造性的选择。他还发现，大多数描述自己处于“心流”状态的人很少分析是什么让他们感到快乐。他将“心流”定义为“感觉与自己正在做的事情完全融为一体，知道自己很强大，至少在当下能够掌控自己的命运，并获得一种与结果无关的愉悦感。”这正是我每次游泳时享受到的感觉。

Csikszentmihalyi concluded that stepping outside of normal daily routines is an essential ingredient in Flow, as it required an element of creative choice. He also found that most of those who described being in Flow states had seldom analyzed what made them happy. He defined Flow as “feeling completely at one with what you’re doing, to know you are strong and able to control your destiny at least for the moment, and to gain a sense of pleasure independent of outcomes.” This is exactly the sense I enjoy every time I swim.

大多数运动员都难以达到心流状态，大多数教练也对其理解甚少。而那些有幸体验心流状态的运动员，大多是偶然的。但据他们自己所说，相当一部分全浸式游泳者确实体验到了心流，而且——一旦体验到——重现那种状态就成了他们的主要动力。游得更快几乎是达到心流状态的必然结果，而非他们游泳的首要目标。如果说精通是任何全浸式游泳者最纯粹的目标，那么对心流的理解就是实现这一目标最宝贵的助力。

The Flow State eludes most athletes and is poorly understood by most coaches. And most of those athletes who are fortunate enough to experience Flow do so mainly by chance. But an extraordinary proportion of Total Immersion swimmers, by their own accounts, do experience Flow and—once they have—recreating that state becomes their primary motivation. Swimming faster becomes an almost inevitable result of achieving Flow, rather than the primary goal of their swimming. If Mastery is the purest goal of any Total Immersion swimmer, then knowledge of Flow is the most valuable aid in getting there.

心流的要素是什么？

WHAT ARE THE INGREDIENTS OF FLOW?

Csikszentmihalyi 描述了心流的几个关键方面。所有这些方面都与我在本书中阐述的方案有着天然的联系：

Csikszentmihalyi described several aspects that are keys to Flow. All have natural links to the program I’ve laid out in this book:

 

 

1. 你正在参与一项你重视并认为有意义的活动。可以肯定地说，你不会花时间去做如果您不太重视游泳，请从头到尾阅读这本书。

1. You are involved in an activity that you value and find meaningful. It’s safe to say you wouldn’t be investing the time to read this book all the way through if you didn’t value swimming highly.

 

 

2. 当你全身心投入时，你会全神贯注、专注不已——这或许是出于与生俱来的好奇心，或许是因为如果你不完全专注就无法成功。正念是TI游泳的一项组织原则，我们为专注、专注的游泳提供了无数的辅助和目标。

2. When involved, you are completely engaged, focused, and concentrating—either because of innate curiosity or because you couldn’t succeed if you weren’t completely focused. Mindfulness is an organizing principle of TI Swimming and we provide countless aids to, and targets of, focused, attentive swimming.

 

 

3. 你拥有清晰的思路——知道需要做什么——并且能够轻松监控进度。鱼式游泳的基本技能——顺势游下、划水、流畅移动——为你提供了清晰的目标，而划水计数和感官技能练习则为你提供了衡量成功的便捷方法。

3. You enjoy great clarity—knowing what needs to be done—and have simple means of monitoring how well it is going. The essential skills of Fishlike Swimming—swimming downhill, piercing the water, and moving fluently—provide you with clear goals, while stroke counting and sensory skill practice provide you with ready measures of success.

 

 

4. 你在任务的难度和掌握它所需的技能之间取得了微妙的平衡。如果太容易，你会感到无聊；如果太难，你会感到沮丧。按照第 8 章中六个循序渐进的课程顺序，你可以轻松地保持这种微妙的平衡。

4. You strike a fine balance between the difficulty of the task and the skills needed to master it. If it were too easy, you’d be bored; if too difficult, you’d grow frustrated. By following the sequence of six progressive lessons in chapter 8, you can easily maintain that fine balance.

 

 

5. 当你沉浸在练习中时，你会如此专注于眼前的任务，以至于你会享受到一种前所未有的宁静、永恒和超越自我的感觉。再次强调，正念对于游泳至关重要。

5. While involved in your practice, you become so focused on the present task that you enjoy a sense of serenity, of timelessness, and of transcending ego in ways you never have before. Once more, the value of mindfulness that we emphasize as essential to swimming well.

 

 

6. 你享受内在的动力——任何能带来心流体验的事情本身就是一种奖励。游泳带来的回报越多，你就越能随心所欲地创造心流体验，你练习全浸式游泳的动力就越大——这正是“良性循环”的定义。

6. You enjoy intrinsic motivation—whatever produces Flow becomes its own reward. And the more rewarding your swimming becomes, the better you become at producing Flow experiences at will, the more you’re motivated to practice Total Immersion Swimming—the very definition of a “virtuous cycle.”

我希望我已经为你提供了工具、洞察力和动力，让你在自己的游泳中达到精通和流畅的境界。如果是这样，愿你永远拥有快乐的游泳圈……也许有一天，其中一圈能带你绕曼哈顿一圈。

I hope I’ve given you the tools, insight, and motivation to achieve Mastery and Flow in your own swimming. If so, may you always experience Happy Laps … and perhaps one of those laps will one day take you all the way around Manhattan.

特里·劳克林

Terry Laughlin

纽约州纽帕尔茨

New Paltz, New York

2002年11月

November 2002

Terry@totalimmersion.net

Terry@totalimmersion.net

— Appendix —

变得健康如鱼：

全浸式练习示例

Becoming Fit and Fishlike:

Sample Total Immersion Practice Sets

一旦你明白，比起无意识地在泳池里游泳，智能训练更能有效利用你的时间，你就会问一些更深刻的问题：在泳池里应该做什么？多少次训练、多少次感官技巧练习、多少次划水计数才能达到最佳效果？以及，最好的方法是什么？

Once you understand that intelligent training is a far more valuable use of your time than mindless lap swimming, you’ll ask more penetrating questions about what to do at the pool: How much drill practice, how much sensory skill work, and how much stroke counting will yield the best results? And what’s the best way to do them?

传统的“训练”会混合游泳、划水、踢腿等动作，以及一些死记硬背的练习，让你感到疲惫，并让你忙碌一个小时左右。在TI练习中，每一组动作都有明确的目标——而且通常不止一个层面：教授一项基本技能、提升意识或培养一个难以掌握的习惯——同时又不忽视健身。每一圈都充满目标，用心练习。

Conventional “workouts” mix swim, pull, and kick sets and a few rote drills to get you tired and keep you busy for an hour or so. In TI practice, every set has a specific identifiable purpose—and is usually working on more than one level: teaching an essential skill, heightening awareness or imprinting an elusive habit—without neglecting fitness. Every lap is purposeful and mindful.

这里提供了一套入门练习示例，教你如何将“完全沉浸式”课程的经验教训融入到高效、有效的训练模式中。第 8 章中还包含更多建议，你也可以在www.totalimmersion.net上找到更多示例练习。最终，当你的身体逐渐适应“鱼式”训练的感觉时，你就会敏锐地意识到应该专注于什么以及需要付出多少努力。与此同时，这些练习也会为你提供一些灵感，帮助你设计出更适合你的课程。将使您专注于改善经济状况，并在保持健康的同时养成平稳运动的习惯。

Here’s a starter set of sample practices that show you how to take the lessons of the Total Immersion program and put them into an efficient, effective training format. There are additional suggestions throughout chapter 8 and you can find more sample practices at www.totalimmersion.net. Eventually, as your body learns what being Fishlike should feel like, you’ll develop a keen sense of what to concentrate on and how much work you need. In the meantime, these practices will give you some insights toward designing sessions that will keep you tightly focused on improving your economy and making smooth movements a habit while staying fit.

您可以通过增加或减少一组动作的重复次数或轮数，或者增加或减少重复距离或建议的休息间隔来随意修改组数。

Feel free to modify sets by increasing or decreasing the number of repeats or rounds in a set, or by increasing or reducing the distance of repeats or the suggested rest interval.

基本平衡组：

练习之间休息三次瑜伽呼吸

Basic Balance Set:

Rest for Three Yoga Breaths Between Lengths

这套500码系列训练包含七个平衡练习，旨在提升你在水中轻松获得支撑感的意识——“不再有下沉感”。这有助于你所有动作更加流畅、高效，并节省体力。在像这样将如此多的练习组合成一套之前，请先花些时间熟悉并熟练掌握每个单独的练习。

This 500-yard series uses seven balance drills to heighten your awareness of how to achieve a feeling of effortless support in the water—“no more sinking feeling.” This helps all your movements gain fluency and economy, and you save energy. Before mixing so many drills in a single set like this, take time to achieve ease and familiarity with each of the individual drills.

2 × 25 仰卧平衡

2 × 25 Balance on Your Back

2 × 25 杆头铅球甜蜜点

2 × 25 Head Lead Sweet Spot

2 × 25 主动平衡，参见第 8 章，练习 2（每侧 3 次瑜伽呼吸）

2 × 25 Active Balance, see ch. 8, drill 2 (3 yoga breaths each side)

2 × 25 手引甜蜜点（右侧 25，左侧 25）

2 × 25 Hand Lead Sweet Spot (25 right side, 25 left)

4 × 25 滑冰（接下来的三个练习中，右侧和左侧交替进行 25 秒）

4 × 25 Skating (alternate 25s right side, left side on next three drills)

4 × 25 低位滑冰

4 × 25 UnderSkate

4 × 25拉链滑板

4 × 25 ZipperSkate

 

 

变化

VARIATIONS

• 在您使用 TI 计划的前两到六周内，将其用作练习的标准热身。

• Use as a standard warmup for practices during your first two to six weeks with the TI program.

• 重复两到三次（1000 或 1500 码）以集中精力掌握平衡能力。

• Do the progression two or three times (1000 or 1500 yards) to focus intensively on balance mastery.

• 随着平衡能力的提高，每次练习后，游 1 到 2 次 25 秒或 50 秒的完整划水，重点是感觉与练习期间一样平衡（有支撑、放松、舒适）。

• As your balance improves, swim 1 to 2 × 25s or 50s of whole stroke, after each drill, with a focus on feeling just as balanced (supported, relaxed, comfortable) as during the drill.

呼吸技巧练习游泳系列：

休息三次瑜伽呼吸/25 或五次呼吸/50

Drill-Swim Series for Breathing Technique:

Rest for Three Yoga Breaths/25 or Five Breaths/50

这些平衡旋转练习能增强你在呼吸时保持“挺拔”和平衡的感觉。它还能让你养成“向空中滚动”的呼吸习惯，而不是转动或抬头。你的主要目标是在向空中滚动时保持“挺拔”和针尖般的姿势。

These balance-and-rotation drills heighten your sense of staying “tall” and balanced while breathing. It also imprints the habit of breathing by “rolling to the air” rather than by turning or lifting the head. Your main focus is staying “tall” and needlelike as you roll to air.

进行 1 至 4 轮以下练习，其中一轮为练习长度，一轮为游泳长度：

Do 1 to 4 rounds of the following with one length in the drill and one length swim:

2 × 50或4 × 25滑冰游泳

2 × 50 or 4 × 25 Skate-Swim

2 × 50 或 4 × 25 UnderSkate-Swim

2 × 50 or 4 × 25 UnderSkate-Swim

2 × 50 或 4 × 25 Zipperskate-Swim

2 × 50 or 4 × 25 Zipperskate-Swim

每组100码，左侧换气50码，右侧换气50码。当你在右侧滑行（右臂伸展）时，你会向左侧换气。在下一个游泳距离，向左侧换气，然后在下一个50码时换气。第二种选择是在所有游泳距离中双侧换气（每3次划水一次），在右侧滑行后，更多地关注左侧换气。在所有训练距离中，专注于滚动当你翻身仰卧换气时，身体会超过你的“甜蜜点”。无论游多远，在翻身换气时，都要注意保持一个像针一样的长身体姿势。

In each set of 100 yards, breathe on the left for 50, and the right for 50. When you Skate on your right side (right arm extended), you’ll breathe to your left. On the next swim length, breathe to the left side, then switch on the next 50. A second option is to breathe bilaterally (every 3 strokes) on all swim lengths and just focus more on the left side breaths after Skating on your right. On all drill lengths, focus on rolling past your Sweet Spot when you roll nose-up to breathe. On all swim lengths, focus on keeping a long, needlelike body position as you roll to the air to breathe.

针对“滑溜”身体姿势的练习游泳系列：

休息三到五次瑜伽呼吸

Drill-Swim Series for “Slippery” Body Positions:

Rest for Three to Five Yoga Breaths

这个 UnderSwitch 练习游泳序列可以提高您“刺穿”水的意识，同时还可以教您将手臂划水与核心身体旋转的力量联系起来。

This UnderSwitch drill-swim sequence improves your awareness of “piercing” the water while also teaching you to link your arm stroke to the power of core-body rotation.

进行 1 至 4 轮 (4 × 25 + 2 × 50 + 1 × 100) 如下：

Do 1 to 4 rounds of (4 × 25 + 2 × 50 + 1 × 100) as follows:

4 × 25：奇数 25 秒换边/偶数 25 秒游泳（尝试双侧呼吸）

4 × 25: Odd 25s UnderSwitch/Even 25s Swim (try to breathe bilaterally)

2 × 50：25 次双下换臂/25 次游泳（前 50 次左侧呼吸，后 50 次右侧呼吸）

2 × 50: 25 Double UnderSwitch/25 Swim (first 50 left-side breaths, second 50 right-side breaths)

1 × 100：25 次三重下换/25 次游泳（尝试双侧呼吸）

1 × 100: 25 Triple UnderSwitch/25 Swim (try to breathe bilaterally)

 

 

变化

VARIATIONS

• 反转顺序：进行 25 秒的三重下换水/游泳，然后进阶到 100 秒的下换水/游泳。

• Reverse the order: Do 25s of Triple UnderSwitch/Swim and progress to 100s of UnderSwitch/Swim.

• 随着你的游泳水平提高，在100米比赛中进行25次练习；75次游泳练习。“游得和练得一样好。”

• As your swimming improves, do 25 Drill; 75 Swim on the 100s. “Swim as well as you drill.”

训练游泳系列将训练技巧融入整个划水动作

Drill-Swim Series to Integrate Drill Skills in Whole Stroke

随着技能的提升，增加游泳与训练的比例。训练长度可以提高平衡性和身体姿势；游泳时，要运用重点，帮助你将训练中获得的见解运用到你的划水动作中。坚持“训练得好，游得好”的原则。

As your skills improve, increase the proportion of swim-to-drill. The drill lengths heighten balance and alignment; on the swim lengths use focal points that help you take insights gained from the drills into your stroke. Stay committed to the rule of: “Swim as well as you drill.”

进行三轮 4 × 100 米游泳练习，具体如下：

Swim three rounds of 4 × 100 Drill-Swim as follows:

#1 25 ZipperSkate/25 游泳 ( × 2)

#1 25 ZipperSkate/25 Swim ( × 2)

#2 25 ZipperSwitch/25 游泳 ( × 2)

#2 25 ZipperSwitch/25 Swim ( × 2)

#3 25 双拉链开关/游泳 25 ( × 2)

#3 25 Double ZipperSwitch/Swim 25 ( × 2)

#4 25 三重拉链开关/25 游泳 ( × 2)

#4 25 Triple ZipperSwitch/25 Swim ( × 2)

#5–8 重复上述步骤，但每次训练 50 分钟，游泳 50 分钟

#5–8 Repeat as above but do 50 Drill/50 Swim

#9–12 25 三重拉链开关/75 游泳

#9–12 25 Triple ZipperSwitch/75 Swim

变化：

VARIATIONS:

• 如果您感觉到任何形式上的崩溃，请将 100 次分成 25 次或 50 次。

• Break the 100s into 25s or 50s if you feel any form breakdown.

• 随着您的整体划水姿势不断改善，进行更多组 25 次练习/75 次游泳练习。

• Do more sets of 25 Drill/75 Swim as your whole stroke form improves.

• 增加多重转换练习（双拉链和三拉链）的比例，以进一步培养您的节奏和时间感。

• Increase the proportion of multiswitch drills (Double- and Triple Zipper) to develop your rhythm and timing more.

• 用双重和三重过度切换代替紧凑、轻松的恢复，成为习惯。

• Substitute Double- and Triple-OverSwitch as a compact, relaxed recovery becomes habit.

训练-游泳组合，培养特定技能或意识

Drill-Swim Combinations for Developing Specific Skills or Awareness

 

 

将训练见解运用到整个划水动作的关键在于，在训练和游泳过程中，只专注于做好一件事。如果你进行 25 分钟滑冰/25 分钟游泳训练，并在训练过程中专注于“保持头部在一条直线上”，那么在游泳时，只需专注于头部的位置即可。以下是一些其他建议的训练和游泳练习的重点组合：

The key to transferring drill insights to the whole stroke is to think about doing only one thing really well on both drill and swim. If you do 25 Skate/25 Swim, and focus on “keeping your head in line” during the drill, then think only about your head position as you swim. Here are some other suggested combinations of drill and focal point for drill and swim:

钻头 游泳长度的焦点
UnderSkate 像针一样滚动以呼吸；一直滚动到空中。
拉链溜冰鞋 轻轻地摆动臀部和双腿，“靠在肺部”；感受水的支撑。
UnderSwitch 游泳时自由翻滚。
拉链开关 “刺穿”水，让你的身体穿过尽可能最小的“洞”。
三下 游泳时保持“连接”；用整个身体去游泳。
三重拉链 轻柔、紧凑地恢复；你的手刚离开水面就立即重新入水。
三倍以上 用指尖切开一个洞，然后将手臂干净利落地穿过那个洞。

变化

VARIATIONS

• 从多次长度的练习、一次长度的游泳开始，逐渐增加到较少长度的练习和较多长度的游泳。

• Start with multiple lengths of drills, single lengths of swim and progress to fewer drill lengths and more swim lengths.

• 用一个练习和一个焦点进行 200 到 400 码的练习，以深深地留下印象。

• Do 200 to 400 yards with one drill and one focal point to imprint it deeply.

• 按顺序组合几对钻头+焦点，以提高您的适应能力。

• Combine several pairs of drill + focal point in sequence to improve your adaptability.

摆脱训练轮：

通过全程划桨练习来提高划桨长度

Take Off the Training Wheels:

Whole-Stroke Sets to Develop Stroke Length

这些组合会教你距离如何影响你的划水效率，并让你养成严格检查训练决策（多远、多用力、休息多久）如何影响你实现永久效率的目标的习惯（spl = 每长度划水次数）。

These sets teach you how distance affects your stroke efficiency and put you in the habit of critically examining how your training decisions—how far, how hard, how much rest—affect your goals of making efficiency permanent (spl = strokes per length).

划水长度练习 1

STROKE LENGTH EXERCISE 1

游泳 25 + 50 + 75 + 100。每次游泳后休息三到五次瑜伽呼吸。

Swim 25 + 50 + 75 + 100. Rest for three to five yoga breaths after each swim.

记录你在25米自由泳时的划水次数，然后不必严格限制划水次数，只需保持稳定的配速或努力，看看其他游泳项目的平均划水次数会有什么变化。如果你在25米自由泳中划了15次，那么在50米、75米和100米自由泳中，你的划水次数比30-45-60次高出多少呢？不要评判自己；只需记录下来并存档以备将来参考。

Take note of your stroke count on the 25, then without trying to strictly limit your count, just swim at a consistent pace or effort and see what happens to your spl average on the other swims. If you took 15 strokes for the 25, how far above 30-45-60 strokes are you on the 50-75-100? Don’t judge yourself; just take note and file the information for future reference.

划水长度练习 2

STROKE LENGTH EXERCISE 2

游泳 100 + 75 + 50 + 25。每次游泳后休息三到五次瑜伽呼吸。

Swim 100 + 75 + 50 + 25. Rest for three to five yoga breaths after each swim.

从简单的100开始。计算你的划水次数，然后除以4。这个数字将成为你剩余组别的“N”（基准划水次数）。例如：如果你划了72次，你的N就是18划水次数（72除以4个桨长）。同样，只需记录你在75-50-25组别中，与54-36-18划水次数的差距。

Start with an easy 100. Count your strokes and divide by 4. This number becomes your “N” (benchmark spl) for the rest of the set. Example: If you took 72 strokes, your N is 18 spl (72 divided by 4 lengths). Again, simply note how far below 54-36-18 strokes you are for 75-50-25.

划水长度练习 3

STROKE LENGTH EXERCISE 3

游泳 25 + 50 + 75 + 100。

Swim 25 + 50 + 75 + 100.

重复练习1，但这次要有一个特定的重点——例如，藏起你的头，或者钻进一个较小的洞里，或者游得更安静。只需记下你的划水次数；不要试图达到任何特定的次数。这纯粹是一个实验，看看技术上的“调整”是否会影响你的SL，教你如何影响——并最终选择你的SL。

Repeat Exercise 1, but this time with a specific focal point— e.g., hiding your head, or slipping through a smaller hole, or swimming more quietly. Just take note of your stroke count; don’t attempt to hit any particular count. This is purely an experiment to see if technique “tweaks” affect your SL, teaching you that you can affect—and ultimately choose your SL.

划水长度练习 4

STROKE LENGTH EXERCISE 4

游两轮，分别为 25 + 50 + 75 + 100。

Swim two rounds of 25 + 50 + 75 + 100.

第一轮：戴拳套®游泳。按照你之前的成绩游，不要刻意追求任何特定的划水数。你的划水比不戴拳套时的速度高出多少？

First Round: Swim with fistgloves®. Just swim at your previous effort, not trying to hit any particular count. How many strokes above your ungloved spl are you?

第二轮：脱下拳套。®无需尝试特定的计数，将您的划水次数与之前的 spl 进行比较，以发现拳套®如何影响您的效率。

Second Round: Remove fistgloves.® Without trying for a particular count, compare your stroke counts to your previous spl to discover how fistgloves® affect your efficiency.

游泳 高尔夫

Swimming Golf

我们引入了配速钟，但使用速度比 (SPL) 和自觉用力程度（心率）来衡量任何速度提升的“成本”。提升速度最简单的方法不是付出更多或更艰辛的努力；而是学会以更经济的方式在任何给定速度下游泳，释放能量，游得更远或更快。

We introduce the pace clock, but use spl and perceived effort (heart rate) to measure the “cost” of any speed increases. The easiest way to increase speed isn’t more or harder work; it’s by learning to swim any given speed more economically, freeing the energy to go farther or faster.

版本 1

VERSION 1

在接下来的50米游程中，保持相同的时间，但减少划水次数。例如：

On successive 50s, swim the same time but reduce your stroke count. Example:

总击球时间 32 次 + 50 秒 = 得分 82 分

32 total strokes + 50 seconds = a score of 82

总笔画数 31 + :50 = 81

31 total strokes + :50 = 81

总笔画数 30 + :50 = 80

30 total strokes + :50 = 80

目标是每50米都保持相同的时间，同时不断减少划水次数，直到在不牺牲速度的情况下无法再减少划水次数。解决这个问题将为你带来宝贵的“游泳智慧”。

The goal is to repeat the same time on each 50 while continuing to subtract strokes until you can’t shave any more from your count without sacrificing speed. Solving it will give you valuable “swimming intelligence.”

版本2

VERSION 2

连续50次划水后，保持划水次数不变，同时减少时间。例如：

On successive 50s, maintain stroke count while descending your time. Example:

总笔画数 30 + :45 = 75

30 total strokes + :45 = 75

总笔画数 30 + :44 = 74

30 total strokes + :44 = 74

总笔画数 30 + :43 = 73

30 total strokes + :43 = 73

全浸入式练习集示例

Sample Total Immersion Practice Sets

为了提高你的分数，你需要保持完全相同的划水长度，但每次划水速度略快一些，以节省时间。你会惊讶地发现，多一点努力就能快速增加很多划水次数。如果这些划水次数没有转化为足够的速度来降低你的总分，你就知道自己浪费了时间，可以立即采取措施解决这个问题。

To improve your score you need to keep exactly the same stroke length, but take each stroke just a bit faster to shave seconds. You’ll be amazed at how quickly a bit more effort can add a lot more strokes. If those strokes don’t translate into enough speed to lower your total score, you know you’ve been wasteful and can take immediate steps to fix the problem.

游泳高尔夫的变奏

VARIATIONS ON SWIM GOLF

• 戴上拳套® “打”高尔夫。你的成绩能接近不戴手套时的水平吗？戴手套打几轮后，再脱掉手套打一轮。在“训练”你的双手之后，你的成绩比之前不戴手套的比赛有所提高吗？如果是，请记录下你当时的感觉。

• “Play” golf with fistgloves®. How close can you come to your ungloved scores? After several rounds with gloves on, do another round without them. Does your score improve over previous ungloved sets after “educating” your hands? If so, lock in the sensations you got.

• 你能用多少种方式得分？确定你的“标准杆”后，测试一下你能用多少种不同的划水次数游出略高的分数。如果你的记录分数是77分，你能用30、31、32、33和34次划水游出80分吗？哪种划水方式感觉最轻松？

• How many ways can you score? After you’ve established your “par,” test how many different stroke counts you can swim at a slightly higher score. If your record score is 77, can you swim a constant score of 80 at 30 and 31 and 32 and 33 and 34 strokes? Which feels easiest?

• 获得良好成绩后，测量心率或估算自觉用力程度。64 分（心率 120）比 64 分（心率 150）要好得多。

• Take your heart rate or estimate your perceived exertion after a good score. A score of 64 with an HR of 120 is much better than a score of 64 with an HR of 150.

游得更远：为一英里游泳而智能构建

Going Longer: Building Intelligently Toward a Mile Swim

传统的长距离游泳训练主要依靠的是码数……其主要效果是培养缓慢的节奏和低效的划水。本次TI 训练计划会塑造高效的划水姿势，并逐步延长你能保持的距离。为了准备800米游泳，一开始可以做5  x 100米，然后每次增加1个，最后一周达到10  x 100米。

Conventional training for a longer swim is with sheer yardage… the main effect of which is to imprint a plodding pace and inefficient stroking. This TI training program imprints an efficient stroke and progressively extends the distances you can maintain that. To prepare for an 800-meter swim, begin with 5  x100 and increase the number by 1, to reach 10  x100 in the final week.

 

 

1. 测量你的效率。轻松不间断地游10到15分钟（半英里游5到10分钟）。每游100码左右计算一次25码的分段。如果你能将这个分段保持在最低分段的10%以内，那么你就可以游得更远了。

1. Measure your efficiency. Do a relaxed nonstop swim of 10 to 15 minutes (5 to 10 minutes for a half-mile swim). Count your 25-yard split every 100 or so. If you can you maintain it within 10 percent of your lowest count, you’re ready to go longer.

 

 

2. 养成流畅游动和经济游动的习惯。一开始不必担心游多远或多快；专注于“游得如何合适”。每周游两次设定的基准。每次游完后做八次瑜伽呼吸。只需数划水次数，保持流畅游动并逐渐养成习惯。如果感觉有些不适应，可以多做瑜伽呼吸和/或放慢速度。

2. Make Flow and economy a habit. Don’t worry about how far or fast at first; focus on “how right.” Swim the benchmark set twice a week. Take eight yoga breaths between repeats. Just count strokes and make Flow and ease a habit. If you lose it, take more yoga breaths and/or slow down.

 

 

3. 增加距离，但保持效率/经济。随着基准设定的提高，重点要放在轻松度上。每周只修改一个变量。其他变量保持不变。

3. Build distance but maintain efficiency/economy. As you increase your benchmark set, keep the focus on ease. Modify only one variable each week. All other variables remain as before.

第一周。游泳10×100米。每次游泳之间进行6到8次瑜伽呼吸。保持spl至少比第一次测试游泳时低10%。（例如，如果你的平均spl是20，那么100米的目标spl是18。）切勿用力呼吸。每次完成这组训练时，都要感觉自己可以轻松地保持这种状态。如果你的spl或easily下降，可以进行恢复性休息：做50米你最喜欢的练习。

WEEK 1. Swim 10 × 100. Take six to eight yoga breaths between swims. Maintain spl at least 10 percent lower than on your initial test swim. (For example, if you averaged 20 spl, aim for 18 on your 100s.) Never breathe hard. Finish the set each time feeling as if you could easily keep going like that. If at any time your spl or ease break down, take a recovery break: a 50 of your favorite drill.

第2周。减少一次呼吸的休息。

WEEK 2. Decrease rest by one breath.

第3周。在最后 2 × 100 时稍微加快速度。

WEEK 3. Increase pace slightly over last 2 × 100.

第4周。平均声压级降低 1。

WEEK 4. Decrease average spl by 1.

第5周.将重复次数增加到 12 × 100。

WEEK 5. Increase number of repeats to 12 × 100.

第六周。减少一次呼吸的休息。

WEEK 6. Decrease rest by one breath.

第7周。在最后 4 × 100 时稍微加快速度。

WEEK 7. Increase pace slightly over last 4 × 100.

第8周.将重复次数增加到 14 × 100。

WEEK 8. Increase number of repeats to 14 × 100.

第九周。减少一次呼吸的休息。

WEEK 9. Decrease rest by one breath.

第10周.将重复次数增加到 16 × 100。

WEEK 10. Increase number of repeats to 16 × 100.

第 11周。在最后 6 × 100 比赛中稍微加快配速。

WEEK 11. Increase pace slightly over last 6 × 100.

第12周.将重复次数增加到 18 × 100。

WEEK 12. Increase number of repeats to 18 × 100.

即使你不能严格遵守每周的计划，你也不会因此而失败。以此为榜样，制定一个有目的、循序渐进的训练方法，提升你在长距离游泳中保持高效划水的能力，培养出最佳长距离游泳的素质，以及在自己选择的时间段内经济地进行长距离游泳的能力。

You don’t fail the course if you can’t stay precisely with the weekly schedule. Use this as a model for a purposeful, progressive approach to increasing your capacity to maintain an efficient stroke over lengthening distances, imprinting the qualities that produce the best long-distance swim, the ability to swim economically for a long time for a duration of your choice.

来自我的书架

From My Bookshelf

我书架上的六本经常被翻阅的书对于我在五十岁（或任何其他年龄）保持强壮和灵活来说，是无价的指导来源。

Six well-thumbed titles from my bookshelf have been a priceless source of guidance for me on staying strong and supple at age fifty (or any other age).

 

 

《保持柔软：伸展运动的无限乐趣》，约翰·杰罗姆

（Breakaway Books）著。

Staying Supple: The Bountiful Pleasures of Stretching, by John Jerome

(Breakaway Books).

《柔韧的身体：健身、力量和灵活性的新途径》，

作者：萨拉·布莱克（Thorsons）。

The Supple Body: The New Way to Fitness, Strength, and Flexibility,

by Sara Black (Thorsons).

《伸展运动》，鲍勃·安德森（Shelter Publications）著。

Stretching, by Bob Anderson (Shelter Publications).

瑜伽身心（DK 出版）。

Yoga Mind & Body (DK Publishing).

《普拉提健身：无需器械，在家强化、

拉伸、调理身体的终极指南》，

布鲁克·西勒（百老汇）著。

The Pilates Body: The Ultimate At-Home Guide to Strengthening,

Lengthening, and Toning Your Body—Without Machines,

by Brooke Siler (Broadway).

球上普拉提：世界上最受欢迎的健身

球锻炼方式，作者：科琳·克雷格（《治愈艺术》）。

Pilates on the Ball: The World’s Most Popular Workout Using the Exercise

Ball, by Colleen Craig (Healing Arts).

问：是否有“跑步者完全沉浸式体验”？

Q: Is there a “Total Immersion for Runners”?

答：是的！丹尼·德雷尔的《气功跑》 。

A:Yes! ChiRunning, by Danny Dreyer.

多年来，我一直渴望找到一种跑步运动，能够像“全浸式”游泳那样，将跑步的理念和精神融入其中。2003年秋天，我终于找到了。从十几岁到四十出头，我一直享受跑步，把它当作一种可靠的健身方式，并享受着跑步带来的内啡肽带来的快感。我从来都不是一个“认真”的跑步者，但我确实喜欢偶尔参加5公里或10公里的路跑比赛。但从43岁到52岁，我一直饱受慢性伤病的困扰，这让我无法跑步，也无法参加铁人三项比赛。每当我跑超过两英里（约3公里）时，我左腿的比目鱼肌（小腿根部的深层组织）就会出现疼痛的痉挛。但在阅读了丹尼·德雷尔 (Danny Dreyer) 所著的《气功跑步》 (ChiRunning) (西蒙与舒斯特出版社)的预发行版，并参加了丹尼主持的为期一天的气功跑步研讨会 (参见www.chirunning.com ) 后，几周内我就能跑六英里甚至更远，而且没有疼痛、受伤或疲劳。

For years I wished I could find the equivalent for running that has the approach and spirit that Total Immersion brings to swimming. In the fall of 2003, I finally found it. From my teens through my early forties, I had enjoyed running as a reliable source of fitness and the pleasure to be gained from endorphins. I was never a “serious” runner, but I did enjoy participating in the occasional 5K or 10K road race. But from age forty-three to fifty-two I was frustrated by a chronic injury that kept me from running—and triathlons. Whenever I ran farther than about two miles, the soleus muscle (deep tissue at the base of my calf) on my left leg would go into painful spasm. But after reading a pre-release copy of ChiRunning (Simon & Schuster), by Danny Dreyer, and attending a one-day ChiRunning workshop (see www.chirunning.com) led by Danny, within weeks I was running six miles and more without pain, injury, or fatigue.

与“完全沉浸”一样，气跑将我们许多人机械式地进行的活动转化为一种经过检验的活动，通过专注练习充满智慧、经过深思熟虑的动作来发展。与“完全沉浸”一样，气跑的重点是通过更有效的动作来提高速度和耐力，而不是跑更多更艰难的距离。最重要的是，与“完全沉浸”一样，它确实有效！所以，如果你已经从“完全沉浸”对游泳的影响中受到鼓舞，并且希望在跑步中获得类似的体验，我推荐你尝试一下气跑。

Like Total Immersion, ChiRunning takes an activity that many of us do by rote and turns it into an examined activity, developed by mindful practice of intelligent, thoughtful movements. Like Total Immersion, the emphasis is on improving your speed and endurance through more effective movement, rather than more and harder miles. And best of all, like Total Immersion, it works! So if you have been encouraged by how Total Immersion has affected your swimming, and you’d like to have a similar experience with running, I recommend you check out ChiRunning.
